text: aroma is `` off the chain , '' as the kiddies say nowadays . rather than compete and muddle all these scents meld into a unified aroma of awesome . perfect .  the only thing slightly disappointing about this beer for me was the mouthfeel seemed a bit watery .

it poured a beautiful copper color with lots of bubbles coming up from the bottom of my beer-clean glass . the beer had abundant head that agressively stuck to the side of my glass and slowly and inconsistently faded , starting from the middle of my glass . this beer really was quite attractive .  it had a light feel on the palate with mild carbonation .

well after all the hype i had to give this one a try , pours motor oil black with two finger tan head , smells of alcohol and burnt espresso , tastes the exact same , if i were to roast some espresso beans until they were charred all the way through , then threw them into a blender with ice and vodka , thats exactly how this tasted to me .  thin mouthfeel , this is the achilles heel of the beer .

pours a solid black with nice size ( 2 to 3 fingers ) of frothy toffee colored head . wonderful sticky and frothy lacing .  mouthfeel is ok. fairly light body , more than i 'd think it should be at this abv .

for me , the appearance of a well poured guinness is stellar . the deep rich near-black mahogany tint of it , while the flow of bubbles seems to defy physics is near magical . always great poured over a bent spoon atop bass pale ale or harp lager as well !  a- blackness with a espresso colored head s- coffee beans ground soaked in licorice coffee and dark chocolate really bold t- straight up coffee and espresso with bitter chocolate and a slight tang finish m- medium carbonation and a bit watery for the style d- i drink 3 cup of coffee a day who am i to judge ?

s - beautiful wet hopped aroma with a citrusy and piney profile that is extremely fresh . there 's also a bit of bread and caramel malt present .  this is almost as good a stout as they come . i like guinness extra stout better because it has more bitterness . but this stout is smooth and easy to drink with a nice bitterness . if you are looking for a stout to bring to a party this is a good one because it is not too bitter . almost everyone i have served this to has liked it .

bubblegum , banana and cloves . smells just like i 'd like a hefeweizen to smell . the taste does n't live up to the nose , however .  tastefully good as well.with the same taste of chocolate milk with a hint of hops and lots of malt.i could have this one for breakfast lunch , and dinner.what ya mean i 'm a raging alcholic.i beg your pardon.this is one tasty beverage , one that will put a smile on your face all day long .

it 's really smooth and i appreciate the level of authentic bourbon present in the nose . the flavors consist of chocolate , roasted malts , light coffee with cream , vanilla , barrel and alcohol . the 9 % is n't hidden at all and after the nose , is pretty surprising . and it is n't the bourbon that is overpowering , it 's the abv of the beer itself .  smell is of old corn/rice and skunk . pew . taste was horrendous . a skunky malt liquor flavor mixed with sweet rice/corn adjunct . maybe it went bad on it 's journey from the carib-bean ? looks like i should have gone for the sam light that was also in the fridge ...

smoke , roasted malt , a little vanilla , some wood , and a great rich wine smell that mixes perfectly with everything else . fantastic . t - taste is not quite as good as the nose , but its still quite nice . o - this was my favorite one , just due to the amazing aroma .  the mouthfeel is just average . also , carbonation is lacking enough to make this feel sticky .

s- this beer smells great , typical ipa smells ; pine mandarin , pineapple , grapefruit .  the rye is evident , as is a tangy almost sour note along with the bread . a little over-carbonated ... i found it slightly distracting and that it may have affected my enjoyment of the beer 's complexity . light-bodied and very refreshing . while i have little to no experience with beers of this style , i enjoyed this one and i believe that its a great refresher during the summer months .

the beer has the unique feature for this style by including a spiced-raisin aroma although it is mild . no hops contribution to the scent .  m : slick mouthfeel with a medium amount of carbonation that can be prickly at times . body is medium and has a bit of resiny stickiness to it .
smell is of butterscotch and very pleasing . like you are about to have a delicious dessert .  mouthfeel is perhaps a bit thin for the style but not bad .

2008 vintage , into tulip . the nose is utterly complex with interplay of sour , sweet , fruity and sherry aromas . the sourness takes after balsamic vinegar which is quite intense denoting an aged example , as do the obvious sherry-notes . the malt is quite rich with caramel and slight chocolaty character while fruity esters are reminiscent of raisins , plum and black cherries . a very faint mushroom-like bitterness indicates that brettanomyces has been used to add sourness to this one .  m : the feel is slightly creamy but on the lighter side of medium bodied . could be a bit thicker here ... d : if you like coffee beers i could see someone drinking good amount of these .

s : strong piny medicinal hop kick , very strong and spicy floral aromas with a bit of grapefruit rind mixed in , there is also a lightly detectable sweet and grainy maltiness hiding in the wings here as well , very fresh smelling . t/mf : this is were i was a bit disappointed after such a nice nose . d : very nice and fresh and strong hop aroma but that is where the goodness ends for me . still there are worse ipas out there than this one .  this is a great beer . the aromas are sweet and malty , with hints of caramel and vanilla . this beer has a nice , smoky flavor with hints of toffee and vanilla . this will definitely be going on my `` favorite beers '' list .

2010 batch @ harvest fest 10/1/11 a : golden body with fluffy white head and a good cling s : smells like it will be very good : lots of sour-adding oak , some noxious funk and tartness . t : definitely a let down .  light carbonation and light-medium bodied . flavor is a hospital antiseptic . said to be an ipa , i understand pigs fly too . looks bad , smells bad , tastes worse , higher abv is hidden . waaay overpriced at $ 10.45 for a 330ml bottle from colonial spirits acton , ma .
light copper with a thick , mousse-like , sticky-as-hell head .  carbonation a little higher than i expect in the style but still manages to be exceptionally drinkable .

s : belgian yeasts , lemons , a touch of honey at the end , dust , peppers , banana and clove . t : taste does not match the smells .  drinkability : mouthfeel is a little thin , but this is a very solidly crafted stout , up there with the tops in style .

really nice . t - red wine grapes , cherries and leather stand out to me , as does the vanilla and wood from the barrels .  not too complicated , but a pleasant experience overall . goes down quite easily ( in part because of the low carbonation ) .

very nice . smells light , not expecting much malt in the flavor . where are all those delicious hops i smelled ? as with many ipas , i find that it smells better than it tastes .  the mouthfeel is less crisp then i had hoped .
appearance - slightly hazed yellow/straw . puts a good finger and a half of white foam on the glass . a nice ring of lace frosting at the high water mark .  medium bodied , highly carbonated .
smells amazing . the pine and citra form a wave of hoppy goodness .  m-medium bodied with slightly more carbonation than i prefer in a porter .

bottle poured into a tulip glass . brilliant clarity . thick white crop of foam with good retention and moderate lacing .  medium bodied , it seems a little flat at the beginning , but there 's sharp carbonation at the finish , which is a little watery and silty .
pours pale gold with a massive crown of stiff white foam .  slightly sour , a bit thin , highly carbonated . quite drinkable .

this beer pours a nearly perfect copper color with a voluminous , tan rocky head . the head slowly fades until a loose layer of foam lays atop the beer , which displays excellent clarity .  m -- light carbonation . good body with a lightly soft mouthfeel .
overall a fantastic beer .  it seems to light and over carbonated for a stout .

a - deep gold color s- amazing , citrus , grapefruit , & bubblegum aromas t- bitter hops ( grapefruit-like ) with fruity undertones . m - dry to the finish o- i was impressed that brewers were able to capture strong complexity for such a bitter , hoppy brew . overall i felt that the bitterness was way overpowering , leaving my mouth dried out .  thin on mouthfeel medium orangish-amber with a 1 finger offwhite head that leaves a respectable amount of lacing . taste : broad caramel maltiness with a warming alcohol changes over to a restrained english hop bitterness . notes : a nice esb , although the abv is much higher than say , honker 's ale . drinkability ranks fairly high but the alcohol content is above that of a session beer .

pours out very clear straw color with plenty of carbonation and a rich frothy white head that lingers and laces , truly beautiful .  mouthfeel was slightly thin with a very tasty caramel taste on the tongue . the finish was semi-sweet , slightly dry , very nice for the style .

s : a rich citrus , piney hop aroma is released when you open the bottle and once in the glass that 's all you can smell . sweet grapefruit - fantastic smell . t : unfortunately the smell seems more powerful than the taste which seems a bit on the light side .  a little thin , flavors do n't linger or expand much .

a- pours a pitch black hue with brown and amber highlights , small tan/brown head that is mostly sustaining , fair amount of lacing throughout s- fruity scents dominated by raisins and dark fruit ( as advertised on the label ) , i am also getting tones of apple , peach , belgian candy , sweet caramel/toffee malts , and a modest alcohol presence t- initial taste is raisins , raisins , and more raisins ( almost cloyingly sweet ) , followed by a variety of fruits and spices , yeasty/bready/sweet malts , a little bit of chocolate and belgian candy , finishes with sweet malts , a touch of bittering hops and warming alcohol presence m- medium/full bodied with good carbonation , nice slick texture that coats the tongue in sweetness d- 9 % abv is well-masked , but this definitely a sipping beer to be enjoyed over time ( much like a port or desert wine ) .  light bodied though , almost watery . in a way this is an ipa-light - some similar desirable flavors and aromas , but less bitterness , less alcohol , and lighter bodied .
fruity nose classic ipa ( not the barleywine as is sometimes said ) .  mouf & gt ; meh . okay . average .

aroma is amazing ... whisky , vanilla , smooth smoke , chocolate , big roasted notes and some oak . taste was a bit of a let down after the wonderful aroma . i picked up a lot of sweet chocolate , some booze , big on the bourbon flavor . this was a rare treat to enjoy i am very happy i had the chance .  mouthfeel is light and carbonation fades to almost flat .
smell : thick , sweet , treacly , appetizing taste : smooth , bitter , slightly sweet . not as sweet and deep as the smell hinted at .  body was very light and thin .

the head recedes smells great , rummy , oak-y , sugar cane , caramel , coconut , spicy , very layered and complex nose . there 's a little hop bitterness in the taste but all else is overpowered by the rum and oak taste .  i found the body to be a bit thin carbonation medium to low .

smell : very sweet . some booze cuts through the richness . incredibly decadent . taste : one of those beers where you say `` wow , '' after the first sip .  it 's light on body , and not especially interesting - but as fruit beers go , this was excellent .

s : the aroma is forceful - sweet butter nougat , hazelnut and almond liquor , amaretto , fig , sweet nuts , dark cherry , vanilla ... almost an amaretto stench . t : tangy up front , highly carbonic , muted sweetness much as in the nose , delicate but rich nuts , light molasses , vanilla , all warm soft and lightly sweet , nuanced , dynamic , but flavor light . a delicious dubbel , but with such rich aromatics , the flavor in the mouth leaves more to be desired .  the body was medium to medium light .

aroma : sweet candy like roasted chocolate , burnt marshmellow , citrus and spicey hop arma . smells so good ! appearance : clear , dark brown with ruby highlights . this beer kind of dissapointed me becasue the hop aroma is supposed to be a lot more intense . i was expecting a burst of hop aroma which was n't really there . this is a well brewed beer and very tasty .  the mouthfeel was the only thing that detracted from the beer in my opinion , as i found it to be a little to watery for my personal preference .

the smell is the best part of this beer : very hoppy and `` dirty '' . the taste is good , but i feel that it 's a bit weak compared to dogfish head 's 90 minute ipa . overall , a good ipa , but not the best i 've had .  m - a little watery for the style , but not objectionable .

it pours a cloudy golden orange color and smells delicious . the nose had hints of orange peel , coriander , hops and light caramel . drinkability was a little low though due to the over carbonation and the sweetness of the beer overall , but very good . will buy again  the only thing i felt was it could use a little more carbonation to balance the tart flavor and make it more perky .

a - black ... cool s - nutty and fresh with some fruits behind but not really much of a scent t - tastes like an oil mixed with dirt .  not too complex- makes for easy drinking , as does its texture . carbonation level seems low , though as an earlier commenter noted , it is actually just very fine .

murky , fluffy smells ... well , wheaty and sweety ! the perfect hefe .  though this is a red ale of stormy garnet and the menu states it is `` brewed with 20 % honey malts for a touch of sourness '' ( honey = sourness ? it is not merely that this red ale tastes bad ; it is absolutely offensive . of the lowest evolutionary order . the entire beer is corrupted by spoilage and should n't be served publicly .

the aroma is awesome . right away it reminds me of kuhnhenn raspberry eisbock with huge notes of sweet raspberries and chocolate .  this beer was skunky ... skunky like a becks . and i couldnt find any other component of this beer redeeming enough to get over that skunkyness . my encounter with this beer started out ok ... it has a pale yellow appearance with a medium amount of head . taste exhibited becks ( or maybe even becks light ) levels of skunkitude , again with a bit of clove chasing after it to apologize . definitely not recommended .

extremely fruit-fillled aromatics - pungent apple sauce notes lead the way into a more diverse array of stone-fruit esters . lush oaky notes with a touch of bergamot in the finish - complexity grows as the beer warms . i 'm still impressed that the base beer can be improved upon by soaking up the best characteristics of the barrels it is aged in , but these special editions of harvest ale have certainly `` matured '' more than simply `` aged .  m : medium to light body with medium to low carbonation . would have preferred a bigger body by far .

pours a very deep brown from a 550ml bottle with a two finger head that retains . it 's opaque and pushes pitch black .  average feel for the genre i 'd say . it 's pleasant in sips and gulps and a few of em would be just as enjoyable as one .

the smell on this one is incredible , and leaves little to be desired . a lot of chocolate hits the nostrils as well as bitter espresso . this is by far the best porter i have ever smelled , thus far . the taste is not quite up to par here .  m - the mouthfeel is a little light , with little carbonation .

the aroma is strong and super sweet . at the end is a nice hint of the wood . the finish is wood and alcohol . overall , this was ok. its very similar to the utopias to me .  m- thin and smooth with almost not carbonation feel . kind of has the texture of a flat soda .
poured in my struise glass the beer has an enormous white head and a nice yellow fluid with lots of carbonation going on .  m - a little on the thin side .

smell : sweet fruit like berries , pear , and some citrus orange . strong spiciness not sure what kind of spices , maybe coriander . a bit musty , but in a good way , as it warms up it starts to smell like bread dough . overall : pretty good drinkability , the appearance is really disappointing , but the ( more important ) smell and taste are great !  m- light in body and light to medium in carbonation .
aroma is whoa grapefruit ! nice brew , maybe a bit over the top , but for an anniversary brew , you do what you have to .  medium bodied and a bit sticky in the mouth .

the smell is bright and strong . lots of clover but also a healthy dose of lemon and banana . it is a quintessential hefeweizen smell . the body is a bit weak .  mouthfeel : thin body and medium carbonation overall : a nice geuze , a bit too watery for my liking though .

really good . t : milder than the smell , with a taste of mostly apples and cider , creamy caramel , and a mild woody gin finish .  mouthfeel is a bit light , to me , for the style , though it seems appropriate for the flavors that this beer brings to the palate .
wonderful aroma . warm and oaky , molasses . almost get a bbq sauce scent , very spicey like a worcester sauce . very interesting tastes in this one , unusual .  mouthfeel : medium bodied .

mbc 's big jamoke pours up with a modest carbonation that creates a very creamy beige-khaki brown head that encompasses the very dark brown-mahogany body .  thin bodied , and just sufficient carbonation , but i suspect the growler is at fault much more than the beer .
smell - very nice . i definitely get the grapefruit , and the citrus , although there is something almost astringent lingering .  m honestly its way too light of a mouthfeel .

nose is a great baltic porter , tons of dark roasty malts , lots of chocolate , some coffee , dark syrupy molasses and brown sugar , caramel , vanilla , baker 's chocolate , cocoa nibs , light chewy oats , just a hint of earthy hops i think . taste starts with lots of roasted malts , again chocolate , baker 's and cocoa nibs , bit of burnt coffee , some oats and creamy malts , fairly creamy , some vanilla and caramel , light syrupy flavors , a bit boozy . overall decent , it has a great nose , and some good flavors but missing the body , a bit boozy , and it just feels watery and flat .  a little too thick on the tongue , but nice .

smell : the aroma is very good . lots of cinnamon , nutmeg , and all spice combine with the pumpkin to give a nice pumpkin-forward aroma . overall : the aroma is by far the best part about this beer .  the mouthfeel has average carbonation and ismedium bodied yet feels a bit thin at the same time , as it falls off the toungue quite quickly .
deep brown pour with a gigantic , rocky , tan head .  mouthfeel is sticky-sweet and dense .

avery mephisopheles ' stout pours a brownish-black with a half inch thick , smooth , foamy , brown head . head retention is excellent and lacing is thin , yet consistent .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with likely carbonation . that , and the over carbonated pour make this beer a something i would not recommend .

beautiful smell of bourbon it 's you first then caramel , vanilla , and a hint of oak .  a fairly light bodied beer with near champagne carbonation ... a bit too much for me , although i know many like this in their wild ales .

this stuff truly smells delicious . t - in taste it lacks the hop punch one would expect from the nose .  mouthfeel is pretty average , as is the smell ... i ca n't think of anything distinctive about these characteristics .

a - black as night with a thick frothy brown head . fades slowly leaving a thin solid layer of foam on the beer with excellent lacing .  lighter body than i thought it would be with with very low carbonation..the weakest point of the brew . easy drinker for the abv and ignoring the mouth feel , a nice brew .
great lacing that lined the entire glass . cloudy .  the body is thin and slightly anemic . a little more carbonation and body would carry this really unique beer into the stratosphere .

pours a deep , rich plummy color topped by a lively head of sloppy , sticky looking foam . this has a very healthy head that sticks around and laces majestically .  a bit thin , but a very good stout flavor develops in the mouth . i 'd have preferred a bit fuller body .

poured into my pint glass the beer is dark chocolate brown bordering on black . the dark mocha head bursts to full three fingers and flirts with going over the top edge of my glass . after a brief rest the head fades leaving a small cap and no lace .  the mouthfeel was thin with a slightly dry aftertaste .
very enjoyable smell , roasted coffee , chocolate , combined with a truffle like fruitiness . the alcoholic notes get more and more present , and totally unbalanced .  body is a little thin .
pours a fluffy/clingy finger and a half light tan head over a crystal clear dark rust brownish liquid .  mouthfeel : pretty thick and a little syrupy . i 'd actually like a little more carbonation .

exceptional aroma , not alot of ipas can match this , very floral and unique , with grapefruit and mango front , notes of apricot , lemons and lychee streaking through at times . brilliant nose , could smell it all day . turned out to be a rather balanced ipa , the nose was so great it would be hard to match on the flavor as well . if you can get this one fresh it 's absolutely worth it and the nose is unique even amongst the ever growing masses of ipas .  the taste is fantastic , but the beer is a little thin and a bit hot ; not a good session beer , but great type of brew to have after a long day .

very sweet , but extremely complex . awesome . taste is intense sourness and bitterness , which tapers off to not much else .  this beer was purchased at cyclone liquors , in ames , iowa . the beer was very dark in color and tasted very well . i drank the beer warm and i think it was a good beer . i would try this beer again if it was presented to me . it had a very nice sweet taste for a german dunkel , which i am not a huge fan of .
this beer pours exceptionally well for a three finger thick cranium in a light tan color .  mouthfeel is rather thin and average .
this beer has an amazing champagne look . it has a crystal clear brass body with damn near perfect white head and lace .  too carbonated , the mouthful of liquid seems to almost crumble right away .
smell is dark fruit , roasted malts , vanilla , oak , and a touch of coffee/chocolate .  m : i feel that this could have used a little more body and less carbonation , but overall ... not bad .

pours a cloudy dark reddish color with bright fluffy white head , great thick malty aroma . has a nice malt beginning to the flavor but is very thin after that .  mouthfeel - a bit too carbonated which overrides the wonderful taste at first .
smell- very fresh malts give a whiff of roast , toast , and even some plums .  mouthfeel is grainy and oily , body is medium to thin , carbonation is sharp .

the beer has massive yeasty bready smells . the beer has a very good combination of fruity ( apples , grapes , pears , plums ) jelly smells . oddly enough the smells of this beer bring back memories of my grandmothers kitchen smell .  m light body for the style , but not unpleasant .

refreshing , quite complex , and just the right temperate on the citrus .  being from the adirondacks i quickly likened this to adirondack brewery 's bear naked ale , yet a lager version , and a bit more wheat-filled . the mouth-feel is nice , but nothing special ( not flat , not too bubbly ) . in short , its a dandy brew- we all enjoyed it and thought it was pretty cool to have something that is only currently available in growlers from the brewery ( spring seasonal ) , drink up !
appearance : nice maple syrup/caramel bronze , it matched really well with the polished bronze colored bar where i was sitting .  this one was surprisingly thin in body .

on tap at iron hill north wales , pa . served in a pint glass ... a - jet black with a 1 finger mocha head brought out to me . the head was unbelievably thick with amazing lacing that coated the entire glass .  the mouthfeel was medium with a syrupy sweetness on the palate .

the aroma of berry funk with a hint of crust that smells delicious . the appearance is rich pinot wine color with a white head and tons of berry sediment floating on top .  the mouthfeel i found oddly watery ... but still fairly full bodied at the same time . carbonation was fairly mild - maybe that lended to the `` watery '' sensation .
acidic and fruity nose . fun berry aromas . the nose was the best part of this beer .  m : full bodied and creamy , the slightest touch of carbonation and a smooth , somewhat watery finish .
a : deep brown with a nice fluffy tan head . 2-fingers to start , slowly receding . perfect .  good carbonation , which i appreciate . minimal complexity to this beer .

delicious smelling ! t- tart , slightly sweet with more ale grains in the taste . decent , but i was expecting more fruits in my mouth .  m. thin to medium body with a somewhat biting carbonation . ends fairly dry .

citrus notes are bright and festive in the nose , enticing . t : the nose is somewhat deceiving , this is a bitter bomb .  hate to say it , but the bottle/case i have is absolutely awful . other than a hint of coriander spice all i got was an overwelming sourness that made this one of the few i had to pour down the drain . they obviously put wayyy too much orange peel in their mix . if you can get past the sourness it is par for a wit bier course . i 'm hoping this was a bad/expired batch because ... .as far as mill street goes imo , stick to the coffee porter ...

pours a big white head that takes up half a tulip glass , then settles to a half inch of meringue . body is dark yellow with some wit-like cloudiness .  it was pretty smooth for stout and for for the alcohol content . i tried it with a few other beers .

it smells great . t : the taste didnt exactly match the smell but the taste was good too .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied with thankfully a burst of carbonation near the end , making it a little less watery than it initially presents itself to be .
awesome retention .  the mouthfeel is thinner when compared with other stouts , merely decent .
intense sweet banana scent . very full bodied aroma .  low carbonation . a bit coating , but not to syrupy/thick .

smells like sweet vanilla milk , caramel and butterscotch tastes like sweet vanilla milk , caramel and butterscotch . very sweet , pretty good .  mouth feel is sharp and crisp , with a high carbonation level .

the smell was slightly chocolate . 2007 bottle 02/23/2008 beautiful smell like gourmet chocolates , an amazing improvement over the last year . this beer is a really good example of a cellar-worthy beer . 2006 vintage 01/10/09 smells malty grains , some chocolate , tastes good and probably ca n't get much better .  perhaps a bit thin for the style , which i suppose makes it a good pale ale for summertime quaffing .

s- awesome char smell with chocolate and roasted coffee , and supported by a rich dark fruit sweetness . hoppy bitterness is a fantastic undertone . m- nice smooth mouthfeel .  slinky and a little thin , but ok .

s : chocolate , peanut , fruit , raisin . rich , but it took me a while to pinpoint exactly what this reminded me of , then it hit me - hazelnut !  it pains me to trash a beer , but this brewery needs a swift kick in the pants . i ordered this to give the brewery a second chance , since the white cloud ale i had the day before was patently awful . after a couple sips , i took it back to the bar and told the bartender , saying i wanted to try the local beer , but could n't drink it . no lager is intended to be a sour beer . he added that it 's sort of an acquired taste , but happily replaced it with a real beer . i could n't finish either of these sour beers ( and not like it 's brewed intentionally with brett ) . whoever the new guy is , he needs to clean up the brewery and get back to basics with brewing .

the smell- incredible . at first , very sweet smelling- hints of pineapple . for such a strong beer , it finishes very abruptly , leaving you with just a tad of malt . overall , incredible .  mouthfeel : i 've always thought this was a little off ... not quite enough spine to offset the sweetness .

a little swirl allows a bit of malt to show up , which smells simple enough .  i could drink this one all night long . just the right amount of sweetness with a little more than expected carbonation . pale yellow in color , lemony aroma.very clean with little aftertaste . easy to drink and very enjoyable . will definately drink again .
beautiful floral hop aroma ... with maybe a touch of spice .  m & # 8211 ; thin , refreshing , light , plentiful , smooth carbonation .

appearance : deep , rich , amber red . poured semi-aggressively to yield 2 fingers of nice , tan , creamy head which started to reveal some interesting pitting after a bit . moderate lacing .  the beer feels just a bit thin on the tongue .

smell is very appealing indeed : very fresh , clear orange , a bit banana , defenate floral hoppyness , and also some spicyness/clove .  mouthfeel : a little slick , thinner on the palate than i expected drinkability : a fine porter , would definitely drink again .
wonderful aroma of coffee , milk and bitter chocolate , and a touch of smoke .  body is on the thin side of medium and the finish is both mildly astringent and slightly bitter .

really delicious smell t : very tannic finish ... almost too much . not as sour as the smell suggests , but very nice . lots of flavor going on !  mouthfeel is a little thin and alcoholic with low carbonation . overall this beer has a nice balance of flavours but i feel the barrel presence is a little bit too subtle and the mouthfeel a bit too thin to prevent a higher score .

a- a dense golden/honey color . a nice spongy two finger head with great lacing to the end .  mf : the carbonation is n't quite as spritzy as i would hope to go along with the huge sourness , the body is light d : this is a great lambic .
a : dark brown and reds blend into an opaque liquid topped by 4 fingers of off white head that paints the glass all the way until the end . a beautiful beer .  m- low carbonation , medium-body .

s : a typical fff piney , citrus hop parade hits you strong up front , with delicious burnt cocoa , cinnamon , and brown sugar following . an epic nose that promises much . t : unfortunately , the nose can not keep it 's promise . there is still some malt left underneath , but it is just not coming through like it does in the nose . as a huge fan of toasty porters and stouts , it ; 's kind of a let down for me .  the beer is somewhat oxidized , but still highly drinkable very light bodied bitter , true to the the style . this is a prime candidate for a session beer . at 3.8 % abv , it 's alcohol content makes this a clear choice for something that could literally be consumed all day long , starting with your pancakes !

wow , the pour results in an inch thick head and a nice burned orange body . the lacing left behind is like an intricate work of art .  mouthfeel - this seems a bit watery for my liking , and a bit light too , it does n't take away from the beer too much though luckily , still great . the carbonation seems pretty good , maybe a bit overcarbonated .

( s ) - plenty of rich molasses & raisin with an even richer vanilla & whiskey-like smokiness . ( t ) - just like the smell with a pronounced raisin & cocoa profile .  m - not as thick as i 'd like it to taste considering how rich the smell is . d - very drinkable , with the lighter mouthfeel it 's easier to forget how much you 've had .

while really good , not as good as aroma . overall : really good . would have liked the flavor to measure up to the aroma but you still ca n't go wrong with this one .  m- seems a little thin , but nicely carbonated .

aroma is a sweet malt-candy smell , bready , with a note of ginger and sourness . this beer tastes almost as good as it smells .  the carbonation is unfortunately at a distracting level , but the feel is strong enough otherwise to not hurt too much overall .
as the beer was going down in the glass , it left an incredible , thick creamy lacing all over the glass . appearance was pretty cloudy , light copper color .  pretty average mouthfeel overall .
smells and looks like a hefeweizen . tastes banana , tropical . citric . extremely refreshing , great summer beer .  mouthfeel : the carbonation is light , as is the body .
aroma is brilliant and vibrant , full of citrus hops and apricot . nice .  very light bodied , but carbonation seems too low to me .
aroma was an incredible with scents of spicy dark bread .  the carbonation is moderate high . i think it is a bit high for the style but the carbonation does not take anything away from the beer .

pour revelaed an extremely thick and long lasting creamy white head.as it reduced it left rings of lace in the glass.the color presented was orange and somewhat cloudy.mouthfeel wasnt very crisp and seemed a bit watery.the finish left a sharp sweet or tart twist that dissapeared real quick.a bit bitter in the back of the throat with a wheaty grain taste.a spicy aroma thats not too strong but is there.tastes of oranges , lemon , cloves , corriander , and honey are noted.overall good with a medium body .  in my opinion , flying dog brewery has created a great seasonal , smooth-tasting beer with very little bite or after taste . i would definitely recommend it to any self-respecting beer drinker who might be having an end-of-summer party this or any october .

nice copper color smell : could totally smell those pumpkin pie spices . nice !  good carbonation and medium bodied . flavor is spicy , yeasty , hints of sweetness that gets buried by the yeast . lingering yeasty aftertaste .
the beer looks great ! s : i get some notes of honey , grass , caramel , and light seasonal summer fruit .  m : flat , slick , and that 's it . not quite watery , but pretty close .
this beer was a very nice , deep red/brown color , and it had a very nice and thick head .  it was a little thin .
i can also catch a slight nose of peaty scotch if i catch it the right way . fantastic aroma here .  3.0 m : medium body . smooth , but not creamy .

22 oz bottle poured into imperial pint glass a - pours a near black opaqueness with a large 2 inch tan colored head . a good looking beer .  mouthfeel : both the carbonation and body are on the higher end of the light range .

the first smell i picked up on was tropical fruit smells , including banana and something else ( ca n't put my nose on it ) . there was also a spiciness , and sort of a leatheryness , and a slight maltyness that i find typical of most belgians and pilsners ( pilsner malt ? there was a lot going on in the aroma , which makes me want to revisit this beer and think it through more carefully .  mouthfeel is quite viscous , with not a lot of texture . feels full and a bit flat . could use more carbonation to cut through the smokey flavour more .

smells amazing , like the normal version with some oak and bourbon . the smell was amazing to me . i thought the taste was a bit hotter than the normal irs , but that 's to be expected .  m : feels alright . average .

brilliantly clear , tawny copper hue . pitted , steadfast ivory white head . persistent , massed lace trails .  my first tripel style beer , i spit it on my counter . the flavors of fruit combined with a bitter aftertaste left one bottle down the drain , and three still sitting in their case . anyone near me is welcome to the other three . while i am confident in the quality of this product , this style is definitely not for me .

bourbon colored with an excellent 3 finger head that rises a good 1/4 inch above the glass . very foamy head that last a long , long time .  the drawback on this beer is the carbonation - it 's too heavy . sparkly but with a nice dryness in the finish .

crazy amount of hops , smells awesome . t - tastes of citrus hops , pine , grapefruit , smooth fruity malts . d - this is definitely a very good black ipa .  the nose is caramely and very malty . a little too carbinated for a traditional barleywine but lines ones gut like the best of the bunch ! being a sucker for barleywines i have to give this beer high remarks .
looks like a magazine beer ad . beautiful clear , light , orange-amber color .  body is light and the carbonation is lively , a bit too much for my preferences .

s : smells delicious . tart fruit all over the place . fairly satisfying . m : huge carbonation level makes it just a tad unpleasant , but not so much so that i dont still enjoy the beer overall .  but there are hints of dark fruits that seem to disintegrate on your tongue , slight astringent alcohol tate/smelll this is defiantly a very drinkable brew .

sweet malts , wheat , maple syrup , and barrel aged booze in the nose . wheat & sweet malts with a hoppy backbone . boozy on the way down , leaving your throat tingly .  while the champagne-like extreme dryness may put off some , i think it makes the beer truly unique and tasty as opposed to unblanced .

huge smell of prunes , chocolate , a hint of molasses and some licorice . has that belgian `` funk '' as i call it . i do n't care , smells great ! deep rich chocolate and molasses covered prunes . this is a brew that has been blessed by the gods . there are hints of mint and licorice along side with a hint of anise and some bitter chocolate . a+ taste ! omg this beer makes me want to guzzle , but i think twice and enjoy each and every sip .  and this is a surprisingly warming , earthy-tasting beverage for a `` summer ale '' -- i would n't mind opening up one of these in midwinter either , except in that it lacks body . it 's in the mouthfeel that the summeriness stands out .

under all of this , i can still smell some gumball and barnyard odors . an amazing smell and likely a very unique one . t - more grapefruit pith and that same pine , but i still ca n't figure it out .  medium bodied with carbonation that was a little too high and too coarse for my liking , but it did n't turn me off completely . my only issue was the carbonation .
the smell dances on the nose , full of floral and hops .  the mouthfeel was a little on the watery side but i did n't feel like it ruined the experience .

750ml corked bottle poured into a tulip glass . ( a ) - pours a hazy golden yellow color that produced a huge 2+finger fluffy white head with fantastic retention . it is sticking to the glass in webs as it dissipated .  m - a little thin-bodied and watery and a little low on the carbonation .

aroma is fabulous , even at this temperature . delicious . well worth the $ 6 canadian that i paid for it .  ran into the maui brewing company while killing time until our dinner reservations were ready . there was a very slight bitterness in the aftertaste but was well hidden in the passion fruit sweetness . found the beer to start like any average golden ale but the aftertaste was what i really liked about it sorta like an ice tea aftertaste .

a - a very light straw color with great clarity and a large , thick white head . perfect . this looks tame like a corona but has loads of complexity .  the beer seems to thin a bit in the mouthfeel . very clean beer for a triple , slightly thin in the mouthfeel , but that helps give this beer a nice clean dry finish .

the first thing that struck me about this stout was the aroma , very complex , almost sweet , with what i thought could have been vanilla among other things . the # 1 surprise was the texture and consistency of this beer , i was expecting something much thicker , more like guiness , and boy was i surprised , a much smoother , lighter consistency with a great taste and just enough flavor to let you know you are drinking something quality without being over whelming . it took me more time to get a good overall sense of this stout then i would have expected , a compliment to the complexity of the flavor .  lowish carbonation and a slightly thin mouthfeel .
pours from the bottle to a reddish orange with medium off-white head that lingers , and excellent lacing .  toward the end of the drink , the beer felt almost flat .
s- malt . candied sweetness . chocolate with a touch of vanilla .  smooth and to the point , bit of a sweet aftertaste in the sweet sticky beer way .

this one gushed out an extremely creamy , frothy off-white head with a suprisingly long and stable retention . the bottom was also very appealing , golden orange-yellow hue that was opaque and reflective .  light , decently carbonated , and quenching for the desert dweller .

glorious aroma of silky dark chocolate and dark-roast coffee beans . very pleasant . the dry , slightly acidic roasty finish leads well into another sip .  it also takes a hit because while it looks thick , it feels a bit thinner than it should be .
the aroma is wonderfully pungent . other than the presence of ginger , the only thing i was n't smelling was an evergreen tree .  m : thinner and crisper .
s - smell is terrific and pops way more than a lot of nitro beers i 've had .  m - this is the weakest part of the beer . medium body with a little too much carbonation .

a : fantastic clarity , golden , and a relentless head , a 3 millimeter head is still visible after 20 minutes , leaving rings of lace in its wake .  the carbonation is nice throughout . thinner than expected also .

smell was outstanding . malts , and dried fruits , raisins , prunes , etc , very complex and really builds the base for the beer . very , very nice . no bitterness to speak of and a lingering toffee sweetness at the end . overall an excellent doppelbock , right up there in my top 3 .  the overall feel is dry , like it should be , but unfortunately , it 's also a touch chaulky , which is pretty unfortunate .
appearance is dark brown/red , with a tan pancake head and nice lacing .  m-a bit watery for my tastes but the taste makes you forget about it being slightly thin .

s - very pronounced chocolate aromas , backed by roasted malts , some earthy , pine hops and a touch of coffee as it warms t - follows the nose , with the hop character very subtle , and the coffee barely making a presence as it warms .  mouthfeel : the body is oddly thin , and crisp .
very enjoyable . taste is a little harsh , the sweetness takes a vegetable turn .  nothing special here .
wonderful caramel , butterscotch aroma with a delicate spiceness .  m- thin to medium in body . highly attenuated with a soft carbonation .

an amazingly rich and creamy nose with strong aromas of toffee , cream , and roasted marshmallows . body is very good . drinkability : whatever hesitancy i had after seeing how it looked following the pour were overcome by the amazing aroma . a solid , flavorful drink that i would kill to try on cask .  medium bodied and dry .

aroma is complex , vinous , hay-ish with hints of scotch or cognac , appealing old cereals past their prime complements sweet caramelic malt . it smells old malt basically . taste is on the sweet side , lots of toffee/maple flavours with honest hints at wood and resin . very vinous , but certainly less intense than the beautiful aroma . once the yeast comes into play , it becomes drier , earthy with a dirty waters feel .  4.5/5 m : crisp , medium body .
really enjoyable . t : sweet malts and slight hop bitterness .  carbonation seems spot on .

smell is strongly sweet & sugary , with citric , woody hop presence . interesting & complex but sweeter than i prefer .  a malty mouthful without much carbonation . resiny flavors fill the mouth but do n't obscure the big malt . this one is quite drinkable with an interesting mix of flavors that rise out of the basic malty sweetness .

pours crystal clear orange-amber color with a dense 2 finger off white head with great retention that reduces to a fairly thick lacing cap that lasts the entire glass .  nice floral hops and malt starchiness in the finish . it 's a drinkable beer . heavy in the stomach .

appearance - pours dark enough to block out all light . a big bubbled mocha head springs up and i have to quell the pour a bit to calm things down . it caps off and forms a nice creamy cover with large spacious bubbles of foam below it .  mouthfeel was week and its not complex at all .

the aroma is like a fresh hop cone very nice . from what you expect with the aroma is a slight let down but that said it is nice . the taste malty to start the taste turns to a earthy hop flavor .  mouf & gt ; nice , nothing special drinkability & gt ; sure thing

it has a pleasantly pungent , complex smell . all sorts of flower and herbal along with some mint .  if you aerate the beer in your mouth , it really releases the co2 . it would do well as a beer to server with medium to strong cheese .
pours a beautiful deep dark brown with a nice big everlasting tan head .  a little lighter and less sweet than many `` real '' belgian beers , and a little thinner in the mouthfeel department .
s : smell of yeast and coriander that gives way to banana . t : taste not as complex as the smell , but still pleasing .  mouthfeel was fine but that doesnt make up for much .
great chocolate smell as soon as the cap came off , smelled just like a candy bar .  m - crisp and bitey , high carbonation - the bottle overflowed when i opened it .

smell is full of strong c type hops . strong pine and grapefruit with some cinnamon in there . cedar wood and a little hay scent . faint pineapple smell .  parching on the tongue . almost no flavor : slight sweetness up front , trace of bitterness on finish . really .
s : a very rich banana/clove mix , just about perfect . no hops , no nothing .  light bodied .

this beer smells amazing . t : very roasty , lots of coffee , lots of chocolate , some sweetness in the background .  on tap this poured as a golden straw colored ale , clear and bright with less than an inch of head . there is an apparent hoppy aroma that followed with a similarly dominant slight-hoppy taste followed by the expected bitters - very tasty . i stopped with one . not to discount its drink-ability , there are just several others i wish to try .

smells good too , obvious floral hops and substantial bready slightly sweet malt , both of which hit at the same time . this review is probably going to come out higher than it should due to the deceptively good appearance and smell .  m_on the lighter side with a bit too much carbonation . the carbonation is along the lines of a tripel which is a bit too much for the style . d_the light body while a flaw style wise make this fairly easy to drink .

t - while the aroma is astounding , the taste does not do the aroma justice . it 's one of my top 5 ipa 's , i 'd say , but compared to the outstanding aroma , the taste is considerably less in amplitude .  m - a little thin , sickly-sweet finish .

gorgeous dark burgendy like ribena syrup . redy brown highlights , good head retention but minimal lace .  fairly thin and smooth , mild to medium bodied . breckenridge definitely delivers a vanilla porter as i would expect a vanilla flavored porter to be . i suggest toning down the roasted barley and focusing more on bittering hops .

the aroma was like a big hop garden bouquet with a little sugared pixie dust spread all over . i was ready for the taste and ready to be blown away , but was not .  mouthfeel can be too fizzy if you do n't make sure to pour high for tall head . when i 'm drinking more than one beer , this is my favorite second or third , as it 's got enough hops to satisfy , is not highly alcoholic , and sells for a real good price where i live .
pours a near black with a khaki colored that head that shows great retention and lots of body .  m : not too bad , there was a little bit of body .

nose is fantastic ! uniquely fruity , like a cranberry-mango chutney . hops are detectable and make this a complex sniffer , probably the best smelling tripel i have ever laid nostrils upon . fruit levels take on the best from belgium , impressive . very nice brew , might be my favorite that i have had so far from the bruery .  the only thing that could be improved on this beer is the mouthfeel . a bit light for my tastes , but like i said it has incredible drinkability without making you get too full too quick .

very nice . taste & mouthfeel : drier than the aroma suggests .  actually thought it might be bad but when i drank it there was plenty of carbonation . smell : a toasted malty smell with an almost cardboard smell . taste : very strong toasted smell but more of a bitterness then a sweetness . note : no date on the bottle but wondering if this beer had gone bad . will try another attempt at it but not really looking forward to it .

smell is incredible : pure piney , grapefruity hops with a veneer of rich malt . and that in itself is amazing ! finishes like an unsweetened soda .  lighter mouthfeel than expected . d - full flavor and light mouthfeel .
dark brown/black body with a dense chocolaty head . a thick cap remained throughout .  m - moderate carbonation , medium bodied .

pours a tad darker than the regular irs ... as noted by the darker head . has a nice finger of head that dies quicker than the regular .  mouthfeel works just fine , but is a little watery . highly drinkable .

the `` flaws '' in the smell work better in the taste , at least . it 's a good flavor , but it feels to me like the flavors need to stand out more . this beer smells awesome , but taste-wise it falls a bit short .  the huge head tipped me off and my first taste confirmed that this beer was infected . as a homebrewer , i 'm sure to sample every beer i brew before i give it to a friend . a little qc goes a long way .

very alluring aromatically , strong bakery smell , quite yeasty , some wheat a little bit of sweet and citrus thrown in .  mouthfeel is smooth , crisp and almost watery , with medium carbonation and a medium body .

pours from 21 oz bottle to pint glass , a deep , dark , caramel-color with a straw colored two-finger head that seems to grow with time rather than dissipate . frothy lace definitely persists .  the mouthfeel was quite thin with a very fine and mild carbonation .

bottle : poured a bright golden yellow with a super huge pure white foamy head with great retention and super good lacing .  m - light bodied , not overly carbonated , clean finish , mild fruity aftertaste fades quickly .

pours out a slightly chill-hazed brassy tangerine with a wealth of tiny bubbles making their way to the head . head is massive , foamy , and almost spills over the top . leaves some near solid lacing on the glass .  nice chewy mouthfeel , but significantly under-carbonated . the only thing it lacks is carbonation and a decent head .

the smell is amazing , strong coffee aroma , more so than any other coffee stout i 've had , easily the best aspect of this stout . the taste is a bit more reserved with the coffee as it 's hard to beat the strong aroma , but there is a good deal of coffee and roasted malt , hint of chocolate , and a decent bitterness in the end .  m : standard mouthfeel for a low alcohol ale .
smells great ! t-hmmm this is a fairly complex beer , which is surprising coming from abita .  mouthfeel : medium and semi-smooth . bottom line : this is one of the most bland beers i 've ever had .

pours a rich black midnight color with a soft tan head and lacing . moderate viscosity . good head retention and lacing through out the tasting .  it states `` the deep coffee flavors are created naturally during the brewing process by dark roasted malts . '' then later it notes `` stout brewed with coffee . anyway , i 'll refer to this as a steady drinking stout because of its thinness , otherwise it 's pretty enjoyable . not particulary complex but enjoyable taste of roasted malt with coffee . abv seems pretty low as i had two with no noticable effects .

big fluffy two finger head that wafts the hop aromas well , tons of lace and excellent carbonation . color is a kind of murky dark amber . smells great . i love it , the quintessential california hop heaven . tons of grapefruit cascade , melon , guava , apples , cherries- all with a subtle fresh-cut woodsy pine backbone and soothing aroma of fresh mountain air .  the mouthfeel was medium bodied with adequate carbonation .

smells of strong peat , as you 'd expect with the name `` islay '' , but there is nice chocolate and roast balance . sweet flavour actually . very creamy mouthfeel , very sweet .  it is light bodied and enjoyable . it has a light hops aroma and a light bodied feel to it .

so dark you could hide a black sheep in it . cute labeling , special bottle , and usda organic slapped on it make it stick out yet it yields something akin to canadian made guinness .  a watery texture and lighter body than i expected from the nose , with a moderate amount of carbonation .

damm , skippy , now thats what a stout should look like ! deep , cream black pour . an absolutely beautiful , thick and fluffy brown head , clings to the side of the glass endlessly .  this is about my only complaint of this beer-too much carbonation ! carbonation gives a foamy/frothy mouthfeel .

s : brown sugar , molasses , caramel , dark rum , raisins , and a little toasted malt . t : this is nothing but sweetness and malt in your face . it 's a slow sipper , which means i ca n't handle more than one bottle in a sitting , and it 's just too damn cloying to take even that .  overall , i quite enjoyed this beer . it 's got a fresh and interesting taste that makes it a decent drinking beer . deliciously fruity hops , nice malt sweetness , comes across as quite fresh . noticeable taste of apricots which i quite like makes this distinctive and something i look forward to drinking . disappointing finish however . lots of interesting things happening up front and then nada . nothing really lingers which is a darn shame , 'cause overall this beer is well worth a try . still tasty after each bottle . mmmm .
as pretty as beer poured out of a can into a glass can be .  mouthfeel is just a tad watery .

awesome aroma . on the buds , some more bong resin , pineapple and rind characteristics . the bitterness is fairly clean and enjoyable . underneath all the hop activities lies an unassuming caramel and toffee base .  long , super bitter piney bitterness , aftertaste almost of pine-sol but i love the hop attack . problem is that it 's too sweet and slightly syrupy , especially evident in the middle . a little harsh and unbalanced overall , big beer and it shows .

this smell is really on the money and superbly enjoyable . tasted honey sweet with dark malts and dark fruits that fades into a smoky birch bark and a really dirty lime or rhubarb sourness .  m - medium body , with moderate to high carbonation . a bit too carbonated for my liking . slightly thin , would like a bigger body from a stout . the mouthfeel is lacking , and sweet flavors of vanilla and chocolate make it too much like a dessert beer , one is all you need .
the aroma is great . lots of citrus and pine notes . overall a very good and strong ipa ( 9 % ) .  mouthfeel : body is light to medium and slightly watery .

( s ) - a ridiculously rich aroma . awesome whiffs of oaky bourbon with sweet toffee and caramel with an even more glorious smell of cocoa covered dark cherries behind it . its strong , but smells really stinking good .  the mouthfeel is just a little light and watery .
pours a very dark brown , black in the glass , with a nice tan head that maintains down the glass . excellent rings of lacing .  the mouthfeel is a bit weird ; kind of a harshness on the tongue .
very pleasant aroma . i may have picked up some caramel in the flavor as well as some sharp citrus aspects and some sweetness .  the mouthfeel is a little on the thin and watery side though .

nose : chocolate and caramel , some fruit notes like plums , brown sugar . quite sweet smelling , marshmallow and milk chocolate . nice roasted malt character as well , a bit of burnt toast , a bit coffee .  even with the earthy malt flavor , the overall feel stays on the thin side .

smell is grainy , nectarine and dried apricot frutiness , caramel , leather , damp earth . very little alcohol noticeable . overall the nose on this is great ! slightly fruity , caramel sweetness , subtle amounts of cedar and tobacco .  5/5 m : medium body and smooth . the lighter body makes it sit not-too-heavy , and it would be easy to partake of a few of these on a cold night .

the smell is very nice . lots of tropical fruit flavor on this one and sweet candy .  m : crisp and a very smooth , medium body , medium carbonation , finish is slightly sticky . tad too thin for my liking , but not too bad .

aroma of roast , ash , chocolate , dried fruits , vanilla , bourbon , caramel malts , and alcohol . taste of dark fruit , some tropical , sticky molasses , roasted malts , vanilla , and bourbon - alcohol .  lightly bodied , perhaps overly so , with a passably dextrinous mouthfeel .

s- smells like autumn . upfront you get a nice whiff of pumpkin and spices . the rum creates a perfect blend here . adds a great alcoholic sweetness to the aroma . t- after the aroma , i ca n't help think that this was a let down . the blandness actually intensified as the beer warmed .  m : hmmm . it may be a tad too aggressive with the carbonation .
very fresh and clean smell , hardly any yeast aroma .  m : medium-bodied , creamy , resiny , thin finish .

s - bitter coffee , good coffee smell . this is disappointing . the nose is really good , but you do n't get much of that coffee on the tongue .  m- the mouthfeel is a little lighter than expected , almost watered down .

appearance this oatmeal stout was almost black with a monster head that just blew up on contact with the glass . it was dark tan and left some good lacing .  solid mouthfeel , nothing noteworthy , but nothing wrong with it .
pours deep burgundy/ with 3 fingers+ of sand/tan colored head . superior lacing & head retention s : chocolate & coffee ( ?  m- just average .
one of the darkest black beers i have ever seen . the only one that compares off the top of my head is dark lord .  m : smooth on the palate .

* subtle but complex aromas of dark chocolate , ripe cherries , sour fruits , currants , figs , beer bread and burnt sugar . taste is not as complex as the smell , and almost underwhelming with more dark chocolate notes , unripened dark fruits ( plums , grapes ) grain and yeast .  mouthfeel is a bit lacking . this is not a full-bodied beer , as i would prefer , but the carbonation level is to my liking for a barley wine drinkability is very good for a big beer .
the smell was light , floral and fruity ; i almost imagined it apricot if i had n't known it was raspberry .  body is very thin for a dipa , medium carbonation .

probably the best smelling brown ale i 've experienced yet . t- almost porter-like at first , with up-front dark malt , lots of nuttiness , a bit of dark roasted grain , and a slightly metallic finish .  m : surprisingly on the more carbonated side with a slight fizzy mouthfeel .

appearance : very much a rich dark brown color that lets no light through . great measure of head .  i first had this beer a year ago and fell in love . so i was excited to see it appear once again this fall . i find it a very easy beer to drink even for the inexperienced beer drinker . flavorful and rich with malts , a slight hint of hops towards the end . the aroma is sweet but not overpowering , you can definitely smell the sweet malt that went into this brew . i highly recommend this beer . unfortunately its not around year round but it definitely will give you something to look forward to come fall .

a light orangey hue , spewing forth grapefruit and mango goodness with a slight bit of malt . a nice bitter , touch of sweetness and plenty of citrus fruit . pretty tasty , nothing to go too wild over , but enjoyable nonetheless .  m : decent mouthfell , it has to have this considering how light it is .

smell is very sexy - pure belgian goodness . taste is very good . this beer is very drinkable . each sip is very nice as you get a great whif of that aroma . belgian yeast is very impressive - the unique flavor qualities never get old ; they are very subtle .  quite watery for the big flavor this one tastes and smells different from the main stream craft ipas , which is a pretty new category i 'll give it that .

aroma is amazing - brandy , caramel , brown sugar , dark fruits , vanilla , and oak . bummer i 'll probably never have it again , as rare as it is .  a light- to moderate mouthfeel , hints of sour flavor linger at the back of the tongue after the swallow . i do n't pick up much of a hint of carbonation in the mouthfeel .

thanks to nate for bringing this , bottle into a bells tulip ... pours an ugly light brown , muddled , with no carbonation at all ... the aroma is awesome , lots of vanilla , really nice wood notes , a little bourbon , caramel , and a touch of hops ... as great as the aroma is the tasting is as outstandingly awful .  m : light body , watery touch , smooth with low carbonated in the mouth .
sweet and tart raspberries , this is fun to smell ! very nice .  the mouthfeel is just a touch too syrupy , though it does n't detract much at all from the enjoyment of the beer .
bottle poured cloudy amber large white head that lasts thru the whole experiance .  first sip reveals a much thinner body than i expected and average carbonation .

pours an opaque darkness with a huge stiff dark brown head that decomposes like an ice cream sundae , massive 3d lacing present .  m : the honey seems to add a little body to this , but other than that , just average .

s - strong citrus and pine/juniper nose on it . very fragrant making you expect a delicious taste to follow . m - lots of bitter tangy sensation at the back of the tongue following a few sips , but strangely lite and unsatisfying . d - decent drinkability , but not exceptional . it 's a strange beer : starts off great with an impressive hops-laden nose , but then does n't really delivery .  this beer pours with a very pale yellow body topped by a medium thick head with some lacing left behind . not much flavor or aroma but more than you get from most light beers . the aroma was sour and bitter and the flavor was malty with a hint of bitter hoppiness .
t : bit of a let dowm after this promising smell . orange , citrus , grains and a little hops .  mouthfeel : a bit thin and watery .
s : sweet dark frut nose come out followed by a chocolate toasted malt . on second whiff i am reminded of chocolate covered cheries .  mouthfeel - smooth , yet a litle effervescent .

s - the first thing that hits you is a bourbon alcohol smell , which is quite potent . the aromas are incredibly complex , i 've never smelt anything like it . it is incredibly sweet , it makes your teeth ache just at the thought of it ; maybe this will lessen with cellaring .  not too much that i can to the other reviews here . this beer was nothing but dissapointing . the label does say ipa right ? where are the hops ? i know that it does n't have to be a hop bomb but the flavor just is n't very good at all . i 've got 5 bottles left from this 6-pack . now i have to decide if i struggle though them or i just pour them out .

a floral citrus smell hits you hard with a smell of some sweetness to it that seems to be hiding in this hoppy beer . mouthfeel- a good amount of carbonation to it between medium to heavy in its feel , about average in my opionion drinkability-is n't the best but with conditioning you can become very use to it and then it becomes very appealing . just brilliant .  my only complaint with this beer is that it is a little thin .

i smell orange , tangerine , kind buds , papaya , pine , and hints of rock candy . the aroma is lovely ! it smells like someone is peeling an orange next to me . good , but not as amazing as the nose .  start is lightly sweet , the top skeletal in feel , the finish lightly carbonated , hops shy in their spiciness , a bit medicinal , dry aftertaste , quite drinkable but a touch different than my normal american over the top beers , and frankly scarlet i dont give a damn , im ready for a change .
an inspiring view and almost magical looking . big , sticky off-white head .  it has a medium body and a fair amount of carbonation , but again feels a bit weak .

nose is surprisingly funky . a very pleasant surprise .  smoky , malty and mildy coffee-like . deep black with a thumb thick mocha head . fore is hoppy bitter then roasted barley malt follows . very much in the fullers vein as opposed to the more roasty and coffee/chocolate flavored american porters . very nice brew .

it has a great thick fluffy dark mocha colored head perched upon a jet black body . the head was still present a good 5 minutes after pouring .  t - great pilsner , very slight hops , clean finish m - light body d - very smooth and very drinkable .

poured out a beautiful and dark midnight black color with a cascading and creamy rich head of tan foam .  a bit thin , for i think i like them a bit more bodiful , but smooth and flavorful i do think this one , yes .

robust cherry smell that is fantastic . taste is almost all cherry , wheaty malt underneath .  m - the bitterness and acidic notes can be a bit of a turnoff , and its a bit prickly going down , thus not the smoothest dubbel i 've had . o - a tasty dubbel , but not my favourite .

it smells like a a big pile of hops . there are also some alcohol esters and actually a decent aroma of biscuit-like malt . t : hops dominate .  my first new pumpkin beer of the year . i love october ( because of pumpkin flavored beers ) . this is definitely not the best pumpkin beer i 've tried , but it 's still a very good beer . if you like shock top 's wheat , you want to try this . i ca n't promise i 'll buy another 6 pack , mostly due to price and wanting to try new things .
opaque amber-brown pour with a dense , 3-finger white head and tons of lacing .  a bit too foamy actually . last swigs : overall enjoyable . that 's cheap !

smell is pretty classic , dry minerals and sour citrus , floral and sugary , very appealing . taste is very full for a smaller beer , but not what i was hoping for ( or smelled ) .  m : medium-light in body .
big aroma of alcohol and vinous fruit , almost christmas pudding-like .  smooth , mellow finish , and a thin watery mouthfeel .

`` hello , my name is coriander and pepper '' says the aroma in a pleasing fashion . a bit heavier and sweeter than i would like hurts its drinkability , but the great aroma and pleasant flavor make this a very nice beer .  ( m ) smooth , oily , and flat . it 's a solid beer , or a solid base of a beer that could be improved only with a better mouthfeel .

aroma is rich and complex : sweet , sticky maltiness rich in caramel , accompanied by a ripe fruitiness and a good deal of citrusy hops . i do n't detect any oakiness .  mouthfeel : a little thin , medium body , low carbonation , medium flavor . underwhelming mouth .

the nose is bursting with fresh blueberries . very sweet nose reminds me of waffles , muffins , cereal with its grainy like finish . the blueberries are n't as dominating in the flavor as they are in the aroma . buttered bread , toast , tart fruity quality .  m - this one finished a little dry , too much so for my liking , but the carbonation was nicely balanced , making it very smooth .

big aroma for such a little head ; bright fruits , dried fruits , plum , cherry , red grapes , slight caramel and a smooth yeasty character . fruity malt character also displays some earthy , hearty grain notes and much of the same fruits as in the nose . nice medium yeasty twang marries well with the fruit notes .  m - pretty watery and thin .

was picked up by my bro-in-law and quickly swept away to milly 's tavern to begin our pre-race inebriation . the pumpkin ale was a solid beer , and had a wonderful nose and flavor . the color was clear golden and the glass came lined with sugar and spice !  m : somewhat thick , bread-y . but smooth .

appearance - deep muted red , like the embers of a fire almost . the head is light beige in color , extremely dense and creamy like melted marshmallows on hot chocolate . the lace is a full blanket all the way around the glass .  on my first stop on my michigan beer tour . the grand cru on tap was a very nice start to my tour . the first taste was wonderful , but , the flavor of the beer left my mouth looking for just alittle more .

the aroma is a very nice rich creamy milk chocolate . the best part of this beer is that the aroma is so strong , it is a major component of the beer even while drinking the last swallow . nice feeling coming out of a bottle .  m -- slightly too watery , does n't really coat the mouth like i would hope but it washes down clean with no bad lingering tastes d -- this is it here , i think this is the beer i would use to introduce someone new to ipa 's .

the nose on this one is about a mile deep . i get tons of nutmeg , chai tea , cinnamon , vanilla , ginger snap best describes the aroma . i ca n't stop smelling it . most , if not all the aromatic qualities come through on the palate . very creamy and spicey . overall the drinkability is good . great aroma , great flavor and mouthfeel .  could use both more body and carbonation .
pretty impressive for what i 'm reviewing as a wee-heavy .  the mouth is a tiny bit like flat soda which was the only off-putting part of this beer .

this smells promising . taste : toffee , brown sugar , caramel , dark fruits and sharp alcohol .  malts help to round it out a little , but that bitterness hangs around for quite a bit m : medium body with typical sa carbonation , slightly oily d/o : well , apparently zeus is known for that intense piney flavor , so it is highlighted well here .

the nose really is redolent of pepe du chat , gooseberry , bright herbal citrus with a nice minerality with a touch of dry malt - very sauvignon blancesque .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin and the carbonation is quite sharp ; a bit fizzier than i 'd like .

this alt looked fantastic ! has a rich , deep , clear chestnut color , with a very fine light tan head topping off at about 1 '' . the head dissipates at a very slow rate , and leaves top-shelf lacing .  taste : a bit thin for a porter , almost to the point of being slightly watery .

very strong baking chocolate smell - the kind that smells delicious but is really dry and ends up too bitter when you taste it . what a deceptive beer - first you notice it because it is a ris in a can , then it looks and smells great , and then it just lets down big time in the taste .  the mouthfeel is slightly buttery but leans more towars a syrup-like feel . carbonation would be greatly appreciated and add a very unique feel for this beer .

smell- huge pine , bitter citrus , terpentine ? love it ! big aromas have me very excited about this beer . taste- the pine needle flavor instantly greets me , along with a nice bittersweet malt finish . there is a lot going on here , and i can taste a duality of hops types playing here .  i wish the mouthfeel had a bit more viscosity ... .but i say that about every stout .

s : the glass was a foot and a half away from my face and i could immediately smell a warm pumpkin pie coming out of the oven with a nice floral hops on the back . t : the spicy pumpkin flavor swirls with a strong caramel malt flavor .  t - again , bicuit and nut . nice and malty , virtually no hop bite , but tasty none the less . d - i have had this a ton in the past , but i only just got around to getting another one for the purposes of reviewing .

beautiful fresh dry-hop aroma . the malt is not hidden , though , with a pale malt aroma blending in with the floral hop resins .  m : somewhat thin body , slightly watery ; could do with more carbonation also .

it smells distinctly like pineapple cake . i mean you get the sweet pineapple and a really bready smell underneath . probably my favorite smell in a beer ever , different than the norm for an apa . definitely does n't live up to the smell but i enjoy it . the carbonation level is good and there is n't really a harsh aftertaste . there certainly is n't anything off-putting , and i would recommend it to anyone , at least for the sake of smelling it .  smell is cocoa , touch of coffee , licorice , slight vanilla , a whiff of smoke . taste is thick creamy , dark and bakers chocolate , touch of espresso , end is dry and slightly bitter , a woody aftertaste .

sampled on 4-7-09 pours a clear deep red/brown , with a huge , foamy , clingy , off-white head that leaves crazy thick lacing .  from the perfume river in vietnam ( no really , that 's what the label says ) , on to the beer : poured into a mug , it 's a clear yellow color with a soda-like head . this flavors in the beer do n't meld together well for me . there 's more cooked corn , a mild astingency , and a straightforward bitterness that battle each other for supremecy . even at ice cold , it took some work for me to stomach this beer . round off the edges and we might have something more tolerable .

aroma is great . cherry , oak , cabernet , phenolic , yeast , sour , sweet tarts ... mouthfeel is a touch awkward with carbonation at first , but mellows during the drink as it warms . dry on the finish .  m - felt a bit thin to me .

head leaves a serious amount of lace on the glass . really a great looking pint of beer .  a - black on the pour with no head whatsoever s - big burnt malt and bittersweet chocolate aroma along with some bourbon , some oak and vanilla in there as well , slight alcohol , as the beer warms up , smells almost like straight bourbon , maybe more like a bourbon and cola t - big bourbon flavor right up front , lots of oak as well , some bittersweet chocolate in the body , finish is more bourbon and oak along with some vanilla , alcohol notes , long finish m - a bit too flat for my taste , full-bodied but totally devoid of any carbonation action in the mouth d - i 'm glad port put this in a 375ml bottle , because this is a sipper , treated this almost like fine bourbon sipping for quite awhile , but i could sip on this all night very interesting beer .

huge nose consisting of bourbon aromas with licorice , chilies and chinese herbs . smells exotic , like walking into some strange shop in chinatown . rich and oily with tons of spice and bitterness .  heavy bodied but also heavily carbonated . less carbonation would have been preferred as experiencing more of the beginning flavors would make for a more enjoyable tasting .

when you smell this beer , you know this is a big one . lots of power and lots of liquor , much like rum with some fruity notes to me . it felt like port or a fortified wine in my mouth and the taste was rather like a really , really nice rum .  little fruityness . light to medium body , oily , light carbonation . could be a little more carbonated .

overall , a seemingly pleasant ipa , that tastes wonderful at first , but then bites back too hard and dies flowery . still pleasant on the nose and eyes and foretaste though .  the carbonation is ok ; small fresh bubbles at a decent strength .
there was very good retention and excellent lacing .  medium thin body manages a bit of creaminess .
d - this is pretty good ipa .  m : finish stays around for quite a while , almost too long , really coats the mouth .

delightful smell . the taste , not so much .  the mouthfeel is light bodied with a high level of biting carbonation ( the carbonation is the only part of this beer that i 'm not too fond of ) . quite dry due to the high level of carbonation .

full and rich , with dried fruits overtaking the nose . lots of vanilla in here , as well as some caramel and licorice . t : quite a lot going on in this brew . nothing too special here . d : so scarily drinkable . at 11.5 % , i feel that i could sip this all night .  this brew is 5.2 % abv and my bottle looks exactly the same apart from the two silver australian international beer awards one from 2007 & the other from 2008 in the top left of the label anyways it pours a dark cola hue with a fast vanishing two finger head and sporadic lacing , the aroma is fresh chocolate icecream and vanilla expresso , it has an average mouthfeel with tastes of fresh chocolate icecream , vanilla expresso , macadamia and it finishes with a light bitter mouthfeel , overall a nice brew that is just lacking that full mouthfeel of a stout in my mind but in saying that its very sessionable and ill definately buy this again .

appearance : pours a bit 3+ finger thick tight off-white head with great retention . looks great all the way .  had this during o'briens wet hop festival . pours clear orange with a white ring of bubbles . lots of caramel with some tropical hops in the nose . kind of like a fruitcake . earthy , yet citrusy in the taste . bit sweeter than your normal ipa . grapefruit and blood orange . good stuff .
on cask at the guildford arms in edinburgh poured a golden yellow , with a white creamy head and excellent lacing .  mouth feel is reasonably rich .

on initial pour this is one of the finest looking brews i 've ever laid eyes on .  the body is sufficient to carry the 10 percent alcohol which is impressive by itself . some spicy notes and an effervescent type of feel to it .

small amount of lace around the edges s : roasted coffee and dark chocolate hit the nose first . very sweet smelling , as well as the presence of alcohol t : initially it was more bitter then i expected from the aroma .  t - tastes like a combination of pine-sol and a basic light lager m - who cares ?

aroma is quite hoppy , mostly grapefruit , pine , citrus rind . mild buttered bread aroma , some pinneaple , a hint of spiced banana .  first pull provided a mouthfeel that was a little more smooth than i would have expected , just short of creamy .

a deep amber reddish beer with a mother of pearl head . the head on this brew is large fluffy , lasting and pungent .  carbonation is n't bad , with fairly good activity after each drink . mouth-feel is a bit dry .
aroma has nice sweet notes , but it 's dominated by hop perfume . nice pine and floral notes abound .  it has a medium-light body and it 's pretty smooth .

smells great . huge floral and citrus hop aromas with a bready malt that asserts itself more as the beer warms .  m - this is where the beer ranks fairly average for me . under carbonated and a little bit flat , would have liked it to be heavier , stickier , and have more of a bite .

nice aromas do n't match the taste anymore .  it has little to no head on it with a soft pour . this beer has a good balance of spices that is not overpowering . the aftertaste is mellow . this is one of the darker ales that i have drank but all in all i would give it another try . especially on a snowy winter day .
