smell : wow ... i was n't expecting this at all . incredibly hoppy , honey , almost strawberry jam sticky hop smell . taste : i found it a little too watery at first , which was a dissapointment . another intriguing brew with an awful label from ray mcneil .  m - a little water , but it goes down smoothly d - this is a really good beer .

s ) pumpkin pie ... this really has it covered . this is spiced , but not over the top , which made me very happy . a very nice balance of pumpkin and beer . this is quite smooth . nice finish and aftertaste . o ) i have n't really had many pumpkin beers , but i 've heard good things about this one , so i finally gave it a shot . i 'm really glad i did .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with low yet sharp carbonation .

this is very easily the best smelling beer i 've ever whiffed . taste is very disappointing . the smell is this brews strongest point , but it is also the source of the beer 's greatest flaw .  m good medium body , with a lot of carbonation , either takes away from this beer .

s : amazing aroma . very syrupy and sweet smell . lots of brown suger/toffee/caramel notes , some faint char and even some coffee . o : the smell on this beer is phenomenal , but the taste just does n't deliver .  mouthfeel : it 's a bit heavy for the style .

head clumping is visible and the head retention is well overall . moderate lacing and pretty clear .  muted roastiness and chocolate malt notes . deep black body with a decently firm and lasting thumb thick head . roasted coffee beans int he fore followed by toasted and burnt bread and some mild chocolate notes int he finish . finish is dry and coffee tinged great classic porter .

incredible and intense . t : bitter roasted malt throughout . overall , a fantastic beer .  always looking for a great session beer and this one fits the bill for me . great bitter citrus aromas with just enough malt balance on the taste to keep the acidity in check . great piney hop character with a nice citrusy finish . my only complaint on this one is the price , for $ 11.99 a six i would prefer stone keep the etched bottles and give me a 4 % abv beer at a more reasonable price .
makes a nice , thick head with staying power . deep , dark brown color with a lighter ( and nicely creamy ) brown head .  mouthfeel - rather bubbly , fairly thin .

d - spectacular aroma displayed on a solid background of malt . the aroma is still so full and excellent that it makes up for any weakness in the flavor profile .  thanks to ncvbc for this great extra best by 12/31/08 bottle poured into my sniffer produced a good fingers worth of tan head that turns into a ring of lace around the glass on top of a jet black body aromas of toasted malts , coffee and chocolate with a slight funk ( i 'm glad i am not the only one to pick it up i though my nose was going ) earthiness , sweat malts , light chocolate , molasses good balance of flavors the only real complaint is it is a little thin for a stout good drinkability i could drink a few of these a night easy .
just excellent .  mouthfeel- medium body with very little carbonation .
the smell is filled with some nice hops with a good bit of sweetness .  light feel with lots of carbonation .

smell is impressive . it practically filled the room as soon as i popped the crack . super floral hoppy , it just smells beautiful . taste is more muted and one sided , but still tasty . overall , quite good beer .  spicy and yeasty on the finish , this beer is medium-light on the palate with a high level of carbonation , much higher than i care for , really foaming up in my mouth .
s - mmm , what a good smelling beer . delicious smell , and a lot of it .  the mouthfeel is medium but i think the beer would be better if it was properly carbonated .

a little unusual too . overall , a unique and very enjoyable iipa .  a chore to swallow . lingers on the palate like a bad cigarette . overall : not something i 'll ever subject myself to again . there are way better means of getting trashed than this , and though it 's cheap , it 's not at all worth the gagging and self loathing .

a sexy , blurred mahagony colour with patches of head . would leave small remnants of lacing .  it looks like a pale ale should , there 's some yeast on the bottom of the bottle and the head stays for a bit . i 'd rather have a bit more malt presence , it 's just too hoppy and bitter for me . drinkability , if i had to choose between this and a macro , i 'd take this . edit on 10-3-04 i 've raised my review score , since i 've either started loving the hop , my tastes have changed or the fact that this is one of the few decent beers you can get around here on a night out and i 've become more accoustomed to it .

pretty nice ; once i got used to it i really started to like it .  i can see why the word peat was used before in a review the mouthfeel was medium to light i will agree it needs some more body to it this is a good brew and with a little tweaking it could become world class .
the smell of it was great . the taste was not as impressive , but i did enjoy the chewyness .  come and drink this corn syrup !

huge pumpkin aroma with a bit of spice not unlike pumpkin pie ( which i was eating with it ! ) . my wife loves pumpkin and is not much of a beer drinker and really liked this beer .  mouthfeel - a little gritty , though a light body to it .

rich , sweet aroma of dark fruits , powdery chocolate , and fortified red wine . easy drinking , pleasant and nicely fragrant .  decent head , minimal lacing , crisp smell with just a hint of hops . the hops are more noticeable in the taste . really nice american lager . makes bud look like the crap it is . my only macro beer ( maybe amber bock , too )

smell is pure oranges and very faint hops but the smell is amazing . taste did n't lead up to the smell kind of a big build up and then aahh .  i think i 'm a bit parial to this beer for 2 reasons . it 's not by any means a `` specialty '' beer , it 's your typical lager and since it 's been around since before any of us were born it 's got a nostalgic feel . excellent beer in my books , average for most .
pours deep brown with a nice creamy head of foam .  i think if the mouthfeel was better it would have made a world of difference imo .

smell : extremely tart , cherries , acid , mushroom , funk/barn/horseblanket , leather and oak taste : extremely sour , i could n't get the taste of this one out of my mouth till dinner the next day . similar to the smell , vinegar , lots of must/mold , leather , oak , and sour/tart cherries .  mouthfeel : hoppy and rough , but a bit fuzzy .

a- nice burnt orange coloring with a decent head and great lacing s- unbelievable aromas ... the tropical fruits are just amazing . you could mistake this for a glass of juice . t- kind of a letdown from the smell , but really the smell set the bar ridiculously high . this is definitely one of the better iipas i 've had the pleasure of tasting .  high carbonation detracts slightly .

called the skellig irish red on the chalkboard , but confirmed with watch city that it is their shillelagh irish red . magnificent , bulbous cream of head that frankly amazes with its ocean of white and a knifes edge cut ; huge stick and lace . dark red hue with a dead quiet calm and plenty of crystal clarity .  mouthfeel : it feels like an astringent hop bitterness , but i sure as heck ca n't taste any hops .

aroma is great . rich dark chocolate . wow , what a disappointment after the aroma . mouthfeel is nice . a shame that a beer that smelled so good did n't live up to it .  m - medium/light body with little carbonation good with spicy food .
nice hop aroma right off the bat . very piney and resiney .  the motuhfeel is moderately carbonated and slightly watery .

a wonderful nose and the quality of a strong ale . reminds me greatly of oaked arrogant bastard .  the hops however tastes amazing but it needs more malt m - very light mouthfeel d - probably the most drinkable 7.2 % beer ive ever had

the beer pours a jet black liquid ; impenetrable by light . the head is a nice coffee color , about an inch right up to the edge of my pint glass . the head retention is excellent and the lacing on the side of the glass leads down to a creamy top of the beer even when almost gone .  medium bodied with medium carbonation . i only wish this average mouthfeel was supporting an average taste .
this stuff smells great . a very unique sweet plummy/buttery smell . tastes good , too . does n't taste like 9 % at all .  for the mouthfeel , i found this stout almost watery in consistency .
s : a lot of hops here , citrus and floral , smells incredibly fresh , like sticking your nose in a handful of hops .  slight astringent twinge . d- very good `` sessionable '' strong ale .

it is astoundingly complex . t - it tastes like a better-than-average barleywine , but not by much . d - a mixed bag ; full of lore and hype , looks intriguing , smells wildly complex , tastes like an old abused barleywine .  it was also a little to carbonated for me in the mouth feel category .
this beer looks great ! very hard to pick up the toasted and almost roasted malt aromas .  mouthfeel - very enjoyable borderline complex character .
smell - aroma was bery pleasing with a definite berry aroma .  crisp taste - not heavy as expected ... hints of smokey , woody flavors - has the appeal of a coffee porter ... mouthfeel is average .

aroma is the best part . lots of grapefruit and citrus . tons of hop aroma . taste is great . tons of hops . reminds me of hop slam a bit . mouthfeel is good . overall an awesome beer that i 'm going to want another growler of .  smooth , nice , a little thin maybe . not a ton of carbonation at the end which leaves it a little watery .

a - golden and slightly hazed with coppery highlights and a foamy , cushiony head that jets to the surface and clings to the glass like glue as it subsides . head retention is fantastic , and would be even without the aid of the etching at the bottom of the glass . fantastic .  way too thin in the mouthfeel category , however .

s : bourbon and caramel/toffee smell . t : reminds me of a barleywine with a bourbon shot dropped it in .  taste is dominating by anis with some candi sugar . body was above average and alcohol was well hidden .

a very complex and inviting aroma . the taste really follows the nose , with a sweet melange of spices careening across the tongue . it 's very complex , but unfortunately does n't smell quite as good as it tastes .  m : a touch thin .
smell was out of this world . very fresh hop smell , got me all excited about the fist sip , but ... taste was very underwhelming .  ) my only qualm was the the body seemed a little thin .

pours a dark brown black with a large creamy brown head that retains well and laces the glass .  a medium to full body . possibly a little too thick ( syrupy was mentioned earlier by easyr which sums it up well ) as it took me a while to make headway down the glass ( unusual for me ) .

aroma of spruce and tiger lillies . supremely floral . this is not the aroma of your average triple . this beer could be marketed as liquid potpourri , and i 'd be proud to buy a lame plug-in air freshener that smelled like this . certainly , all the qualities are there .  the feel is smooth , suprisingly light for a beer that seems so heavy . while i feel that this is one of north coast 's better efforts ... though none are really bad , i do wish that it had a bit more body .

dark fruits and double fudge with a wisp of grass ... .nice ; profile is a bit of a letdown from the aroma . a very good approximation of a london stout although a tad thin for an oatmeal stout , it is very decent .  thin , oily body ... definitely needs some more heft .

overall , very nice smell . taste is fruity , quite a bit of the banana in the smell comes through in the flavor .  smooth , medium body with a palate almost entirely made up of bitter , herbal hops ; perhaps trace notes of biscuity malt can be detected , but they are virtually non-existent . finish is long , dry , and bitter , and leaves you wanting more , which leads to a great level of drinkability , especially for a hophead .

smells pretty decent as well . quite delicious , really .  the only real flaw for me with this beer is that it 's a bit thin , but that 's a bit nit-picky and did n't detract at all for me from this wonderful beer .

s- it has a nice nutty character absent form most stouts i 've had . hazelnut and almonds combine with a bit of roasted malt and some coffee to make a nice aroma .  color and mouthfeel are average for the style and fine .

great aroma , hope there is more of this in the palate . pretty decent .  so we have another german pilsner . i 'm still amazed that there are so many of these . i 'm still unable to get passed the grassy flavor of these . i just which they 'd add something else to mute that flavor down a bit . then again that would change the style and it would n't be a pils anymore . anyhow this brew is clear yellow with an earthy natural aroma and taste . the style just is n't for me .

stoudt 's double ipa 12 oz bottle medium pour in a mug recent brewing , ingested 12/06 poured a hazy orange amber with a rocky off white fully lasting head with excellent lacing that left layered ring of lacing upon every sip , like reading the rings of on a tree and tracing it 's age . smelt of strong sweet grapefruit and orange , tropical pineapple banana bubble gum or starbust mystery flavor , parsnip , with light barnyard and earthy yeasty flavors . overall , a great dipa that balances a malt sweetness backbone and strong hops nicely .  now i understand the meaning of the word `` swill '' . i have an enormous amount of respect for european beers . avoid . trust me .
'' in the glass , beer is a dark mahoghany color , very attractive .  m - average mouthfeel . carbonation on par , but a very thin feeling brew .

the appearance is simply beautiful . a rich brown that seems to be characteristic of most trappist ales . this actually sort of reminds me of the way eku 28 eisbock smells , which is odd for a trappist .  a tad thin .

a : a clear and deep golden-coloured liquid , with a nice-looking white head that leaves a nice ring of retention . beautiful .  decent palate , a little thin like the others in the series , but fairly smooth .

roasty bittersweet belgian chocolate . all low notes , tiny musty . surprising spiciness accompanies the stout yet without much depth .  mouthfeel i kind of like the mouthfeel to this one . the carbonation isnt bad , and it goes down smoother than most .
absolutely fantastic aroma . t & m : sweet chocolate , citrus hops , and toasted black malt all make their appearance .  feel is also a bit thin and fizzy .

pours bright orange , with a nice soapy head incredible hop aroma , tangerine , grapefruit , malt biscuit and some caramel sweet upfront with a bitter pine , citrus hop bite and a hint of booze very creamy , delicious and pretty well balanced for a double ipa overall it was a very enjoyable beer .  m : lightly carbed , thin , slightly oily , tannic finish .
the aromas is astonishing , this is the most coffee like of any coffee beers that i 've tasted . excellent .  m - medium body , not a lot of carbonation .

this is a powerfully aromatic ale it hits you the moment you open it . there is a strong candied fruit smell here . candy dates , pineapple , cherry , and a raw tobacco scent . about the most aromatic beer i have smelled in at least a year , maybe more . pliny the younger and three floyds dreadnaught are the only two on the same level of complexity . mouthfeel is good . drinkability is ok .  mouthfeel was a bit thick , and it was not quite as carbonated as i would have liked .

pours a hazy light auburn in color . plenty of head and very nice lacing .  hmmm . drank this because a chick bought a pitcher and the service was terrable . it 's like club soda with a twist of beer . not much color , not much flavor . not bite of hop . not really much to say about this stuff . it 's pretty popular with girls ...
smell has a great malty dark fig aroma . very warm smell . taste is also very malty .  m : the body is light but sugary and grainy with a moderate carbonation .
it 's got a nice effervescence and aromas of citrus and orange .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and resinous , this is really the only fault i can find .

2011 batch 1 - 750ml bottle poured into a cbs snifter a : black as night . gorgeous finger-and-a-half dark brown head that leaves a nice full cap throughout consumption .  mouthfeel : bubbly and light body . the mouthfeel is a little peculiar and affects my experience .

whoa ... a : freakin ' black as my heart with a big tan head and lots of lacing . i really do think dark beers are the nicest to behold .  the only fault is that its a little thin bodied but that 's what makes this brew dangerous .
overall , this beer looked and smelled great , but has too much bite to really enjoy .  the mouthfeel is a bit astringent .

a - black as can be with what started as a monster tan head that has died down a bit but still lingers s - big roasted aroma 's mingle with notes of vanilla . this is just what i look for .  a : pours a dark brown with a two finger head ; burnt orange around the edges of the glass when held to light ; lacing is excellent s : smells of caramel and coffee ; very earthy aroma t : tastes like a bitter coffee initially , but the sweetness of caramel and honey slowly creeps in m : i think its a bit too watery and the carbonation does not seem right d : two in a sitting is nice ; i 'm generally not a porter fan , but i enjoyed this beer

a very pricey brew in my area , with a four-pack going for nearly $ 13 ... was shrewd enough to pick up a single 12oz bottle which still ran me a hefty $ 3.50 ... pours a beautiful , dark , mahogany-brown tan color that resulted in a fluffy white head that had some staying power ... smell is malty , with a prunish aroma ... taste is very complex with an almost root-beer , licorice flavor that tingled on my tongue for awhile after the first-sip ... i really enjoyed this brew , put for the price , not sure i 'd pay again unless i could find a single ... definitely interested in the pale version from this brewery ... the taste is sweet , but an alcohol presence is certainly noticeable.. a good brew , definitely recommended ... .  mouthfeel is on the thin side for a stout .

this beer has the most incredible smell in the world . '' the big wafts of vanilla , caramel , and butterscotch fill the nose and is absolutely delectable . i could enjoy the aroma of this beer for hours . one bomber was enough for me , and i was pleasantly surprised .  mouthfeel : medium bodied .

beautiful , beautiful honey color with a thick , but not creamy , head .  the mouthfeel was about what i expected going in , but i thought it might a little over-carbonated . the aggressiveness of the carbonation was a little distracting .
bright dark orange colored beer with a large frothy , long lasting head that could only come from belgium .  the body is medium with decent carbonation .

s - amazing nose ; delicious notes of chocolate , slight coffee , and super smooth oat , with roastiness present but generally transformed into the aforementioned dimensions . it reminds me of the smell of instant caf mocha , prior to the addition of hot water . ) finally , there is an appreciable hop that comes in at the end and lingers , providing herbal and vaguely floral notes on the finish .  m- low carbonation and very low mouthfeel .
the beer smells pretty good , very hoppy like one would expect from this type of beer .  the mouthfeel is a bit overcarbonated for the stle but not bad .

i thought is was a hefe at first , but upon tasting , i was corrected . smells of a crisp hop dryness and mandarin orange . the hops carry over in to the taste but it is backed by an odd cheerios like grain .  m. a bit acidic d. overall a nice iipa .

the pour reveals very fine de dolle bubbles . the beer is a beautiful copper color .  pretty thin mouthfeel i guess , but overall its a great balance of flavor and drinkability , something i would definitely buy again .
smell : very well balanced . citrus notes with a very nice malt background .  carbonated but not overly so . on the lighter side of medium bodied , i 'd say .

s - sweet complex dark stone fruits . cinnamon apple fig . with a bit of pimento . mild oaky hickory hop smells . although not as complex as the smells it is yummy .  this is a man 's beer . none of this flowery wine swilling critique lingo . light color , smell and mouth feel , who really cares . outstanding dry & hoppy flavor without sweetness . when bought in the 30 pack , cost is about 50 cents each . the best macro being produced !
s : this beer smells incredible . huge vanilla aroma that is mixed with a huge coffee aroma .  this feels thin for some reason . carbonation is good and proper .
i absolutely love the aroma of this beer , and with more restrained alcohol its drinkability would improve .  mouthfeel too prickly and astringent but medium body is appropriate for style .
a - this beer pours black in color . this is a beautiful looking beer .  the only knock here is that it was a little thin . m = is it possible to be creamy and watery at the same time ?

terrific chocolate and coffee notes with some fruity hints as well .  feel seems to be about medium in body , but slightly watery , with a lingering semi-bitter dark unsweetened chocolate/coffee bean aftertaste .
a harmonious aroma of raisins and rosemary , dominating . dates and caramel , intoxicating sugars . wow , taste is right there too . it 's just alluring .  mouthfeel is on the light end .

not much there in the way of lace ... s - i could smell the hops when i was pouring this ... beautiful floral aroma with a little citrus ... like putting your nose in a bag of fresh hops t - good balance for how much hop aroma there is ... more on the sweet malty side rather than bitter ... definitely a sweet aftertaste .  tart and dry feel , but not overly so . lower carbonation detracts a little , really the only flaw in my mind .

smell is so awesome . the belgian yeast esters mixed with the hoppyness of the ipa is out of this world . probably one of the nicest beers i have smelled . it smells better than it tastes . it 's a very good beer but i like the smell of it alot better .  mouthfeel : this was my one issue with this beer . it loses carbonation quickly , and with not that much to start with , it is kind of a bummer . a little sticky as well but the taste makes up for a bit of this .
light amber beer was topped by a thick head that left some of the thickest lacing i have seen in my career .  mouthfeel : this is the one downside of this beer ; it 's just a bit thin .

poured this puppy into a duvel tulip , which helped to bring about an ample 4 finger thick fluffy and off white head . the body is very murky and peach in color . head retention is great , as well as the lacing .  i thought the mouthfeel was a touch watery but the whole packaged seem very much an alluring strong-lawnmower , early evening session beer .

poured a deep dark reddish-brown into my guinness pint glass , and the tan head reached the top . beautiful .  tingly in the nose which is common with sour ales but this is n't sour at all t. sweet with dried fruit , malty m. has a biting quality , a bit to carbonated .

poured at the rock bottom brewery prior to seeing the blue man group . beautiful honey gold color ... poured with no head .  an e-mail from the brewery indicated that twins lager is not the same beer as hauenstein , just with a different label . schells tells me that the twins lager uses a different recipe and yeast than the hauenstein , but a side by side comparison leaves me wondering why they would go through the trouble . i have always liked `` cheap '' beers . the beer drinkers of olden days wanted it cold , crisp , and cheap . but for afternoon lazing back and swigging , there is certainly nothing wrong with a cold bottle of twins lager . twins lager might be `` twice as refreshing '' as the label purports , but , boy would it be a treat to drink an original recipe fitgers again !

presentation : it was served in a tulip glass from tap at the pizza plant italian pub . appearance : looking into the glass it had a deep reddish brown colored body with a creamy light tan head . the head was long lasting , thick and it left tons of sticky lacing to cling to the sides of the glass in thick rings . ( very impressive ) smell : the aroma hits first with a bit of boozy alcohol .  boosting the carbonation would help .

s- big nose , this is got it all for a west coast ipa , grapefruit , pine , and light citrus notes . this is sort of sweet smelling , but not from the malt . o- this is the last i had from the hop box .  light-medium carbonation and medium bodied . flavor is sour apple cider without the expected hops from a bitter , one has to question if this bottle has gone bad but after reading other reviews apparently it has n't , even though it has n't been brewed since 2006 .

this is mouthwatering and powerful . t : follows the nose . though it is not as powerful as the nose imo . m/d : a full body that is low on the carbonation end .  m - sort of dry but hops represented well in this brew .

this is beautiful , and refined . man , the nose really had me going , but the taste did n't follow through .  there is little ( hardly any ) carbonation here , and the mouthfeel really does n't pack a punch at all .

a - pours a gorgeous pure orange color with a nice white dense head . it recedes slowly and it is sticky and very attractive .  m/d - mouthfeel is nothing special , the steely hop bite takes a bit away .
incredibly fresh hop aroma . absolutely unbelievable . must try these galaxy hops for my homebrew soon .  shockingly light carbonation feel . i think the mouthfeel is off from what it should be .

river horse special ale esb pours a deep cloudy gold with a massive pillowy head that took up half the glass .  mouthfeel : low carbonation , light-medium body , slick texture . a bit flat all in all .

i 've had a few of these and this one plays up the humidor to 11 . incredible . t. the jai alai flavor is played down a bit to the predominate cedar flavor . the grassy and citrus hops are very nice with a good malt .  m : medium body but the finish is not as crisp nor as clean as it could be .
this beer was very jeckyll and hyde for me . the smell is also terrific : citrusy , apricot , peach ( as others have noted ) .  mouthfeel was a little thin , that 's my only complaint .

s- smell is absolutely perfect . sweet , floral tones with a huge aromatic pineyness . t- taste is milder than expected from the ipaesque nose but good none the less .  seems a bit thin , with very soft carbonation .

nice tall white head with very sticky lacing .  thanks jpm30 . clearly sour taste that sweetens as you drink it . vineous and slightly rich , wood only detactable before the taste buds are overpowered.. great after salty fish . a slightly milder alternative to a cantillon , overpowering the mouth but not for the entire day .

two brothers heavy handed ipa : terrific aroma , very full and noticeable from several feet away . some heavy malt syrup aromas coupled with flowery hops make the aroma very appetizing . slick mouth feel .  m : light but slightly creamy body .

this brew pours into the glass with a black body topped by a thick creamy , light brown head with a good amount of lacing left behind .  feel left me a bit disappointed , however , as it was thin -- too thin for this big of flavor .
black with a glorious creamy beige head with great retention and lacing .  the mouthfeel was light but a bit chewy .

the three-finger beige head displayed great retention as a fluffy cap . eventually the cap became rocky and left little islands of foam floating atop the liquid . the lacing was also excellent , in curtains ; top marks for appearance .  this beer has a flavor i really like m- pretty thin and bubbly , almost reminds me of a bmc feel o- one of my favorite tasting pale ales .
the smell is perfect , like cranberries , very tart and almost bitter . you can really smell this all the way up your nose .  m : a bit thin , i was kind of expecting it to be a bit more viscous .

appearance : pours a dark black body with neither much head nor lacing smell : dark , rum-soaked fruits , bitter chocolate and tobacco taste : starts out rather sweet , with a heavy dose of malty dark fruit ; then a blast of tobacco and bitter chocolate blend together ; the finish , however , is a bit disappointing as some sour medicinal notes creep in at the very end mouthfeel : rich and full-bodied with a decent level of carbonation drinkability : were it not for the finish , this would have been an extraordinary brew . based on some other reviews , i 'll have to keep my eye out for another batch that may not have the bitter aftertaste .  nicely carbonated .

perfect fruit scent . clean , pleasant , and wonderful . almost erotic , even - i want this beer to have my abortion .  mouthfeel is somewhat disappointing . if we 're talking about banana bread here , then it should be thicker , like bread .

appearance : the body is a deep black color . the head is a velvety light tan color , small bubbles , two or three inches tall , excellent retention as well and lacing .  m/t : light to medium body , watery and a good amount of carbonation . however with the light body , low bitterness and virtually zero aftertaste , i could session this beer .
s - about 0.2 seconds after the cork popped , the air was almost filled with a rich , dry oak smell . lots of brett in there as well .  medium bodied fairly low carbonation .

a : poured a dark clear ( filtered ) chocolatey amber color with a rich white foamy head .  tastes like , yeah , tart blueberries ( probably artificial blueberries ) . just sweet & weird & sweet ... really tough to finish one . much like a cheap , too-tart wine cooler .

one of the best aromas to come around in a while for me . very decadent chocolate here ... sweet , silky ... you can really smell the cocoa nibs here . a slight hint of hop bitterness as well but this is a very chocolatey aroma . the body is a bit light , and the taste is certainly full of chocolate , but is more of a mix between a sweeter chocolate and a bitter , roasted chocolate . this marriage keeps it from becoming cloying or just being too bitter . what was a pretty sweet and rich beer on the nose was n't quite so on the tongue .  i did notice after a while that it has been pulled from tap that it acquires a lack of a better word , a buttery taste that really dos n't go good with anything . i do like this beer and i 'm not bashing it . the buttery taste in my opinion did not take effect until thirty or so minutes after pour . i do keep some in my fridge . i have shiner before to make burgers with , which turned out great . good beer for beer lovers .

it pours as close to a pitch black without actually being pitch black . great head retention so this really has it all going on in appearance .  slightly under carbonated for my taste but not really a flaw .

s : bright fruit , almonds , yeast , nutmeg , and delicate toast round out this great smelling saison . t : begins with off-dry fruit -- apricots , grapes , and lemons -- slightly acidic .  m : relatively light though not particularly carbonated .

the smell is really where this beer shined - a rich aroma of nicely roasted barley - coffee and chocolate predominated as well as a milky lactose aroma . this beer fell flat on the taste ( or maybe that 's just in comparison to the nose ) - it started off sweet , but never really delivered on all the flavors i had smelled . still , kudos for the nose . i probably wo n't be purchasing this again .  drink this on tap at city beverage in durham . i like the color and mouthfeel , though a bit thin for a heavy beer aroma is slightly sweet and complex spices taste is toasted barley , spices , and slight caramel with little head . drinks easy for a heavy beer

perfect . not as great as the nose but still excellent . m : prickly hops , of course , some mild warmth from the alcohol , and some light carbonation .  i think that the long trip from greece to williamsburg , va did n't treat this beer too kindly . pours and looks like the standard heine-clone . taste was rather flat .

good lacing & head retention s : intense almost burnt caramel & malt & some alcohol t : smokey caramel & a little aclohol up front , then a hint of cherry & oak . finishes with dryness , a slight smokeyness & a praline sweetness mf : sticky rich body with excellent carbonation & balance drinks good , but 2 would be about my limit .  not as sweet as oscura , but the mouthfeel reminded me of it . it is a little light in the feel for an imperial but ample carbonation maybe to much .

pitch black with a cocoa colored head . tons of lacing .  as a swallow i think the first thing i notice is that this is a tad light , but still serviceable in mouthfeel . a nicely balanced apa if not a little thin . im still pleasantly surprised !

crisp . ( t ) - has a rather tart profile with some serious pineapple & grapefruit citrus up front . ( m ) - a tad higher carbonation level than you would expect from the style , but it really is not too bothersome . really crisp because of it though , with really potent citrus .  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with no carbonation .
pours with a red-brown body topped by a medium thick to thick foamy lasting head with good lace .  the mouthfeel is light with a decent amount of carbonation .

incredibly clean , with absolutely no imperfections in the malting or hops . extremely delicate . the flavor is incredibly clean .  m : the feel is creamy and medium bodied . rather light for a ris and that really detracts from the beer in my opinion . the mouthfeel is lighter than what i come to think of when i thik of a ris .

smell is dates , toffee , chocolate , some light roast , touch of floral , quite nice . taste is very roasty , rich chocolate , cherries , bit of beef jerky smoke , powdered milk , weird fruitiness , kind of cloying flavour . i enjoy the aroma a lot , and the flavour as well but there are a couple that were off , but my mouth felt kind of dirty after drinking it , pretty strange , i 'll try this again but i 'm kind of on the fence at this point .  m_slightly below medium bodied and very effervescent .

poured from a 750ml bottle into a spiegelau tulip . appearance : pours a clear medium amber color with orange highlights and a fluffy 3 finger off-white head . excellent head retention and nice lacing .  s : candied pineapple , yeast , and hops well balanced t : a typical ipa taste with accents of pineapple ; yeasts and hops , well balanced m/d a bit thin , carbonation too small and too much , abv on the high side and quite noticeable good beer
it lasts forever and settles to a nice pillow . usually old ales have no head at all . i 'm amazed this looks so good .  m : very smooth , but seems pretty thin in terms of the body of the beer .
appearance : pitch black . very dark head .  mouthfeel is lightly carbonated , a little thick ( like a dark lager ... blech ) , and generally mediocre .

copious white , sea-foam head is bubbling up and down . really gorgeous . only thing not making it a 5 : wish the color was a bit brighter s_obvious green apple , wet wood , slightly dank t_very tart , green apple , very lively .  not sure what they used for malt , but very sugary at first . the hops comes in and stays with you . almost like an ipa with the first snoot full of hops . i suppose they have to keep winning people over cause of the whole inbev deal . king of beers , so i am not surprised .
very complex but i am at a lose for words .  m - slightly thin and sweet .

smells delicious . sweet raisin and toffee come through very clearly .  it 's viciously acidic , but tasty . i like acidic ... i 'll drink straight malt vinegar . this is fizzy alcoholic pomegranate juice with nothing to resemble beer to my palate . i would n't hold `` not tasting like beer '' against a legitimate ale beverage , which i 'm sure this is , except that i like beer , and i do n't like this .

the smell is quite pungent . i can smell the glass from a foot away ! sweet caramel malts are picked up in the nose , but are nothing in comparision to the huge hops assault . it is very hop foward ( understatement ) . this is easily one of the most unique and bitter beers i have ever had . the hops oils make it quite slippery and oily going down .  very light mouthfeel .

this reminds me a bit of pte with that ridiculously great aroma and bitterness but not quite having the citric hop flavor that i would normally want in a dipa . this beer is incredibly bitter on the back end and the hot alcohol make this beer difficult to session .  the mouthfeel is fairly overcarbonated and dry .

poured a slightly cloudy , amber to copper color with . nice frothy two finger off white lasting head . ample lacing cling to the glass .  mouthfeel is medium with a thick body but too much carbonation for a barleywine .
aroma : hoppy , hoppy , hoppy . awesome !  m - heavy , with little carbonation .

aroma is complex and deep- cherries , plums , cloves , cinnamon , orange peel and nutmeg all seem to float on a platform of caramel and molasses . but what starts out as intriguing eventually becomes overbearing by the end of a 750ml. , and those phenols become too prominent .  m- thinner than i would like and overly fizzy from too much carbonation .

the bouqet is powerful , with bubble gum , circus peanuts ( the candy ) , bananas , caramel , toffee , honey , flowers , and a hint of the big alcohol that awaits . drinkability suffers due to the huge abv . this went well with a salty , deep blue cabrales from spain .  m- a little light and watery , but not awful . makes for easy drinking .

it smells great but does n't live up to the smell .  mouthfeel is surprisingly tingly and sharp from the tiny carbonation and i suspect a hop i ca n't discern in either the aroma or taste . mouthfeel is unfortunately a little weak and thin for style to my mind .
clear chestnut hue . thick , persistent head leaves belgian lace .  average body and carbonation .

appearance : pour is dark chocolate with brown edges . perfect two-finger tan head .  mouth : such a light and watery mouthfeel that it becomes distracting pondering the feel when you should be appreciating the tastes . drink : the nearly too-light mouthfeel is redeemed by the drinkability of this brew .

tons of mango on the nose . sweet and tart mango flesh with an herbal , citrusy hop note buried under the fruit . a great nose , i really like the fruit character . this was fairly enjoyable and very easy to drink , but i would n't go out of my way to try it again .  m - ok and average .

amazing body color , rich and golden , yet leans towards the orange .  this is n't the fault of the brewer so maby it had great head . the main problem with this beer was infection . i 'm sure it was an infection because when i sniffed it i thought for a second maybe i was at the movies about to dig into a 12 dollar medium popcorn . past the buttery flavor i could taste blueberry almost which i 'm sure was n't intended either . it 'd be interesting to taste one from a different batch .
outstanding imo . a : normal , yellowish/orange .  palate : medium body and higher end carbonation .
appearance gorgeous , cloudy orange body full of sediment with a decent head .  mouthfeel : this beer has adequate body , but i would like a bit more texture .
this is a really great nose . tastes not quite as good as it smells , but still solid . smells great and is solid all around - worth a shot .  m= a little thin . boring mouth on it .

bottled on : ( should be on the bottom right hand side of the bottle but its just dots ) purchased through lakeview liquors , chicago , illinois price - $ 9.99/bomber appearance : pours pitch black with a creamy mocha colored head . with each swirl of the snifter another layer of froth reveals itself . looks tastey .  the mouthfeel was lowly carbonated .
copper pour , good lacing and head here .  definitely a little too carbonated for my taste - the mouthfeel was a little too creamy , masking the flavor .
excellent retention and good lacing as well . looks intimidating .  had a typical pilsner mouthfeel .

the smell is pleasing . tons of sweet banana and light belgian candied sugars . a nice belgian yeast is present in the smell , with nice sweet lemon scents . a nice beer overall , but not as clean as i would have liked to see .  m- average medium bodied beer o- great take on a saison style beer .
it poured black as a tuxedo in a dark closet . it came topped with a dense , dark-brown head that had a lot of staying power .  mouf & gt ; sudsy .

s : a lot of good stuff going on here . dark , rich , even sort of ... tropical .  mouthfeel is a bit watery not much body to it , but on a hot day like today , i could take plenty of these guys down .
s : this is an amazing smell . chocolate , malt , cream , milk , caramel , coffee and vanilla can all be found . nice . m : silky smooth .  m : a light-medium feel to it and kind of syrupy .

pours black with off-white/brownish head in one finger thickness that lasts for very long time , generous lacing . perfect .  m : earthy with a little grapefruit at the begining and a little pine at the finish . light carbonation .

one of the best smelling beers i 've ever tried . good amount of pumpkin . clean and delicious . lighter side of medium in body . not sure if this is a drastic improvement from regular pumking , but this is surely tasty .  i almost gag every time i take a sip of this . tastes like day-old miller high life with some bread , chocolate , and coffee mixed in . it looks like cola , and at first it smells like oh , say , a bottle of old milwaukee . if only it tasted even half as good as old milwaukee . please , for your own sake , stay away .
the aroma was suprisingly good , with banana , cedar , mild hops , vanilla and ginger .  mouthfeel is smooth , but almost unpleasantly so .

smell is of fresh hop , so fresh.just layers of vegetal , cirtusy hops with a slight hint of pine and pale malt .  a : solid black , modest lacing even at the beginning , but once the beer was gone so was the lacing s : malty , chicory , lingers nicely t : dominated by coffee ; bitter stout ; the oak comes through nicely ; not very complex m : casked , so it does n't really buzz in the mouth overall , a really good beer , but not as complex as i was hoping ; still , very worthwhile

refreshingly bright . taste : hoppy and full of citrus . not quite as balanced as the smell but it 's just as refreshing . the malts definitely bring some yang to the hops yin .  m. a little too sticky , it feels syrupy , but without a sweeter taste it fells a little off .

s- totally amazing smell . just like pumkin pie .  mouthfeel is full and seems overcarbonated for the style , but overall has the typical heavy/slightly syrupy mouthfeel characteristic of wheat beers .
the scent is a wonderful molasses .  mouthfeel is fine - it 's a very light lager .
great aroma , sweet malt , banana , spice , wheat note . medium feel , too cloyingly sweet for me  body is ok , nothing special but not bad . very boozy finish .
the aroma is deliciously hoppy with some citrus notes .  m : light bodied and well carbonated .

excellent ! overall : amazing aroma , very complex and inviting , but i think it set me up for a super complex flavor profile that was n't there .  m : the body is not as thick as i was expecting . it on the thin side as far as stouts go , but drinks very smoothly . i would have liked a thicker body , but that 's just being picky .

a heavenly delight of a smell taste : 2.5 this beer is incredibly sweet . loads of candy sugar in this , i am sure . this beer has crazy sweetness its very cloying .  mouthfeel is a little thin , though .

smell is intense . lemon sour acidity , pepper , lots of sweat & musk . sweet florals . earthy funk . it just seems more then a tad empty when compared to what i smelled up front .  the beer poured hard but the carbonation ended up being low and the mouthfeel medium .

smell - the rich , complex sugars here steal the show . in particular the raw sugar aroma was indistinguishable from the real thing .  the bier finishes quickly but is not overly dry . the malt department is a little thin for me but damn well done !

a : damn near perfect in my book . nicely hazy , radiant golden orange color . it 's got a big , soapy head that settles into a cap and leaves big sheets of lacing . so far so good .  mouthfeel the beer is slick on the tongue with strong carbonation . the body is a little lacking , medium-light .

i am still basically against fruit in my beer . the smell is the expected apple smell . i have granny smith apples in my house year round so this was evocative of that .  feels quite creamy at first , almost in a draft-stout kind of way , which struck me as odd . would rather it be crisper and a bit more carbonated , though .
kudos to these guys for making such a fine looking beer . great head , elegant lace , interesting to look at .  do not know if this was an aberation , but this caused a lower score in mouthfeel .

appearance- clear , dark , copper-colored ale with persistent , cream head . full carbonation . lots of lacing .  finishes with a sweet malt taste m- medium bodied with decent carbonation , not as full for an octoberfest as i 'd like but still good d- very drinkable and easy to use to introduce others to a seasonal beer

great hop bouquet -- sweet and juicy , with citrus highlights laid over a smooth backbone of stonefruit ( mostly red ; think cherries , plums , grapes ) , and a little oak . i really like the aroma this beer puts out . the body of the beer is a lovely dark amber color that tinges toward straw around the edges of the glass .  the taste is metal , sweet malt and finishes a nasty bitter . this is not a beer to be revisited unless it is on tap . i need to quite trying these imported green bottled beer . i do n't think i 've had a good one yet . on tap is a different story since kegs should n't get light damage . of course then there 's temperature . . .

huge deep malty scents , with lots of caramel and toffee and a nixe bit of earthiness , as well .  pretty weak mouthfeel , it 's a bit watery . i 'm enjoying the flavour and aroma quite a bit but the mouthfeel is a bit weak . but lacking in mouthfeel .
true amber in color with perfect clarity .  mouthfeel was the only thing i was n't too keen on- felt a little spritzer-ish .
consumed 2 days later a : poured a deep maroon color with good carbonation and a dirty white head s : caramel .  the body is rather thin though .

the aromas were of blood oranges , honey and moist , fleshy herbs ( ie . basil , bluegrass , cress , sorrel , epazote , etc . ) on the palate these images were joined by flavors of toasted , dry biscuits . it was vermouth-like in its exotic spicing and dreary , liqueurish texture ( blame the poor handling ! ) yet its bracing , raw , and complex extraction of herb overcame even this `` flaw '' . can a great ipa arise by accident ?  m : medium-full bodied , zero carbonation , silky . d : lacks the warming feeling that is usually related to a winter warmer .
very dark reddish brown color , with a nice , sticky head that dissipates intoa thin persistent sheet .  m : over carbonated - fizzy .
smells wonderful . taste - tastes buttery and lemony .  mouthfeel was a bit heavy and undercarbonated , but that may have been more of the fault of the bar i was at , and not the beer its self .

pours a beautiful orange color with a decent head into my glass . i love the color and it 's almost a shade of copper .  the head vanished quickly , but the carbonation level remained high . the aroma was overwhelming sour cherries ... mouthwatering sweet aroma that shows a huge proportion of cherries used in this brew . definitely on the sugary sweeter cherry beer side .

a : big creamy tan head , very dark body s : roasted coffee , cherry , chocolate milk t : chocolate , chocolate , chocolate .  mouthful mouthful is okay . has decent carbonation , but i 've had better as far as carbonation goes .

pours a gorgeous , deep garnet red - almost burgundy - with a large , rocky , creamy-tan head which dissipates slowly leaving heavy lace on the glass . not much for smell - faint floral hops and maybe a touch of sweet yeast .  mouthfeel : there is a lot of bitterness .

s awesome whiff of freshly brewed coffee and oats . bits of chocolate are also pleasing on the nose , as this is very simple but rather enjoyable . burnt roasts add to this smooth and creamy mixture of scents .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and watery .

s : raisins and dark fruits with a mild white wine aroma .  taste is more of the same ... some wild floral flavors , hints of citrus ... seems like the dominant flavors have switched from the citrus to the floral characteristics . i like it , for sure , but could use some balance . i 'm not a big fan of the bitter taste left in the mouth ... but it 's still plenty drinkable . a definitely above-average ale , but not the best .

however the taste is a shadow of the wonderful aroma , which is a disapointment only because it smelled so nice and i was excited for something special . nice , but i wanted more . overall it is a nice beer from a solid brewer .  this is a seasonal brew , do n't know if it is offered everywhere or if it was given adequate time to chill before serving so i 'll reserve final judgment for later .

the aroma is possibly the best feature of this brew . very sweet and flowery , almost of lemon , chamomile , and honey with very strong hop overtones . a nice light amber color , slightly darker than the 60 minute .  m : still a bit watered down , but again , it 's better .

smells creamy/milky with rich , almost sweet coffee , chocolate , kaluha , cocoa , and a touch of green hops . absolutely divine . the flavor is roasty with burnt/charred malts , coffee , chocolate , and a medium bitterness .  mouthfeel : typical red stickyness drinkability : i love this beer .

s : it smelled very malty with hints of doughy white yeast and whiffs of ripe white ( apricots and pear ) s fruit and sweet citrus ( mandarin oranges ) .  mouthfeel is thin for a stout imo , but not bad .
s - cherries , orange peel , and fresh fruits combine to create an enticing aroma . a definite yeasty quality is also present .  mouthfeel was my only complaint .

smell is beautifully complex & bright , like i just walked into an herb garden : really picking up on the rosemary , floral notes that are big but gentle , something kind of savory like oregano , maybe some basil or mint notes in there . seriously , this is fantastic , i do n't think i 've ever smelled a beer like it .  m - lots of carbonation maybe bordering on too much .

a - no pop when i pull the cork , pours a lifeless , soul sucking , pitch black , with a big oily slick on top , no head s - big nose of chocolate , coffee , vanilla , carmel sweetness , booze , smells pretty damn good t - taste is nowhere near as robust as the aroma , huge coffee flavour , basic sweetness , booze , gigantic roasted coffee finish m - no carbonation , heavy mouthfeel , dry finish , big boozy warmth d - another half assed effort from mikkeller no carbonation , ridiculous , over the top coffee flavour , and massive booziness ( even after cellaring for close to 2 years , best before is aug 2011 ) .  thin to medium bodied with moderate carbonation .

when you smell it you immediately feel the cocoa and then som pleasant toffee and grass . the taste is also dominated by cocoa without becoming either too bitter or too sweet , perfect balance . however , it lacks in mouthfeel , it doesnt quite feel as heavy as the taste suggest .  no sediment at all when bought fresh . this really brought out flavors you could not taste beforehand . a wedge of orange or lemon is a nice touch also . best served a little warmer than most beers . goes really well with food . a beer you could drink all night especially during a good bar-b-que .
it has fantastic light floral hop aromas . the alcohol content is n't particularly high and their are some superior apas around .  mouthfeel a bit thin .

this has a nice hop smell right out of the bottle . with smells of carmel , malts , and a sweet smell .  it 's a black colored beer with ruby edges . fairly nice nose , with a variety of dark fruits , as well as a bit of chocolate and coffee . really nice nose . flavor is fully packed , loaded with dark fruits ( blackberry , plum , cherry and currant ) , as well as some notes of dark chocolate , coffee and a light hint of alcohol . i like it .

330ml bottle served into an snifter glass.enjoyed on sep11.pours intense orangish copper in color , chill haze appearance.crowned by a creamy light yellowish off-white thick layer froth.brief retention leaving some spotty lacing.yeast & intense caramel malt aromas . buttery bread , toffee hints & slightly fruity -apricot & peach- notes to the nose.spicy , orange zest & subtle coriander flavors.gentle warming alcohol.sweet bitterness in the middle.medium but intense body.soft carbonation.dry bitter finish.smooth fruity aftertaste.a beer for a long & paused drink.a nice warming beer .  a - it was still cascading when the glass arrived to the table ... settled into a deep , deep brown body with a brown head ... the head was creamy yet bubbly and it retained as one finger tall ... sheets of lacing were left s - there was a lot of chocolate in the nose with some subtler coffee notes ... dark fruits were present as well as a noticeable hop presence t - again , the chocolate presence was throughout the entire beer ... it tasted like bittersweet chocolate ... the dark fruits came out in the middle ... i would say dates were most prevalent because there was a nice , sweet caramel note throughout ... the coffee flavor showed up briefly at the end as well as the hops ... it did n't leave a bitterness on the palate though m - light bodied ... this was indifferent for me ... you would think the nitro would have added some body , but it actually came across as watered down o - the description said this was an homage to yard 's brawler ... i believe i had three of these one night ... the chocolate flavor is nice and it 's all around ... there are other players that join in the flavors ... you ca n't beat 2.6 % abv , talk about session ! ... my only complaint is the watered down mouthfeel
nice . t : strong hop taste that might be too overpowering for the malt backbone .  the mouthfeel is a bit too watery and perhaps a bit chalky .

looks like a cappuccino with a marshmallow melting into it . leaves amusing puddles of lace behind and seems murky and cloudy . exquisite - a marvel to behold .  this beer poured nicely with a creamy white head , giving off nice citrus aromas . the flavor was shocking , however , reminding me of kool-aid orange flavor , and with almost as much sweetness . i could n't distinguish any hop bitterness , though it could have used some to balance out the excessive sweetness . this beer tastes as though all the yeast were filtered out , and then orange kool-aid added post-fermentation

aromas were fantastic : bready , citrus-fruit and cloves were wonderfully balanced . it was not too strong , but the aromas were apparent .  it was my first fruity beer . it kinda tasted like an apricot . i was expecting most of a fruit taste like wine , but no . and i liked the picture on the bottle . and since it came ithaca i just had to try it . over all the beer was worth it . it 's good . : )
into a tulip . pours the closest to motor oil i 've ever seen in a beer , dark crimson/brown head , dense retention and heavy legs .  the mouthfeel is medium , slightly watery .
somewhere there is a aroma i ca n't describe , but it is very familiar . marvelous aroma , but it ca n't keep that promise .  mouthfeel is a little too tingly for me with the carbonation .

it really fits the style .  this was my first encounter with pumpkin ale . i must confess that i could not finish the bottle . i had the distinct impression that the beer was trying to taste like something and not quite getting there . fearing the latter , i tossed the bottle after about five sips .

wonderfully hoppy scent with a citric , floral edge . notes of toffee and orange in the aroma . taste does n't quite live up to the aroma , but overall a nice , easy-drinking harvest ale .  aroma of fresh fruit and a bit of must , faint barnyard . taste starts with blackcurrant , very dry , moderately sour . hints of vanilla . finishes with more fruit and some mustiness . complex . would love to see it age .

the aroma is full of dark fruit , raisins and plum with hints of caramel and notes of chocolate . subtle vanilla notes with a smoke tinge . whiffs of spiced rum .  nice golden color with plenty of carbonation . the head of foam was really thick and creamy , but it dropped down to a this lace in about 15 mins . at first i was n't crazy about the taste , but about 3-4 sips into the beer i changed my tune . it is not like any beer that i typically drink , so i did n't what to expect.interesting brew , i would buy this again .
smell : sweetened chocolate , floral notes .  m-medium carbonation with a fairly dry finish o-listed as a pale lager ?
pours a deep brown with ruby highlights into a tulip . creamy off-white/light khaki head leaves excellent lacing and retention .  mouthfeel : a bit thinner than expected , but not bad .
very sweet aroma as if a tripel plus fauna , citrus and a spiciness i ca n't define .  in the mouth , it 's rather average , with light carbonation .

smells very good . taste - very sweet up front with lots of raisin and some dark almost cherry flavor . very unusual . it tastes like a funky port , frankly . a very interesting `` beer '' .  m - a little harsh , not as smooth as other ipas .

4.5 s : dry hopping has done wonders . tons of mango . after that comes pineapple , grapefruit , and orange . balancing maltiness with caramel and breadiness from the yeast . 3.5 d : decent , but nothing special .  creamy flavor does not carry over into the mouthfeel ; light bodied beer without much carbonation .

aroma is rich : sweet chocolate , vanilla , with strong whiskey notes . overall a decent beer , but somewhat a let down .  nothing to write home about when it comes to mouthfeel . kind of a club-soda feel to the beer , tingly . though there seems to be a strange `` romanian roulette '' effect where every sixth beer is kinda soapy .

the aroma is very fruity and hoppy : orange and maybe a hint of apple mixed together . ester 's given off from the yeast is quite detectable too . this is a very fragrant beer . helios tripplebock is crazy for being a german brew , as it is a total hop bomb .  dare i say it seems a bit on the thin side . the meatiness in the flavor is not backed up by the body . not bad , but just a little disappointing ... this is a fine stout .

very nice aroma of christmas spices , oak , raisins , old sherry , toffee and treacle .  i can feel it in my cheeks . it does n't have any off aromas specifically , but it definitely has the acidity for it . undrinkable , i 'm pouring it out .
a delicious aroma of coffee , and bready malts , and a flavor which delivers with a nice hop bitterness at the finish .  refreshing when ice cold , pleasantly balanced when it warms a bit .

devastatingly attractive . dried herb in color . brilliant nose . obviously aged and incredibly smooth on the palate but the cellaring destroyed the hop presense .  the carbonation is surprisingly strong for the style .

clear golden amber body with a steady level of carbonation and head that leaves a quarter inch of film like white head ; crystal clear .  the mouthfeel is sort of watery , but it 's alright . this drinks very well .
quite nice . p : rather boxy and angular at first , with no discerning flavors other than a malty bitterness .  this beer has a fairly heavy body , a bit too much for my tastes .

smells awesome . if this tastes anywhere near as good as it smells , i will be happy . the smells are simply fantastic - if i have another bottle , i may just let it sit and inhale the fumes rather than actually drinking it .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied to me . could be a little thicker on the tongue .

this beer opens with a strong cranberry wash and finishes with an odd mix of the tart cranberry and heavy saccharine of the molasses . it 's certainly enojyable enough , but has trouble deciding whether or not it wants to be a dessert beer .  it has a pretty high carbonation .

growler the bruery placentia , ca a clear light golden with a big and thick foaming white head . the head sticks around for quite a while and eventually leaves thick and sticky lacing all down the glass .  the palate is somewhat thin for the style but it 's still smooth .
it smells great , a little like their nut brown ale , which along with the oatmeal stout are two of my favorite beers .  m - thin with medium low carbonation d - not a bad amber .

quite nice overall . taste : bit of a letdown here ; there are mild caramel and nutty flavors , but not much depth ... there 's a bit of biscuit on the finish and it 's kind of acidic , almost tart actually , and some mildly fruity flavor that i ca n't quite place and is mildly annoying .  m - thought it was a little flat , but not bad .

the flavor is not quite as complex as the nose would suggest but it is still quite good . it starts out with some dry oakiness followed by dusty cocoa .  m : carbonation is a little weak ( especially since i poured moderately , and received an aggressive head ) leaving a mouthfeel thatis not strong enough for me to consider it cask-like . a little watery ... d : all things considered , i really enjoyed this beer .
1,000 review a- awesome copper red appearance , great foam and nice head when poured from a bottle .  carbonation is a bit low for the style .
pretty simple , but really pleasant . 3.5 t : similar to the nose only very much subdued .  i also find it a little thin .

sediment floats about in a strange vapor-like form . just the head by itself is more complex than most beers , sits on top the whole time , slowly getting all awesome and chunky looking and leaving good lacing .  ill start this by saying i am not a lager drinker by any means . the smell is very summery with hints of citrus and the taste is very malty . the taste is very rounded and balanced . nothing is too harsh or overpowering it all just sort of settles around itself . would drink again !

spicy and compliments the smell . m - thin and smooth , carbonation does not come in to play which may be from the age . d - this beer is very drinkable .  mouthfeel is decent , this beer seems to foam up in your mouth .
great foamy white head .  m- medium body that was slightly under-carbonated . with more carbonation , all the flavors would bite that much more .
this is quite possibly the sweetest smelling beer i 've ever sniffed .  m-explosive carbonation . tough to gauge the feel over the bubbles . a bit too carbonated for me .

on the nose : ( hold on a sec , i got ta blow my nose , goddamn pollen ) sweet pine and hops sandwich , a touch of dry alcohol , almost has that earthy breadiness of belgian trappist offerings , slight prune detected as well , an excellent olefactory exercise on the mouth : tastes flatter than it looks , not to a huge detrement mind you . the 10.5 % is subdued on the take , nice warming in the gullet however , not as interesting as the nose , solid but nothing to go gaga over imo . drinkability : for the style it is standard if not a touch boring overall , a nice beer , one to start people out on the style perhaps , the abv is well hidden here so take some care .  very good light lager . hints of barley and hops , with a smooth slightly dry aftertaste . this brew had a short lived white foamy head and lower than normal carbonation . i would highly recommend this to any light beer drinker .

a massive , three-inch head rose up to the top of the tulip glass . lacework aplenty . a real beauty .  i 'd love to try this on cask , if only to taste it more directly without all the carbonation dancing across my tongue .

750ml a : really looks great with red notes . the amber color really makes this look appetizing .  in the glass , the elderberry dominates . the taste just off , sour in a nasty way , more like rotten fruit than any sort of pleasant tartness which might be expected from the berries . we gave this a decent try to see if it would get better , but in the end just could n't drink it .
smell : really great smelling chocolate aromas .  body is light and a bit watery , not too syruppy at all .
beer pours black with a creamy brown head .  m : crisp feel at first , mellows gradually before eventually becoming a little sticky/gummy . light-medium body .

average lacing & head retention s : coffee & a bit of chocolate , grows stronger as this warms t : coffee grounds , black patent malt , a bit of mocha & herbal hops up front .  t : bitter chocolates and cold black coffee .mmmmm m : a bit thin in the mouthfeel , slight warming in the finish which i found dry .
great aromas of chocolate , caramel , vineous fruit and roasted grain . could have used some more bitterness , but a fairly good beer overall .  the body is pretty light though and clean .
this beer looks really , really nice .  its sucks to know that in a different format this could be so much more . body and carb is okay , but by this point i 'm already at the meh stage .

the aroma is just amazing . it is easily the best smelling ipa i 've had in my young beer tasting career .  i was not a big fan of the mouthfeel of this one . i 'm all for thick imperial stouts , but somehow this one was much more syrupy than i liked , it felt a little to sticky sweet in my mouth .

many thanks to drweizen for sending this in his shipment of holiday beers ... the beer is quite carbonated ( with a slow pour , i got half head ! ) and leaves a gorgeous lace pattern on my glass .  the taste is also very floral and hoppy , but its a smooth onset of flavors , doesnt smack you like other ipas , which ca be good or bad . the flavor doesnt last as long as other beers in this catagory . overall a pretty good beer , i think most peple will enjoy this one .

appearance - ruby/amber with a light brown head . alcohol is very present , almost like a rum in the presentation .  smell was sweet , with a citrus hint and strong english ale smell . initial taste was interesting , and i was n't sure about whether i would like it . by the end of the bottle , it had become one of the best beers i 've tasted . i would n't recommend it for any parties , but in small groups of like minded people i would say good call . very drinkable beer . looking forward to trying more from the brewery ( if i can find it )

chocolate head over a pitch black pit , some sweet lacing ... some mild anise and roasted malts tingle the nose , also a hint of acetone in there .  the taste is also fresh but a with bit of watery mouthfeel .

on tap stone brew co. escondido , ca a dark , hazy orange with golden yellow edges and a small white cap atop . messy , spiderweb lacing around the glass . a very beautiful glass of beer !  m : average , nothing of note .

a - perfectly clear , fresh honey golden color . s - wow . piney citrus . loads of hop aroma . with the nose , i expected a haymaker of hop bitterness , but it was actually fairly subtle to me . m - medium-bodied , nice feel .  the only complaint i have is that the texture left much to be offered . overall i great beer .

great nose and look that screams hops but the taste is not really that hoppy and has a soft finish that is in contrast to the huge nose . very drinkable but not really a balanced beer and not really fitting the style .  the only detraction i can fin is the below average body .

lovely sugary sweetness , rich chocolate , and coffee nose & # 8230 ; the bouquet shows excellent depth , very inviting . the palate is less enthusiastic . fairly complex & # 8230 ; excellent hops influences at the finish , it builds on the coffee flavors nicely .  mouthfeel was ok .

a - solid black brew that allowed not even the slightest bit of light to peep through ; medium brown head that was retained throughout the session and left a nice coat of lacing s - smell of alcohol was certainly present and the aroma was mostly that of whiskey , with a whiff of coffee scent t - the flavor profile was more balanced than the aroma suggested , with whiskey and coffee as the most prevalent characteristics , though there was a hint of chocolate m - smooth texture with a somewhat sticky finish d - overall easy drinker , but the whiskey flavor lingers a little too long as a result of the sticky finish .  mouthfeel is on the thin side , but not bad . crisp , clean , pleasant in the end -- not overwhelming , a little tart .

very lovely appearance . aroma : roasted malt , oak , dark chocolate , molasses , hints of brown sugar and coffee .  under carbonated and somewhat thin bodied , there is a coffee flavored finish that is truly amazing .

big fluffy cap of beige foam makes a nice stand and keeps itself steady for a good while before dismantling itself to a heavy skim and lots of thick lacing .  flavor is more of the same with enough body to keep the brew honest . good mix of sweet and bitter and a weaker mouthfeel that allows for more on a warm summer day .

strong aroma consisting of citrus bananas , cloves , vanilla and an overall strong alcohol presence . there 's a lot there . the mouthfeel is pretty full although something seems a bit off with a tangy , somewhat sour , very yeasty , citrus ( oranges and bananas ) flavor . i 've had other tripels recently that are better , karmeliet and chimay cinq cents come to mind , but this is a better beer than i original though .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with low carbonation and is a bit watery .

s : wow . the hops smell great in this one . at first it smells like that first hop addition when you are homebrewing . very aromatic and appealing . some grainiess in the background from the malts .  the only thing i was not pleased with with this beer was the mouthfeel .
dark brown pour with a solid tan head .  it was watery with no carbonation , and had a bitter aftertaste . but it had good flavor and decent body , and was fairly clean and easy to drink .
the hop aroma was very good , while the malts were only so-so .  the carbonation is heavy and it adds harshness to the palate . medium-full body .

the spiciness attacks your olefactory senses with a vengence . aroma reminds me of some winter warmers i 've had .  drinkability - taste is pretty good , stays consistent throughout , isnt too thin , and has a reasonable abv so overall this would be a good beer to have a few of if you options are limited .

aroma is just perfect . a slice of pumpkin pie in a bottle is what this beer is . picture perfect . easy to drink with good mouthfeel .  m - takes a major ding here for not having much carbonation . it has a medium body , but the lack of bubbles make this seem borderline watery .

s - the nose on this one is as good as it gets . t - just wonderful - almost as perfect as the nose . this outstanding beer 's only downfall . d - great . tons of booze and heat on this one , but the outstanding vanilla and coconut flavors allow me to drink as much of this as is available !  very carbonated feel on the tongue .

s- jeepers creepers there 's some bugs in there . super sour and funky with lots of acidity in the nose . t- so sour and tart with tons of acidity . bright brilliant sour cherries , strawberries and underipe plums .  the mouthfeel is a bit harsh with the 8.0 % alcohol , but i have found very few tripels that can hide the alcohol content .

body is significantly darker than i 'd expect out of a typical hefe , but not to the point that this should be called a dunkel ; kind of a thickly hazed tarnished bronze , with weird , grainy chunks of yeast . massively fruity , spicy , and complex . it 's nice to see japanese brewers stepping outside the box a little . sadly most of the other flavors from the nose are very subdued here , though the cidery sweetness remains . drinkability : this is one of those beers that 's more fun to smell than it is to drink , but it 's still pretty good . worth whatever exorbitant price i paid for it in nagasaki , but not as enjoyable as the pils .  taste : mirrors the smell , but the flavors are weaker than their aroma counterparts because of a thin mouthfeel .

sure smells like the season . the taste does not live up to the wonderful nose . too bad .  ) i would like a little more bready/chewiness as the mouthful feels a tad more thin than what i 'd prefer for this style .

raw in your face noble hop aroma . just amazing . poured a tiny bright white head that disappeared when i looked away . the hop flavor does n't approach the strength of the aroma , but that could be a good thing .  mouthfeel lots of fizzy carbonation , lighter bodied , finishes dry . the high carbonation combined with a thinner than usual mouthfeel really did throw off the beer making the flavors less prominent than i feel they could have been had the aforementioned two things been toned down a bit .
perfect looking beer .  as readily available as bud , and a whole lot better . a great fall-back session brew , which is good with a meal , or having several at a baseball game .

yeast totally non-flocculating , so even a careful pour would have left 1/2 the bottle behind if i didnt take some yeast . aroma was typical ommegang , sour and spicy with vapors of peach and cherry . palate was less sour than aroma and about 1/2 way between duvel and ommegang ommegang . the `` fine dose of yeast '' did cause massive rumbling in my plumbing later that night though .  palate : medium body , thinner than expected actually , but goes down smooth .

aromas of pine , citrus , floral , and just all around nice and hoppy . tastes a little bit of a let down compared to that nice aroma .  t : wood chips , obviously , tastes like a sauna smells , charcoal , molasses , savory like breakfast sausage , soy sauce , real sharp sweetness that 's broken down by hops lurking in the background and that 's absent at the finish m : medium body , very low carbonation , i 'm surprised this was n't the cask ( it was n't but they did have it ) , dry bitter charcoal finish . the mouthfeel was a big drawback for me , it was very flat , considering this was the draft veraion .

pretty pleasantly sweet smelling brew . taste and mouthfeel : tasted of pumpkin , ginger , plenty of assorted spice , and plenty of very sweet brown sugar flavor in this as labeled .  feel is smooth and well-carbonated though a bit on the thin and watery side . medium-full body , not too heavy . leaves a nice sticky coating around the mouth . a bit thicker and less bitter and it 'd be great .
it has a wonderful smell of yeast and citrus .  the mouthfeel is just a little light for a tripel style . just a little watery and fairly light on the tongue .
pours a dark brown with nice ruby highlights and a very frothy cappuccino head that lasts and leaves abundant lacing .  m - nothing special . just a regular lager thing .

very hoppy taste . right away you can smell the cascade hops which it smells like its been dry hopped . hopefully i bought an older six pack  texture is smooth but only slightly fizzy , leaving a slightly sweet fruity finish .
s : strong enticing smell of toffee , vanilla and butterscotch . t : much the same as the smell .  nothing spectacular in terms of mouthfeel , but i 'll buy it again .

a - deep dark , opaque black color with a thick head , excellent retention s - gentle coffee-like roasted grain , malty , no hops noticed t - roasted grain characterized by coffee and tobacco flavors ; hop balance but no detectable flavors ; fairly clean for an ale , but faint hints of yeast esters noticed ( but appropriate ) m - medium-to-light body with moderate carbonation d - this is quite an enjoyable milk stout .  the colour is a light straw , probably the weakest colour i have seen in a pale lager , the head is very pleasent and has some serious glass cling ... the aroma is very skunky when first opened but quickly disappears and the taste is highly sweet malts on a thin body , very nice for dining , not a stadium brew ... i first reviewed this brew in march of 03 , approx 10 monthes ago .

it reeks of pumpkin pie without being too aggressive with it . the pumpkin pie aroma does n't dominate the taste and it actually tastes like a beer instead of some kind of pumpkin pie flavored wine cooler .  have you ever canned tomatoes ? if you have , you should be familiar with the smell and flavor tomatoes have when cooked . this beer had an overwhelmingly strong odor and taste of spicy stewed tomatoes . it was too strong to drink . i know this is not normal for this beer from the other reviews of it i have read ( and the style does n't allow for many strong flavors ) , but it was only days past the best by date and had been stored in a refrigerator . there was also some floating particles in the beer which i also assume is not normal , pilsners typically being filtered . i will come back and rerate , but i 've been told by some fellow raters that i should take this beer into account for my rating .

smells absolutely wonderful ... pungent aroma of hops all the way ... piney , citrusy hops and i 'm loving it ... i want to smell this all night ... terrific blend of piney/grapefuit hops and sweet malts.. thought this was going to be a hop bomb all the way which would have been fine but i 'm surprised at the balance on this one .  mouthfeel was ok ; about the same as urquell .

750ml , 2009 ( ? ) vintage pours pitch black and completely opaque with a one finger frothy beige head that slowly fades into a lasting ring . sporadic rings and spots of lacing are left behind .  it smells of rotten banana peels , rotten apples , and molding compost . the flavors are very sweet and kind of medicinal . it leaves a clove laiden aftertaste behind , making you think you just had an artificial banana milkshake . i just do n't understand what two brothers was going for on this one .

11.2 oz brown bottle with best by date beer is a beautiful medium brown . nice 2 inch head made-up of very small bubbles , no foaming agents here !  this is a very good pumpkin beer . picked a 6 pack up at the local market , came home on a chilly night here in rural mi , and my girlfriend and i finished the whole six pack . lots of pumpkin taste , beautiful color , and an overall great seasonal choice . i would n't drink it in warm weather , but on this cool fall night , it hit the spot . i could see picking this up in the future to bring to a bon fire , or to enjoy while i hand out candy on halloween . cheers !

looks fantastic ! sort of a hazy golden apricot colour with a finger of foamy head that sticks around .  initial taste of a sparkling mouthfeel with a puckering sour cherries that coat the mouth incredabily . the palate duration is average . medium body .
