a- pours orange-amber with a massive , foamy and creamy head that retains amazingly , gives duvel a run for its money . the cloud is as big as the head of others .  less fizzy than anticipated in the mouth .

smell : lovely aroma of toasted fresh bread with earthy hints of nuts , vanilla , and molasses . drinkability : starts off with a great aroma , but the taste slips just a bit .  nice dark brown color with fantnaztic lacing ! smells choclotly with coffee . tastes even and thick with cocoa sweet caramel flavors continuing thru . good for its class this porter represents well , its much better than its younger brother . would drink again .

nitro-tap , nice pour into a pint glass at henry 's 12th street tavern in portland . color is brownish-black , thick tan head has excellent retention all the way to the end .  i wish the carbonation was a little more noticeable in the mouth .

smell was deep with plenty of sweet chocolate aromas and bitter grains .  a : dark reddish copper ; flat head ; strong carb ; not much lacing s : strong raspberry aroma , very inviting ; occludes other smells t : expected sweet -- it is n't ; the raspberry dominates , but it 's quite sour , draped over a wheat-beer-like base ; i must confess , this tasted terrible to me ; it tasted like nothing else i 've had , so i do n't think this is something against the genre m : good carbonation redeems the experience a bit overall , a terrible beer , for me .

pours straw yellow , with little head . ruby red grapefruit dominates the smell . very bright citrus , little malt .  i like a little heavier of a mouthfeel than this offers , but the lighter feel is not surprising considering the crystal appearance .

30 cl brown bottle poured into a pint glass ( it 's the only glassware i own ) . a : super-thick , rich , creamy , mostly white foamy head . in fact , the head was so thick that this small 300 ml bottle would n't fit into my imperial pint glass without waiting for some of the head to thin out .  it is about a medium mouthfeel , with almost no carbonation .

a : pours amber color , small white head , slight lacing down the glass s : smell is very citrusy , slight malt background t : taste is also very citrusy .  mouthfeel is fairly thin but not unpleasant .

nose : oaky vanilla , caramel/toffee and apple skins dominate this so-called imperial ipa . insanely sweet and syrupy like most of dfh 's `` super beers '' ( ww stout , raison d'extra ) .  mouthfeel is a bit too thin , especially in view of the heavenly head and ample lacing .

the aroma on this beer was exceptional . cinnamon and plum came across strongly , along with hints of ethanol and orange rind . it had a nice bitter finish , but i struggled for awhile to get a handle on the sweet , fruit flavors that seemed to stay with the beer for the duration . i was thinking cherry with a few orange notes , it seemed very familiar , and then i finally put my finger on what it was reminding me of : cough syrup .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with medium to high carbonation .

reviewed 12/27/2008 ( bottle ) : pours a pretty clear darkish orange colored body , with a huge foamy off-white head , very lasting .  m : um . it was carbonated and did n't leave any odd off flavours on the palate .

s - best feature . aroma of bananas , clove and bubble gum t - caramelized sugar , sour mash , banana m - a bit sour as you drink through the bottle , like an underripe banana , cloying sweetness d - becomes monotonous the more you drink of it .  a sticky medium body with good carbonation . a bit too sticky for me .

poured into tulip glass from 12oz bottle ... a- bright crystal clear gold . large two finger fluffy white head . one of most beautiful dipa i 've seen .  the taste is awesome m : medium bodied , perhaps a bit too heavy , with decent carbonation , not the best , but is good enough for an apa .

head retention was excellent , melting down to a slightly less huge frothy , rocky head . lacing was thick and plentiful ... .a beautiful looking beer .  the body was light and there was not enough carbonation .
smell- nice pungent scent of pine hops amidst lots of powdered sugar .  mouthfeel is a bit thin , but thats a minor complaint .

aroma is very fruit dominated , and not by any single one . peach , lemon , starfruit , lime , mango ... it 's an intoxicating tropical melange . some contrasting oak and fresh yogurt notes are there too , lending some harmonizing 'wild ' elements without getting too funky . flavor is moderately puckering , tart and verging on lemony sour . hop elements are present though indistinct in the mix , lending some possible leafy orange tea notes , and residual bitterness .  s - some grassy hops paired with caramel malt t - slight hop bitterness resolving into some serious roasty malt , but then it 's all gone fairly quickly with just a hint of woody bitterness m - quite light with just a hint of carbonation on the back of the tongue ; the slight bitterness endures for a whlie d - quick drinkable , though the excessive roasty malt will probably get in the way ; little to no alcohol warmth nice drink ; did n't expect it to be as dark as it is - listed as an american porter , but it 's almost a supercharged brown ale .

s : smells phenomenal ! booze , oak , and sweet sugars upfront . breadiness on the backend . t : good . not great . has a nice boozy / oakiness to it , not a whole lot else .  first off , great pics , great blurb on the back , just fantastic presentation . this beer is belgian to the core , color , nose , taste . there 's an abject fizziness to the brew i could do without , reminds me of shasta in the summer of my youth , a memory i did n't need to dredge up . taste is sweet & light . barring the cost , this is the kind of beer i could drink all night . this is a solid beer , but not the hellion i was expecting .

the aroma is particularly good on this stout ; there is a lot of fresh blueberry aroma , along with nutty , chocolaty , and yeasty aromas to compliment . the beer pours with a very deep black color and a head that stays around the rim of the glass leaving a swirl on top of the beer . from the smell i expected this to be very fruity , which in it 's own right it is , however not in an alcipop sort of way . flavors that hit the tongue right off the bat are a little overwhelming but very nice to pick through .  the mouthfeel is thin , however , and it 's over-carbonated .
a : black it is ! with a thick brown head .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied .

it smells nicer than it tastes , imo , but is still a nice porter !  rated as a stout the mouthfeel is a bit thin , the carbonation is a bit high , and the finish is a bit less than one would expect .

typical of the wheat and carapils . s - pineapple , mango , apricot , piney hops balance with the carapils aroma . all in all , good balance . m - smooth medium body with soft carbonation . d - well , i ca n't really detect any alcohol , it drinks really fast , and it 's delicious .  mouthfeel is light , and carbonation is set at medium .
a real nice sniffer .  light bodied for what i was expecting , but then it does n't claim to be a porter or stout .
smell is perfect - best smelling sour i 've ever had .  some hop aroma and flavour , a little to light in the body for my liking .

s : very , very nice . belgian yeast and sweet breads hit first , closely followed by pine and citrus hops . nice complexity and balance here .  alex dumped this on this ! ... pours an ugly apple cider color , murky medium brown , not much carbonation ... the aroma is terrible , generic wood , rotting pears , and vanilla . ca n't stand this ... the taste is dry hopped wood ; a piece of wood that was drenched in dry hopped water . this is ugly , and smells and tastes terrible . skip

the aroma is very deep -- anise , fennel , mocha , coffee and a burning alcohol nose -- awesome . really a marvel . strange .  mf : a bit thin , light body , medium to high carbonation d : another winner from sierra nevada .

a : pours a golden amber color with light copper edges against the light . has a frothy off-white head that retains pretty well at a fingers ' thickness , and deposits nice lacing down the glass .  active carbonation to form lacing but it does n't feel on the heavy end of the carbonation spectrum .

s : kiwi fruit and pink watermelon with a hint of yeast , very pleasant . t : nice floral component , early on flowery with and hint of dandelion greens and grass .  m : medium light body with medium high carbonation .
s- excellent . wheat , yeast , and citrus immediately hit the nostrils as you pour this one . t- initial taste of sweet malt and citrus .  but a little watery .

2009 bottle a : poured in goblet-1/2 inch thick fluffy khaki head , lasted about 2 minutes . amber/ red , light brings out reddish hues even more . good carbonation , light stick lacing .  mouthfeel & drinkability : lighter bodied and less bitter than most other ipas , which makes for quite easy drinking .

pours a clear orange , chunks , one of the coolest looking heads ever , kind of a reverse cascading tan , head goes fast , some lace .  the nose of the beer is strong and gives off a nice floral hop aroma . the flavor is sweet and semi-tart with fruity tastes . behind the sweet fruit , there is a slight but smooth alcohol presence . the earthy hop bitterness comes in at the end and fades away with the semi-dry finish .

pouring a deep black with ruby tinting around the edges , out of bounds also has a creamy , tan head which gives way to an attractive , spotted lacing .  mouthfeel : a bit thin the only thing i can say i 'm disappointed about here just seems watery i even recall the original munich formula having more body but hey sturdy carbonation excellent o-fest .

341ml bottle poured into pint glass feb4 2010 a reddish brown with loads of sediment being pushed around by a large amount of tiny bubbles . the head is massive and has great retention and leaves a fair bit of lace as it slowly falls .  m : a bit overcarbonated , dry , thin , light-medium bodied .

i 'm intrigued by the label that tells me this beer is a mix of young and old ipas aged in french oak ; intrigued because i like hops and like the effect that age can have on hops . i liked the earthy , woody aroma of this ale . i liked how the earthiness and vanilla-oakiness emerged among the caremelly malt and herbal hop flavors .  m - the hops lingered a bit too long and had a metallic feel at times .

12 oz bottle cloudy , dull golden amber color with a massive , creamy light brown/off white head . very dense and foamy , the head hangs around forever and leaves a lot of lacing .  decent carbonation , a little thin on the malt profile for the style .

poured into a fluted glass around 6c a : copper and crystal clear , with a nice 2 finger tan head that lasts a long time and laces nicely .  i am starting to view the boston beer co. as a-b or miller taking a stab at the craft market but still wanting to appease the masses rather than being strict to beer styles . a big dissapointment for an apa
looks really viscous and is extremely dark . excellent cascading head .  m : medium body and high carbonation .

smell is hops - straight , beautiful hop smell . seriously , smells awesome . okay , taste is lagging behind a ways .  ( i actually do not care for this sweetness , but the beer still has great flavor ) m : nice carbonation , but the body is a little weak .

the beer itself pulls a pitch black into the glass and lets no light through . darkness is right . head retention is decent , leaves a perfect lacing behind .  if you closed your eyes and smelled this you would think your smelling a good octoberfest beer due to the scent of carmalized malt and faint hops . has a carmel toasted nut flavor on the tounge and finished dry . i like the fact that this irish red is a little more bitter than most red ales but still not overpowering . tongiht i will be reviewing 4 of hook and ladder beers as i bought a gift pack that came with 3 bottles of 4 different beers . the beers i got were backdraft brown golden ale pipe and drum irish red ember amber ( a type of black and tan made with their backdraft brown ale and golden ale ) . try these beers if u can find them they are good

one of my all-time favorites ... have n't had this in a couple years now ... midnight black with a small tan lace ... great nose ... sweet milk chocolate ... some java tones ... some roasted malts ... a little thin in the mouth ... not as a rich as i remember ... nice burnt malt taste ... not as much of a creamy texture as i remembered ... .not as good as i remembered but still solid ... .a pretty dry finish ... .i 'm a bit disappointed as i came into this review expected to put this in the high 4 's , but it is not that good ... still it is worth trying if you see it .  m - decent body with a bit more carbonation than i 'd like from this style .

the aroma is very nice , a heady mixture of malt , honey and alcohol . unfortunately the flavor does n't come close to fulfilling the promise in the aroma . the body is carbonated with a rather lager-ish character .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin and harsh from the acidity and carbonation . also finishes quite dry with little to no bitter .

22 oz bomber served in a tradional english pint glass this beer poured a cloudy medium to light brown , with decent 1 inch dense head that left moderate to heavy lacing .  m - light body , with a carbonation level that is probably too sharp for the style .
smell is flowery , and very aromatic .  malty and corny .

appearance- deep brown-caramel colored pour . leaves wonderful lace streaks and patches . almost the entire glass was caked with lace after i was finished .  slight hint of the hop flower but the malt dominates , sweet , crisp , fresh and pleasing to the senses with the start lightly sweet , satisfactory malt presence , and top light to middling in feel . this is a style where i like the lighter body , as it lets the flavoring hops shine through , quite quaffable , a damn fine session beer me thinks , and i thank royalt for this bottle .

5.0 s : this is my absolute favorite type of dipa , i can tell already . it has a malt bill that can stand up to the hops in flavor and complexity . hops are citrusy with emphasis on orange and grapefruit . malts are full of caramel flavor and dark fruitiness like a barleywine . i did n't know what the hell i was tasting . the malts were a big disappointment as it was n't as complex as i would have liked . mainly just has the caramel flavor . 4.5 d : i would definitely like to have this been again , but not too often since it 's quite expensive .  m-its a little undercarbonated but the balance of the sweetness with the malt and subtle hops make for a relitivly complex october beer . d-easy to drink and very nice to have this time of year , easy to session .
a- pretty beautiful . a reddish amber color , just glowing .  m - smooth and thick , but hard to hold onto . unpleasant taste does n't do it well .

the aroma is like a fine , dark , bitter black coffee . it actually has more of a sharp aroma than a lot of ris 's i 've had . this beer has a light apperance and a strong nose , but the taste parrallels the appearance . this beer has enough flavor and an intense aroma that can keep me interested for a few pints .  m : mouthfeel is decent , goes down reasonable smooth even with the slight burning sensation .

excellent . sweet and sour fruits cominate the taste , but caramel malts creep slowly in , along with alcohol , honey , and even some wood . the feel ends up pleasantly sweet and smooth .  the body is surprisingly light with moderate carbonation , helping to make this very drinkable .

poured with a massive head and beautiful lacing with a murky golden tint - i have to admit the pour was promising .  unfortunately , it is basically flat , with a heavy mouthfeel . overall , this beer would be unbelievable with good carbonation .

do n't be turned off by the little green specks floating around as they are chucks of hops leftover from fermentation and help accentuate the huge hoppy aromas . pours a nice creamy golden color with slight greenish hue to foamy head . aromas of malts and hops give way to dried fruit .  m- very carbonated and light for a lager .

poured into a guinness tulip pint on st patty 's day with a big , booming , thick , puffy head that slowly reduces to lacing . very nice .  mouthfeel is a bit fizzy , and another beer where bottle-conditioning would have a positive impact .

black as the abyss with a dark sticky head .  much like the ingredient list on the back , there are scent of malted barley , malted wheat , hops , and yeast which gives it an almost caramel scent . starts out making you think this will be a heavy tasting beer with its malted ingredients like a stout but instead it finishes rather light . drinks rather smooth as the malted ingredients really hit the taste buds . finishes rather clean smooth . a decent beer with a rather interesting drinking experience .

brilliant color ! poured fairly rough and produced a solid one-and-a-half-finger head that 's dense and creamy like whipped topping . good retention that went down to a rich layer and left thick patches of lacing .  mouthfeel is about average for an ipa .

body is a pretty golden amber color , crowned by a good amount of thick white head that leaves some good lacing on the glass .  the mouthfeel is a bit watery and cool in texture , it goes down nicely and is a little bit better than water .

smell : piney hops , citrus ( grapefruit , peach and pineapple ) . overall : the aroma was out of this world . it 's very much like an ipa . just did n't seemed very well balanced .  mouthfeel was unremarkable .
a nice , interesting nose .  drinks a little heavy because of all the sediment but feels watery and thin on the palate . adequate carbonation but not incredible lively .

super sweet aroma with lots of yeast an plenty of sweet , dark fruit . some toffee aroma as well . sweet flavor , though there 's a little sharpness there as well that reminds me , again , a little of port .  m : thin , do n't take that the wrong way though but easy drinking .

terrific . tons of pepper and biting bitterness on the tongue . big letdown from the outstanding aroma . lots of citric flavor , especially grapefruit and orange , but the sweetness of the malt just does not do any justice to the balance and drinkability .  has a very light mouth feel , which makes it a more-then-one beer .

no head retention or lacing huge oaky , fruitty boozey nose , beautiful t : dryness , raisins , dates , & breadyness with a slight booze presence up front .  mouthfeel is a little thin and aftertaste is a little too much ... like the brew has gone stale , although i know it has n't .
the pour was impressive as a dark chocolate filled my beer mug , the smell was pretty good with those hints of chocolate coming to bear .  m : a little thin in body d : good .

the scent is sweet and hoppy . there is also a freshly milled pale malt scent that is very nice . i ca n't wait to drink this beer .  take this beer for what it is ... a nice `` treat . '' it 's not something you will want to drink all night long . but for a nightcap , or change of pace this beer fits the bill . the vanilla taste is not overpowering , it 's there , but not so bold and overpowering that it seems fake .

the scent on this beer is very sweet . tons of grapefruit and orange come through very strongly . also get a lot of alcohol in the nose . upon first sip , i get so much thrown at me at once . the hops are a bit overwhelming , as well as the booziness .  the mouthfeel is decent , but could be a bit more robust to support the flavors .

i absolutely loved the smell of this , chocolatey , with some sweet fruits from the yeast and subtle hop profile .  i got this beer in the beers of the world gift box for christmas . immediate taste is a lil sharp and bready with a hint of citrus in the smell . it was not an out of this world experience , but it is a very light and enjoyable beer for everyday or get togethers .

the smell is probably the best part of this beer . sweet and herbal with a touch of honey , hazelnut , citrus of some kind . the finish is very dry . pretty cool beer .  presentation 11.2 oz ''ceramic '' bottle with blue foil over the cap no date on bottle . pours with a think creamy head that dissipates as quickly as is rose . light brown with a hind of deep red . a smell of caramel and alcohol , taste is more of the same with a slight earthiness to it . finishes cleanly .

smell is amazing ! nice and sweet and very hoppy . very appealing and aromatic . a very good blonde .  m- a little thin , but not too bad . nicely carbonated , with a slight bitter hoppiness at the tail end .

huge four fingers of bright white , soapy head .  but it has quite a few pros : this beer is intended to be consumed with food . if you want to have chinese food with a light drink then this one is just what you are looking for ! it 's a typical lager : crystal-clear blonde , discreet taste and weak aroma . i usually do n't drink lager beers but this one i can have by the barrels while there 's food on the table . this beer is what you want to drink when you do n't want to drink !

a very strong and pleasant aroma . tastes light honey sweetness and clove up front with perhaps a bit of orange zest fading to bready malts with trace hop bitter finish .  i 've always liked this beer , and if they beefed up the abv and gave it a little more body , it would be the perfect porter . why grant 's beers share these characteristics i do n't know , but if they ever did beef 'em up a little , they could truly be a contender .

( s ) - a very fruity aroma with fresh orange peel and lemon . a very vibrant fruit driven profile with hints of a hay/wheat dryness .  t & m : for a doppelbock a little thinner bodied than is usually expected .
poured a very deep brown with a massive brown head and tons of carbonation .  the middle is kind of hoppy , but somewhat thin . the finish is dry and quite hoppy . a decent light beer .
a pretty good looking beer .  mouthfeel : pretty heavy for a porter but very drinkable even in the heat .

aroma was ridiculously appealing - sweet malt , caramel , maple , vanilla , oak , some dark fruit , and alcohol . wow . d - this was a sipper , but drinkability benefited from the fact that it tasted so damn good .  this is a bit thin , but still great .

a definitive malty , smoky scent with maybe a hint of apple lurking .  i have had ipas that went down a bit smoother but this one is n't bad it still goes down good but with just a little more carbonation and bite .

the smell is also great , sweet and hoppy and quite complex with smells of oak and apricot as well . the oak is a nice note in the aroma , but becomes too much on the taste level with very heavy oak throughout and unddetones of dry vanilla . mouthfeel is nice as far as heft goes , and theree is a good bit of creaminess , but the tannic oak cuts against it somewhat . too unbalanced for me to really call this very drinkable .  mouthfeel was very thin for the style , but added to the higher level of drinkability .
brown shugga pours a gorgeous copper color .  mouthfeel is a bit light .

appearance - very dark red , but clear and looks quite impressive when held up to light . 2 fingers of head with very good retention and lacing .  surprisingly light mouthfeel makes it a fairly easy drinker for a 9 % er

this beer has a decent amount of hops for an apa and the nose is quite nice , but the flavor and mouthfeel do n't offer enough to really set this beer apart .  mouthfeel : light/ medium body with excessive carbonation that somewhat hinders the flavor .
absolutely one of the most beautiful beers when poured into a dimpled stein . amazing ruby red with a thin layer of beige head that dissipates quickly .  medium body , maybe even a bit thin .

plenty of bubbles could be observed rising through the body , in short , it looked great ! the head produced somegood laceing as the beer was consumed .  the only downside of this beer was the mouthfeel , which was fairly flat and watery , probably due in part to the low % abv .

i actually smell this beer about 2 feet away when opening . very citrusy and piney , a small amount of orange juice sweetness is present . a very nice extreme beer , i may be afraid to try fresh .  a really really long aftertaste in the nose .

rings of lacing were left on the glass as the chugging commenced - nice ! the aroma was of a fruit forward chardonnay . citrus and floral scents were immediately detectable , along with a sweeter malt characteristic and alcohol .  a little less carbonation and this probably enters `` special '' territory .

smell : smells fantastic . sticky , sweet , grapefruity , piney , lemony with a touch of pepper on the back end . i will try again , just because it was so delicious .  yack ! i 've had this lots over the years , but this time it got a major problem with butterscotch . aroma smacks me down wth that butterscotch - ugh . but , somewhere in there is some malt and a little chocolate , good malt . flavor is butterscotch - blaaahh . ca n't finish it . draft lines are clean here too . no more , pleeeeze

delightful aroma but blindfolded you would never identify this as a strong dark . regardless , very nice . salvation rr reasserts itself in the taste .  smell : balanced scent with undertones of both malt and hops ; predominant smell is faintly sweet yet mainly grainy aroma . taste : well-balanced flavor , neither hops nor malts are predominant , the combination of which is apparent throughout the beginning and middle , dissapating for a clean finish . drinkability : refreshing and palatable , the quality of yuengling speaks for itself . definitely a beer that can be enjoyed regularly .
i was much more impressed by the pour and visual of this beer than by taste or drinkability . nice puffy styrofoam cloud of a head .  light-medium bodied with crisp high carb .

pours a dark black color with a thin brown head .  ordered this one in a taproom and was vary pleased . this beer is solid , as one might expect from north coast . it 's is as good as any pilsner i 've had . it drinks easy , has a hint of subtle fruit flavor , and smells very good . it also pours very nicely from the tap with a fluffy head . i 'd pick this one again on draft and might pick it up as a favor for a host when a house guest .

the hop aroma is like sticking your nose in a bag of cascade hops and taking a deep breath .  does smell a little like `` beer , '' as my wife would say . so sweet on the tongue . slight raspberry tartness but it is like drinking raspberry sorbet after it melts . it is still trying to recover from the sweetness . a good once in a while beer . sorbet beer , i tell ya .
pours a cloudy yellow with amazing white head that stays through out the whole glass .  there is a very little carbonation factor in this beer .

poured the 22 oz bottle smells amazing , looks great , with good carbination the flavor let me down , the initial impression was stellar but followed by a light bodied lingering hop flavor that doesnt seem to justify the body style of the beer .  im stoked i can try a beer from this brewery even tho it is a collaboration but ive got nothing but good things to say about mikkeller and heard good reviews on these other two so looking forward to it , it pours a very light honey hue with decent carbonation that leaves a one finger head with sporadic lacing , the aroma is floral hops , apricot , bananna and a nice belgian yeasty aroma too , it has an average mouthfeel for the style almost syrupy and has tastes of yeasty bread , citrus and of course a pleasant floral hop finish with the alcohol well hidden , this is definately an easy beer to drink and if it didnt cost $ 18 ( aus ) i could drink it all night .

poured from a 12oz bottle , into a 16oz glass mug , color was a beautiful hazy golden , with a huge 3 finger+ fluffy head .  i picked this lager over the ale 's offered , due to the miserable heat wave here in no . cal . it was an appropriate choice . saaz hops seemed to be prominent with good malt base . a nice refreshing beer . nothing spectacular but very acceptable when in the mood for this style .

very double ipa , and enjoyable . taste is more subtle than i was expecting , bitter hops all the way through .  body is medium , and perhaps errs to light every once in a while , which does n't help the flavours as much as it could .
pours a very dark brown with a nice frothy one finger of off white head that sticks around a while .  m - smooth going down , a bit thin , finishes dry .

probably the sweetest ipa i 've run across . aroma of candy and berries . nicely hopped with clear strawberry and other berry notes .  m- a little too carbonated for my liking , that makes this beer have a little `` sting '' to it ( especially if it is served too cold ) .

s : earthy tart wheat , lots of honey , sweet toffee , and a nice floral hop/heat combination . bit-o-honey candy comes to mind .  easy drinking but it has a different mouthfeel , it almost leaves a film in my mouth .

it has a really nice , spicy aroma with a solid grain backbone .  its perfectly balanced and not overly done . m very medium , which i find most all stone beers to be and i dont really complain about . the carbonation is present and isnt overly aggressive or submissive .

smell only needs one word : raspberries . lots of raspberries . also smells a bit tart and kind of like juice . very sweet and tart at the same time .  all of the good notes that a belgian has , with some american notes such as a much higher rate carbonation , more citric fruitiness . the high carbonation almost makes me question whether or not it 's natural , but i doubt stone would rape this brew with added co2 like the macros do .

smell : lovely aroma of apples , pears , and light citrus - notably grapefruit . slightly sour smell comes in at the end . a very sour character shows up that is a bit cloying , then the beer finishes strong and unpleasantly bitter .  it feels very thin in the mouth , close to water .

looks less viscous then i had expected smell is bourbon all the way . probably the most bourbon i have ever smelled in a ba beer . the smell prepares you for a very chewy brew but the mouthfeel isnt so .  mouthful : somewhat over-carbonated but generally decent mouthfeel .

body is somewhat lighter expected while pouring , but looks black in the glass s : oak and coffee , come sweet roasted malt . t : slight sweetness .  beer/brewery - old fezziwig ale/boston beer company ( samuel adams ) city/state- boston , massachusetts style winter warmer abv 5.9 % ibu 27 date 10 dec 2011 serving type 12 oz bottle glassware pub glass appearance mahogany in color with a thin head with a brownish white color aroma- fruity and winter spices , all spice , clove and nutmeg i think taste pumpkin pie without the pumpkin , a lot of clove , also has a bit a of a bitter ( non hop ) after taste mouthfeel very light and bland ob feeling conclusion other than the after taste this is a great christmas beer , not quit a winter warmer as they abv is a little low , but still a good flavor to think of around christmas .

espresso and chocolate aromas , with hints of vanilla , roast and brownies , quite the vibrant little blend of malt aromatics . slightly bitter and astringent malt , but still decadent and enjoyable , with chocolate and cream flavors .  light body with a very active carbonation .

aroma is a nice fresh hop scent .  could use more malt or residual sweetness but for a regular american coffee stout it does the trick mouthfeel is a touch thin and watery but there is a bit of creaminess from the nice carbonation that keeps this one going .

poured into a nonic . pitch black with two fingers of creamy off white , frothy head . looking good .  the reason behind that tenacity turns out to be that it 's a bit overcarbonated . there 's a great nuttiness in the flavor here that i 'm seeing as chesnuts , but it could be the power of suggestion , and a little bit of roast . tasty , but just a tad too gassy .
smells very tasty .  mouthfeel if very alive and crisp at first sip . maybe a bit overpowering on the carbonation .

begins with a very strong and pleasant aroma , sweet and alcoholic with raisin notes dominating and , upon further reflection , a hint of lemon ( ? the strong aroma and dark color leads one to expect a full-bodied , malty sweet meal in a glass .  i found that the beer smelled and tasted rather skunky , unlike most other beers that i had tasted and was deeply disappointed by it . it felt ok in the mouth and looked very nice in its green bottle but was not worth my time .

beautiful 3 finger head , caramel , frothy and persistent , reddish mahogany nice stream of bubbles , good lacing ; if this did n't look so inviting i would put it on a shelf and leave it there forever !  it 's almost too sticky and thick to be pleasureable , kind of like a toned-down bourbon county stout . i 'm not a big fan of the finish , which comes off like sweet wort of a stout ( oily and a bit thin ) . m : very thick , with some relief , but then a lingering silkiness .
pours brown with ruby hints . there are two healthy fingers of head ( boy , is this a live beer ) and the retention and lacing are top notch .  m : medium mouthfeel with moderate carbonation .

smell : the wonderful aroma starts with the smell of concord grapes . holy hell , this liquid smells amazing . its like a huge fruit salad mixed with brandy and raisins ! taste : so does it taste as good as it smells ? well , the taste is of plums , raisins , and maybe prunes .  the mouthfeel is medium with some sharp carbonation .
great retention and lacing . looks fantastic .  feel is thin bodied overall , but well bodied for the style .

the nose is excellent . chocolate , caramel , dark breads , a little honey and molasses . the nuances from the nose did n't really carry over .  this is the least impressive quad from the trappist breweries ... do n't get me wrong , it has a similar taste profile , although not that perfect as a westy 12 or a rochefort 10 , dark fruit , plums , candy sugar , but i did n't like the mouthfeel on this one . too much sparkling going on ... pretty funny thing is i just absolutely endlessly adore the la trappe quadrupel oak aged batch 1 version ... so so so much better then the regular one , especially when the oak aged version , bottled this summer , is coming around fantastic ! i like their dubbel more too .

aroma is very malty : my schnoz detected caramel , spice , wine-like notes , and a certain booziness . we had beatification , allagash black , westvleteren 8 and westvleteren 12 before this beer , so maybe it was just upstaged and i might have thought it exceptional on any other night .  m : thin mouthfeel with moderate carbonation .

it poured amber in color with a creamy-brown 3+finger head that lasted quite a while . it left gobs of sticky lacing all over my glass .  the mouthfeel is larger light with a very , very slight fizz .
the smell is enticing , pumpkin , cinnamon , and clove . tastes like a belgian brown , but the spice is overdone .  ( m ) - this is where the beer starts to fail in my opinion .

the color is a nice clear , bright amber . the nitro can pours a thick , foamy head that rests nicely on top of the glass and leaves patchy lacing .  m : mouthfeel is a bit thin , considering how robust the initial flavor is .
very bright , very glowing red body . cream-colored head is boisterous and rocky .  mouthfeel : thin yet flavorful .
s : grapefruit and evergreen needles . you can smell the aroma of bold hops from yards away . t : simcoe , welcome aboard .  good carb , but feels a bit thin and watered down in general .
citrus ( grapefruit ) - yes , strong and good , wow . apricot flavor notes .  mouthfeel is fairly carbonated , a bit sour , finishing dry and crisp .

the beer smells absolutely beautiful . like bittersweet chocolate and espresso , with some caramel and molasses notes . this beer smells really fantastic . taste is a lot of the same .  i 've never had this in europe because there are too many good beers over there to risk the experiment , but does it taste better over there ? anyway . the carbonation is nice and the golden hue is lovely . but the smell and the taste are the real reason i drink a beer and this one fails . sorry . i would prefer any american macro brew to this and i will drink alum for the buzz before i 'll drink those so this must be a bad beer .

this beer pours a clear orange with a white , foamy head and smells hoppy and briney with hints of concord grape . personally , i find this beer to be too hoppy ... it would have been very nice without that second , stronger wave of hops .  the feel is a little odd . it does n't seem to be too carbonated , but the bubbles sting like sprite against your lips .

s - the nose is quite nice , suggesting vanilla , oak , smoky whiskey , chocolate and marshmallows . basically the nose is colored like a s'more . o - it is a nice beer , but way underachieving , and almost frustrating to drink as a result .  lively carbonation is a bit excessive , but the body is quite smooth .

aromas are full of the whiskey barrel , but really well balanced with a ton of tree fruit - especially apricots and apples . flavors are a rich mix of fruits , thick bread/yeast , honey - lots of honey , just a kiss of hops , vanilla icing , maybe some fruitcake ... just a lot going on here . and fairly sweet , but delicious . as it warms , it converts to creme brulee and banana pudding - but never loses the whiskey barrel .  12 oz bottle poured into weizen glass , only glass i could get at my buddy 's house a : great pale golden color , light head with decent retention , great clarity s : great floral aromas t : not a pale ale that is actually an ipa , not overly bitter and slight maltiness m : good carbonation , could be a little thinner o : great pale ale , not just a copy of other american pale ales .

amazing . t : sweet malt that has plenty of peat flavors that i love so much in scottish ales .  magic hat usually disappoints me , not that their brews are n't good , it 's that some of them just are n't tasty- till now . magic hats roxy rolles is right up there with ithaca 's cascazilla and troegs hopback amber . a definite seasonal must have for me . great ! ! !
a- golden amber with a creamy one and a half finger head .  very basic but very good m= average carbonation and average weight .

overwhelmingly the finest ipa i 've ever sniffed . perfect . m - very good . nice carbonation and appropriate chewiness without being syrupy .  mouthfeel - foam is scarce and small bubbles and light caramel that fades quickly . slightly thin .

i believe that the triple rock has discovered the perfect color for this sort of beer . it is both red rock and red brick fitting both of its names to a t. head is thin and white with good retention . zero carbonation .  m - surprisingly , its a bit thin and lacks carbonation .
oustanding pine and cedar aroma . as i drink this , the bitterness taste bud region in my tongue goes haywire .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and the carbonation is too light in my opinion .
clear walnut color with a lot of fine streaming bubbles and a rocky , long-lasting head .  m : medium body with a sticky quality when it enters the mouth .
smells pretty tasty .  mf- raw resinous and sticky , becoming oily , medium carbonation , slightly astringent , dry and grainy in the finish d- well rounded ipa , but not the best around .

the aroma of this beer was the highlight for me : banana , apple , belgian yeastiness , other fruits ... really great . golden yellow in color with a small ring of head at the top after it settles . alcohol comes through very nicely . sweet aftertaste is enjoyable .  this review is from notes in my `` travel journal . '' obviously the beer is now `` retired . there is some berry in the attack . the flavor smoothes out to leave a clean finish . it is a very drinkable beer , but not what i normally seek out .

poured a nice golden color with a dense rocky head pronounced piney and citrusy aroma , along with an earthy spice to it . huge hop bouquet . this beer seemed a little thin and light bodied for an ipa .  bought this over a month to two months a go and decided to give it a go . it is an ipa so it does have a nice bright orange to copper color . the taste and the smell are sweet and fruity , the only bad thing i have to to say about it , is the taste of tea is very lacking . i cant pick it up but , other than that i wish that stone , ishii and baird made this more as a yearly offering , cause its really good

when you first pour it , it wafts clean fruity and spicy saison notes . put your nose to the glass and everything intensifies going from mouthwatering to mindnumbing .  i think this batch was contaminated . so , this review only applies to the specific beer i drank . it had a floral hop finish . so , that extra ester punch made it deviate too much from the pale ale style . so i ca n't say i liked it , i 'd try again and find a better batch .
it 's wonderful . t- initial malts , some yeast , bread and biscuity notes , and strong warming alcohol .  m : dense and creamy with low carbonation .

smell is very hoppy , very floral .  had to give it the maximum points for appearance , because even out of an imported bottle , it looks just right . comes in with an alcohol bite that 's almost like an imperial . pertty nice taste , though , and if you had some , i would n't refuse .

wonderful citrus aroma of oranges and grapefruits . the nose is n't just there , it smacks you in the face - and this is a wonderful thing . if i could give higher than a five for aroma on this beer i would . taste - this beer is called hop dragon and consequently is all about hops . great bitter kick that almost goes unnoticed because of all the other great things about this beer .  cons : the low carbonation level does hurt many factors of the beer , but it is such an exquisitely brewed offering , it 's only a minor issue .

beautiful looking beer to be sure , dark , dark brown with a very attractive frothy tan head . just looks so good in the glass .  the mouthfeel is light carbonation , somewhat on the watery side , but very drinkable .

i absolutely love the smell on this beer , but i also love peaty islay scotches . the smell reminds me of a campfire on a beach , with the peaty campfire smoke , wet wood , and leather aromas . the complex aromas are a little subdued on the palate . tons of different flavors in this beer , but none really stand out in front .  m - a little strong on the carbonation for my taste .

starts off creamy white and then cascades from the bottom of the glass to the top changing to black as it goes . there is a thick off white head that lasts forever and covers the sides of the glass in foam and thick rings that mark each swallow .  very pleasant indeed . great hop character . this is a fairly balanced ipa . hard to say , it might just be because this particular bottle is more on the room temp side , but i would like more effervescence . a good beer all in all . i will be sure to drink it again , only a little colder and faster . more drinking , less typing ... .
there is a strong , heavy caramel smell to the beer .  m : thinner than i expected , pretty fair amount of carbonation , once again a little more reminiscent of a porter than a stout .
bottle poured into a glass a : a rich and frothy off white head with great lacing and retention .  maybe a touch too much carbonation .

smell : this beer smells amazing . getting chocolate , coffee , and a little dark fruit . definitely follows the nose . chocolate and coffee , maybe a little raisin .  the mouthfeel is the only thing i think could be improved here and it very well may just be that i am having it from a growler .

one of the best looking beers . the cascade effect is great and the lasting tan head is inviting .  this beer has a lot of flavor for a light . too bad its not a good flavor ! nothing impressive at all here . i 'm not sure what they are putting in this beer but its not worth the 7.99 they are charging for a six pack . i would recommend pabst blue ribbion over this any day !

pours a coal black beer with a good reddish brown head .  a light , medium in body . extremely active on the palate ; too carbonated , that really takes away from this hop-filled wheat 's pleasanty flavors .

the aroma is a nice blend of peaches , caramelized pecans , wheat , toasted bread , and a hint of bourbon . an interesting and unique dunkel , with an amazing aroma but it 's too sweet to have more than one .  not bad at all , really , although a bit thin for the most part .

anyhow , when you have a need for hops , this one certainly takes care of the fix . aroma , yes , just like it should be- huge citrus , flowers , grapefruit rind , oranges , probably lemons and limes if i was n't diving in so fast . this beer has a nice solid body holding in a creamy , milky nectar thats very smooth . the finish is bitter but smooth , maybe a little woody from all the hops . it only lacks a little malt complexity in the flavor , the malt seems a bit basic but does hold up well to the hop explosion .  mouthfeel was ok , not too thin , right amount of carbonation .

a- pale translucent body with thick white head . great head retention . leaves behind plenty of lacing .  the mouthfeel has a little bit more carbonation than i would like a brew of this calibre to have , thus the 3.0 .

nose was also top notch , liqourice comes to mind first followed by a healthy serving of alcohol which was no surprise at this abv , also some very sweet candylike notes as well . taste for me was ok . i really must admit that i had high hopes but this was n't bad by any means just not as i expected .  as with several anchor offerings , i feel the carbonation is a bit overdone , but is n't powerful enough to be overly distracting .

this pours a hazy reddish orange with a 2 finger head of foam . it looks fabulous in my nb goblet .  the taste is ok. it seems a little flat coming out of the can compared to the tap . nice clean finish , no lingering aftertaste . definiteley a session beer if drinking from the tap .

a : nice transparent firey oranges with pleanty of carbonation rushing from the bottom of the glass . s : the first whiff provided an array of tropical fruit notes like mango , peach , pineapple . very much t : sticky resinous pine and bitter grapefruit are the most prominent flavors with hints of citrus coming through in the end . it also has a nice clear herbal finish .  pours a three finger light tan head that fades quickly to a ring leaving a little lace . dark cloudy amber color . light carbonation and light bodied . caramel nose . starts balanced but then a caramel flavor that stays to a clean finish . a tasty wheat . $ 2.49 for a 500ml bottle from john 's grocery iowa city , ia .

50cl bottle poured into my paulaner weissbier glass a - hazy pale golden body , with the thickest ice-creamiest 4 finger head i have ever seen . super brussels lacing on the glass throughout .  t- roasty , sweet malts , coffee and dark chocolate m- starts off nice and creamy and full , then towards the middle loses a bit of it 's body and seems to get watery , only to return with a solid finish .

a true imperial ipa , copious amount of pine and grapefruit . truly a beer geek 's beer ... my wife hated this beer . this is a well-made beer , and i certainly enjoy haivng one every now and then , but more a treat than a beer staple .  m - the feel is not terrible .

strong dance of raspberries , prunes , blackberries , oranges , ribes . you feel it 's still young on the nose too . t : sour taste of raspberries .  had some fruity and clove flavors but was covered up due way too many hops for the style - not to mention that it was bitter . i barely finished it . other reviewers liked this beer and seemed to have a much different experience than i did which leaves me to believe that they have consistency problems or maybe they use different formulas for each location ? btw this one was sampled at the brewpub near the fleet center .

s - the spicy , phenolic aroma hit me as soon as i opened the bottle , and once the beer has a chance to open up in the glass it expands into notes of chocolate , dark cherries , raisins , almonds , pepper , cinnamon , and lots of clove . d - very complex beer that manages to avoid being overbearing despite the high alcohol and big flavors . the smell is absolutely spectacular , reminds me of samichlaus , but more interesting . the flavor is quite interesting as well , and i really like the way it finishes , but there is something about the initial sweetness or phenolic character that i find a little cloying .  i 've been waiting to try this one for some time now and it was well worththe wait ! i could smell it 's fruity aroma as soon as i opened the bottle , it has a nice dark cloudy amber color to it that is topped with a nice thick head . it goes down very smooth and just warms up your mouth , and you can really taste the spices in it .

2009 vintage a- deep violet , crimson red just a beautiful awe-inspiring color and massive towering head that seems to be independent of the beer and an entity all onto itself .  body is fairly thin , but that is expected for the modest abv .
the nose is very complex with hints of soy sauce and salty taffy .  the mouthfeel seems a bit week and flat , but it 's not bad .

aroma of a quad / stout mix with the figs , plums and spices plus a hint of grape hi-c infused vanilla . full bodied , viscous without being cloying , chewy . the alcohol is amazingly restrained , not even the inherent warmth you 'd expect at this abv level .  if i had to log a complaint , it would be that this stout is too thin and less of a cream offering . however , it is full of flavor and easy to drink despite being 6.5 % abv .
aroma , port , sherry . it 's sweet but very inviting . sherry quality very present in the taste .  the body was a bit too thin for my tastes in this style .

the fluid is dark caramelly clear with a huge three finger head of off white , which eventually receded to a half finger width with lacing still attached to the glass .  mouthfeel is a little on the thin side .

as the beer warms , these scents blend beautifully . t : opens tart with assertive notes of grapefruit , lemon , bitter orange , kumquat , grass , salty brine , and oaky , lactic yeast .  m : full bodied but way too over-carbonated .
smell is quite tart smelling , bit of sweetness , can easily make out the raspberry aroma .  too much carbonation for this style ( -1.0 ) .

a nice cloud of white head that really sticks around and leaves nice lacing . beautiful in the glass and that nice tart , musty funky taste .  m-medium body and syrupy with a grainy tough texture . strong carbonation and a slightly messy carbonation in the finish .
aroma is very pleasant . sweet .  ; very sweet ( perhaps overly ) m : a bit syrupy overall , a fantastic barleywine style ale .

this beer smell awesome ! ! ! as i drink it , the problem is , what flavors match up with these aromas ? the beer has a great london/english fruity estery taste with christmas ale type flavors of nutmeg and cinimmon . i wish i had more than one of these to review beacuse its a really complex ale that i would like to clone . a very drinkable ale with a great nutty spicey fruity finish .  mouthfeel is medium with more carbonation that i expected due to no head showing up .

amazingly complex . taste follows nose and begins with dark malts and honey sweetness .  poured from bottle to tulip glass a : brilliantly clear pale yellow color with huge 3+ finger head that fades very slowly n : nose of a light belgian type wit with some light malts , touch of spices , toasted quality , touch of yeast t : starts with more malts and toasted quality , pretty light otherwise , a touch of light fruits and banana , slight earthy marzen quality , no spices m : very light and somewhat watery f : finishes dry and very crisp with a fading earthy marzen taste , would make a good session beer final thoughts : its a very light tasting oktoberfest/marzen .
smell is excellent and unique . predominate smell i get is apricot .  bittersweet finish . kind of think and syrupy on the palate .

amber highlights s- smells of nice mild hops and a nutty undertone t- has a rich caramel taste .  m - nothing special just went down really easy ... .it was n't bad tasting ... .i was surprised how quickly i finished it because it went down fast .
s : sweet and dark ... rich .  a little more carbonation may have helped this one with its texture . just a tad thin , becoming a little dry but not crisp in the finish .

pours a clear amber , nice thick white head forms , as it drops leaves some pretty epic lacing , settles to a nice layer , great retention . looks great , smells good , but the alcohol takes too much of it .  light in body and fairly thin on the tongue . smooth and lightly carbonated .

smell is on the sweet side but hoppy as well , sweet bubblegum scent , weed , juicy citrus and a malt punch , great scent . taste is enjoyable , alot of different things balancing sweet and hoppy in that order with the above mentioned scents going into the taste without the weed .  m : light-medium body with an oily mouthfeel , and a dry and resiny fade overall , not a bad beer , though it does stray from traditional belgian dubbels in a few aspects : not as sweet or yeasty as the classic belgian examples , a little hoppy for the style , and its too light .

pours a dark brown as you 'd expect in a chocolate , and the aroma is pure chocolate . unbelieveable aroma . really hoped that the taste would match , but no .  wow this has to be one of the worst ideas in beer history . trying to cross a pale ale with a belgian and what you got is something that is a distant cousin to both . instead of leveraging the style 's strengths this beer doubles down on their worst attributes . a very hoppy tatse that fights like a strong ale . not a fun beer and a true shame that it might discredit weyerbacher 's other great beers .
very good appearance and smell overall .  medium carbonation .

served in the `` new '' sam adams lager pint glass , the beer pours dark , dark brown ( might as well be black ) with an inch frothy brown head . head retention and lacing are both pretty good .  light to medium bodied , carbonation seems to be at the right level .
nose is heaven , sweet green apples , almost like a sour cider .  lacks hops . lacks malt or any toasting . crisp , dry , clean , even a little bit bitter and metallic .
a - pour pitch black with a tall brown head .  mouthfeel is a bit of a problem for me . the carbonation level is also a factor , making it hard to enjoy in gulps .

smell : wow , mazing ! roasty , dark chocolate , very coffee forward , sweetness . taste : very good , nice and roasty . overall : very good beer , i would certainly want to have this again .  m - a little thinner than i thought and more carbonated than i would expect .

the flavor is a letdown after the excellent aroma . it starts off strong , with bourbon , milk chocolate , and an upper level of roasted malt that continues on to a honey sweet midpalate segment , things seem to go downhill from here with the advent of a combined onslaught of stinging alcohol heat , burnt malt , astringency , and harsh solvent .  the taste is sweet and smooth , with a hint of hops but the most prevalent taste is of lemon . finishes with a very refreshing aftertaste . i would defiantly suggest this beer to even non craft beer drinkers .

it 's a solid gold with a sprightly white head .  the body is is a serious letdown , nowhere near rich/full enough and it crosses the line into watery . the carbonation is appropriately subdued , and does n't overtake the lackluster body .
the aroma kick is amazing , a strong citrus , fresh piney hop nose . overall , highly drinkable , in the west coast pliny type tradition .  mouthfeel is surprisingly light but overcarbonated .

a - a faint haze in an amber brew with a slight reddish tint . a frothy head that is long lived with thick clumps of lacing .  like drinking sour grass , probably the best way to put it m - low carbonation , slightly astringent d - not very drinakble , i had to leave a third of it

t- very very nice . lots of chocolate & lots of coffee .  ) it has very low carbonation witch makes the mouthfell very average with about that of a tap bud lite , only a little tingle from the carbonation .

the smell is very good , nice and spicy in a way that is concentrated without being overly intense .  this beer poured a dirty blonde color , with a haziness that made me suspect that i would n't enjoy this beer too much . aroma was malty , and flavor was a sweet maltiness with only a hint of hops . this was n't what i was expecting from an american pale ale , and i really did n't enjoy it . i may have gotten an old beer , but there is no date code on this beer , so i have no way of knowing its age and it gets what it gets ... most of this one is going down the drain .

very nice . mouthfeel : a little thin and watery . taste : i was a little disappointed after the wonderful aroma . the flavor was very muted and somewhat watery , not unlike the mouthfeel .  m - exceedingly bitter . needs to be a little creamier for this style d - not a session beer .

big hop aroma -- a bit sugary , citric and piney . lots and lots going on just in the scent , and i can feel the back of my tongue tingling already .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and syrupy with a bit of sharp carbonation .

smell : so wonderful ... the smoky peaty aroma fills the nostrils . cloying . i really did n't care for the sweetness of this beer .  m : very thin mouthfeel however strong carbonation makes overall body light but full .
smells of lemony tartness , fresh grainy malts , and yeast .  it is a bit thin , bordering on watery with adequate to slightly low carbonation .

a : dark orange to amber in color , ring of head with nice sticky lacing .  wtf did they do to this beer ? this is the first time i tried it since they put in the new brewhouse and i 'm not impressed . this used to be a wonderfully drinkable beer with orange and subtle spice flavors that made it quite refreshing . now its just overloaded with phenolics and all you can taste and smell is cloves . i ca n't get past the phenolic flavors enough to even finish a bottle . just horrible .
a - clear golden yellow with average ultra white head . moderate retention and good lacing .  tastes pretty amazing really . watery on the tongue but ends dryish .

very promising . and then : the taste is a bit disappointing after that great smell . good , but not exceptional .  mouthfeel is just ok-nothing too incredible but quite drinkable especially at the 6.5 % abv .

aroma is of banana , the spiciness of clove , and actually some pineapple . taste is not as good as the smell . it 's a bit earthy , and far less of a phenolic presence than most hefeweizens i 've had .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and somewhat tannic , but the overall effect is quite interesting .

a huge aroma of starbucks mocha frappuccino jumps out of the glass . sweet chocolate and nice roasty smell mix in for quite a nose pleasing aroma . cappuccino leads the way in the flavor of this brew .  m : medium to full body but needs more carbonation .

cappuccino , freshly whipped cream , vanilla extract , milk chocolate powder give the nose a soft , enveloping appeal , cherry syrup , brown sugar , this noted it does have an unprocessed graininess to it which approximates hop bite , fills your nostrils and stays there for some time . in the mouth it 's medium-bodied with an acidic punch which jolts you and momentarily forestalls the arrival of the cappuccino , vanilla pudding , whipped cream , graham cracker pie crust , cinnamon powder , licorice and baker 's chocolate . there 's also more of a perfumed lift than downwards pressure on the palate . tart cherry pie wafts through the finish .  i always drink my high life out of cans ! it looks like beer , smells like beer , and tastes like beer ... to keep it simple . this is my go-to macro , and will always be as long as miller keeps it the same ! prost !

s : chocolaty , coffee , roasted malt , maybe some caramel tones . the appearance and smell had me so excited for the taste , only to be let down by a watery drink .  this beer is not awful but it is not good either . if use to be better , i think , back in the days before aluminum cans and pull up tabs . beer is fizzy and gives a good head and that is about the only good quality it has .

a : this beer has the darkest head i have seen . i would describe the head as dirt brown .  the taste is very good , it could use a bit more body but the flavors are great . tons of chocolate and roastiness dominate the profile but there is also some caramel and hops . the bitterness is at a great level in comparison to the sweetness , especially for the style . the guy below me has it right : not quite edmund fitz or blake butte but this one is one of the supeb examples of the style .

deep , shiny gold/light copper with good , medium creamy head , that lasts a few minutes , medium white sticky lacing , hugging the glass a good while .  picked up a few of these `` oil cans '' at a local liquor mart . this is the only place i 've seen them . i like the regular fosters occasionally , and have fond memories of it from various parties and times in life . after looking at the color , noticed that the can said `` caramel coloring added , '' so nothing real to go by there . i liked this , i guess , but the drinkablility was hampered by a fakey sort of bitterness that did n't hold a candle to the fuller 's and young 's of the world . kind of caught in my throat . i pick up the regular if it 's on special , but for a real bitter , this ai n't it .

oh , man ... the aroma on this is , perhaps as the name implies , heavenly . almost a perfect balance in the nose -- fruity , pine needles , grapefruit . and this one goes through three `` hoppings , '' kettle , hop back , and dry hopping ... awesome . the flavor is just about perfect . a fine balance of hop flavors , including a nice grapefruit bitterness and a light bready undertone . but , as a whole , this is a very drinkable beer ... and quite delicious .  m : a bit light in the mouth , but it kind of coats your mouth as well .

2009 batch 2 a - pours a nice beautiful red that is a cross between a tomato and an orange . a nice pinkish 3 finger bubbly , foamy head that goes does down to about 1 finger . beautiful .  ambrosial start , lots of malt , the top skimpy in feel with the finish having a delightful hop spicy bite , the carbonation moderate and the aftertaste droughty and long lasting .

very nice presentation . aroma is forresty ( real word ? ) with grassy , herbal , piney , sprucy hop notes along with citrus notes of grapefruit and lemon rind .  reminded me a bit of bmc with a bit of syrup added for sweetness . the taste is more of the same with a quick malty dryness at the end that seems to say , `` ha ! had you fooled..you thought there was about to be something pleasant here , did n't you ? in fact , this may get sacrificed to the kitchen sink . as i always say , in total fairness to the brewer and his ( or her ) intentions , this may have its fans , but it most assuredly is *not* for me ...

smell is amazing ! you can pick out both beers , which is the goal of black and tans . prism hits the nail on the head , because in the beer , you can pick out the lemony hops of the pale ale and it goes very well with the licorice aroma of the porter . carbonation is right on , not too much , and at a very natural level . it brings something else to the table , and yet it works for the style .  mouf & gt ; easy , average .

the nose piques my interest in this brew as the aroma is highly reminiscent of a belgian triple with strong esters of alcohol , yeast , and caramelized sugar . entry is muted until the midtaste takes over by blanketing the tongue with a thick coating of honey . my numbers reflect my overall impression of this brew ... nice appearance , great nose , overpowering honey midtaste & finish .  the body of the beer is actually approaching medium and the carbonation is not overly fizzy as many macros are .

the aroma is filled with dried dark fruits , apricots , honey , and wheat toast . overall a good beer , that will become a great beer over time .  my first taste of it was great , however it lacks in the balance of the malts , and has sort of a over roasted taste . altogether though , this beer in my opinion is the best of the coors brand and i would recommend for something new . not a everyday beer though .

the smell of this brew is grassy with some minor inclusion of earth and peppery notes . a faint note of funky cheese blends with some vinous aspect of white grape skins . fairly decent across the board but on a day like this , it paled in comparison to some of the other geuze offerings sampled .  there was a very light mouthfeel , but an extremely dry , crisp finish .
smells like sour cherries and sour grapes with a white wine smell .  m-medium carbonation . medium body , slick .
fairly strong aroma and inviting . t : definitely citrus forward , although the flavors are a bit more muted than the nose lead me to believe .  the mouthfeel is a little lacking in carbonation too .

s -- amazing smell of dark chocolate and roasted coffee , no sweetness to it , but very pleasant . t -- the coffee in the smell comes through the strongest , with a hint of the chocolate .  mouthfeel is okay , no carbonation to speak of .
s : wonderful nose . toasted notes with some malt character hiding behind it .  mouth feel : a bit thin on the palet , or maybe the aroma and taste make you expect more in the way of mouth feel .

s : big fresh aromas of earthy grapefruit , and vanilla cookie dough . t : bit of a let down here .  it must be said that this beer is a bit astringent on the palate and a bit thinner than i would have liked , but it is still rather drinkable .

the initial smell is awesome -- somewhat of a bubble gum and lemon mix . a strong taste of fruity malt/yeast and a very dry aftertaste , the strong feel of hops comes on towards the finish of this one .  mouth feel is thin pretty characteristic of bbc 's beers which makes this a really drinkable session stout with a lot of flavor .
s : bold and healthy hop aroma . perfect ipa smell . t : dry and hoppy .  a rather thin aqueous body with less carbonation than expected , but otherwise nothing wrong with this brew .

brett funkiness shows its face , but is n't as prominent as in others from similar varieties . like the smell , the brett funkiness is more subtle than others .  the mouth was a bit oily but not unpleasantly so .
smell : pine cones and grapefruit at first then the malt comes through real nice . taste : hoppy as expected but where 's the malt ?  it is slightly watery on the palate .

good strength and good harmony between the components . the nose is awesome , but that 's the only thing that is .  m : starts off creamy , but i 'm pretty quickly struck by how watery this is . the carbonation is decent , but i find this surprisingly thin .

s : best nose on a dipa i 've ever experienced . the alcohol is actually a complement to the hop aroma , however . this is one of those `` i wish this was an air freshener '' aromas . t & m : flavor is interesting -- some herbal and grassy hops , some notes of citrus , and a good smattering of pine . it does n't seem to be as balanced as stone ipa , but it 's still pretty tasty . the mouthfeel is very nice -- a sticky , full , and lasting feel with a long finish .  m : fairly thick , carbonation seems a tad high .

i had this beer tried next to or , poured from a bottle into a pint glass ... a : a pitch black color , very tiny white thin ring of a head , pretty poor looking ... s : smell is awesome . tons of hoppy citric and grapefruit notes , with some sweet honey and vanilla ... t : wow . a bit of a letdown very little hop bitterness and a strong cloyingly sweet flavor with little complexity ... m : smooth , could use more carb ... d : a decent enough beer , but its the worst between either and or !  mouthfeel is ok , but too watery and thin feeling for my tastes . drinkability is quite good , the only real flaw i found was the weak mouthfeel .

s = this had me hoping . smell was very sweet and inviting . nice fruity ( plum , prune maybe ?  mouthfeel : high carbonation gives the impression of a thinner mouthfeel , and the carbonic acid and alcohol bite knock this one down a little in the mouthfeel rating .

s : peaty , peaty , peaty . slight hint of oak back , but peat dominates the nose , entirely . t : first taste , blast of peat overwhelms the palate , nose , pores , everything .  a-garnet with small ring of foam s-raisin , pancake syrup , faint vinager t-assertive sour front , sour cherry , some malt sweetness , dates m-medium , with average carbonation d-very tasty !

a - pours a very clear rusty orange/chestnut brown with just a short layer of white foam that quickly disappeared s - really nice citrus aroma , mango , orange & grapefruit , really nice smelling beer t - mango , grapefruit and orange and lemon rind , there is a bit of bitterness that seems to taste like the rind not hops .  under carbonated .

great `` belgian '' lacing & very good head retention smell : sourness & then woody , lactic notes .  not too many micro 's that come out with a light ale . hats off to them for bringing this to market to allow folks who are used to drinking american mass producted swill to move into a easy drinking michigan micro brew . lighter than sam adams but more flavor then the bud and miller 's of the world .

appearance : gorgeous beer with strong lacing throughout the entire glass . it looked sooo good , but there is almost no aroma .  the beer really lacks in body . carbonation is great . overall this was a good beer but the body creates a void .

i am smelling a creme brulee desert right now ... i do n't think i could tell the difference from the real thing . exceptional . there is a touch of courseness in the back of the throat from the abv and bitterness .  taste/mouthfeel : this beer is slightly oily , with a very limited carbonation .

drank it on draft at legacy and at reading country club i have also had three cases of it made for them by the lion in bottles it is smooth favorful light and not biteing , nice head great smell very refreshing to drink it is a amazing product that they have made it is very nice to just sit and drink again and again .  the mouthfeel is thiner but still good .

a : aggressive pour yields 1 finger of dark tan pillowy head with great retention .  a wonderful beer . one i have had before , and thought it would be great for the new year . it 's dark brown hue and brownish colored head was delightful . the taste of cocoa and hops pleased my nose . the roasted flavors were soothing , but left a little bit of an after taste .

nose is `` oh my fucking god '' chocolate . this smells like a combination of the greatest cup of pure milk chocolate , chocolate milk or hot chocolate with touches of espresso , coffee , dark burnt coffee beans and pure vanilla beans .  light copper color with a large head s. malty with a slight resiny hop smell t. more bitter than sweet but well balanced with roasted malt m. a little to acidic and carbonated for my tastes d. a good lighter amber ale that i can heartily recommend
carbonating is correct level o : the aroma is great , but the taste is way over bittered with pine .  mouthfeel is very dry with almost no carbonation .

the aroma is so spot-on for the style that it makes me wonder how skull coast did it ... how do you get that much non-artificial-smelling watermelon aroma into a beer ? just exceptional , with juicy , fruity 'melon notes backed by a hint of wheat and hops .  cake/nutty malt up front with a huge , thick spiced tea hop flavor headbutt with the swallow . not just season 's best , but saranac 's best . i usually find them to be just an average brewery but this stuff is nice .

appearance : pours with a massive amount of head , ca n't even pour the bottle in one try . awesome lacing . the beer itself is black as black can be , without even a hint of any other color around the edges . drinkability : this beer is a beautiful thing to behold , with amazing lacing .  mouthfeel is a bit thin .
it 's a good inviting smell .  m- smooth , but a tad thin . carbonation is good , as is the thoroughly smooth finish with a tad of warmth .
aroma is excellent ; spicy and piny .  m - a little thinner than i imagined , though based on the aroma , i might have been expecting a double ipa .

s sweet and complex on the nose . honey , orange zest , and chinese 5-spice . touch of clean alcohol and fresh bread . light malt character on the backend coddles a soft alcohol note . the finish carries a rolling bitterness , and the malt that balanced the ending alcohol note slowly fades to give way to a brighter boozyness .  incredibly light with cereal grains , very grainy taste , hops are nowhere in site . there are way better summer beers out there .

poured from a 12 oz bottle , 2008 version a : pours a clear mahogany brown , with ruby hues , under a big slightly off white head . excellent retention and lace .  i always look forward like most do the annual stone anniversary brews.poured a rich deep amber with a tight and sticky one finger off white head , big hops in the nose with a mix pine and herbal/leaf , there is a gummy , fruity-like sweet note as well.the mouthfeel is a bit sharp i will say it crashes down the gullett at first , it does begin to smooth out after a few sips but still seems a bit harsh.no holds barred hops hit the palate up front with big pine and big herbalness , a healthy does of sweeter alcohol gives a slight burn along with a bit of dark fruit.very good but seems like it something that should sit for awhile , still another fine one from stone .

the first thing that hits the nose is fresh , sweet apricots . notes of peaches and a creamy aroma come through as well . t- very sour with lactic acid . the fruit was far more subtle that i thought it would be , based on the smell . the fresh apricot flavor comes through a little more clearly as the beer warms . d- a bit of a sipper , considering how sour it is , but overall very good .  mouthfeel is way more thin than the head and lacing made me think it would be . very quaffable .

the aromas amazing . its like smelling a glass full of fresh fruit . theres a little belgian malt in the aroma as well , but the fruity character of the beer is the most amazing quality of the beer . the yeast flavor is intense , and a little distracting , though .  just some `` laying down '' advice : had the extreme plesure of six-year bottle conditioning tasteing , in which years 4-5 were exceptionally good . year 3 was quite good , with anything under that seemingly `` young '' tasting . after year 5 the qualities that make it a stellar barley wine were fading .

you can smell the fresh raspberry puree aroma from almost 2 feet away ! the first sip hits you with an insane burst , it tastes like you just bit into a big overly ripe juicy berry . i really enjoyed this but personally could not do more than say 2 or so glasses at a sitting , since there is so much flavor , so it would not be a good session beer , but it really is very great tasting !  mouthfeel is soft and a little heavy .

i 'm really enjoy the sweet fruits and big malts in the aroma , red grapes , sour dates , soft and tangy with chocolate malt and a dry-sour yeast aroma that is really nice . mild heat at the end .  perhaps another way to explain the feeling would be a textured shandy . noting the high praise this saison received , i have trouble fathoming such a bad experience .

a - a beautiful pour . deep amber with an inch of off-white head . as the head slowly goes away it leaves great lace and ends up in a creamy , bumpy layer on top of the brew .  4/5 m : surprisingly thin side of medium , slightly tongue numbing , spritzy .

outstanding complexity . tastes like various coffee creamers ( amaretto , irish cream ) poured over pumpkin pie .  nice carbonation , but this comes off as a little thin . this should be more drinkable considering its thin body , but as this is a stout , the thin body is a bit of a turn off .

s : quite good . vinous , and i 'll assume chardonnay-like , notes are at the forefront , with brett and lemongrass also inserting themselves into the mix .  m : the thinnest , lightest imperial i can remember , but the intensity doesnt have to be overpowering .

the bashah has a body that is as black as midnight - very striking and its only with light held up behind the glass that you can catch a glimpse of deep ochre hue . produces a thick deep tan 2-3 fingers of head that contrasts beautifully against the dark body .  flavour is better than expected- a little woody and slightly spicy , with a thick strong maltiness . i 'd like the hearty body on this one , were it not for the turbocharged carbonation .

s : the strong aroma of hops greets you right away as you inhale and is then followed up by a citrusy malt smell .  do n't brewers taste the beers they brew after they 're done ? how many sips does it take to get stone juxtaposition to the center of my sink drain ? i think this beer is really spent burnt coffee grounds blended with colgate toothpaste in a bottle .

smell : cocoa powder and chocolate . sweet but not cloying so . really digging the aroma . taste : where 's the sweetness ?  a touch lightly bodied , with an oily , but thinnish and passably dextrinous mouthfeel .

the smell is great , very fresh , yeasty , sweet and fruity . some dry straw , scattered by the wind , some strawberry , some peaches , some plums . after these heavenly aromas , the taste appeared surprizing and a bit disappointing . almost like an eku maybe ... deeply chocolaty , but with an annoying alcoholic character . after tasting the beer , even the smell gets less interesting .  thanks walter a-a nice rich amber , good head , some lacing that turned into a small bubble ring s-a slight bready smell , some citrus ( makes me think of citra hop ) slight sweetness and then tart t- close to the same as the smell , there is a slight tangyness in the middle of the drink , it 's a good thing m- it 's moderately lively not as much bite and tingle i was expecting , a clean wet finish o/d- overall i really like this , it 's not the craziest ipa but it 's more than just decent , drinkability , i can see myself finishing this growler , this is a tasty beer and one i really like
