as soon as i opened the bottle , i was smacked with a heavy hoppy smell , easily reminded me it 's an ipa i 'm dealing with . s : an amazing combination of hops , pine , citrus , maybe some grape . t : interesting , with the token ipa hoppiness being the most notable aspect of it all . d : daunting at first , especially for me , not a huge fan of ipas , but i have to respect this beer . the dynamic flavor-smell combinations are remarkable , and though it 's not my favorite , the never-departing flavor may be the reminder that it is something to be reckoned with .  an american classic . good fall back beer , or one to enjoy when a less complex brew is desired .

s - huge chocolate nose akin to hershey 's chocolate syrup or even a tootsie roll . the aroma is simply amazing . very solid chocolate stout with an 11 % abv that hides behind a wall of bittersweet chocolate goodness .  the carbonation and the color were good , but this did n't make up for the off taste and smell .

it smells awesome and makes my mouth water just anticipating the first taste !  the mouthfeel is light , but hey , its a light beer ! for drinkability , again , one of the beers that could probably never offend me .

this big california ipa packs a heavy alcoholic punch at 8.5 % abv , but for such a great smell , i was let down with the taste . do n't get me wrong , its good , but it is not the best for this style .  remarkably good . but pay attention : almost 10 % alcohol , but you hardly remark it . it does not have that much body , but it surely has a delicate taste . i 'm a bit more inclined for brown beers , but this one is really good , and not brown at all .

i was up in hell 's kitchen for halloween and my buddy took me to this place scruffy duffy 's ( coolest damn sports bar ever , check it out if your ever in ny ) and would n't let me order anything until i tried a guinness on tap . dark and smooth , almost coffee like .  lowish carbonation and a light , smooth mouthfeel .

the smell was exceptional and exciting , with a remarkable variety of spicy tones that are too complex to describe . with great anticipation , i tried the first sip , which was heavenly . and then it happened ... a nasty aftertaste that i could n't quite place but did n't like .  m : very carbonated .
long trail ale poured copper ; clean & clear , topped by a nice , tall , dense white head .  smooth mouthfeel with a moderate amount of carbonation and just a little watery in the finish .

aroma is great . i really get a spicy sage aroma on this one . a sweetness from the herbal notes really plays perfect with this one . really a perfect nose . taste is spot on too .  it is a little light in body but i 've noticed that porters and stouts are generally lighter from a can .

smell was very appetizing , a rich sour cherry with a bit of roasted malt . taste was not nearly as robust , pretty much just a strong stout , a nice bit of burnt malt and coffee , coupled with a nice tartness from the cherry , but not nearly as rich and complex as the aroma had me expecting . mouthfeel was very rich and creamy , medium body .  had this on tap when i was being introduced to the lager style of beer . it 's smell is very specific to the beer and is appealing if you are craving a medium-bodied lager . its has a malty intake and a bit of a spicy , hoppy after taste . it goes down smoothly but the taste tends to stick around and interfere with ordered food . it is very drinkable but as stated , but be careful when drinking this with food .

aroma smacks you . good and hard . hops and oak would be an obvious statement . my notes indicate an amazing floral and woody perfume aroma . initial flavor is upfront pine and sweetness .  mouthfeel : heavy , chewy , slick , low carbonation borders on flat .

head is a bright off white , watery and light , not much retention or lacing ... outstanding aroma , very funky floral muskyness , some nice brett ... taste has some nice things going , this is a musky sour brett saison , not sweetness , makes no bones about it . crushable musky saison , well worth trying .  heavy mouthfeel .

s : strong and good balance of malt/hops in the nose . sweet and bitter , but not bittersweet .  taste some roasted chocolate flavors . flavor lingers on the tongue after each sip . not quite what i would consider a savoring beer , but tasty none the less . i could drink this beer around the fire in the winter or after raking leaves in the fall .
aroma is wow coffee , rich robust , you want it , it 's here , with a nice dark malt sweetness underneath .  feel is a bit coarse , but just a bit .

flavor did not quite live up to the aroma . it is a bit more piney than the aroma suggests , but still is dominated by citrus . there 's a strange quality right at the beginning of the swallow that i ca n't really describe except that it 's not positive .  nice aroma of hops but i would hope for a bit more being a hops lover . the celebration ale , from the same company , seems to hit the spot more than this beer but still worthy of a place in the fridge and still better than many micro beer ipa ii . sierra nevada seems to me to be the only mass beer company that brews excellent beer for `` mass beer '' prices .
s : pumpkin pie baby ! very nice . t : pumpkin spice , clove , nutmeg and caramel from the malts .  carbonation is fizzy on the tongue where it should be soft and creamy .

ahh , the smell makes up for the poor visual aspect ... it is phenomenal ! nonetheless , this is an outstanding nose . barrel aging is very evident upon tasting , as is the alcohol . to me , it almost seems like a tripel and a half , as it needs a bit more body-adding malts and the alcohol is a bit rough ... but that is being a bit picky , i am very glad i brought this out for my 500th .  mouthfeel was somewhat on the thin side , but still quite acceptable .

this poured out wonderfully with a growing tall head of very tight frothyness of light tannish color sitting atop a glowing deep mahagony , rubyish copper highlighted gem of a bottom .  finishes dry with nice mocha notes & a touch of charred grain mf : very oily & smooth as all hell with low carbonation & nice stickyness .

a : light brown tea-like color with a large three finger off-white head and good retention and globs of foam grabbing the sides .  the silky smooth mouthfeel was fantastic and carbonation was spot on .

pours a deep dark chestnut brown color that is nearly opaque with mahogany edges when held to a light and a two finger frothy , soapy tan head . very good retention , only slowly fading into a lasting cap that coats the glass with chunks , rings and splotches of soapy lacing .  mouthfeel : amazing . creamy and smooth , thick .

12 oz bottle poured into a snifter - best before oct. 19th 2007 appearance : harsh pouring reveals a generous 2 '' head that lasts quite a long time . the head is tan with tiny bubbles that leaves a bit of lace behind .  a - opaque for sure ; not quite black , but very dark brown ; 1/2 '' tan/light brown , creamy head that diminishes to a thin layer pretty quickly ; lacing here and there , around the glass s - very nice aroma going on here ; notes of roasty malts , dark chocolate , hints of milky sweetness , and nice qualities of gingerbread too t - dark chocolate , vanilla , cinnamon , and ginger come first ; milky sweetness lasts from start to finish that is reminiscent of espresso ; slight bitter finish with roasted coffee beans and ginger as well m - medium to full bodied ; slight dry finish ; some carbonation that feels nice on the tongue ; can feel some warmth from the 9.2 % abv ; texture is very milky , creamy , velvety smooth o - i just ca n't get over how exceptionally smooth this beer really is .

poured a medium copper hue with a huge chunky white head . there was very good retention and sticky lacing .  m - they got the `` rick creamy '' part right in the description . the beer has moderate carbonation and has a nice creamy feel to it . it 's incredibly creamy and smooth and fits the style well .

a : jet black with a nice dark mocha head that sits just barely above the beer . perfect for the style s : has a very nice mellow scotch smell that is not too harsh along side a slight sweetness of vanilla and honey .  m - the mouthfeel is fantastic . creamy , smooth and light with a perfect amount of carbonation .
a- pours a deep brown with a big two and a half finger mocha head .  m : really a standout porter . carbonation is perfectly dialed in and gives a very subtle tingle on the tongue .

'01-'02 : starts by pouring a jet black , your unable to see through it , with a nice dark tan head that settles with deep fluffy pockets .  m : great , chewy and resiny , full-bodied and robust , with a smooth finish , compared to the rest of the sip , just what i 'm looking for in a double ipa .

a : pitch-black , a thick , frothy tan head very slowly settles , on top of lively carbonation . looking very good indeed .  the mouthfeel on this ale was great , and i think the mouthfeel of just about any beer is enhanced by cask conditioning . it had a nice thick feel on the tongue .

pours a dark dark brown black sprouting a fluffy sculptured light cream tan color head with microscopic tightly knit bubbles . this beer produces a curious industrial like nose about itits not particularly robust , but to me the low level background radiation is like some synthetic yet curiously copasetic waft stealthily sneaking in upon my nostrils.. the flavor is predominantly malt .  mouthfeel : full bodied , chewy , carbonation is spot on .
a very appealing looking brew .  it has a wonderfully creamy mouthfeel that makes each sip a pleasure .
pours pitch black into a snifter . the visual is as appetizing as it 's ever going to get for a stout .  the texture is likewise decadent , being somehow both silky and creamy .

11.2 oz , 2007 bottle a : deep brown , not quite black under a nice sized tan head . excellent lace and retention .  fairly light in body for such a big beer , drinkability is good . the mouthfeel was amazing thanks to the silky , rocky head which remained throughout the entire glass .

pours a jet black wth a huuge , really tight brown head that retains really well , beautiful !  bordering on chewy as you work toward swallowing . carbonation was excellent on tap , just enough to contribute to a dry and clean finish despite the initial sweetness of the beer .

ths one poured a dream , you shoulda seen it , looked like a photo from a beer book . billowy head sticking out of the glass all proud and boastful , very cool .  huge bodied and full ( again , suggesting iipa classification ) . this is a beauty on cask .

pours a clear golden blonde with three fingers of fizzy rocky head , that drops slowly to a nice cap .  m : so good i ca n't get enough . nice thickness with light carbonation and a good oily texture make this a delightful treat for my mouth .

pours really black with a big , pillowy dark brown head .  has that totally coating feel like a warm thick cask draught , just almost oily in its feel and velvety ( aside from the alcohol ) . really like this about this beer .

has to be one of the better looking beers i have ever poured . university of texas , burnt orange color and beautiful head that was reminiscent of vanilla ice cream on top .  perfect mouthfeel for a beer of this kind with controlled carbonation and appropriate body .

the beer pours a nice orange color , and an aggressive pour yields an initially massive off white head , that fades to a one finger height before lingering . an impressive amount of lacing in generated , almost enough to garner a 5 .  first sip is velvety smooth textured average body with minimal carbonation .

pours up a beautiful grapefruit color with a very thin white head .  and even so , it is still incredibly smooth , and the alcohol flavor can not be detected . the body is huge . one of the thickest beers i 've had the pleasure of eating . very good stuff .

they have to put some sort of chemical happiness in there to keep everything together ... beamish is almost black , but truly more ruby brown than anything . the head is bleached mocha with a fantastic nitro lace pattern .  m - this is one of my favorite parts so far about this brew . moderate amounts of carbonation that whirls around your tounge and warms it in the process .
great retention and globby lacing .  m : medium viscosity , very smooth and creamy on the palate , with low carbonation .

appearance- very dark , almost black pour . fat 2 inch head just about overflowing out of the glass and excellent lacing .  mouthfeel is full bodied and smooth that feels pretty creamy on the tongue .

pour was exceptional . the head rose faster than expected , and shot over the top of the mug - but it did n't overflow .  m/d - the mouthfeel and drinkability are exceptional . this is a simple brown ale that i could knock back one after the other .
pours a very nice black color with some ruby hues and a thick white head . i love to watch this beer settle .  m - thick , very smooth and very viscous with little carbonation .
bottle , a : pours yellow-orange , with a very long-lasting white head , great lacing .  mouthfeel . amazing , thick rich and seems sweet but comes together .

quite close to black with a fine textured tan head . i love the way the beer horizon ( the separation between the beer and the head ) looks . it stayed that way throughout the beer .  starts with roasted coffee flavor , mouthfeel is incredible smooth .

a- pours an absolutely crystal clear light orange with a one finger white head .  taste- wonderfully intense malt , and a big bready character that thankfully outweighs any unpleasant sweetness that the malts could impart . fantastically effervescent , it rides into the mouth and over the tongue with confident grace ... all the while alive and outspoken .

pours an absolutely gorgeous dark cola body that illuminates to a caramel-amber when held to the light . creamy , light tan bubbles form a sizable froth on top and slowly settle to a thick veil of foam , thanks in part to a vigorous carbonation level .  perfect silky creamy carbonation .

one thing of note on this beer is its beautiful appearence , dark caramel coloring , and nice thick head .  mouthfeel is very good , a light bodied beer with excellent carbonation ; it dances on the tongue and finishes smooth .

pours a rich golden orange , excellent clarity , good carbonation , topped by a level one finger slab of snow white foam .  good and special beer , cloudy , double fermentation , yeast , hops , malt and wheat are present in smell ; taste fruity , and floral like grassy and herbs ; good for mexican haute cuisine , try with pasta and salads ; mouthfeel exceptional , well balanced and litlle strong for the palate ; 96 % recommended .

appearance : beautiful hazed orange with honey lemon corners . a huge 3 finger off white crown with loads of retention and lace . the crown is really frothy and gets nice and dense like whipped cream after you let it settle and repour a few times .  m : medium bodied with a good amount of carbonation . exceptional in this category . appearance and mouthfeel are certainly worth noting .
this beer pours with a thick and foamy head . wonderful active bubbles slowly float to the top to form a thick white head .  m- awesome thick mouthfeel on this seasonal .

appearance - this beer arrived in a tall , branded pilsner style glass and was yellow-orange with a offwhite , two finger head exhibiting good retention and heavy lacing . impressive carbonation showed off the whole time .  mouthfeel : perfect mouthfeel . very smooth , lightly carbonated .

sticky lacing all the way up the glass , and infinite retention on the eventually short head .  aroma : not overpowering , but hints of citrus-y hops well balanced with malt mouthfeel : medium-bodied with a nice oily coating of the mouth . very smooth with just the right carbonation .
very visually appealing .  perfect carbonation to it .

this beer has a frothy , three finger thick , almost rocky pale white head that sits atop a body that is brilliantly clear and a pale straw color . the color is about perfect and the head is one of the longest lasting and best ones i have seen on a macro-lager .  mouthfeel is damn near perfect for an o'fest , i think . impeccable balance .

on to the beer : little is wrong with the appearance . the head is thick and sports plenty of its original self , peach colored body has the `` glowing '' illusion at some spots . it 's just one bitter mess with some soap and soft waves of phenols ( more specifically , pllastic ) that do n't belong and the beer becomes even more unpleasant .  great mouthfeel .

served at a few degrees below fridge tempeature in a tulip glass . the color is a gleaming orange , and the lacing is setting up with unbelievable sticky cling . superb ! smell- a bold metallic smell booms out from the glass , incredibly phenolic and overpowering the malts and hops .  m - full body , viscous and chewy with low , delicate carbonation , very smooth across the palate with some heat from the alcohol/bourbon content .
great looking deep copper-red with a full tan head that receded to a thin layer with great lacing .  m : very soft carbonation and easy on the palate as a good session beer should be .

pours a dark brown color with a medium sized creamy tan head that retains nicely for a while before slowly fading to a light ring and leaving a moderate amount of sticky lacing .  f : wonderfully thick .
old plowshare stout is a very dark reddish brown ale with a frothy , bubbly light brown head that has great retention and leaves lumpy lacing .  m : super creamy as it should be .

pours a very nice syrup brown color with some dense eggshell head that laces nicely and sticks around for a while .  the mouthfeel is dry with a long and deep finish which is full of blackened malt and char . very very nice .

a : pours a beautiful bronze with ruby highlights . this beer looks fantastic . s : smell is of juicy citrusy hops , with an abundant dose of pale and caramel malt .  excellent ! incredible smooth and silky mouthfeel .
pours a lighty hazed burnt orange , huge cap of frothy and sticky white head , great retention and lacing .  m : full-bodied , a very firm and brilliantly sructured beer .
perfect lacing . very good retention .  mouthfeel & gt ; exciting ... not too bubbly . full score .
other regards it 's pretty good : poured with a large foamy , frothy , fluffy , off white head that lasts a while and some lace .  m : perfect carbonation amount .

brown bottle , there 's a spot for a bottling number on the back label but it 's blank , poured into a pilsner glass . appearance : pours a crystal clear golden yellow , lots of carbonation bubbles rising inside . probably a good one to bring to a party , as it looks similar to the macros , but tastes much better .  it 's thick , creamy , rich , and robust .

appearance : shakespeare stout pours out nearly black with a full 3 fingers of mocha colored head . retention is very good , and lacing is very abundant .  the mouthfeel , though , was the best part . it fills your mouth with mousse like consistency with very round edges .

330 ml bottle , a : pours golden orange with an extremely long lasting rocky white head with nice belgian lace .  the mouth feel is perfect - not watery , not syrupy , well carbonated , and very refreshing .
this beer looks like the platonic ideal of beers . light amber/orange color and a fluffy white head that dissipates slowly .  mouthfeel is full bodied and super smooth . very enjoyable .

drank on-tap at deep ellum , allston , ma poured a deep brown/black with a two-finger , bubbly , cocoa-colored head that slowly faded to a thick ring of lace . large , irregular-shaped patches of lacing coated the glass .  you can feel how well-crafted this beer is : perfect body ... thin , but not too thin ; carbonated , but not overdone ; hoppy aftertaste , but not a tastebud destroyer .

a - deep orange with a thick off white head that good retention and lacing down the glass .  extreme balance and smoothness in this beer , its quite good . big full body with a champaign like fizzyness . im impressed .
appearance : this beer is magical . a perfect brown head sits upon a black body , grabbing the glass and not letting go as i drink .  m- great mouthfeel .

it left a medium brown head of about an inch that quickly receded to surface skim , and thick , but ephemeral lacing . i know everyone says it 's black , but it 's really the darkest shade of brown possible ( you can see this in bright light ) , and opaque ( even in bright light ) .  the mouthfeel is light , with excellent particulates that roam the mouth . a most excellent brew that i would n't hesitate to try again .
this porter poured very dark , with about 2 fingers of just off white head . there was fantastic lacing left on the glass .  matches perfectly with the thickness of the body .

a-pours a pitch black color with a finger and a half tan head .  very nice feel in the mouth -- rich , thick , tingling bubbles , kind of evaporates on the tongue . medium-heavy body , quite a bit of honey , i get this apple quality .

a - pours with one finger of white foam on top of a perfectly clear , copper colored body . the head settles slowly and leaves nice , thick lace .  the texture is just flat-out perfect and this is about as easy to drink as you can want .
pours a very nice chestnut brown with a quite good head that sticks around as a cap throughout . very good lacing as well .  silky smooth on the tongue and exceptionally creamy .

best by june 28 2010 poured into a rave vos tumbler . half a glass of milky , fluffy , off-white head that is slow to settle .  m : the mouthfeel is dense and creamy and frothy ... and almost stout-like . excellent .
the head is an extremely pale tan and stands at two inches tall . the head is frothy and light .  incredible mouthfeel .
pours a beautiful light honey color . have n't seen a pale lager with such nice color .  m : very thick , borderline creamy . superb .
well , this beer pours pretty nicely .  mouthfeel is incredible , one of the smoothest beers i 've had .
came out of the tap a deep brown , almost black color .  mouthfeel : has a great mouthfeel . it has exceptional smoothness .
pours pitch black and thick , and makes a milk chocolaty looking huge amount of foam .  m : very creamy feeling , small bubbles , not too sticky .

a - black is right . the head is a medium brown and standing about three-quarter inches tall before slowly fading to bumpy and frothy top .  mouthfeel is a heavy but perfect . heavy with lots of lactose , light but fizzi carbonation .

pours a cloudy , very dark golden orange/chestnut mahogany brown color with dark golden orange hues when held to a light source and a two finger frothy , pillowy yellowish beige head . excellent retention , only slowly fading into a lasting cap . sporadic chunks of soapy lacing left behind .  m : the carbonation on this one is perfect . perfect mouthfeel .

a : a stunning deep brown near black with cranberry highlights . a inch of toasted head comes after a medium pour . the head slowly fades to an impressive 1/3 inch . lacing on a dark beer ?  the mouthfeel is incredibly creamy , with the tastes of chocolate and dried fruit coming through .

a - dark maroon with lots of capuccino colored head .  mouthfeel : thick , creamy and full-bodied , smooth with just enough carbonation . spicy warming alcohol remains through the finish and leaves a tingly sensation in the mouth and a nice warmth throughout .

the head is fluffy and impressive with a slightly off white color and nice staying power . it leaves pretty average lace .  the hop particles make it sticky as hell , the rim of my glass is sticky , my lips are sticky , and the mouthfeel is outstanding ! as far as double ipas go ( which let 's face it this is really comparable to an ipa ) , i still prefer either pliny or any of the alpine ipas , but this is a nice change of pace .

appearance : pours an incredibly rich , thick molasses/mahogany . you 'll be hard pressed to find a better looking beer than this .  the aroma speaks strongly of roasted grains , as you would expect from a stout , while on the tongue the beer has tremendous body .

i think what happened was that the strain of bacteria or yeast that the brewer exposed the beer to ate more of the dextrins and made the beer less full-bodied . 3/22/2009 beautiful burgundy color .  i keep tasting chocolate ice cream ... dry chocolate ice cream ... not cloy at all ... very fantastic finish and mouthfeel ... german beer ftw will buy again !

huge , foamy beige head that leaves several lace rings smeared down the glass . kinda like the glass is wearing a striped shirt .  mouthfeel/drinkability- sublime mouthfeel , super-easy in the mouth .
body was black as night with a tan head .  beautiful .
poured black with a thick brown head . the retention was great . very creamy and capuccino like looking head .  it is full bodied and creamy in the mouth .
appearance ; beautiful black color with an attractive tan head .  5.0 on the mouthfeel with a huge creamy full-bodied mouthcoating that covers every bit .
pours a luscious peach/dark gold color with a substantial , fluffy , two-finger head that exhibits excellent retention and lacing .  velvety mouthfeel and smoother than sinatra .
a smooth golden color with a nice fluffy white 2 finger head .  this beer feels absolutely perfect in the mouth .

could n't get too aggressive with the pour b/c it has some major head on it . nice gold , perfect clarity , big puffy white head .  m : this stout has an amazing creamy mouthful like a well done milk stout without being too creamy or way too thin like most crap stouts . medium to full bodied ; a really nice medium carbonation on this one .

22oz into nonic pint in the mid-forties . booming 4f of cream-colored head , over a clear but rich amber body - tons of carbonation present , and lots of sugary/sticky lacing .  m : perfect . it 's thick without being cloying .

wow , orange , slightly reddish , as it let 's the light pass through ... it 's beautiful . such a strong head , off-white .  the mouthfeel is where this shines , exceptional medium body and smoothness .
great looking beer .  perhaps my favorite aspect is the full and very creamy mouthfeel .

poured a dark golden orange to light amber in the glass ... yes , almost the color of the jewel amber . lots of beautiful bubbles in the pour reminding me of a guinness that end up creating a full 2 finger craggy beige head that melts to sticky lace .  m= smooth and crisp . feels resinous as well which is great for an ipa . d= super drinkable .

the bottle popped furiously , and poured with a full head and glowing color .  mouthfeel is as silky as they come , the sensation over the tongue is as pleasurable as quaffing god 's nipple lactations . taste is , however , the killer here because it 's just not as explosive as the complex nose and full body could easily have supported .
the imperial stout was very black in color with a dark brown head . very pretty .  the body is just fantastic : full , creamy and smooth .
pours a completely opaque pitch black . light brown head with some big bubbles around the edges .  full bodied , heavy on the palate and full of flavor . i love it .

cloudy gold with a large foamy head . head had very good retention , and eventually became a fine lace which left rings all the way down the glass . the appearance aside , this is not a very good beer .  mouthfeel is exceptional ! this beer is smooth , silky , creamy .
pours a beautiful dark brown with a slight ruby hue on the outer edges , nice thick microfoam head that leaves nice lacing .  m : medium body with a fantastic carbonation balance ! amazing here !

beautiful amber color . medium just-barely-off-white head that is nice and dense . very lasting lace .  the texture on this is great . with the silky texture and sweetness , this is a good sipper , but nothing you 'd have more than 2 of in a single sitting .
a - looking pretty good , especially after being poured from a room temperature shelf in almost clear glass .  still i thought the aroma was alittle weak , but once it hits your mouth it is amazing .

a- body is a moderately pale amber hue that pours with a nice 2-3 finger foamy white head . body is uniformly translucent and has the head has great retention with lots of lacing left all the way down the glass .  a great take on belgium ale ; apples , pears , lemons , apricot and orange flavors nustle their way thru a carbonated full bodied swig .

it pours midnight black with a huge , dark coffee-with-milk mead that does n't die easily and when it does , it leaves lacing thicker than most beers have head .  m : the mouthfeel is perfect . full and creamy with a little grittiness in the texture .

it almost overflowed out of the glass but soon settled into a craggy , dense mountain of a cap . massive cordillera of lace are plastered to the glass .  the mouthfeel is outstanding . substantial , but not quite so thick as to confuse it with a stout .

its pale golden body is saturated with torrents of lacing , and topped off with a meringue-like head of admirable retention . o : i do n't understand how people pay an extra $ 3/6pk for this garbage over bud ; it 's essentially the same stuff .  mouthfeel is exceptional . it feels good in the mouth but leaves no lasting memories on the taste buds .

poured into a pint glass ... appearance-maybe the best head i 've ever since on a hefeweizen . considering many hefeweizens bodys look similar this is getting a 5 . frothy 3 finger head that i 'm enjoying just sit there and watching the bubbles slowly pop .  the mouthfeel is fucking perfect : it 's thick and creamy .

ahh , maudite . a beautiful beer from a beautiful brewery . pours a dark , stained oak or cherry colour . nice , 2 1/2 finger froth head that clings to the glass .  mouthfeel is super creamy and silky smooth .

great looking beer .  mouthfeel- this is an exceptionally smooth saison , with the mouthfeel rivaling that of the saison dupont , my favorite of the style and one of my favorite beers . the tank 7 is definitely a thicker beer , very complimentary to the flavors .
head is enormous and very thick and creamy .  mouthfeel is phenomenal , rich and creamy it 's quite thick and chewy without going over the top .

appearance : clear golden with a reddish hue and a white head that falls back into the beer . a bit more carbonation and less blueberry and you have a perfect red ale as the color is stunning !  the mouthfeel is outstanding , substantial and even sticky .

a careful pour of half of this 500ml bottle created monster head . a- mud brown with an auburn tint . giant head died down to an okay 3mm leaving sprinkled lacing . subsequent gentle pours always ended in huge head .  mouthfeel ; very tight and lively carbonation , slick and creamy in the finish , pretty complex and admirable .

appearance shows off a pale orange body with a cloudy clook . a sticky and rocky cream colored head sits atop almost 2 inches thick and slowly fades .  the mouthfeel was very very thick and creamy and not as thin as say a sierra nevada .

light beige head is 1/4 inch on the pour but recedes to a thin cap . big gobs of sticky lace are solid down the sides of the glass .  deliciously smooth . coating the entire mouth with a lasting finish .

lighter and brighter looking than i expected , nelson poured without any `` redness '' i typically , and erroneously , associate with rye beers . a clear hay golden hue , with a beautiful cream white head ; excellent retention and lacing .  excellent mouthfeel and not too heavy .

pours a honey colored amber color with a three finger tight bubbled head with lots of wispy lace from start to finish .  the mouthfeel is perfect . it is full bodied with low carbonation , and oh so smooth .

a - pours a very dark brown - almost black - with a two-finger , well-carbonated , beige head that slowly dissipates to a 1 cm head . very attractive drink , as well as bottle which is slightly shorter and wider than most 12 oz bottles .  bear republic really , really nailed the mouthfeel on this one .

a : what a gorgeous beer . a good pour yields a 1.5 finger head that fades quickly , and leaves a decent amount of lacing around the glass .  m - smooth , silky , full body with the perfect amount of carbonation o - great brew !

a : lovely dark red-brown , nearly opaque , with an antique-white froth that 's thin but resilient .  t- the taste is starts out very smooth and creamy from the mouthfeel with some of roasted malts quickly followed by a nice bitter finish . m- the mouthfeel is silky smooth from the oatmeal with a moderate amount of carbonation . d- very good stuff , and not too boozy for a 9 % beer even though you can feel the warmth .
appearance was dark reddish .  mouthfeel is silky smooth , really nice . body fairly full and the beer leaves an impression all the way over the tongue .

pours a motor oil black with some brown edges and two fingers of mocha tan head . threads of lacing line the tulip . however , for some reason the beer is extremely green - perhaps it 's the victim of oxidization ?  mouthfeel is utterly smooth with just a hint of carbonation ... placidly perfect .

the colour is pitch-black ; the two finger head is pale beige , airy and uneven . massive amounts of lacing .  the feeling in your mouth , however is gorgeous ! smooth , silky , incredible.. so incredibly good that i actually said 'incredible ' in a french accent because it deserved such smoothness ... i 'm not going to lie , as for drinkability.. i 'm not as into this as anchor 's or even sierra nevada 's , christmas offerings this year , but it is still very drinkable to this lass .

big fluffy head that towers more than a half inch out of the pint.. pretty white color that leaves lace all the way down the glass ... hop hazed deep golden liquid .  this beer has an excellent mouthfeel .

tasted june 22nd 2011 ( from notes ) poured into a la chouffe tulip a - a clear blood red , one finger tan head and some lacing s - alcohol , wine barrels , sweet dried fruits , earth , oak , french vanilla and more sweet and alcohol t - alcohol , lots of sugar , sweet malts , tons of sweet dried fruit , black cherries , wine barrels , raisins , charred oak , molasses , carmelised brown sugar and vanilla .  ( not a huge coffee stout fan ) ( blasphemous i know ) the greatest thing about this beer is the smooth creamy texture that is present while drinking .

on-tap at the toronado . dark orangey brown with a nice 1/2 '' head of thick white foam that leaves killer lacing on the glass .  really wonderful . the mouthfeel is the most impressive and outstanding attribute of this beer .

comes out of the tap a rich opaque warm sable with a thick , fine-bubbled , almost guinness-like light tan head that leaves some good lacing .  mouthfeel - heavy body with mild carbonation . it 's perfect to me .
a nice perfect one and a half finger head rises from it that 's a tan color and has great retention and some spotty lacing .  mouthfeel : delightfully creamy and full-bodied . very pleasant .
very attractive beer . massive sticky foamy eggshell colored head rises to 2 fingers and holds there forever .  mouthfeel was virtually perfect .

appearance : pours a two finger thick tight bubbly dark tan head with very good retention . jet black body with minimal carbonation . head slowly fades to a good foam cap and leaves some nice lacing right away . a thin film remains until the end leaving some good looking lacing down the sides . a nice beer to look at .  mouthfeel : fantastic . great carbonation , no real aftertaste and washes easily over the palate .
brilliantly clear light copper hue . creamy , dense well retained head . beautiful in appearance , but lacking in all around flavor .  the mouthfeel is full and velvety .

appearance - perfect ! black with brown 2 finger head tiny bubbles smell - very pleasant as one would expect..malty , chocolatey , caramel and a very slight smokeness taste - very balanced as usual from a uk brewer .  m : great carbonation feel with a nice medium body . amazing here . perfect !

a truly spectacular appereance , deep chestnut with reddish purple highlights . a massive head that left thorough lacing . really attractive . quite pleasing minus the fact that no taste seems to linger .  mouthfeel : exceptionally smooth and silky as can be .
this really is a lovely looking beer .  mouthfeel is what always gets me on these beers , i love the chewy creamy coats your throat feeling here .

pours to a beautiful deep dark brown body with a hint of ruby red when held to light . hosts a decent 1 and a half inch rich tan head , leaving some lace as it fades .  mouthfeel : spot on in my opinion . medium to medium-lite body with perfect amount of carbonation .
rich reddish brown colour with a creamy beige cap .  extremely smooth tasting beer . bodied is so full its nearly chewable . mouthfeel is full and round . finish is clean and very smooth .
euro dark lager fits the bill better . looks good , as expected . dense tan head , lots of lacing .  m - perfect carbonation .

drake 's denogginizer pours a surprisingly dark amber . an aggressive pour results in more than 4 fingers of ivory colored foam sitting atop the beer .  amazingly smooth going down ; full bodied with light carbonation .

charcoal black with an inch thick teddy bear brown head that quickly sinks to an eighth of an inch . excellent lacing persists for some time thereafter .  mouthfeel is heavy and smooth with a nice small bite of carbonation , wonderful .
it looked very promising , poured thick and black .  t- pretty solid all around . very smooth , robust , and thick .
a : orange colour and a huge 4 cm head that sticks around due to the high carbonation .  incredibly smooth mouthfeel , likely due to the aging .

pours a deep chestnut with a thick white head which dissipates pretty quickly but leaves some nice lacing .  the mouthfeel was phenomenal . to have a cask conditioned beer is such a treat , and i 'm glad my neighborhood bar always has one beer on cask .
pours into 't hofbrouwerijke chalice a deep dark chocolate brown with a huge , i mean huge , light brown head . this is a head that just wo n't quit . it 's stunning .  perfect creamy mouthfeel .

an absolutely beautiful pour generates a very active three finger head of dark brown chocolate colored head that quickly faeds and leaves no lace .  mouthfeel is thick as hell and creamy , perfect for a big ris this is smooth as hell , much smoother than beers with this much ash flavor usually are .
topped with a frothy and creamy mocha colored head . looks pretty damn tasty .  wonderful full mouthfeel .
really lovely to look at .  very nice full bodied mouthfeel . easily drinkable .

what a shame ... pours a pretty golden-amber color topped by a huge , thick , creamy white head .  mouthfeel was phenomenal - silky smooth and with a slight hops bite on the tongue , giving 'way on the finish to a great caramel sweetness .

absolutely beautiful long-lasting cascade and unbelievable merangue-like head .  thick with just a little bit of slickness and just enough carbonation . sly fox oatmeal stout is a solid beer with a fantastic mouthfeel ; probably something i would order again .

real dark brown . nice big dark tan head that retained throughout the beer and laced the glass nicely .  the finish lingers for a while , almost spicy with a slight alcohol burn m - pretty ideal for this style i thought .
probably the most impressive head i have ever seen on a beer .  mouthfeel : very thick and very very smooth , wonderful mouthfeel .

pours dark brown nearly black with thick fluffy , chunky milk chocolate head that leaves hefty amounts of 3-d lacing as it slowly falls , damn this looks good !  where this brew really stands out is the creamy mouthfeel . that smoothness works to perfection with sweetness , but does n't work quite as well with bitterness .
looks very lively . this looks amazing and out of control .  the mouthfeel was spot on and the taste was close behind .

a - very nice lacing left by a frothy white head with strong stamina on top of a copper colored and translucent body . i even witnessed the bartender pouring some head away .  mouthfeel was awesome . farily prickly carbonation with some slight drying on the finish due to the barrel aging .
two fingers of thick billowing collapse into a thin cap that left sticky lacing on my glass .  m - huge , thick , syrupy , creamy , perfect carbonation .

i had this on tap and have to say was extremely impressed by its beautiful golden color , and fine head .  feel is pretty rich for the style , although it 's medium body it 's almost full really , with such a rich , smooth feel . excellent . honestly , it 's not very typical of the style at all , but i 'm not letting that change my rating .
this brew pours an opaque black color . the head is large , and fluffy with a color of white speckled with tan .  full creamy mouthfeel with a low carbonation . thick , thick mouthfeel .
as the foam subsides it applies some good lacing to the glass .  m : nice and light , yet still has some body . very smooth , good carbonation , good residue . exceptional .
poured into a 20oz pint glass has a hazy , cloudy straw colored body with a thick , just-off white head that leaves beautiful lacing .  but the mouthfeel is absolutely incredible .
a- damn sexy looking in my pilsner glass . it sits atop a slightly hazed , deep red almost apple cider colored body .  body is medium-full for style , and this is just about perfect on the way down .
pours a beautiful clear golden orange with a plentiful fluffy head and excellent sticky lacing .  m= perfect dryness and crispness .

blood red color with a thick pink foamy head the color of blush wine .  m - creamy and rich . the carbonation is very laidback ... almost feels as if it floats on the tongue . very soft ... puffy , in a way .
dark brown color with a smooth , silky , creamy , long lasting head of white foam .  mouth is extremely crisp , clean with tremendous carbonation and a nice light body .

pours vibrant pale gold with lively streams of carbonation sustaining an impressive large white head and leaivng lovely lacing .  however , the mouthfeel of this beer is phenomenal , on the tim of your tongue it tingles , in the middle it is smooth as silk , on on the edges it is a touch syrupy ( amazing ) a good beer , but not worth the price they charge for it .
terrific retention and lots of lace . stunning .  mouthfeel is outstanding . super thick and syrupy , that flavor coats the palate forever .
a- pours a golden apricot color . quite hazy .  the carbonation is perfect . i love this .

a clear copper ruby when held up to the light with brilliant head retention and honeycomb lacing .  bitter black chocolate moves into the woodiness and finishes boozy m- creamy , full-bodied , coats the mouth and boozy heat d- really impressed with this one .

dark copper with a 2 finger off-white head from a 22 into a pint glass . i drink slower , so i poured the remainder almost 30 minutes later and it still formed a 2 finger head . this is much lighter in the smoke than any rauch that most people have had .  m : medium body with the perfect amount of smooth , yet lively , carbonation . truly excellent .

presentation : 750ml brown bottle , corked and caged , with great label , poured into a belgian-style chalice that 's been in the family for 3 generations apperance : absolutely stunning dark garnet brew with huge ivory whipped cream head , lots of carbonation with amazing cap retention smell : big powdery belgian yeast tones , a bit of juicy dark fruit , light phenols and spice ... it all melds together nicely , but nothing really jumps out individually , it 's a bit understated actually taste : much bigger/spicier than the soft aromas suggest ... .there 's lots of sweet spice up front here , with ( cloves ) ?  the mouthfeel is absolutely perfect for a porter , so smooth and silky .

poures a deep tranparent amber in color . leaving a half finger of retention.thick gloppy rings of lace . : ( i was pretty excited to taste this after its wonderful appearance and terrific aroma .  the mouth feel is the richest and thickest i have ever tasted in a beer !

appearance perfect looking . the frothy , sticky head is everlasting .  m : fairly full body is well-attenuated for its strength , with an off-dry finish . perfect balance imho ... just enough residual sweetness to keep the alcohol from being too drying .

this one pours a beautiful orange copper color with 3/4 '' off-white head .  mouthfeel- damn , this sh*t is creamy ! smooth , medium carbonation , but goes down super smooth . nice light bitterness in the aftertaste .

pours jet black with 3 fingers of brownish , mocha head that just screams ice cream float . tons of sticky lacing & very good head retention s : roasty malt , rich , dark & fruitty with woody hops , & booze once warm t : roasty malt , dark choclate , herbal hops along with molasses , leafy & minty hops up front .  perfect mouthfeel .

lovely hue , a truly good bright ruby red , with a collapsing , but pleasantly silky head of yellow white . it 's a really lovely looking american red ale , absolutely what you want from the style .  tiny bit of alcohol flavor let 's you know it can do some damage m : super creamy dipa , full bodied , good bubbly carbonation ( do n't know why there was n't much head though !
poured a gorgeous amber pink , with a thick white fluffy head . plenty of lacing .  the mouthfeel is outstanding , like an expensive champagne and it finishes very dry .
pours beautiful dark brown with red edges , almost black with a huge tan head that sticks around and leaves walls of creamy lace .  m - perfect body .

a nearly perfect pour . smells and tastes of the usual hefe spicy , peppery yeast , clove and banana , with a touch of citrus ( maybe lemon ) sourness .  all the great flavor of the bottled lhms here , but perfectly creamy and full in texture . this only further reinforces my belief that nearly every big beer should be served nitro .

it 's one of the prettiest beers i 've ever seen ! deep , dark brown with a hint of ruby when held up to strong light . a tan frothy and foamy lasts and lasts , leaving waves of sticky lace on the side of the glass ( artful ) .  the mouthfeel was amazing . nearly full-bodied .

canned on 10/26/2011 a : pours a deep , clear ruby color with a finger of thick light tan colored head .  the mouthfeel is freakin unbelieveable for me . unique and probably the finest mouthfeel i have felt in any belgian , ever .

this pours out the same deep orange color as the last one with the same solid fluffy head , lacing , etc . as appearance goes , there is nothing left to improve upon .  mouthfeel is heavy bodied and velvety smooth .
pours a deep black color with a half inch frothy head .  full rich mouthfeel , particularly fun after back-to-backing the hansenns cassis .

app : deep amber clear . very thick fluffy white head w/lace .  mouthfeel was creamy and exceptional . i was surprised to be able to drink the whole thing since i am not a fan of coffee at all , but this was a pleasant change of pace for me .

this one pours a hazy yellowish orange with a white head that just will not go away . looks great overall .  sweet malts are offset by crisp hops together producing a wonderful balance and mouthfeel . sooo smooth !
a - this is a beautiful looking beer .  mouthfeel was absolutely terrific .

thought this beer had a really nice color . an excellent color . i 'm thinking mahogony , but i 'm not sure exactly what color that ... but i 'm thinking like a deep deep wood varnish color ... really nice .  m/d : a full body that is creamy and velvety smooth .

this is absolutely pitch black with a very surprising thick and creamy brown head that settles to a thin covering that still looks fantastic .  this beer has an amazing mouthfeel , very full and luscious , super smooth .
a- pours dark clear gold-yellow with a white and beautiful head . big carbonation , looks fantastic .  m : incredibly creamy leaving a nice coating around the mouth that tingles slightly .
had this one just a few minutes ago , and i have to say i 'm was very impressed . gorgeous presentation especially in a decorated glass german stein .  m- feel is exceptionally clean and smooth .
almost black ( ruby red highlights ) with a nice brown head that leaves sheets of lace .  m : the feel is thick and chewy with a nice creamy texture .

a : thick and black , dark almond head ( more like a thin disk of residual bubbles ) s : strong note of alcohol , bitter dark chocolate , coffee m : very alcoholic feel ; initial taste of a dark stout followed by the heat of a liquor akin to scotch .  the mouthfeel on this beer is abosolutely amazing , almost like carbonated cream , it is wonderful and invites another sip immediately .

there was also a good bit of effervesence in a brew that was a beautiful golden-yellow color . there was decent head retention throughout and the `` belgian lace '' that was left behind was beautiful .  this is one of the thickest beers i 've had . very heavy and smooth mouthfeel .
a - in a word , beautiful . a rocky off-white rocky head sits atop a lovely ruby-red body . one of the prettiest beers i 've had the pleasure of drinking .  mouthfeel is perfect , my ideal belgian .

dark chocolate brown with a nice , thick , creamy , khaki head atop .  silky silky smooth on the mouth , it makes it feel as light bodied but if you take the time to get a feel it 's almost medium . just fantastic . o- this is deffinitely a good saison , the mouthfeel is the highlight .
this brew pours with a deep amber body topped by a medium thick head with lots of lacing .  m - creamy and full in the mouth , so good , this is just what i want in a marzen .
this batch was amazing ! the color was orange and hazy .  m - extremely smooth .

looked great on the pour . hazy apricot with a thin wispy head .  this was the first belgian i ever had . it has a very creamy smoothness that i really love . finishes long and dry with more fruityness .

a- the pour yields an opaque black body with a small khaki colored head composed of tightly knit bubbles . the head is long lasting and leaves complete rings on the sides of my glass .  mouthfeel the best part of this beer , really smooth with just a little bit of carbonation .
a one finger , mocha colored head has supreme retention and some amazing lacing to go along with it . very nice looking .  perfect . d- a remarkably smooth beer , although a bit mild .

this beer pours absolutely beautifully , pale yellow in color with a massive and i mean massive head .  round velvety texture , excellent carbonation , and ( as you would expect ) some warming . exceptionally satisfying brew - if not my absolute favorite from unibroue , it is the one i return to most often .
poured an opaque brown , as expected from a stout , with thick , pillowy tan head and excellent lacing .  all kinds of malty goodness going on here - silky smooth , slightly pinpoint carbonation .

a- caramel amber beer , nice dark coloration , super huge head with sticky lacing .  m-grand canyon deep and gordian knot complex . amazingly tantalizing on the palate . while it looks still in the glass it bursts with palate stimulating carbonation with each sip . like an amusement park in your mouth ! this is a highly enjoyable and palate stimulating sipper . a mighty fine drinking brew .

glass : snifter temp : cellared @ approx 45 degrees this is perfect appearance for a stout . it 's as black as black can be . the head takes a long while to recede to a nice thick surface covering , over an 1/8th of an inch thick . visually , this is quite an impressive beer .  a great feel that has a body that replenishes itself .
it pours a dark , coppery amber with a frothy , persistent , off-white head .  mouthfeel is of a super smooth , velvetty batch . this may be one of the smoothest , silkiest brews that i have had .
pop goes the cork and a soft pour fills the glass with a clear golden color and a dense white head filling the upper half of the tulip .  ideal texture for an ipa .

a- pours a very hazy yellow-orange with a thick white head that lasts a long time and leaves lots of lacing . exactly what this style should look like .  for the style , this is an exceptional mouthfeel .
dark-brown/mahogany color with a full creamy tan head and good carbonation which leaves sheets of lace .  the mouthfeel is full and warming , in fact , this beer is a huge belly warmer .

hazy and dark copper-amber in color with a thick cream colored head of super tightly laced foam that left great lacing at it receded at a slow but steady rate ; the head reminds me of an improperly baked cake very slowly losing its leavening .  the beer itself is pretty thick , and mixed with the lingering foamy head , it feels great in the mouth for savoring what taste there actually is .

per label `` a kicked up version of our popular wee heavier '' , i had the pleasure of trying that brew a few years back while in asheville and i have to say i liked that one better.poured into a 22oz nonic a deep amber/brown with a pillowey 2 finger light beige head atop that settled ever so slowly into a frothy mass leaving broken rings of lace behind , from there down hill.muted aromas slight brown brown sugar and fruit but it doesnt show thru enough , flavors stay with that theme very light with some malt tilted sweetness like brown sugar and raisin but its really light and watery tasting in my mind.hmm kind of a clunker here was expecting much more from a pretty good small brewery in western carolina .  what got me hooked was how smooth and creamy this beer was . fantastic . this beer is by far one of the richest and creamiest beers i have ever had .
a - pours a thick 2 fingers of tan head that sticks around for quite some time .  great palate , though . even when it gets warm , great warmth and sliky smooth syrups .

this one is really impressive out of bottle , with a deep , opaque brown-to-black color topped by a huge , fizzy beige head that settles to a persistent ring .  altogether pleasing to the tongue and brain , it also had a beautifully full mouthfeel from the oustandingly appropriate delicate carbonation .
oysters ... hmmm ... pours a blackish black with a black interior and black edging . nice looking bubbling dark brown foam . really attractive .  awesome mouthfeel .

it 's so cloudy you ca n't see any yeast in it , just an opaque gold glass . thick , white head that keeps a barrier of foam for the entire bottle .  easy to drink due to it 's creamy mouthfeel and pleasant flavor .
sterling scarlet brown under a large canopy of tan .  silky , creamy , and perfectly textured , this mouthfeel ca n't be beat .

) , puckered 10/06 slow pour in a tulip glass poured murky pale orange with a huge rocky fully lasting white head with good lacing .  m : soft , smooth carbonation , big and viscous body , excellent finish . there 's very little more that i want from a big ris d : i drank my bottle in an hour and was craving more notes : i did n't really expect much from this beer because nh have n't really impressed me with much of what they 've done but hot damn , this was impressive !

pours out great , an excellent pitch black with a nice tan head and good lacing .  taste again where do i start ... sweet , spicy dark fruits soaked in alcohol ( raisins , currents , dates ) , toasted caramel notes , bready , some brandy / rum traces , biscuity , warming alcohol , spicy hop bitterness forces itself through the sweet maltiness , light madeira wine hints ... feel - so silky smooth ... rich and creamy ... light viscousness.. low drinkablilty for this one - a beer for savouring and sipping slowly ... overall - a phenomenal beer ... highly recommended .

bottle purchased at liquor world , somerville , ma poured a slightly hazy , very light and pale straw yellow with a tight , bubbly , three-finger , bone white head . tons of cascading , spider webbing lacing formed large ridges that last well after the beer was finished .  mouthfeel is perfect -- light but not watery , highly carbonated ... perfect for the style .

i 've been avoiding this beer , but my wife bought me a sixer so here we go ... poured into a sa perfect pint glass , and it looks pretty good with mounds of soft and pillowy head , and a golden/slightly hazy body .  m- creamy smooth with just the right amount of carbonation and a nice , dry finish .

pours black with virtually no light around the edges . towering cap of light brown foam that grew on the pour like one of those ash-growing snake things from a fireworks stand . retention is great , as is the lacing .  t/m - well carbonated , providing a prickly yet very smooth feel as it rolls across the tongue .

the brew itself is a spectacular amber-orange color that is crystal clear . the head dissipates to a constant quarter-finger thickness with excellent lacing all the way down . while it has a fantastic appearance , everything else is only slightly above average ( for microbrews ) .  the mouthfeel on this beer is great , so creamy with just enough bubbles that make it not to syrupy .

pours a cloudy gold with a beautiful creamy two finger head that does n't let up much .  the best part of the rwanda gatsinga coffee stout is in my opinion the mouthfeel which is extremely smooth and leaves a pleasant malty coffee-dominated aftertaste and a smile on your face .

a- pours into my pint glass a light mahagony with a finger of bright foam . this trails into a lacing pattern that reminds me of a coral reef , quite beautiful .  mouthfeel is superb . great level of spice , perfect carbonation , medium body .

a -- pour a cloudy pale gold color with two fingers of head that recedes fairly quickly but leaves some lacing on the glass s -- smell is spices , banana/clove , light wheat malts .  the mouthfeel is luxurious , thick , and chewy . amazing . i am impressed with this brew . flavors are great and the mouthfeel is unearthly .
superb head retention . appears to be an impressive looking stout or porter .  m - the creamiest beer i 've ever had . wow . thick , smooth , perfect .

appearance : pours a deep copper body with a lush , creamy-looking white head .  the feel is super dry , tannic and superb on the palate , rough , sticky , and full ... easy to drink as this crushed by the girlfriend and i in about 15 minutes .

guinness pours ruby black with a beautiful creamy white head that lingers for quite a while .  great relaxed flavor , it has a nice sweetness to it , a good malt body ; it would be a great beer to drink while out on the river all day , as it has a wonderful flavor without having too much ( it was made with this in mind , according to one of the brewers ) . goes down extremely smooth with a great crisp , sweet aftertaste . ( had on-tap at the star city vfd brew fest fund raiser .

the beer poured in a dutch beerglass gives a very nice white head with a dark coppercouloured fluid . the smeel is average , ca n't really say what smells reach out my nose but it 's not spectacular .  mouthfeel is thick and chewy , as it should be fir a beer of this strength .

deep mahogany in colour , crystal clear when held up to the light . the head poured thick & white then retreated to a light surface covering , still maintaining the lace on the glass .  taste & mouthfeel : smoothness is impeccable within the moderate body , big doughy biscuity malt flavour is the showcase of this brew .
looks amazing , as have all the jolly pumpkin 's i 've tried . basically looks as good as a beer can .  mouthfeel : perfect , just like champagne .

the cascade hop explosion was still there , but i was able to handle it this time around and i really enjoyed it . ruby-amber color , bordering on red . awsome color .  m : very viscous and full . smooth carbonation and a nice stickyness make the mouthfeel very complimenting to the taste .

a - dark ruby with tan head . gorgeous lacing .  body is the best part of this brew . flavors are all in check , mouthfeel is full and fat , with a straw-like dryness at the finish . this beer is exceptionally drinkable .

appearance : poured with a huge fluffy white head that lasted forever . the beer is a clear golden color with a few bubbles rising , but the head sticks around anyway . there is a whole bunch of lacing left on the glass after the head falls .  mouthfeel is lucious : creamy and oily , rich in the mouth , but smooth enough to want more and more .

a- pours a hazy ornage-yellow with a nice pillowy off-white head with good retention , leaves some spotty lacing around the glass .  the carbonation is fantastic -- beer feels creamy and smooth- almost velvety .
a gritty caramelized-orange color , a little haze .  m- big , full body ... oily , almost syrupy with unattenuated sugars . very chewy , and it coats the mouth so well . just wonderful .

a - classic dark bronze doppelbock color .  the creamy , delicious texture pairs well with the flavorful personality of the smoked porter . the dancing carbonation paired with the brews creamy-smooth feel and intense flavor essentially block dopamine receptors in your brain .

looks perfect . mounds of off white maybe pretty much light tan head , and has a clear dark copper colored body .  m : full-bodied , silky smooth , velvety rich and downright luxurious in the mouth . these guys have this whole mouthfeel down to a t. notes : malty rich , fruity sweet , and explosively spicy , this bspa is quite enjoyable !

creamy khaki foam tops off this american porter , the surface has a light sheen to it , forming uneven crags and peaks that push above the rim . sticky lacing is left all around , clumped in almost cartoonish 3-d . cola ruby color in the light , with slow trails of carbonation .  mouthfeel is full and round .
pours a nice dark black color , with a huge , chunky , creamy tan colored head , great retention .  smooth , creamy , almost velvet like . really enjoyable .
it has a deep , copper/mahogany color with stunning clarity and a beautiful head . such a nice looking brew !  mouthfeel is fantastic ... light , dry , well carbonated , and quite bitter .
a - golden with a slight haze . massive 5+ fingers of head foam up . excellent retention with a thick cap that remains .  m : rich and creamy . very chewy and thick . little carbonation .

a deep mocha head emerges from the bottom of the glass to form a nice half inch layer . exactly the appearance a big stout should uphold ; textbook .  unbelievably smooth in mouthfeel - bittersweet chocolate and bitter roasted notes played effortlessly on your tongue .
a- pours dark black . one of the prettiest beers i 've seen .  so creamy and smooth it 's almost not a beer ...

gave it a great appearance rating because it totally looks like autumn ! perfect golden brown hue and the thin wispy head perfectly resembles those thin , drawn-out clouds in front of the moon on creepy fall nights .  mouthfeel is exceptional . very smooth , great carbonation , but not enough to distract from the flavors going on .
pours nicely to an amber color with good head .  m : one of the fullest and creamiest dipas i 've ever had .

pours a lovely shiny ruby colour , rich and clear . head is beige , nice and dense and retaining thin crown . lace is good and sticky . looks wonderful .  the mouthfeel is great ... medium on the palate , but slick and well carbonated ... compliments the black pepper flavor perfectly .

towards the end of the night it settles down to a thin concentric ring but a nice swirl brings you back to viewing what i consider one of the most beautiful looking barleywines i 've ever seen .  thick creamy mouthfeel and mild carbonation . smooth silky mouthfeel is lucious .

the pour is ebony in color , the head inconsequential in size , the structure patchy clumps of large bubbles , the color a light chocolate .  full effervescent body , huge amounts of carbonation . an unusual beer that 's quite good .

bottle ( 2011 ) port bottle shop carlsbad , ca dark black with no clarity throughout . thick and persistent light brown head and plenty of spiderweb lacing down the glass .  thick rich and creamy mouthfeel . for such a rich and big beer it is remarkably smooth .
this beer pours opaque and colorless .  perfectly carbonated , with a thick chewy body and a strong alcohol burn .

a - pretty , near black pour with quite a sold 1+ inch head that stays around for awhile .  m - fairly heavy body and solid flavors with moderate carbonation . the flavors are spot , the mouthfeel is amazing and its very drinkable .
one beautiful looking barleywine here . it almost glows a nice dark amber color .  very palatable and no alcohol taste at all m - silky smooth , great carbonation .

this beer pours a hazy orange color . the head is a mammoth three inches in height , and recedes slowly into a large , rocky cap of foam .  body is simply luxurious - rich , creamy , and damn near perfect .

wow , this beer really looks like it was poured from a bar tap ... great body . boddingtons is so unique for being a light-looking golden beer that pours like an irish stout ; those widget things work well .  mouthfeel is very soft and full bodied with light carbonation .

it 's black as the devil , not a hint of light going through this , and a thick brown head which lingers for awhile .  s : caramel , apple , sweet roasted malt t : tastes of caramel , some sour fruit like apple , yeast and hops bitterness/spice , some booze m : beautifully creamy and thick , but has a sharpness from the medium carbonation and booze o : drinkable for a bottle at least , this is an awesome beer .

pours dark amber with a large honeycomb coloured head and lots of lacing .  m : one of the most enjoyable mouthfeels i 've ever had in a beer ; medium-bodied and moderately carbonated , immensely smooth and surprisingly creamy . d : i thought that the taste here was good , not great ... but the amazing mouthfeel and complex flavor keep drawing me back in , and at much faster rate than that of many beers whose tastes i prefer .

beautiful red orange color . a tan head sits on top for a while . a very pretty beer . we tried it with some honey ham and then some apple pie and it was terrific with both .  the mouthfeel is , in a word , glorious . smooth on the tip of the tongue , then seeming to evaporate off your tongue leaving a crisp , somewhat spicy finish .

this pours a beautiful black with a one finger tan head with incredible retention and good lace .  m : carbonation is explosive ( like the cork escapade ) . tickles the mouth with just the right amount of chewiness .

this is the dead-on look for a pilsner ; pale straw color with steady streams of bubbles heading for the surface . the head is huge and sticky and clings to the side of the glass as if it were a life-or-death matter .  m : full-bodied and lightly carbonated with a soft and creamy texture . alcohol noticable in a nice warming effect .

poured into a tall glass , pours a cloudy almost two tone fire red color . genuinely impressive , that i have never seen something like this before .  finshes warming , hoppy & bready , very balanced approach mf : chewy with low carbonation & great balance dangerously drinkable , this would put you on your butt after a couple of pints but a really nice dipa

a dark ruby-brown , not quite opaque , with a 1 finger tan head . i guess that i can get behind some smoked malt , and it is n't too strong in this one and i am sure nicely balanced , but i love schwarzbiers and this one takes what i like away from them . a nice toasty maltiness with some balanced hop bitterness , like a savory version of stout .  just take a sip and get lost in the nearly overpowering flavor explosion and the creamy tingly mouthfeel of this wondrous scottish ale .
a : huge snowy head , billowing above the glass . classic belgian carbonation , bravo .  a full bodied beer that is creamy smooth and goes down really easy .

poured a beautiful amber color . wonderful lacing . just a beautiful beer .  appearance : cloudy burnt orange/brown - nice head retention smell : cinnamon , nutmeg , pumpkin spice taste : hops , cinnamon , coriander , nutmeg - similar to an american wild ale - very tannic mouthfeel : my favorite part very tannic , smooth - the rye dries the palate out so you 're ready for another sip or another bite of food .

it is as black as pitch . a nice , pillowy thick 2 finger head formed and stayed for the whole beer .  m - absolutely creamy and delectable ! the amazing , tiny bubbled froth envelopes and contains any alcohol sharpness that would otherwise make this 8.0 % beer a bit fiery in the swallow . superb . d - the mouthfeel makes this otherwise straight-up scotch ale an incredibly drinkable beverage . but be careful ! at 8 % , this beer is like getting a two-for-one special in each pint !
this brew is quite hazy with a golden orange body . the head produced is massive and bright white .  mouthfeel is the best part of the beer .

a - golden brew with extremely intense carbonation large head fueled by the bubbling .  smooth and creamy mouthfeel makes the small tickling carbonation and otherwise heavier body very palatable . i do n't know if so much milk is my thing , but i 'm glad i tried it .
a : aggressive pour yields 2.5 fingers of pillowy off-white head with very good retention .  mouthfeel : low carbonation leads to thirsty gulps .

burnt amber with a fluffy , light tan head of good size and staying power . lots of foamy lace left in the tulip as the head never really dies but eventually falls to a cm or so in height . there 's still some retention before the glass is finished . very nice .  m- very , very thick and chewy . also quite heavy .
reduces to a thin covering quickly with a handful of bubble trails enhancing the look of a beautiful fall season color .  mouth-feel was velvety smooth and creamy .

the appearance is still wonderful , rich , creamy and delightful , although you get less of the wonderful spectacle of the bubbles gently settling on the surface .  great bubbly mouthfeel , no aftertaste at all .
pours opaque black with a thick brown head .  m/d : full bodied , very smooth , velvet like .

solid brownish black with a massive and thick mocha head that has outstanding retention and leaves lots of lacing all around the glass .  mouthfeel : perfection . the bead is neither too large nor too small .

poured from the bottle into a pint glass a - pours a brilliant off-white three finger head with great retention . leaves gorgeous lacing .  they served it properly too - the temperature was perfect ( not co cold ) . pretty close to perfect .

a - frothy and thick white head standing a couple inches tall with awesome stamina . the body is a hazy yellow .  caramel , mocha , strong booze , brown sugar , raisins , figs , chocalate t-malt , mocha , booze , brown sugar , caramel , raisins figs , chocalate m-spicy , creamy , thick , barely carbonated d- pretty thick & filling .

reviewed 11/16/2008 ( tap @ the stables , st. louis , mo ) : very cool presentation in a kasteel glass with a castle on the stem of the goblet-like glass . pours a very dark blood red body , with a lasting frothy pink head .  m - big bodied , thick , and viscous as hell . middling carbonation fades to a really dry and herbal finish like green tea . wicks all moisture from my mouth !

a : black , opaque , with dense creamy tan head s : mild to medium nose , more spritzy carbonation than anything , slight roasted malt evident t : decent black saison , definite bubblegum and yeast taste , not as clean as i 'd like , somewhat metallic-sharp taste in body , almost reminds me of an average tasting extract homebrew m : medium bodied , good roasted malt but sharp , metallic bitter finish that makes it slightly unbalanced in taste o : not what i 'd expect from goose island for balance and representation of the style  big , viscous mouthfeel does great things for this beer , transmitting a pretty large package ( 10 % , significant ibu count ) into an easy-to-sip package .

appearance : beautiful deep gold color , a lushous two-fingered layer of white foam , lots of rising bubbles , good head retention , flecks of lace aroma : dusty , cinnamony , malty , honey-like sweetness , floral hops , plummy fruitiness , perfumy ( sage and roses ?  mouthfeel is where this one shines , smooth as can be and perfectly carbonated , a light yet creamy quality .

pours a nice deep and shiny orange/amber , with a beautiful white , fluffy head that stays a good while . nice creamy lacing on the glass .  nice touch of bitterness lingers as i contemplate the rich , full mouth feel . nice beer , much more approachable than the expedition .

poured 45 degrees fahrenheit into a tulip glass . comes a deep amber-red with a thick off white head above a vortex of champagne bubbles . gorgeous .  mouthfeel is astonishingly smooth and creamy for such a rich , complex ale .
its pale golden liquid is filled with lively bubbles cascading to the the bright long lasting white head .  amazing mouthfeel . viscous , rich and creamy without being syrupy .
it pours really good it looks just terrific in my pint glass .  mouthfeel- soft , silky smooth texture . full bodied and rich . perfect .

man , this was more of a teaser than anything ... could n't drink a whole pint if i wanted ... appearance is dark with webby head that sticks to everything it touches..the drink is so sweet and finishes semi-bitter , i feel like i just ate a sweet treat with each bite .  really big round full mouthfeel .

a : looks good , like root beer but with a foam that looks more alive . two finger dark soda head , this in turn crowns a jet black beer .  m : full body , and shockingly creamy . this brew is extremely smooth of the mouth .

beautiful , clear dark copper color . excellent clarity here . a moderate cap of light whipped cream , tiny bubbles mostly , sits at the top . this is as pretty as an ipa can be .  very full and creamy mouth . damn tasty .
looks really nice s : light fruity smells , with a caramel malt , slight peppery notes from from the hops , maybe a slight metallic note .  it seemed to just coat my whole mouth on its way down .
great looking pour for a white ale .  this beer is silky smooth with very well behaved carbonation - you 'll have no trouble taking big gulps of this brew !
great looking porter . you would get lost at sea looking through this , perfectly black .  ( m ) mouthfeel is perfect for this beer .

appearance- beautiful honey-tan-golden creamy pour with a nice 3/4 inch fat solid head . lacing is a solid sheet of white down the entire glass .  t : the taste was about average for a stout , almost identical in flavor to guinness m : amazing mouthfeel , so creamy and so smooth .

lovely scarlet/violet color . perfectly clear . nice big bubble , white foam on top .  light in body with absolutely wonderful carbonation , this is airy , creamy and the combination of sourness and spiciness on the finish is unique .
pours dark amber-brown with moderate clarity and a nice and thick light tan head .  mouthfeel was full and rich . this is a very good beer , and quite a unique one .
appearance : clean , clear golden body . very nice looking .  had an appropriate lower level of carbonation that many ris can not compete against . rich and thick on the palate . very warming .
also , a wonderful , frothy , mocha head retains throughout .  the mouthfeel is excellent .

a 1/2 '' medium brown head takes a very long time to fade to a thick film . lacing is impressive , lots of thick , clingy curtains stick around for a while and eventually fade to thin strings that were still there when i went to wash the glass off .  perfect in this sense .

this beer proves that looks are n't everything . pours an utterly marvellous cloudy yellowish gold under a stupendous off-white head that grows and billows into spectacular cumulous clouds of foam on top of the liquid . this head lingers long and leaves very nice lace . ca n't really ask for more in a wheat beer 's appearance . the mouth starts off prickly , but goes flat like magic even before you can swallow . after the beautiful vision , the reality was quite disappointing .  the mouth feel on this one is perfect . the head retention is outstanding and just adds to that smooth , creamy , malty , citrus finish .

dark golden yellow . thickish head . excellent lacing .  smooth and thick ( of medium thickness ) , with small abrasive bubbles ( in the best possible way ) . wish i had let it chill a little longer to see a greater range of flavors as it warmed , but still a nice experience .
a dark body that exhibits a reddish tinge when held up to the light , with thick lacing spiraling down the side .  mouthfeel - very smooth with a rich body and muted carbonation .

what i like about this beer : the aroma is reminiscent of fresh-brewed black coffee . what i do n't like about this beer : the coffee flavor is a bit off-putting . it tastes like cheap , bitter black coffee mixed with beer . overall i liked this beer enough but i have enjoyed several other coffee beers more . the coffee porters and stouts i 've enjoyed have handled the coffee much better . i 'm actually curious how they added the coffee , whether it was flavoring , beans , grounds , or straight brewed coffee .  the mouthfeel is what really sets this apart . having had very few english cask ales , i do n't know if this is gold standard , but it is the best mouthfeel i 've had on this style beer .

pours dark brown with a hint of red and a moderate ring of pink foam .  my favorite thing about this obviously the sweet rich malt character which adds to a very nice body for a beer of this alcohol content .
4.5 a : lightly hazed light orange color . three fingers of pillowy white head with very good retention and plenty of lacing too .  mouthfeel very full and smooth .

appearance : very dark with a thick foam head with good retention . very good lacing .  it 's as smooth as silk - perfectly suited as a dinner and desert sipper and easily the best porter i 've had the pleasure of tasting .

a very nice looking beer .  perhaps there is similar inconsistency here , and i will be wowed by the bottles i brought home sometime in the future ... mouthfeel is by far the best characteristic , supple , creamy and light .

just when you think you have seen it all when it comes to beer appearances , this one comes along . strangely fascinating looking beer .  appearance : amber , clear carbonated , medium head smell : alcohol , grapefruit , and citrus taste : alcohol , grapefruit , malts , hops , and slight caramel mouthfeel : smooth , slightly hard finish , can feel the carbonation ... it is amazing how smooth and unbitter this beer is for a beer with its abv drinkability : i will have this again , but may be one of the few that prefer the 60 minute ipa .

a big fluffy tan head with good retention looks quite nice . some nice lacing is left and the head is very persistent . good looking pint .  m : thick and rich , with a nice amount of fine , late-developing carbonation . perfect for such a big beer .
