bottle courtesy of bu11zeye : poured a slightly cloudy bright yellow color ale with a super huge foamy pure white head with great retention and great lacing .  mouthfeel is extremely smooth & this is a perfect beer to sip on on a lazy pm with no kids in sight !

the appearance was impressive , very black with a nice brown head .  the malt is well back but the beer still has a nice light body . the palate is a great balance of all that and a nice honey quality in the background .
a nice two fingered head forms quickly and had great retention .  mouthfeel is perfect and this is a pretty drinkable brew .
this beer pours with the most beautiful colors of orangish-red . it recieved a perfect 5 .  very excellent mouthfeel and drinkability .

it is a very pretty looking beer when poured into a pils glass . straw blonde colour with a thick white head that lingers for a while .  mouthfeel : on the heavy side of the medium-bodied scale and creamy smooth .

pours an opaque orange gold with a massive , fluffy four finger head . gorgeous , a pour and a swirl can barely keep it in the glass . lots of visible , whitish sediment swirls around under the head . tiny champagne bubbles collect on the outside under the rim , sliding shimmering down the glass into a frothy lace after a tilt .  entering the mouth , i immediately take notice of the huge mouthfeel on this . this is fluffy , powdery , quaffable , and has this charming soft carbonation that is typical of great beers . palate displays a superb spicy bitterness executed in incredible balance and harmony ( this and the mouthfeel are the 2 attractions imo ) , gentle woodiness .

it has a gold cloudy body with a beautiful head and just the right amount of carbonation from an aesthetic point of view . it is a simply picture perfect beer .  what i really loved was the mouthfeel . very good for a lager style beer .
clear dark ruby appearance . creamy , somewhat bubbly , beige head sits on top .  mouthfeel : thick and smooth in every sense of the words -- a very pleasant experience indeed !
the goosinator pours a nice red amber color with a big head that bubbles down to a 1/4 inch creamy smoothe head .  subtly carbonated , with a medium-full body and a delightful smoothness .

the beer pours a dark amber with an impressive frothy head . the retention is excellent and lacing is glass coating .  a - bright golden orange color with some chill haze present , two fingers of white frothy head that leaves thick froth-lace s - not too much rye here , just hints ... hops and bready malt t - hop bitterness up front , sweet bready malts in the back , only a hint of rye in the middle ... the malt backing is about as significant as it gets ... taste 's more like a straight up ipa than most rye beers i 've had m - hops tingle the tongue and give way to very thick , chewy malts that slide down nicely ... full-bodied and very enjoyable d - this is a reeeally well-balanced beer , i just wanted more rye flavor .
dark brown with hints of red , and a solid beige head .  this belgian pale ale has a strong cookie-like malt character and an exceptionally smooth mouthfeel .
appearance : big pillowy off-white head . minimal lacing . burnt orange color .  mouthfeel is really exceptional , which along with the smooth flavors is what i really like .
first pour into pint glass from 22oz bottle- brilliantly clear straw color . head was bright and high but fell to an inch for the remainder .  thick lushious body and moderate carbonation .

lots to read on the label.. pours a beautiful solid brown , with a tan micro-bubbled head that washes the glass like a wave on every drink .  feels amazingly clean and fresh while keeping the flavor of charred wood and grains . smooth , creamy , full bodied , and almost a velvet nature . the carbonation is played on in the background as an overcoat . the simplicity of it overwhelms me .

a - dark caramel brown in color with some golden hues around the edges of the glass . hue , foamy off-white head with excellent retention .  m : the feel is excellent with fine carbonation lending a creaminess that is top-tier and a clean scrubbing finish with the right balance of crispness and aftertaste . d : an fine tripel with classic light fruit flavors mixed artfully with pepper and spice and a top-notch mouthfeel compose a very good brew .

let 's start with first impressions : this big beer makes a big impression on appearance . dark and sinister looking , the rough-textured mocha-colored head sits atop the black body like a russian fur cap . lacing is full and sticky .  mouthfeel is really impressive . very gradual on the tongue and extraordinarily balanced .

a : pours a clear copper color with a big rocky head . great sustain and tons of thick , sticky lace on the glass .  again this is a beer with a very good character but i still feel it does n't perfectly balance m- incredible mouthfeel .

appearance : fantastic dark ale , glows slightly ruby when held up against the light . one of the best heads i 've seen - 1.5cm thick , creamy and slightly off-white . good retention and lacing .  not the stunner i was hoping for m- beautiful mouth feel . i sure hope this is not the `` great sculpin '' i 've been waiting for for that past few years .

it pours an orange yellow glow through the haze . the head is massive , billowy and ice cream like in its consistency .  the mouth-feel was what was remarkable to me , very thick and creamy , i would liken it to a stout milkshake , really satisfying and enjoyable to drink .
usual alesmith great appearance .  perfect carbonation .

beautiful golden bronze colour . head retention is superb , an easy 4 fingers . these certainly do have a tendency to 'explode ' upon uncapping , with foam exiting the bottle for several minutes afterwards .  the mouthfeel is exceptionally smooth and creamy , terrific . thanks bif for the sample .
a - incredible crimson-amber color with a lasting two-finger off-white head .  outstanding mouthfeel ! very drinkable .

a : my usual down-the-middle stout pour results in a near-overflow of creamy , frothy , light-brown foam above a midnight-black body . solid retention and some light , fine lacing .  mouthfeel is big full and smooth very rich and easy drinking with a really satisfing warming in the gut .

a bottle exceptionally beautiful . so , for large qualities , almost everything .  taste- for a double ipa , this beer is not on a mission to wreck the palate ... with so much flavor i 'm surprised that the malts weigh in so heavily . solid . it 's sudsy ( the name of my beloved late parakeet ) and sublime . drinkability- one real attribute about this bruiser of a beer is that the abv ( 10 % ) is completely hidden ... it 's nowhere in any of the above categories . this is more like a nectar , thick and juicy , garnering respect for each sip .
a : the beer is a deep dark brown color , with a large brown head that fades slowly and leaves a thick lace on the glass .  super creamy mouthfeel w/o any overcarbed bite .

baltika # 6 porter is nearly black in colour but has a slightly red hue when held to the light . a handsome porter .  loved the residual stickiness . d- it 's remarkable how fff can make such big beers and hide the alcohol so well .

bottled in july 2011 poured into a tulip glass . still manages to create a creamy , thick-looking head , quite impressive . head fades gradually to a thin ring around the glass with some islands , leaving lots of lacing .  delicious . and i think what makes it delicious is not entirely a taste thing , but a feel thing . so smooth and creamy and round without any heaviness or stickiness . and it 's an appropriate textural delivery for the huge fruits here ( again , fig , plum and raisin dominant ) ; smoky cherry continues to remind of pipe tobacco ; a more general/generic smoke flavor nicely sneaks in with warming ; and there 's a milky chocolate essence entering into the flavor that i did n't detect in the smell .

a : what a great looking stout . deep brown color with an extremly silkey 1/2 '' head that slowly disipates into lacing s : roasted malt t : grain sweet ness and roasted malts m & d : mouth feel was medium and dry .  full of body and creamy goodness .
this beer looks so beautiful on nitro with a creamy long lasting head and glass coating appeal .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied with a dry , perfectly carbonated finish . perfect for the style .
pours black with a dark brown creamy head . very nice beer to look at .  creamy but thin body .
pours a fascinating brownish black with little foam . very appealing to the eyes .  mouthfeel is wow smooth , and drinkability is amazingly good .

pours copper hue , with a nice , long lasting , white head and lively carbonation .  body is n't the first thing you notice , but once the distraction of the sour wears off , you realize this brew is very smooth , neither tacky nor sticky , nor drying . carbonation can be swirled up , and compliments the feel of the sour in your cheeks quite well . all in all , a crazy departure from the normal dfh offerings and dang fine weissen .

appearance : a dark tan head sits atop a black-brown body . long lasting and nice to look at .  the mouthfeel is great , for the bittersweetness from the roasted malts provide the ideal amount of oomph to an otherwise creamy body .

pours a one-finger light khaki head that fades quickly leaving a good lace . nice clear amber color .  in addition , there are hop oils , caramel , some sweetness and perhaps molasses along with a medium body that is oh so smooth and coats the mouth well . delicious and well balanced .
a - black , inch and half of tawny head . leaves amazing lacing that should be in a museum as art .  excellent for it 's style .

11.2oz bottle poured into a chalice pours a murky , deep brown with a thick , one-finger head that has awesome staying power and leaves rings of lacing down my glass .  very full body that stretches the cheeks . just such chewy hops .
in a tulip the beer was near black in color with a light brown head . the head lingered well , and left abundant lace .  a nice chewy , creamy malt backbone makes each sip a pleasure .

stamp directly on top of the white , generic cap announces : bottl 2008* a dark caramel body with a significant amount of sediment floating around that were actually dark in appearance . topping all of that is a nice , creamy white head that sticks around for several minutes . very cool look .  some of the best damn mouthfeel you will ever get in a beer too .
pours a hazy reddish-brown color with a very thick and creamy off-white head . really nice lacing and a good cap throughout .  the mouthfeel was awesome - very creamy and full bodied .
absolutley perfect looking beer .  perfectly suited for sipping and just right for the flavor .

the color was hazy lemon yellow with two fingers of rocky , yellow-tinted head . the cap retained itself beautifully and the lacing was in solid bands .  m - amazing . low to moderate carbonation ( expected ) and full bodied .

the initial pour formed a small head of small dark brown bubbles . as the head died , it left a clinging vine lacing stubbornly letting go of the side of the glass .  wow . the thick and creamy mouthfeel is perfect for the winter months and so warm .

poured out of a 16.9 oz bottle into a tulip style glass . i held it up to the sun on my patio and admired it for a few seconds . ( cue music ) there were two inches of white head that led to a nice white cap that never dissipated .  m- perfect for the style , ca n't say anything more .

this seasonal beer is complex but not quite as well rounded as say the great lakes christmas ale . after finishing my first glass i realized the head had laced all the way down from the top to the bottom and remained throughout , really quite beautiful .  mouthfeel is creamy smooth , thick body , low carbonation .

a busty foamy cap on top ... head is monstrous ! not only is the head big its retention is just as good . head was a soft tan ( cappuccino ) color with craters , mounds , and dense chunks forming all the while leaving a bleary coating of lace . a very good look to this one s : i am having a bit of trouble grasping this one but had no problem realizing this one is sweet and rich .  smooth and creamy , very soft carbonation . booze is extremely well hidden .

poured into a new belgium snifter a - a beautiful clear dusk sunset color , 2 finger head that lingered and lacing through and through and awesome tiny bubbles for days s - pine , citrus , malt , floral , cotton , sweet , grains and maybe a bit toasty t - very nice bitter sweet , pine , orange , melon , pineapple , very hoppy and yet super bitter sweet malty m - coats the mouth a bit with some super bitter sweet lingering .  first sip reveals a smooth and slightly creamy texture , carbonation is almost non-existent as cask ale should be .

bonus points for advertising their smaller drafts as 14 oz , instead of the misleading `` pints '' of many establishments . bright white head that leaves great lacing , a ring for every sip .  it 's just smooth and thick enough to feel perfect going down .

poured a hazy golden yellow with a three finger white head that remained throughout the glass and even continued to grow if left to sit for long . insane ! maintained phenomenal lacing throughout the glass . first off , the appearance on this one was ridiculous for the style .  mouthfeel : crisp , clean , and exceedingly refreshing .
perfect head retention and plenty of lacing left behind in the glass .  its very smooth and velvety , very nice .

still a bit of haze but not anything like a hefe . the beer looks great in this glass !  the taste and mouthfeel is where this beer shines . thick , smooth and creamy with a combination of milk and dark chocolate with just a hint of licorice .

this beers head was wonderfully creamy , off-white/tan , of a good inch . the lacing this beer had was awesome ; it lace in sheets , practically coating my entire mug .  the mouthfeel is dead-on creamy .

a viscous pour and a deep black color , on top a beige head which collapses almost instantly . one of the most beautiful beers i came across .  m : remarkably full bodied and smooth but it does n't have any stickiness , carbonation did it 's job , excellent .

first i have to say the appearance is exceptional . the red color is as someone said very similiar to the color of the label .  the mouthfeel is great on this one too , effervescent and full at the same time .

a - poured a slightly hazy amber-straw color , with a big , fluffy , two-finger head . took several minutes to dry down to a thick cap , which left nice rings of lacing down the glass . very pretty .  mouthfeel is very thick and chewy , silky and long lasting on the palate , near perfect .

this is my first bigfoot so we will see how the talk stands up ... a- really dark ruby red in my snifter . big sandy , fluffy head perched atop . at this point the head seems unwavering . but it eventually faded leaving all sorts of lace .  exactly how i like my stouts to feel -- heavy and chewy .
pours a darker , hazy amber-bronze with very thick , chunky white head resembling melted ice cream .  very big and chewy mouthfeel

boddingtons shows up a light amber , pale gold in color , with a beautiful inch of thick cream , the bubbles being almost indiscernible . the cascading action that takes place as the beer settles and the head rises is fascinating to watch . some of this head stays with the beer , and a thin layer of lace coats the glass all the way down .  lush , creamy mouthfeel , that really could n't improve at all .
pours a nice amber with 2 fingers of head . gorgeous lacing also like nothing i 've ever seen . a solid 5 for appearance .  perfectly carbonated with an amazing mouthfeel .

poured into my duvel tulip a - pours a dark reddish-brown color with a huge pillowy tan head . this is absolutely beautiful , and took a good 3 minutes to recede enough for me to drink it !  super thick mouthfeel .

deep ruby color with a cream-colored creamy head that leaves a nice curtain of lacing . pretty beer , especially with a little light behind it .  the first thing i noticed actually was the incredible mouthfeel .

it 's bronze , perfectly bright . it 's foamy , with a good head and strong laces . this beer shows that a beer made to please the most people can still be made with great quality .  smooth as hell , perfect weight and carbonation .
pours a clear amber/brown , huge thick off white head forms , great retention , excellent lacing .  mouthfeel is sublime . kind of like a benign dreamy tingling that coats the palate evenly .

a huge foamy white head sits a proud of a light red brown body with slight hazing and tempting look .  mouthfeel is absurdly rich and creamy , silky smooth and slurpalicious . ) it 's the best feature of this brew . i mean , i like the taste , love the mouthfeel , and would enjoy having two or three of these , but that abv is on the high end .

could n't decipher a date code on this one , so not sure how old/new it is ... pours an absolutely beautiful pitch black color with a deep tan foamy head .  the mouthfeel of this bastard makes the beer for me -- incredibly soft and smooth for strong ale , probably the result of the oaking .
into a pint glass , poured a cloudy orange/amber with one finger of white , good retention , and great lacing .  mouthfeel : smooth and creamy . alcohol warmth .
looks fantastic ! the head leaves plenty of lace after a couple of minutes .  the mouthfeel is smooth , thick , and creamy .

it packs in beautiful cascading , lively carbonation , a firm & rich off-white head and amazing levels of retention . that and a bold black color make for one masterful visage .  this has an excellent mouthfeel .

into a pint glass , pours about as black as a beer can get , a big huge light tan head with a bubbly middle , good staying power , about as long as the drinkin goes , and lovely lacing .  high level of carbonation with tons of tingle on the tongue . another excellent beer from ommegang .
amber colored ale that pours with a rocky head .  the mouthfeel was the best part : silky smooth and creamy thick ; a perfect accompaniment to dessert .

captain lawrence st. vincent 's dubbel is a great looking dubbel that tastes pretty good . a : red orange colour and a great 2 cm head that lasts very well . highly carbonated .  the mouthfeel is amazing , thick and solid with a lingering savory finish .

they are the best ! beautiful pour , orangish tan with a perfect beige head .  if you have to choose buy the triple , but as stated earlier this beer has a wonderful silky smooth mouth ... great feel for those who have an oral complex ...
pours a thick creamy head and has a dark brown color with hints of amber .  so very soft on the palette - really a unique mouthfeel , just velvety smooth .
the color is pretty cool to look at .  the mouthfeel is a true hallmark of this beer .
a giant , rocky , off-white head explodes out of the bottle , leaving strata-like rings on the glass as it settles , which is a good amount of time .  mouthfeel is rich and creamy .

pours out a very nice copper color with great retention and some of the best lacing i ever saw on a beer mug . very impressive . also has nice carbonation .  m - perfect . exactly how a dipa should be .
just an over-sized glass with great markings . excellent to look at . a clear golden pour with a very generous head .  extremely satisfying in this regard .
great look to this beer .  mouthfeel is about perfect , and the body is about perfect for a bock style .

pours with a rich , rocky head over a cloudy orange body , with lots of lacing . one of the best presentations i 've seen .  very light carbonation and a perfect body for a porter , combined with what i have already mentioned , makes this a very drinkable proposition .

pours a dark golden ruby color with bright red edges and a two finger frothy light beige head . very good retention , only slowly fading into a lasting cap that coats the glass with streaks of soapy lacing .  mouthfeel : truly phenomenal creamy medium body with the slightest touch of syrup likeness .
a : beautiful . three fingers worth of foamy mocha colored head . lots of lacing here .  mouth : velvety good . nice water . sweet , full , but not thick . medium to full bodied .

really beautiful beer , pours a hazy golden color with a huge frothy white head that retains impressively and leaves nice lacing .  mouthfeel : true german feeling on this beer . medium viscosity , rolls across the palate smoothly and is perfectly carbonated . great overall feel and authenticity .

the beer pours amazingly dark reddish purple with a creamy purple head of 3 cm foaming up easily .  ( m ) - this is ridiculously smooth despite its hop dryness and woody bite . great carbonation level and balance .
lots of bubbles along wall of glass . leaves a huge & healthy white cap with bigger lacing along the outside of the body .  mouthfeel : perfect mouthfeel .
a freind brought this brew over ... a : perfect look for a belgian ale . deep dark ruby color like an iced tea .  there 's a fair amount of carbonation that you feel in the swallow .

poured into an imperial pint glass a nice deep garnet color with well defined half finger off white head atop , good richness and definition to the color.aromas of cinnamon and clove mainly , i could tell right away this was gon na be a more heavily spiced winter warmer.heavy cinnamon , clove , and nutmeg on the palate , not crazy sweet just spiced to the hilt , some faint toastiness underneath the spice does come thru after awhile as well some alcohol sweetness.much like their pumpkin ale the winter warmer is too spiced up , i do like this better than the pumpkin beer but it 's still not great by any means .  m : the best part of the beer . very creamy while still having a touch of that hop thickness you want .
a : light brown pour with a good light tan head that leaves lace on the glass after about 1-2 fingers of head .  one of the best mouthfuls ever !
appearance : a wonderful amber color .  the mouthfeel was creamy and medium-bodied with light , soft carbonation .

$ 3.99 lovelly cloudy orange beer , with a large thick creme coloured head . nice looking beer in my half liter germen mug aroma is of yeast , spices ..phenolic , leather and earth nice stuff .  the mouthfeel was outstanding , felt like a cask beer , rich , creamy , smooth .

dark gold , lightly cloudy , with a very big creamy off-white head slowly shrinking to a puffy , rocky smaller head and foamy lace .  this is a big , complex , full bodied beer . the huge amounts of malts in this thing are chewy and even feel like they stick to the teeth some .

tasted in mid-may 2009. nearly opaque , black/brown , with reddish brown on the edges under the light . great lacing , forming curtains in the latter half of the glass .  m : creamy and delicious . everything is dead on here .

a : guinness just looks great in the glass . good contrast with black color with a creamy white head .  it is dense . the mouthfeel is warm even though it was chilled . it is excellent as it warms in the glass .

light brown pour with red highlight and a voluminous foamy light tan head . good retention and some nice lacing , though the size of the head on pouring does make me concerned that this has carbonation issues ( thankfully it does n't ) .  medium bodied , excellent mouthfeel .

appearance : an aggressive pour gives me an inch head of fluffy off white foam on top of a mostly clear pale yellow orange beer .  the mouthfeel is perfect for the style ; adequately carbonated and finished silky and creamy .

nola brown ale , draft a big thick rocky head , deep ruby red color when held to the light . a nice looking beer .  the mouthfeel is smooth and nicely done . excellent carbonation drinkability is good as well .
like the looks of this . full thick head .  the mouthfeel on this is exceptional , so smooth will alcohol masterfully controlled .
a : absolutely beautiful looking brew .  the first thing i notice upon the first sip is the awesome mouthfeel on this one .

pours the color of any other well crafted imperial stout , pitch black but with an impressive mocha colored inch of foam on top . the head displayed some excellent retention and a creamy layer of bubbles from the cask treatment .  the mouthfeel is thick and rich with a nice amount of bubbly to round it out . the taste is full , many-layered . . . wonderful . a little vineous though .

a : pours a bright yellow-orange , cloudy to the point of opaque but with some visible carbonation ; has the usual billowy , long-lasting head of dense white foam which settles to a healthy cap and leaves loads of frothy lacing .  mouthfeel is perfection . perfectly carbonated and very refreshing .

on tap tonight at fountainhead in chicago ... poured into a tulip ... pours dark brown with nice dark ruby red highlights , good clarity . capped with three fingers of cool whip-esque white head that leaves a bit of lacing ... sweet and sour cherries dominate the nose with bits of oak and vanilla .  the mouthfeel on this beer is almost perfect . a nice smooth drinkable beer .
a rich gold hue with white one-finger head , laces astonishingly well . looks like a good beer .  keeping with the chocolate milk theme , the mouthfeel is fantastic .

a : gorgeous crystal clear orange amber with a tall white head that falls to a lacy white ring s : althought this beer has a reputation for a huge citrous presence , i am not getting a lot of that - hops seem more grassy and muted more than anything else t : relatively malty balance for an ipa - hops are coming through at the end with some grapefruit and a clean bitter finish m : med-full mouthfeel and just a bit warm - especially warm for the style o : i 'm really wondering how what i 'm drinking matches up to what i 've read about this beer - the comments and reviews by others seem all over the map ( cloudy vs clear , hoppy vs malty , big vs little etc ) .  the balance here is seriously excellent though , and the mouthfeel is probably the best i have encountered in an ipa , period . truly a creamy elixir , perfect carbonation .

bottle says bottled on 4/16/09 a - pours cloudy orange with huge 3 fingers of pillowy foam that takes forever to die down - lacing is all over the glass . this is one fine looking beer s - very hoppy with a strong grassy aroma - there are so many other aromas also - reminds me of a wine t - bitterness is subdued , bready yeast flavor is present , solid malt backbone m - great creamy mouthfeel - but i wish there was a little more lingering bitterness to this brew d - this is a very sneaky 9 % abv - deceptively drinkable .  mf : it has a thicker mouthfeel than i expected , and it was wonderful .

a : pours a beautiful hazy orange colour . huge fluffy , rocky white head . lots of retention and lace .  this has been sitting in the cellar for about a year and i am convinced it has the absolute perfect mouthfeel .
looks like a good representation of the style .  mouthfeel - wonderful body with great carbonation and just beautifully drinkable .

a careful pour produces a robust , sandy colored , three-finger head with excellent retention and lacing .  it 's definitely thick , but it does n't feel anywhere near as syrupy as it looks . o : this beer has a great appearance and mouthfeel .

appearance : darkest , thickest brown head i 've seen , even a notch above rogue 's shakespeare stout . pitch black even when directly on top of a 60w lamp . tall head , intense lacing .  m - wonderfully full bodied , sticky , smooth . delightful .
bottle : poured an orangey color ale with a huge off-white head with perfect retention .  great mouth feel on this one . no hops or bitterness present at first , but bitter in the finish .

makes an excellent appearances , pours a cloudy rich amber with a large foamy tan head with good retention and lots of sticking .  silky smooth thick bodied with a perfect amount of light carbonation and a ridiculously long lasting , balanced tart and sweet aftertaste .

this thing looks good ! beautiful two inches of white plume on top of a hazy orange , slightly red color that provides a light orange glow when held up to the light . the smell is n't nearly as impressive as the looks , though .  the moutfeel is exceptional - full bodied and thick with appropriate carbonation .

from a bottle , poured into a pint glass a - deep black color with a mocha head .  first gulp of this was outstanding.. nice creamy , mouthfeel to it that just bombards your mouth with sweet , delicious beer flavor .

a - golden yellow with a huge , chunky white head . excellent retention ang big chunky lace up and down the glass . beautiful beer .  mouthfeel : a smooth sugary viscous mouthfeel that is balanced nicely by the carbonation .
a beautiful looking beer with at least a two-finger head that lasts for a while before fading to a nice cap that remains to the end .  wonderful body .
dark black with creamy tan head that leaves great retention and foamy lace .  mouthfeel is perfect - smooth and velvety without being clingy or cloying .
excellent looking brew .  m : absolutely wonderful ... smooth & creamy .

this beer looks perfect ! the bright , clear yellow beer , the fluffy white foam , the constant stream of fine carbon dioxide bubble , the everlasting lace left by each sip , it was exactly how a beer this style should be made to look like .  full bodied with creamy carbonation and a lingering sweet licorice finish .
a nice dark red/amber color with about 1.5 finger head of off-white creamy head . the head stuck around for about 3/4 of the brew and left some nice lace .  m - perfect . it 's velvet on the tongue .

2011 bottle poured into a tulip glass . a - an inch of dense cream-colored foam sits atop a beautiful ruby colored ale .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel is outstanding . it sparkles just enough to give the palate a good tickle , but not so much that it scrapes away all of its flavor .

bottle , a : a dark , black , almost pernicious looking brew , with a beautiful thick tan head .  it 's wonderful . alcohol tingles a little in the mouth and it 's certainly present in the aroma but buried 'neath the fruity yeast . expertly woven into the beery fabric of this brew .
a : beautiful pour from this 440ml nitro can . bright copper with a thick , creamy white head . great lacing left behind .  light carbonation , rich smooth mouthcoating sensation from the oatmeal .

appearance : clear and golden , with a nice , thick and full head , just the way a tripel should look like .  mouthfeel is intensely smooth and velvety , creamy and luscious . lactic milk sugar contributes a boatload of palate-smudging heft . although it 's not one for sessioning , it has a sublime quality that makes you savor every sip .

the nitro-can produced pour is indeed a sight to behold . beautiful black on bottom with fascinating cascading brown in the middle with a moderately sized tan head on top . the taste was weakly creamy and very thin with very little body .  mouthfeel : deliciously smooth with a nice , crisp finish . the high alcohol content gives it a nice warmth as well .

the beer looks really good with a thick brown creamy head , tons of lacing , and a very nice head that lasts and lasts .  a bit astringent . fantastic , full body with a very creamy feel -- pretty impressive .

poured from a growler into a pint glass . pours a deep , clear ruby-brown with wonderful garnet highlights when held to the light . a fat , frothy head of light tan foam shows marvelous retention , holding tight throughout and lasting to the finish , grabbing tightly to the walls of the glass , leaving behind thick , bubbly curtains of lace as the glass empties .  mouthfeel : excellent light and crisp mouthfeel which is perfect for this style .

the beer looked good with a nice amber color and a thick creamy and frothy head that laced and retained well .  nice caramel aftertaste held on the tongue by the thick mouthfeel . creamy thick mouthfeel and modest carbonation .
pours to an absolutely gorgeous deep golden/brownish-gold color with a decent amount of rich foam .  mouthfeel is medium bodied and smooth . an excellent feel .

appearance : even poured slowly to try and minimize the head , i still wound up with a three finger head that was the color and consistency of that foam that you squirt into your walls to insulate them . the color is a very nice dark reddish amber with only a small amount of carbonation . a good start !  mouthfeel is very delicious with some creamy notes but some nice crisps and sharp grassy hop notes .
wow , what a good looking beer . dark dark , dark body and small light brown head ontop .  mouthfeel is great . just the right level of thickness here .

) pitch black colour , moderate brown head . the appearance is top notch , a very fine and lasting brown head .  a festive arrangement with great depth mouthfeel : really nice - creamy and complex drinkability : good
pours clear copper , with a two finger off white head . the head sticks around a long time and laces good .  full bodied and silky .

appearance- one of the best looking belgian pale 's i have seen . a large 2 inch big bubbled head which 1/4 inch remains until the last drop is consumed . excellent lacing stuck to the entire rounded wall of my glass .  the alcohol is kept well in check allowing the finish to cascade over the palate with a ton of character and wonderful texture . strong , long finish .

pours a pitch black color with a two-finger head that fades down to some lacing . good color for the style .  initially the softness of the carbonation and the sweetness of the fruity flavors makes it like a sweet soda ( can anyone remember tahitian treat ? again with the yeast character and the near rancid presence ( the brett i presume ) , yet the overall soft flavors and soft feel are greatly appealing and enjoyable . the light , fine and bubbly carbonation brings an element of childhood fun to the drink ( how about fizzies , anyone remember that ) as it brings a tickle to the nose and tongue . light overall feel and great softness . soft and light and tasty ( again in a soda pop manner ) .

in a chalice , 50f : very pretty beer ; opal and ruby . head is on the darker end of the brown spectrum , but fades quite quickly . the lacing that remains is quite attractive . bourbon hits pretty hard in the nose , swiftly eclipsed by coffee .  the mouthfeel is velvety and thick .

appearance : light yellow in color with a large soapy head that stays around the whole time . the head on this beer is remarkable and deserves recognition . at first the beer was fairly clear but later i swirled some yeast in and the beer became cloudy .  m : a great , great medium body , that grazes you at the tail with sharp carbonation .

i really do n't have anything too negative to say about this beer , it looks great and smells good .  very smooth and rich taste though and perfectly balanced . wonderfull to drink though think it should be drank as i do n't think that more age makes this one any better .
this beer was very dark and had a creamy head that lasted a long time .  thin in the mouth but heavy on the tongue . perfect for the style and the season .
pours a beautiful burnt sunset orange with crystal clarity , finger of foamy head has good retention .  m : an incredibly thick body and big , foamy carbonation . i love the way this feels .

a : pours a dark , um , brown in the glass with some light penetration indicating it 's not opaque . the head is pretty fizzy , with two fingers of creamy beige bubbles generated at first , before receding into a half-finger cap on top of the brew . some streaks of lacing as i drink .  fantastic mouthfeel .

appearance- nice brandy colored pour . one inch plus head . light ring throughout . very nice patchy lacing left behind . very grassy and corny scent .  the taste is a rich velvety malt with an amazing mouthfeel and a fully satisfying richness .
appearance : burnt amber with a big bubbly pure white head that has a steam of rising carbonation feeding it . tons of stickage as the head slowly drops . pretty stuff .  m - perfect for a porter .
bottle : poured a clear deep back color stout with large light brown foamy head with good retention and some lacing .  smooth grit with comfort .
it pours a nice dark brownish black with a cascading burnt tan head .  nice full bodied and well carbonated mouthfeel .
frothy tan head .  m- full , smooth mouthfeel .
best before 26.09.05 appearance : awesome . poured with a nice long lasting beige head .  the carbonation is very low ( natch ) , the body silky smooth , and dead creamy .
12oz bottle - 2006 edition pours a clear mahogany brown with rich ruby highlights .  mouth is rich and sticky yet wonderfully smooth .

bomber poured a clear dark reddish brown nearly black with a lasting brown head .  mouth is very crisp and finishes clean , excellent carbonation . leaves a nice tingling on the tongue . drink is very good i usually would n't want an ipa for a session beer but this one i definetly would have a few more for the evening .

330 ml bottle consumed at a certain way , on to the beer : it 's black with a some hues of ruby red . the head formed on top is extremly thick , is tanned in color , and still holds on top until the last sip . did i mention is shows some rings of lacing ?  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel is absolutely incredible for a milk stout .
a : excellent dark red color . very bright and enticing .  '' love the mouthfeel .
appearance : crystal clear . white head . nice lacing smell : smells like a triple .  m - perfect feel to this medium bodied brew .
this bock pours perfectly with a tight forming bright white head that stays around for a good duration .  mouthfeel is extremely silky smooth .
appearance : pours a crystal clear dark orange color with a huge 3 '' + fluffy head that lasts a long time .  mouthfeel is full but not too heavy .

abc 's smoked porter poured a dark black.a creamy brown head with a solid brown lace around my glass.the aroma hinted at burnt wood.the mouthfeel was a bit too watery for me.smoke is noted on the taste and the aroma.an overall ok porter but not great .  mouthfeel : fantastic . rich without being syrupy . carbonation is just right .

a : nice brown body with a fluffy 1+ finger head that lasted forever .  but what might be the true feats here are , on the one hand , the quality and sock of the flavors given the abv , and the insanely creamy mouthfeel on the other .

almost black with a cream colored head measuring maybe one finger . i love pouring it out of the gan into a pint glass and watching it mix and cascade turning from the color of mud to the color of .  perfect carbonation and ridiculously easy to drink .

wild blue is a red wine colored drink , with a small pink head on top . pretty good amount of lacing .  a faint bit of tannins in the middle of the tongue starts the finish , which is incredibly long with trailing , vineous notes of chocolate and spiced orange peel . ya it 's a bit like those warheads candies , but it 's tucked in such an incredible silky richness .

inky black but holds a hinting of deep brown tone when up to very bright light . fair amounts of thickly webbed lacing sticks across the surface . still looks like one damn good porter . damn i hate when this happens to a good looking beer . not all the approachable beyond its beautiful glass of black .  mouthfeel was great , it was very rich and smooth with little carbonation but it fit the stout just right .

appearance : this brew pours with a wonderfully thick head . lacings are plentiful and surface spiderwebbing is consistant and lasting . color is indeed a reddish amber . excellent first impression .  m : perfect carbonation .
the appearance is outstanding ! s : expresso like smell with subtle malty aroma .  the head portends the exceptional mouthfeel .
pours a nice red amber with a towering white creamy head ... just like every other nitro beer .  mouthfeel : it is crisp , light , and perfectly carbonated .

the pour was very good and this is easily one of the best looking beers i have ever seen with its excelent head , color and champagne like bubbles .  mouthfeel - great smoothness , i was inclined to take a deep draw at the outset , very quenching . restrained carbonation adds to the smoothness .

a : pours absolutely perfect ! cloudy , creamy orange body with a glorious mountain of head that fills just to the edge of the glass and hangs around until the glass is empty .  medium body and a wonderfully sprtizy carbonation keeps it light and makes the tartness manageable .

dark , but clear with ruby/purple highlights . fine beige foam , really sticky with sheets of bubbles coating the glass . good head retention too .  mouthfeel : wonderful balance all over the pallets and each taste-bud . the slightly raised abv can give cause to the minor warmth in mouthfeel .
poured into a tulip . billowing head , color to the amber side of golden and nicely hazed , outstanding lacing .  it 's exceptionally smooth with little carbonation .
this beer was so pretty that i had to stop and take a picture . a beautiful translucent golden color with a billowing white head .  m : very soft , finely carbonated medium body .

my first `` imperial pilsner '' a- a very clear rich golden , maybe slight orange . well formed fluffy white head builds on top , a thin layer sticks around .  really coats the mouth for an excellent mouthfeel .
pours the blackest black with no light coming through .  the lush velvety texture takes control of your mouth .
found this one at julios randomly ... a : awesome look .  mouthfeel is velvety and smooth . great length on the taste .
poured a 2 finger fluffy light tan head with excellent retention to 1 finger cap .  m- the mouth feel is excellent for this beer .
pours a clear deep red-brown with a big white head .  carbonation is just right . mouthfeel is full , lush , but the carbonation keeps it clean .
a : pours a wonderfully bright golden/orange color .  m - rich and thick , very chewy .
a large beige head forms with great retention and lace .  m/d : full creamy body with light carbonation , pretty drinkable for 9 % .

browning 's bourbon barrel imperial stout pours a very nice , pitch black into a snifter with a small , light tan head that leaves lots of lacing behing .  medium bodied beer combined with very active and tight carbonation combines to create an exceptionally creamy beer .
opague black extremely heavy coffee colored heading . that leaves excellent lacing and keeps a nice collar all the way down to the last gulp .  m- incredibly smooth with a nice carbonation .

brilliantly clear with a nice 1 '' head - amber/copper in color . looks great .  mouthfeel is where this beer really shines , and makes one understand why some folks are such lager fans . the balance in this beer is amazing , with everything seemingly in the right preportion .

a big , voluptuous head builds with a gentle pour , dark chestnut in color , creamy , and well-retained . beneath is an inky black body with absolutely zero amount of light passing through .  mouthfeel : so smooth and creamy . very refreshing .
convict hill oatmeal stout pours a solid black with ample dark brown head .  very smooth and full bodied mouthfeel , with medium carbonation .
pours very golden , pretty clear looking . great head that sticks around and some nice lacing .  mouthfeel is wonderful . very thick , full , coats the mouth wonderfully .

purchased 22oz bomber from martignetti's appearance = really good looking hazy , light amber . looks refreshing and crisp .  the taste is initially of a very light porter and with a clean aftertaste that becomes a fruit sensation on the palate . the hop/malt balance is the real achievement here and it really contributes to the supreme drinkability . the smell upon opening the bottle is not an effective contrival of the taste that this beer is hiding as it only gives you an idea of the rooted flavor that is to be unleashed , the supreme balance and sublime flavor . great bier .

pours garnet with 4 fingers of off white/sand colored head . insane lacing & healthy head retention s : sour , vinergary notes up front that dissipates to not much of anything & then comes back t : sweetness & sourness do battle up front , along with serious dryness .  m : wonderfully smooth . nice creamy texture that does n't stick too long in the mouth .
pours a beautiful orange hue with a monster head and sticks around for several minutes .  great mouthfeel .
incredible looking esb . pours with the cascading effect and settles to a bright amber color .  great creamy thick mouthfeel , light carbonation .
huge , billowy head of marshmallow fluff is perfectly `` belgian '' - big foamy clumps of lace are all over my glass .  very rich and full bodied , smooth , chewy , all while the alcohol is hidden .

a : pours a bright light amber with a large dense head that reduced into a delightfully thick dense foam dollop that floated on top of the beer . very active carbonation and fantastic lacing . head stayed forever with very impressive retention .  mouthfeel is quite amazing , therefore the 5 .

looks really nice with the carbonation streaming up all the sides . great retention with the full finger staying around the whole time . great rings of lacing .  the mouthfeel was exquisite . tiny bubbles caress , going a little foamy , opening the flavor as it hits the back of your mouth .
pours deep brown with a stiff egg custard-colored head that fades slowly .  the carbonation is just right here .
honestly one of the most impressive looking ipa 's i 've encountered .  given the balance and great mouthfeel , drinkability was quite good .

pours a nice creamy sunshine-yellow-wheat color . head is thick and creamy which is typical of the widget-type cans .  overall a really complex , fantastic stout , one i 'd be happy coming back to over and over .

poured this brew into a la chouffe glass , just like the last tasting . makes lots of bright white foam , and has a hazy golden colored body .  mild-medium carbonation just enough to excite the palate . to me , this is almost the perfect mouthfeel .

12oz brown bottle . frothy and creamy off white 1 '' head that holds for a while , eventually leading to some nice layers of lacing . very deep mahogany color with a shade of brown .  very rich and robust brew almost creamy . again , excellent . thanks be to lou91 for the opportunity .
pours a deep deep dark brown with a monumental rocky khaki head ... . beautiful .  mouthfeel- the texture of this beer in the mouth is stunning and absolutely *perfect* .

a : the body has a nice bright off orange/rich golden hue with a robust white colored head that sticks to the glass well .  m : the mouthfeel is delightful . fairly thick for an ipa , almost creamy with mild carbonation .

pours hazy gold with a massive , fluffy white head . very promising appearance , but way overcarbonated if you 're shooting for anything lambic-esque .  m - very rich and thick , has a nice little burn and pop at the end from a combo of carbonation , abv and hop bitterness .
pours a dark brown with a healthy sandy light tan head that lingers at a fairly thick level and laces the glass heavily .  m : medium in body with a really smooth and creamy feel on the tongue .
this beer looks perfect . pretty gold color , with a nice big fluffy head .  mouthfeel is quite exceptional .
a - pours a dark , murky brown with ruby highlights .  mouth feel is incredible with some good champagne bubbling going on .

a : pours a deep , hazy plum body that resides beneath a three-finger head of creamy pinkish-tan foam ; good retention and tons of lace . probably the best-looking barleywine i 've seen . beautiful .  m- wonderfully creamy . the carbonation is spot on . one of the creamiest belgian beers i can think of .
a tall , tan , thick head that lasts .  t/m : mouthfeel is perfect on this beer .

poured from a 750ml bottle into my troubadour tulip glass . a dense and enormous mattress of foam tops the ale almost like a merengue . a sudsy lattice-work of lace remains in the glass even after it is empty .  a very smooth , luxurious malt backbone enhances the mouthfeel , but a bitter smack of hops reminds me that i 'm drinking an ipa . quite enjoyable .

a - this looks darker than some stouts i 've drank . great looking head .  very thick with just enough carbonation that completely fills the mouth and leaves a bittersweet flavor lingering on the palate , and a bit of a syrupy feel on the back of the throat with just a bit of alcohol heat that is perfect for the style .

pours dark black with a four finger coffee head .  mouthfeel is where this beer shines the most , imo . creamy and rich and the carbonation is superfine , perfect . this one grew on me a bit as i got into it and it warmed up some , but still not a mind-blowingly good beer .

pours pitch black and completely opaque without even the slightest hint of lighter color when held to a light source . frothy 1.5 finger chocolate coffee colored head that quickly settles into a lasting ring .  m- really interesting . a dry feeling on the sides of the tongue and a sweet feeling in the back . really well done .
pours a fabulous cloudy gold .  mouthfeel was full , thick , and creamy with a rich sweetness on the tongue .

a- deep , opaque brown/black . beautiful , rich , thick , deep dark tan head that lasts forever . even with an appropriate pour , the head was deeper than i 'd ever seen .  mouthfeel- light palate with great carbonation that tickles the senses nicely .
a- beautiful red tint , lightly rising head . head fades relatively quickly leaving no lacing .  mouthfeel : fully body , lower carbonation , love it .

appearance : dark black color , with big chocolate brown head , medium carb smell : chocolate , with malts , and some wood taste : bitter dark chocolate , coffee , alcohol , and roasted malt mouthfeel : dry , slightly bitter , rich full body drinkability : a drinkable imperial stout , the high abv is moderately masked .  each sip of this full bodied beer is smooth and creamy with light carbonation . this beer is so smooth it goes right down .

marzen-fest 2010 continues with a 12 oz into a pint a - pours a very clear , almost perfectly brown color . head formation is strong , frothy , egg shell white .  the rich , smooth , roasted chocolate flavor works well with the silky body . this is definitely highly recommended , as the beers tend to be from great lakes brewing company .

appearance this one poured a beautiful , hazy orange in color with a monster head that i had to control at the pour . it came down pitting , leaving a whitish film all along the inside of my glass .  just a hint of carbonation on the palate - utterly smooth .

delicious and only $ 7/pint..hells yes please . angry and black it pours with a dark brown head , roast and alcohol dominate with some hop aroma , very faded , a little smoke , a little coffee .  in the mouth , the tiny bubbles announce and incredibly smooth and balanced beer , with a roasted , slightly sweet flavor .

'' the appearance was awesome . huge head all the way down the glass .  mouthfeel is as good as you would expect with an aerator . all in all , you can drink it for the mouthfeel but do n't drink it for the taste .
a - beautiful hazy orange , loads of carbonation , four fingers of fluffy head with good retention . very little lacing .  at least it was smooth and the carbonation was just right .

the beer poured real nice , big fluffy head , nice maroon color , excellent carbonation , it was a real treat to see after installing a new air conditioner .  creamy mouthfeel with moderate carbonation .
beautiful crystal clear deep ruby in hue , covered by a persistent , thick , light beige head that leaves loose lace .  medium full bodied , somewhat creamy .

pours thick and pitch black , no light can penetrate this . has a nice sized brown head that fades to medium ring that leaves an awesome lace .  flavor is malty and sweet , and on the finish , bubble gum ! mouthfeel is firm , and drinkability is high .
great head , expected cascading upon serving .  very creamy and full . very dry .

smell is rather striking and unique . slight hints of spice most likely from the chilles , with a really sweet grainy hop note .  let me first say that the brugse tripel used to be one of my favorite beers . nowdays its called brugge tripel and the taste changed slowly ... but a lot of small steps make a big one and today this beer is nothing what it used to be . smell of spices and a little hops , not fresh at all and a dull taste make it just a drinkable beer but nothing great like it had in the past .
the smell of this beer is lovely ; nothing but cherries .  mouthfeel is good , slightly thick .

this bottle required a lot of work just getting the beer out of the bottle . '' at what point do the ibu 's define the triple ipa ? anything over 100 ibu 's ca n't be defined by the pallatte . when you get that high in ibu , then you really risk poor balancing . the coloring a very deep orange/copper mix . i get tons of nice lacing in my st. bernardus chalice .  was pretty decent mouthfeel : smooth and crisp , went down easy drinkability : good enough on a hot day and goes great w/ bbq .

11.2 oz bottle poured into duvel tulip a : perfect . billowing tan head barely contained in this glass . settles to leave full layer of fine tan lacing . as you sip the soft foam coats the side of the glass in sheets not patches .  mouthfeel : good .

l : never seen such a perfect look ; two fingers , lasting foam ; s : pear , citrus , smells like the corsendonk agnus , but with a bit of caramel and celery ; t : as an agnus-addict this taste was a little disappointment ; good , but no more than that ; a bit too sweet and too short of hops/bitterness to complete the taste .  hoping it 's one of those better in a bottle beers i 'm returning to give it another try . so far so good . maybe , and i 'm stretching , some neutral hop spice . this beer makes me try too hard . these hops should be hops should be ashamed of themselves . good malt base to support hops , were they present . bottle is equally bland as on tap .

i have to say that the smell of this is fantastic . t : wow , the taste is a bit of surprise .  taste : a wink of hops , than the shows over , a surprisingly dry finish mouthfeel : decent - nice restrained carbonation , ever so slightly creamy notes : this is the driest , and least bitter ipa that i have ever experienced .

quite surprising ... not because it 's a great beer from dogfish head ( that 's certainly not surprising ) , but because i have never actually enjoyed a pumpkin ale . seriously ever . appearance & gt ; what a beauty . colour reads from dark honey to a pumpkin orange glow . extremely lively .  mouthfeel is about the only thing going for this one . medium body and appropriate carbonation .

the head is fluffy , off-white , and responsible , in part , for the best characteristic of this brew : the nose . the nose is a wonderful mix of allspice , nutmeg , and a bit of cinnamon , laid over a warm , inviting sweetness . it 's like sniffing a particularly delicious cookie . this brew goes down quite smoothly , and does not seem as high in alcohol as i thought it would .  mouthfeel : light-bodied but not watery . it had a nice feel to it .

a : pours a crystal clear amber color with a fluffy white head that sticks around for a long time . without a doubt one of the best looking ipas i 've had in a while .  mouthfeel is actually pretty nice , medium body and carbonation with a creamy quality .

enjoyed from snifters and beer a gift from the brewer himself ... ap : deep dark body , roasted brown head , awesome retention .  m : crisp and clean , moderate levels of carbonation and warmth . medium body .

poured pitch black with a healthy , khaki-colored head .  it has a canned fruit essence to it , but i ca n't pick up what kind of fruit . first couple of sips and i get a strong cherry pie filling flavor . i eat a lot of fresh cherries in the summer so i do n't automatically associate cherries with pie filling . not overly sweet but it does have a tart tang finish . a unique beer that i appreciate as well done , just not to my tastes .

a - pitch black with a carbonated type head that fades quickly s - fruity , chocolatey , roasty , and malty t - huge dried fruit on the forefront followed by massive chocolate and roasty accompaniment . different then most ris , but a pretty good example .  the mouthfeel is very nice , it 's very carbonated which works with the ginger presence , and the mouthfeel is at about a medium thickness .

fantastic lacing & head retention is als really good , a peresitent film hugs the orval goblet all the way down s : slight hints of choclate , cherry & oak barrels t : choclate & oakyness up front .  while the mouthfeel is actually pretty good , the drinkability suffers from this same fatal flaw .
aroma is excellent . it 's full of fresh hops , citrus and pine .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with moderate carbonation .

it feels odd to categorize such a beer as a stout . the aroma is very tame first tiem around , as it warms it become beautiful and fragrant with mocha , coffee , coconut , and lactose together .  feel : moderate carbonation , medium body , exceedingly dry finish .

pours a deep golden yellow with an inch or so of resilient white foam . offers good retention and sticky lacing .  mouthfeel : medium-plus body . medium carbonation . some oily viscosity to the mouthfeel .
pours a bright orange color , slightly carbonated , with a thick pillowy off-white head .  m - good mouth feel . somewhat unique in feel .
'' pours almost black with a generous amber head and fruity , hop-spicy nose .  the mouthfeel is full and nicely carbonated yet still somewhat creamy .
smells wonderful . rich sweet pink grapefruit , pine , oranges , lemon zest . compared to the enticing smell , the flavor is quite a let-down .  medium mouthfeel .

s : about what you 'd expect from an ipa- flowery , with lots of citrus . i 'm detecting lemon , melon , and other tropical fruits . i 'm used to lemony scents from ipas , but this one has something different- it 's the distinct melon i 'm getting from the nose . t : very `` clean '' tasting , lots of citrus at the beginning . the ending is quite bitter , but not a much as some ipa 's i 've tried .  i did n't pick up the barrel aged at first but the body was quite full and large . worth drinking but i believe that there is better in the 8-9 dollar bomber range .

pours a three-finger white head that fades slowly , leaving a good lace . nice , deep crystal clear amber color .  mouth is medium bodied , but with some good tingly action on the back of the tongue , so also good .
lacing is amazing ! aesthetically , an amazing beer .  mouthfeel is nice , good carbonation , but seriously , ca n't get over that ham finish .
dissipates slowly and exhibits great retention with beautiful lacing .  this beer has a high level of carbonation with a very crisp and clean mouthfeel .

super fragrant with aromas of citrus ( grapefruit ) and , actually , agave nectar . there 's a quality about several victory beers i 've had of late ( well , just this and the helios ) that i 'm not that into . that is , a somewhat caustic bitter end .  mouthfeel : smooth and medium thick , low carbonation .
aromas are fantastic ( pure wild ale ) . plenty of interesting aroma & flavor , and smooth going down .  mouthfeel - medium and smooth .
a : a modest pour generated a black body and a massive head of over two fingers . the head was dense and sticky .  body is on the full side of medium . moderate carbonation .

decanting the beer , it pours much like any other solid brown . lots of lacing . a solid look . where the look is no surprise , the hop aroma at the onset takes me back a bit .  it was somewhat thick with some carbonation , and had a hot aftertaste .

sadly , this is another short 's beer that is a huge let down ... a medium copper pour with tons of head . great retention , nice lava stack on the top ... aroma is super disappointing , light with only a whisp of sweetness coming through .  it had a smooth mouthfeel with a little carbonation .

a- glourious golden yellow with a fluffy and foamy white head that retains well in the tulip glass . dies to a fluffy ring and nice cloud that leaves thick lace all along the glass .  m- medium viscosity with a well integrated carbonation .
s - a huge grapefruit aroma dominates the nose . some pine and a sweet malt backbone add some additional layers to the nose . the grapefruit is no fresh and juicy .  fairly thick body .
very nice and original beer - more body would have been better but still a great treat from a great brewery .  very silky mouthfeeland light body , very drinkable and good .
its smell is its best characteristic -- floral hops , malty , a hint of wheat -- really beautiful . the taste is sweety & malty , as well as bitter .  mouthfeel : medium bodied .

bright transparent golden hue with a two inch frothy white head . lots of bubbles and good lacing . perfect appearance .  lovely thick aromas of blackstrap molasses , dark bitter chocolate , strong coffee and deep roasted malts ... awesome aromas to this one ... lazy and flat tasting ... strange bitter almost sour taste present ... . not much in common with the aromas ... thick oily mouthfeel is great but i ca n't get by the taste of this one ... drain poured this one ... maybe a bad bottle but as is , a big disappointment ...
it is very nice however .  m - oily , medium body with a fantastic amount of carbonation .
pours with a light two , five-finger head that stays forever , leaving a good lace .  m- moderate/high carbonation , medium body , lager clean . crisp enough leaving a refreshing feel .
opaque black chocolate under a tall creamy mocha head .  the mouthfeel was decent , medium with adequate carbonation .

pours a gorgeous dark caramel in the glass , with a nice thick tan head .  this beer tastes like sheep shit . this may appeal to some people , but it 's definitely a very unusual belgian ale . i enjoyed drinking half of this beer for the experience . it 's so pungent i laughed out loud . it 's always fun to be exposed to a radically different flavor profile than you 're used to .
a gorgeous midnight pitch-black , with luscious creamy , light-tan head , almost a finger thick . impressive sticky lacing .  medium bodied ; good amount of carbonation .

this brew poured a medium creamy long lasting dark brown head of small to large sized bubbles .  crisp and clean in the mouth , body fits the carbonation well . nothing amazing about this brew , but it 's not terrible and comes in a nifty bottle you can use for ... something ... .i guess .
appearance- black ! ! ! creamy head .  most everything else about this beer was great , looked good , good mouthfeel , but the taste .

this is probably one of the best or at least better wits i 've come across that could rival hoegaarden , but it looks awful ! such a shame coz this smells and tastes just like a wit should .  mouthfeel : lightly carbonated and creamy .
perfect , perfect hazy gold , inviting puffy head .  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with smooth carbonation .

the nose on this one is very strong . some pineapple , orange zest , and grapefruit along with some floral and piney notes . if this tastes as good as it smells , i 'm in for a sweet , citrusy treat . the taste is , unfortunately , not as juicy as the nose might suggest .  long , earthy , dry finish . interesting , somewhat unusual brew .

very vibrant fruity/floral aroma with a hint of peat , grain and sweet caramel malt . all these blend perfectly together to make a fantastic aroma . certainly the best aspect of this beer . it tastes very much like the aroma - fruity berry , white grape flavors with a little herbal spiciness . the flavors are n't as rich as the aroma would suggest . a really nice beer overall . i genuinely enjoyed it , but i only with the flavors were richer .  on first sip you get hit with a strong citrus hop attack . from the aroma to the taste , there is just something that does n't sit well with me . it leaves an unpleasant bitter aftertaste . i love ipas and hops galore . my only guess is that the bitter citrus flavor is what threw this beer off for me .

22 oz bomber poured into a pint glass a- hazy orange with a fluffy three finger head s- not as strong of a smell as i would like it to be , some malts and very little hop aroma for a 100 ibu double .  the mouth is smooth and light .
smell is amazing . has a spicy fruity smell .  smooth in the mouth with nice , crisp carbonation . nice feel , but flavor is not there .

very inviting . t - a little bitterness as if it had dark chocolate and you can taste the alcohol . a rather large let down after the amazing scent . m - good coating , but the only tingle is in the throat from the alcohol .  mouthfeel is nice & creamy .

the color of this beer i find just amazing . it 's so dark as it sits in a guinness glass , with it 's beautiful smooth head . are there bubbles finer than these ? in contrast to how heavy it looks , it 's goes down incredibly smooth and fast .  light mouthfeel with a good amount of carbonation when you drink it .

appearance : this `` holy brew of antioch '' poured quite well leaving a thick head that sustained quite well . lacing is generous and adheres to both the glass and spiderwebs on the surface . excellent so far ... smell : there is a sweet spiciness , maybe like green apples , that provides a good portion of the aromatic body .  m - nice light feel with a crisp finish , accentuated with a alcohol warmth .

bottle into an english pint glass appearance - dark brown/red hue reminds me of high grade saddle leather . a very handsome brew , sir .  m : mouthfeel is crisp , slightly sticky in the front and a little dry on the back of the tongue . pretty good .
really cool head color : it is mocha with a red tinge .  m : medium-high carbonation fits the style nicely .

with a black body to more than live up to the style , kostritzer pours two and one-half fingers of slightly tan head that is quite durable .  dark brown/amber body . it is a very smooth and a sweet sipper . some hops , caramel , candy sugar and oak . not much bourbon . i was way excited to try this and actually find it to be rather average .

a - pours a very deep dark red , with ruby highlights throughout . there is lots and lots of thick , fluffy tan-ish head . it has excellent retention leaving a thick ring on top after it settles for awhile .  m - medium bodied with good carbonation .
incredible retention and ok lacing s- sweet and hoppy .  the mouthfeel of this beer ( outside of taste ) was great . great carbonation , bitter hop aftertaste , medium bodied .
pours a beautiful head of dough bread mass cloudy caramel color .  mouthfeel is pretty good , goes well with the style of light and highly carbonated .
appearance - pours a perfect , clear orange/amber color with an inch thick head that dissipates immediately .  m - good carbonation and it finishes clean . good light to medium mouthfeel .

a -- this one pours with as much head as you want , and probably more . i must have had a little too much force behind mine because there was a fluffy white head up 3/4 of the glass . golden yellow with carbonation bubbles racing quickly to the top . tons of lacing .  mouthfeel is fine and not heavy .

the black body of this brew is topped by a medium thick , brown head with a good amount of lacing left behind .  a bitter spicy bite from the hops hit first . the light body and good crispness contrast the flavor pretty well .

s : a pretty complex smell , though coffee beans tend to be the dominant auroma . it 's nicely accented by a faint hint of sweet chocolate . t : there 's a real bright fruitiness that i do n't really pick up on in the scent that compliments ( but not well ) the coffee flavor that is n't so much roasted anymore as it is just kind of bitter . both are underwhelming to say the least , but this taste is n't as bad as it is disappointing .  it has good texture .

the aroma is out of this world . a very , very bready smell . heavy yeast and a cake-like aroma . immense . the taste is very strong carrot cake . pumpkin spice and brown sugar . hits the back of the tongue with authority . rich and bready , like a sugary cake .  the same color , mouthfeel , and drinkability were there , just the hopiness , aroma , and flavor , as well as most of the bitterness seemed to have blown away .
a : the pour is a deep dark brown , essentially black , with a fluffy tan head .  body is right- light , lively carbonation , not cloying or excessively dry .
this beer pours a very bright yellow sundrenched tint that just beckons to be drunk .  the mouthfeel is very full and hearty almost meaty- sort of flat .
this beer poured a very dark black color with very little light getting through it .  mouth feel is completely crisp , refreshing , and clean .

that jibes with the idea of `` just beer '' a very nice puffy head fills up a quarter of the glass , but it does n't leave much lacing as i make my way through the bottle . color is a nice amber , but the aroma is almost absent .  mouthfeel - good feel , not too thick , kind of creamy , decent carbonation .
this beer poured a black body with a thick dark tan/black head . a beautiful sight to see .  mouthfeel was smooth , slightly thick for a pils , and with a nice carbonation bite .

s : intense volatile pine , fresh grass , lightly toasted bread -- a very attractive , yet clean , smell . d : this ipa is a lightweight when it comes to taste , featuring a flavor profile that just ca n't live up to the remarkable smell . clean flavor qualities are taken too far at times , with only the finish really representing the style faithfully . it is genuinely appealing to sniff and to gaze upon , though .  taste is thin and adjuncty . mouthfeel is good , thick and creamy .
smells strongly of banana and bubblegum , with only a touch of clove . a candied note and a bit of white bread as well .  mouthfeel is very light and well carbonated .

pours a three fingered cream head that slowly fades to a thin layer , leaving a good lace .  has a medium body which is needed to carry all the hops and alcohol . low carbonation lends a nice texture without letting the flavors being cloying .
very clean aroma of bourbon and some licorice .  mouthfeel : nice feeling on the tongue and also a good consistencty .
) aromas are in the background and define it with a rugged , backcountry character .  m : lovely long bitter aftertaste .
a beautiful , reminiscent of the normal guinness cream top decks this dark copper colored beer . blanket lacing .  the mouthfeel is good , but obviously does not improve the flavor !

i 've always like tryign various fruit beers ... .and this one was certainly one of the better ones that i have tried . the raspberries are extremely prevalent to both smell and taste , but not to the point of being overwhelming .  - well carbonated , dries the mouth a bit . nice smooth body , probably this beers highlight is the mouthfeel .

a- poured into an over-sized beer mug , this made for a super robust head . great sticky lacing , a steady stream of carbonation , and an amber/orange body sets this beer up as one of the prettiest looking ipas ive seen in a while . s- i think the full scent has a bit of a hard time breaking through this super dense head !  the flavor that by far took the lead was chocolate ! there 's an overpowering ( and for me , disappointing ) chocolate aftertaste in this beer . mouthfeel- smooth , no complaints here . drinkability- well , the bottle looks cool as you drink from it !
smell is quite strong , a pine and citrus scent with a noticeable sweet honey or caramel malt aroma .  m : smooth and round .

beautiful amber color gives this lager a real boost .  everything about this beer was pretty light - light , crisp malt scent ; light fruity taste ; light body . feel - 4.0/5.0 - refreshing , which was really nice .
it basically looks very impressive ... fantastic .  m : medium in both body and carbonation .

pours a dark reddish brown with a huge off white head with huge fat lacing .  ) mouthfeel is just nicely carbonated and light and the only reason the drinkability is n't higher on my ratings is because after a few 40 's your out of the game for a while .
pours thick and black with a big fluffy head with excellent retention . looks rich and dessert-like .  m : good mouthfeel , its crisp , refreshing , light bodied with moderately high carbonation .
stellar appearance with this beer . it pours a really nice orange amber color with fine yeast particles suspended in it like stars . very attractive .  carbonation done very well .

absolutely gorgeous beer.a ruby-brown color with a very slight head that is quickly gone.very little carbonation.aroma of malt.some fruity , wine like aromas.malt dominates flavor.fairly obvious alchohol.not as sweet as other barleywines.tends to almost be a tad `` harsh '' between the alchohol and hop bitterness.full bodied mouthfeel that obviously speaks for the `` big '' beer that it is.overall a good beer but the harshness detracts slightly.definately a monster in itself.worth a try by all means.i havnt had this in 2 years but remember past samples along the same lines.will be laying a few bottles down this year .  m : medium body and moderate carbonation .

it is a beautiful orange/amber with a nice head .  mouthfeel was the highlight of the beer - it was almost velvety smooth . carbonation was low as per the style but if they 'd added a few more hops to dry out the palate it would have been near perfect .

a-dark brown/black s-nice blend of cocoa and leafy hops..really impresses on the nose . t-hops are a little more forward on the taste ... .interesting hop dimensions ... some bright citrus ... .and some grungy pine and weed like notes ... roasted malts ... .also some darker cocoa ... m-rich ... fuller bodied ... .feels bigger than a regular black ipa ... body fits ... o-top notch effort .  the mouthfeel is very nice.. feels heavy , thick , smooth , and not over-carbonated .

a : pours pitch black and complete opaque . 2-finger foamy tan head that sticks around for a while and leaves great web-like lacing all over the glass .  mouthfeel - it does have a pleasant rich/buttery mouthfeel .
an alcoholic praline . profound amber hues and sticky fingers of lace .  m : nice and thick d : not something ill try again .

pours a cloudy yellow with white high lights . the head is astounding . it is enormous and when the dust settles it remains a nice lacing .  at least its silky smooth and the alcohol is well hidden . this beer , in my opinion , is the weakest of their stout series .
very attractive irs : ink black with a nice two-finger mocha head .  still for such a big beer it had a great body , just not sure if i would want more , until it got about 5 years on it .

s - gorgeous nose on this . roasted coffee , chocolate , toffee , caramel with a bit of a piny hop smell poking in there . still it 's an interesting brew with a complex bill . lots of malts lots of hops . still definitely worth a try ( all of their stuff is ) .  smooth creamy medium body .
a- big tan head on a clear deep amber body with hues of brown in it . nice lacing that sticks to side of glass .  mouthfeel is round and full , thick and sticky .

zero head retention & lacing s : smokeyness & toasty grain , pick up a lot peat & alder once really warm t : roasty & charred malt , dark chcolate & husky smokeyness up front .  the body is full and the carbonation is light . mouthfeel is creamy .

s : i absolutely love the smell of this brew . citrus hop notes . toasted malts . a lingering sweetness . d : good with appetizers , something vinegar-based ( maybe fries ... ) . extra stats from the botm newsletter : serving temp : 45-50 d f ibu : 26 abv : 5.4 % malts : pale , caramel hops : apollo , willamette  light body , good carbonation .

three floyds beers have a unique aroma . the hops come across , thick and flowery . ive heard they use amarillo and columbus hops for aroma . many brewers could learn from these folks . milk chocolate , coffee , a little toasted malt with just a mild flowery hop flavor on the finish . slick , smooth and rich mouth feel , very nice , very drinkable .  m - the brew is wet at the lips but finishes quite dry . impressive . ~ unfortunately i 'm going to struggle finishing this because of the flavor .

d - the aroma is very nice , but the flavor just does n't live up to it ( an unfortunate trend i have noticed with dieu du ciel ) .  body was medium , and the liquid was fairly smooth overall . 3.03 rdev -19.5 % look : 3.5 | smell : 3 | taste : 3 | feel : 4 | overall : 2.5 1366
poured into a tall hobgoblin tumbler , there is a huge billowing light tan head . very impressive presentation .  mouthfeel is medium , clean with a bitter hop aftertaste .

the smell is extremely vibrant and spicy reminding me immediately of egg-nog . despite being very interesting and flavorful it becomes difficult to drink about halfway through .  mouthfeel : light , carbonated , crisp .

a- nice pour into a standard pint glass , about 3 fingers of nice creamy/airy/cloudy head , great release . deep rasberryish/velvety red rusty color . nice consistent lacing throughout .  mouthfeel is very creamy as expected from the nitro can , but i couldnt get past the taste that just did not agree with me .
very nice looking beer in a great setting .  m : fizzy carbonation that smooths out a little into the sip and works well with the body of the beer .
i 'm very impressed with this beers look .  this one is crisp and carbonation is at a good level . body is n't as light as i had expected ; this one 's medium-bodied .

smell is kind of `` down on the farm '' and very deep and enjoyable : aromas of good bread , malt , wool , leather and coffee , subdued but complex and rich .  goes down smooth , no bite , and finishes with an appropriate amount of stickiness . carbonation is on the lower end of the spectrum . nice feel .
pours a beautiful golden color with thick , frothy guinness-like white head .  mouthfeel is light to medium and has a soft feel .

this is the only barley wine i have every tried , and chances are it will be the last . some people love this stuff , not me , not my taste buds .  mouthfeel : light/medium with a tart , crisp finish drinkability : i really do n't crave another of these ; this certainly would n't be a lawnmower beer for me conclusion : just kind of unsorted ( also kind of an odd bitterness on the finish ) ... i tried this a year or two ago and was n't a huge fan ... now that i 'm reviewing it ... i 'm still not .

poured from the 22oz bomber into a belgian duvel glass . appearance- beer pours a clear brown with red hues with a finger thick cap of irish cream foam .  m/s carbonation is fine , alcohol is n't really noticeable `` thanks '' to the bitterness overall i really do n't like this beer , but i guess it has more to do with me and this style than the beert itself .
it is cool watching the carbonation rise from the bottom to the top as the beer becomes less hazy as it settles .  m : solid mouthfeel , carbonation is pretty much spot on .
