the appearance is an exceptional golden hue with a slight red tone . a very minimal white head is apparent with smile delicate lacing along the side of the glass .  an intense experience . the flavour is huge bitter hops - oily and rich with a spike on the back palette . the alcoholic warmth starts deep within the pit of the stomach and travels all the way up to the cheeks . next time i try it will be in front of a fire with a huge cheese platter .

summit horizon red : a : appearance is exceptional , great amber-red color to it with exceptional clarity ! nice 1 '' head that develops yet depletes half-way through .  mouthfeel is creamy and satisfying .
pours a massive , incredibly thick , dense and chunky white head that is long lasting .  m : creamy to a crisp finish with a good carbonation throughout .

pours black and thick . substantial tan head that forms of a billion tiny bubbles then morphs into a very slow fading creamy foam .  the mouthfeel is good - smooth with a right amount of carbonation .
lively . golden with a dense creamy head ... after all it is the cream of manchester ... a nickname i 've never felt comfortable with .  m : medium bodied with a medium carbonation .
bottle : poured a golden color ale with a huge pure white foamy head with great retention and lacing .  mouthfeel was pleasant . a medium bodied chewiness and good carbonation .

smells quite spicy , with cloves and cinnamon and orange peel coming through the hefty alcohol and sweet malt . excellent . a sip reveals a creamy , yeasty , sweet beer , very different from your normal eisbock .  mouthfeel : nicely carbonated and good level of thickness - probably the best part of this beer .
a - pours an inky black with chocolate brown head , very nice looking beer .  m : silky smooth feel . i like the finish . smoothed out my palate .

the aromas are magnificent ! espresso coffee as if fresh brewed .  mouthfeel : the carbonation is well balanced with a nice medium body , leaning a bit on the heavier side . drinkability : the mouthfeel is great and there is no sign of the 7 % abv .

the nose was spectacular . sweet tar , coffee , chocolate , sappy wood all leap from the glass . molasses and brown sugar are buried within the beautiful , rich nose . overwhelming loads of flavors battling for attention .  full bodied with a smoothy , creamy mouthfeel .

black raspberry desert chocolate . slightly smokey and tart in the back . vanilla , fudge , and chocolate . d : described as an `` experimental '' beer , this one is definitely unique . worth a try as i 've never experienced a prominent chocolate raspberry taste in my imperial stouts before and i think i like it !  m : very fizzy , light on body , about right for the style .
s-really smells quite like a full bore ipa .  the mouthfeel was full and sweet .

great theatre watching the tall head overtaken by the liquid and the color is near black and near opaque .  had a funny texture in the mouth and could definitely taste dried fruit but could not discern the type .
pours a lovely coppery amber with a dense , dense foamy off-white head .  the mouthfeel is really soft and creamy , as i figured cask would be .
a : very nice translucent amber color with a half finger of white head . good head retention .  m : crisp , clean , would call it refreshing if it tasted better .

the beer poured a beautiful translucent red colour with a 1 inch tan coloured head .  maybe i could not taste the `` rare '' but this really sucked compared to the 2008 classic gueuze which is a fantastic gueuze .
22-oz bottle opened at local beer tasting ( underground bluz ) . a beautiful brew . this beer can do some damage because you wo n't want to stop drinking it !  buttery thick mouthfeel .
amazing smell -- coffee and chocolate dominate the aromas with some caramel in the background .  m - good mouthfeel . a little heavier thanks to the lack of filtration .
it 's an awesome smelling stout !  medium bodied and decent carbonation .
made a great appearance , poured a classic beer golden with a very large creamy foamy white head with a lot of sticking .  mouthfeel : thick and what you would expect from a ris .

a - pours jet black with a towering tan head , which stubbornly refuses to drop for several minutes . when it finally falls to a rocky couple of inches large clumps of lacing are left behind .  it is pretty full bodied and creamy .

pours from the tap to a pretty chocolate brown with a thick tan head that lingers well and leaves good lacing .  mouthfeel is heavier than i 'd anticipate . i wish i liked the flavor of this because its heaviness is spot on .

really fantastic nose , the raspberries shine through . good interesting beer that is cool to try to reach both the girls and the boys beer drinkers or not .  nice creaminess from the malt . probably the driest amber ale i 've ever had . usually not a bad thing , i like dry beers , but this was too much , there needs to be a little sweetness there to bring it to life . should n't be called an octoberfest and would n't try again .

smells heavy of cherries , very good smell . taste is just as heavy with the cherries .  mouthfeel is about right for style , perhaps a touch undercarbed , but all else is acceptable , though it showcases a flavor profile best left behind the curtain .

12oz bottle into a tulip glass - from the latest release a : pitch black pour with 2 fingers of fairly dark brown head . beautiful beer .  m : mouthfeel is crisp , light-medium bodied and pretty dry .
pours a thick black color with a medium beige head .  mouthfeel was nice and thick ; you know you 're drinking a dipa .
multilayered rings everywhere - one of the best lace patterns i 've seen from a beer in a long while .  m- very smooth . medium carbonation fills the mouth a little . d- good .

s - mango , pineapple , yeast , apple , pear all present . yup , this is citra . o/d - aroma was lovely but the booze is a little rough .  strong carbonation . m. very bitter and the carbonation is clean and tart .
not dominating like some ipa 's , there are also crisp malt notes . the blend is just about perfect . this is one inviting beer !  m : light body , moderate carbonation , nice crisp body .

very nice and clean aroma , even with the `` funk '' .  the body is pleasant and perfectly appropriate for a light belgian ale . full of carbonation , relatively light in the mouth , easy to drink ; no complaints on this front ; this beer only becomes a problem when you have to smell it or taste it .
very heavy hefe pour . thick , deep yellow gold that glubglubs out of the bottle and leaves a giant head .  m : thick creamy mouthfeel .

( appearance ) : pours an almost midnight brown/ black with a 3/4 finger sized light brown foam head . this identity crisis gives it a very cheap and `` college party '' failure vibe that just takes any enjoyment or class out of trying to drink it .  m : well carbonated and thick , fairly heavy . fits the style .
s : strong hop smell with hints of citrus , apricots , and sweetness . d : an interesting ipa with the addition of the apricots .  m - pretty good .
and while it is not terrible , it merely passes as ok. the look is deep and black , and of course the cascading head is beautiful .  the mouthfeel is smooth and oily and the carbonation is alright .

gorgeous . a few streamers feed the head , which retains ok and leaves nice lacing .  really nice body all around ... overall - i would really enjoy this beer if it were n't for the bubblegum flavor , it 's really off putting and not very pleasant .

poured into my duvel tulip glass , poured a rich thick borwn that cant be seen through , a rich creamy five finger head rises to the top and stays awhile , the smell is rich grain and alchoal with a sweet fig overtone , the flavor is figs , hazelnuts , molasses , honney , sweet malt , a hint of folaral hops then malt for days .  m : the body is medium to full with a fairly high carbonation . this is actually one of the best things about this beer .

cola colored perhaps . head is tan , lasts well , and leaves lacing . m- carbonation is medium-light , but dang , for a porter this has a thin body .  there 's big citrus/grapefruit hops , but then a nasty onion/vegetable taste . mouthfeel is fine .

500 ml bottle poured into a stella challis a - creamy , foamy 2-finger head . cloudy , dark-apricot orange . rings of foam stay on the glass as the glass is drunk .  m/d : light and smooth feel on the mouth , drinkable but not something i will ever get again .

the pour is beauty in the glass ( a snifter this time ) . a mysterious murky deep orange that still reveals the active carbonation rising up to the dense 3 fingers of sturdy , creamy off-white crown . once it was swirling in my snifter i got strong fresh hop tanginess , herbal esthers , big florals , and a kind of peanut brittle sweetness .  the aroma contained notes of malt , hops and a discernable alcohol content of medium strength . it had a stong alcohol flavor that was very over powering the other flavors . it was smooth yet burned as it went down . truely a devilish brew !

there is also a nice toffee and molasses sweetness to keep the aroma balanced . there are also hints of dark berries : to me it smelled like blueberry and raspberry . it is a very enticing aroma . taste : more roasted glory , and the first sip was a shock of burnt bitterness ; the overpowering intensity , though , passed after a couple sips .  m : light-medium bodied , creamy , smooth and crisp .
brownish black pour , good head . pretty beer .  this has a very creamy mouthfeel to it despite being fairly well carbonated .

smell : strong coffee notes over roasted malt . fairly straight forward but the limited dimensions it offers are good in their own right . taste : fairly waterly coffee rinds .  mouthfeel is crisp and drying , as it should be .

served in a nonic pint glass , the beer pours a clear gold color with a 2 inch frothy white head after an aggressive pour . head retention and lacing are both pretty good .  the mouthfeel is medium and creamy .
this beer poured a deep mahogany brown color . very clear and was topped with a creamy lacy head .  firm mouthfeel , big and solid . very imperial .

essentially , but not quite , black , it has a large tan head , creamy and long-lasting , slowly shrinking to a permanent frothy head with some nice lace .  appropriately light in body without being too thin .

pours a honey golden hue , translucent and bright , with generous white head . lots of lacing and creamy goodness on the head . only negative is that it is incredibly watery & light .  however , the mouthfeel was very nice , which lent a overall smoothness and softness to it .

aroma is on point with many ipa 's out there and really doesnt smell like an apa . very attractive nose . taste falls short of what i expected but still nice and balanced . has some sweet pineapple like sugary aftertaste that is appealing but throws me off from the lack of hop bitterness .  the mouthfeel was quite good , though . well carbonated and it felt good going down .

crispy , clear , & vibrantly gold . an inch of thinning egg white froth .  i believe the bottle i got was 8.75 percent.. looked pretty good for a esl , smell and taste reminded me very much of great western extra gold.. very malty with a nice solventy sweet-like alcohol burn ... carbonated perfectly , making it halfway drinkable , still hangover juice as far as imports go.. cheers !
pours a brilliant copper ; a vigorous pour produces only a one-inch head but a nice , tight , foamy one .  this beer feels almost delicate .

a- body is a nearly transparent dark copper hue that is served with the perfect 1/2 finger foamy white head . the head has perfect retention the whole way down the glass .  the mouthfeel is notably well contoured . dark and hearty though at times cloying .

the humble brown has rarely looked so good .  we 're okay though , as next time we get a samuel adams winter sampler pack , i 'll give her my cranberry , and i 'll have her boston lager . it 's not a bad beer , it 's just not to my liking . i ca n't even really say why . a bit sweeter than i 'd like , and just nothing that stands out and says `` i 'm great '' .

this beer pours an inky black with a dark brown head .  taste/mouthfeel : mostly hops . heavily malted finish . drinkability : a bit heavy and not quite as good as other european lagers . overall : probably the best gateway to this style .
smell is sweet and a really fruity in aroma . quite spicy in aroma vanilla , cinnamon and black pepper .  there 's actually a nice amount of body to this one .
seems very complex , i love it . t : disappointed from the smell .  mouthfeel is light with a good spike of carbonation .

thick dense white head with great retention .  taste is a very light malt sweetness upfront with a moderately bitter finish of good length and crispness . a pretty uncomplicated beer , good for the style , a good lawnmower beer .
i love the smell of a good lambic though .  nice carbonation and creamy mouthful .

big foamy head , a mix of burnt malt and thick coconut in the aroma & # 8230 ; very aromatic . nice clash of burnt malt that strays to slightly to the acidic side and the mild sweetness of the toasted coconut . very interesting and yet another beer i wish i had with dessert though this would have been better with the sweet potato pie .  mouthfeel is good all around- enough carbo to temper the bitterness , moderately thick , finishes dry . a damn shame .

maredsous 8 on tap in a tulip glass . black cherry color with a nice creamy head . excellent lacing , thick on the glass .  m : fuller side of medium-bodied with moderate carbonation that tickles the tongue and throat . this aspect of the beer is really nice .

i was afraid since this beer emphasized bacon , that it would be like an overly smoked beer that gave a nitrate like amora , but this one is balanced nicely . road tar , malted barley , honey ham , rubber , and charred hickory . absolutely awesome . t- the taste is light and pleasant .  mouthfeel is decent medium bodied and goes down smooth .
2003 : nice heavy white head tops the cloudy golden hue .  feel is pretty smooth , nothing weird here .

appearance : slightly hazy , ruby-amber pour with a voluminous ( and tenacious ) , light-tan whipped-cream head . recedes to floating dollops ... lace everywhere !  crisp , clean mouthfeel with flavors of dry , pale malt . at first , i found myself wanting more flavor , a la boston lager , but the mouthfeel and resulting drinkability really brought things back up for me in the end .
smell is wonderfully floral and hoppy . not floral or hoppy , but more like perfumy .  m - nice . thick .

smell : they put some hops in this , a lot of them . pine , key lime , hop leaf , loads of bitter hop oil , hope there 's a base to catch me ... taste : surprisingly earthy , the hop leaf / european hop profile , was expecting a little more west coast . overall : a very flavorful texas beer , just a little more english than american in taste , like a english double ipa .  feels very creamy but that does n't make the beer more drinkable to me .

1 pint 6 oz tall dark brown bottle with a racer checkered flag on the label with red and yellow print , pewter cap . great retention and clumpy lace .  m. medium-high carbonation , zesty on the tongue .
really nice , dark golden color . really substantial , bone-white head that has little recession .  smacks-you-in-the-face astringent . zippy on the mouth like you 'd expect .

a : pours a vigorous 4 finger creamy white head with excellent retention . lacing is amazing considering the light body , with layers clinging to the side of the glass like a ruler .  feel medium body , pleasant texture , some drying and bitterness in the finish .
poured a 4 finger fluffy white head with excellent retention .  m : medium-bodied with low and sightly creamy carbonation . there is a slight sticky feel and syrupy feel .

awesome . the taste is again huge with cherry flavor without sweetness , cherry pits , a decent amount of sourness , with a good lactic tartness on the finish .  very refreshing in the mouth , its best quality .

color is a soft , medium brown , almost clear . tall , light tan head , which falls slowly and unevenly , creating an attractive effect .  m : the carbonation is pretty much just right , and it 's smooth .
lacing is n't quite as impressive as the head retention , but a great looking beer .  mouthfeel is crisp , the whole drink is refreshing due to the good carbonation .

batch 9359 packaged 9/17/09 a : pours an opaque black with a tight dark brown head which leaves much lacing on the walls of the glass as it fades to a thin layer .  m : medium body and very good amount of carbonation in my opinion .

pours a hazy golden color , with a huge fluffy white head . what a sight , as the head rose easily above the rim of the glass , and held there like an ice cream cone for a lengthy period of time .  mouthfeel is medium with good level of carbonation .

s : some spice notes in the aroma -- cloves , cinnamon , and nutmeg -- followed by sweet caramel and vanilla aromas . there are some floral notes in there as well as a touch of sweet citrus . t : similar to the aroma , spices come up front but do n't overwhelm .  taste - 3.0/5.0 - light `` summer '' type beer , prob good if really hot , some malt crispness feel - 4.0/5.0 - smooth , light , refreshing drinkability - 2.5/5.0 - would have again , if it was hot , but not enough flavor make this a go-to beer

a- pours a brownish color with red hues noted against a white background . the clear nature of the beer allows me to see the carbonation , which is modest looking at best . the head is plentiful and puffy looking , retaining well and leaving behind a thick film of dense foam on the glass .  this beer does have a nice smooth , dry mouthfeel .

taste : something about the taste does n't quite live up to the smell . the taste is a weakened version of the caramel malts in the smell leading into a dark fruit plumlike aftertaste .  medium carbonation .

this beer has probably the best head i 've ever seen on a saison . saison de lente pours a massive 3 finger white head that has almost a pancake batter like consistency . the head retention is fantastic . the lacing is just magical . a thick french lacing accompanies the glass even when then the glass is empty .  lighter body and a nice lively carbonation .

served up a breathtaking deep copper amber that is crystal clear . the head is slightly off-white and looks superb with tightly packed , shiny bubbles that stick around forever and leave near perfect lace . if this beer tastes nearly as good as it looks i will be most happy .  mouthfeel is sticky and sweet with a nice roundness and full character .

aroma is a deep roasted scent that makes me think of chocolate cake baking . color is solid black with good carbonation and a thick tight head .  '' m - actually a nice and robust mouthfeel , i just do n't really want to feel this beer in my mouth because it tastes kind of terrible .
pours a translucent medium copper with some awesome bubbling and a thick doughy head .  good , solid creamy feel with enough dryness to get you through .
smell : wonderful aromas on this beer .  mouthfeel was good and thick , but was n't enough to save this beer from being a disappointment .

pours smooth and deep , with a nice creamy off-white head . great appearance , large dark oily brown head .  i did n't want to buy this because i do n't trust twisted pine to sell me a good beer . since i am a sucker and i love hoppy beers i bought it anyway . the smell was very hoppy citrus , pine and something off i could n't place until i tasted it , butter . this beer was quite disappointing and i poured out the remaining 13 or so ounces after i finished my first glass .
big chocolate smell . sweet malts and molasses lend to a chocolate bar wrapper aroma .  carbonation is very fine , which leads to a good mouthfeel .

sampled on 7-17-10 pours a very dark brown color , with a foamy tan head and lots of bubbles . lacing is thick and clingy , and lasts a long time . very nice .  mouthfeel - some creamy smoothnes , well-carbonated .

the first thing you notice on this beer is the gorgeous pour .  m : chewy and viscous . if anything , the aging has tempered some of the trademark trainwreck mouthfeel and flavors of base dark lord , so i 'm impressed .
pours black as night with a brown head . definitely looks the part of a big ris .  nice mouthfeel .

thick foamy tan head that lasted pretty well , and nice lacing .  glass : new belgium globe aging notes : one year at ~60f in the dark bang for the buck ( oz* % / $ ) : 22*6.2/10 = 13.64 a : orange , white lacey head , slightly cloudy from yeast s : horse-y farmhouse brett with hints of orange t : brett dominates ( horse-stable hay , a little dung almost ) , notes of orange m : silky , coating , lingering , pleasant o : worth drinking , a little one-dimensional with the brett .

poured into an imperial pint glass , formed a 1 1/4 '' light beige head over the copper brew . frothy foam head lasts well , with provides nice , plentiful lacing .  if there is , then this ska brew is a prime example ... this is the second time i tasted a bottle of this brew . this is an extremely clean tasting brew which is a great quality i enjoy , but where are the hops ? the malt and ( not overwhelming ) bitterness serve as great supporting backbones to what should be a wonderful hoppy aroma and flavor . as it stands , this brew is severely lacking in hop flavor/aroma and comes across as a brew which should be named `` delicate '' rather than `` decadent '' imperial ipa .

it smells amazing -- a sharp alcohol bite ( it 's a 21 abv , for crying out loud ) but surrounded with sweet citrus and pine and caramel and hops .  the mouthfeel is medium to full with decent carbonation .

aroma is fantastic , reminiscent of triple sec and cognac . an intriguing failure of a beer .  you do n't get much of the sweet malts you get from the aroma so it really confuses the senses and does n't make for an enjoyable experience mouthfeel is heavy and it sticks to your mouth for minutes .

it smells delicious , but it needs more sweetness and less bitterness to balance the tartness of the brett , no fusels , less carbonation and more body .  pretty much just a tingly water . very smooth and somewhat refreshing beer .

very unique . i could tell from smelling it that it was going to be sour , but had no idea the extent of sourness .  m- a good body to it . good weight and smooth carbonation . there is a strange foamy texture in the finish though .
a : dark cloudy copper body with two fingers of off white head . good retention and lacing .  pleasantly effervescent mouthfeel .

this thing pours up a crystal clear copper with big rocky white head that leaves behind some of the prettiest lace i have seen in a while . great head retention and beautiful rising bubbles in this incredibly clear beer just make this look positively stunning .  crisp , good body overall .
big ripe banana aroma that is quite pleasing . malts can be noted as well .  pretty slick mouthfeel .

my mouth is watering s - super floral , i do n't even need to put my nose that close to get wonderful citrus and pine notes t - a bit sweet to me . m - sweetness sticks a the tongue to much , leaves a sugary oily aftertaste , decent carbonation o - a good ipa , but not the best  i like the feel with some prickly carbonation and moderately light feel and some creaminess from the head .
it smells great , but the flavor just ca n't back it up .  a little sticky and a very bitter aftertaste .

nose is a sweet mix of yeasty malt with creamy fresh fruity notes , almost mellon like .  surprisingly , the sediment was n't hard and i did n't feel a corporeal presence in my mouth . coopers best extra stout was nice on the palate ; softly carbonated and creamy . to tell you the truth , i was a bit disappointed .

aroma : geuze like . very exciting . battery acid , funky rotten hay , sour lemons , feet with warts on em , horse manure , etc yum ! this is fricking awesome . taste : sour cherries , rancid malts , waterlogged hay on a hot summer day , some putrid strawberries that have been stomped by angry goats . delicious . mouthfeel : very light body .  m : medium bodied , good amount of carbonation .

smell was delicious . nutmeg , cinnamon , holiday cheer ... everything a holiday ale should smell like . overall this beer was good . i would definitely try the 2012 redition .  the body of this beer suits the style with the usual level of north coast drinkability and feel to it . definitely the best feature .
) tasted 10/02 : bronze/bright amber color with good tan lasting head .  smooth and refreshing , light to medium bodied with a slight tingling on the tongue .

the nose is bursting with scents of fresh-squeezed oranges , pineapple , guava . good full-bodied ipa with plenty of carbonation zip . i expected more of a fruity-tasting ipa , but this one is herbal , earthy , and spicy .  m - low carbonation , tiny bubbles , overall feels pretty good .

smell : the best part of this beer in my opinion . extremely complex ! i smell the chocolate and coffee but i am also overwhelmed by the super sweet heavenly smell of vanilla . taste : i was so happy that the taste was so refined , understated , elegant and smooth . drinkability : love it love it .  light and creamy mouth feel with obviously knocked down carbonation .

the aromas were inviting and very exciting . t : dark and sweet fruits at the beginning of the sip , hints of alcohol in the middle , ending in a pretty strong bitter kick .  m-fairly dry . medium high carbonation .
big , frothy , sponge-like head towers over the brew and new fully disappears .  mouthfeel is nice and thick and well carbonated . the best part of the beer .

typical intense heller aroma , roasted pork and tons of smoked ham , sweet maple syrup , campfire , just rich malt altogether and intense smokiness . it somehow reminds vermont maple smoked cheddars which is no little task . taste is actually quite wheaty and fruity ( banana , lemon ) so its actually pretty well made since it was clearly the intention , but i dont really enjoy the atmosphere created from wheaty dusty tartness mixed with the big smokiness .  m : moderate carbonation with a decently viscous mouthfeel .

poured a orange copper color with great carbonation and a huge head from the bomber . lots of lacing and plenty of suds left over as i drinl .  m : medium-light body ; moderate carbonation ; smooth and clean mouthfeel .

aroma : sublime ! super sweet , rich dark ripe fruits coupled with notes of chocolate . an all organic ale , not the best dubbel , but respectable .  feels slick , not very carbonated , and heavy . alcohol warming is powerfully strong . lacks balance and drinkability .
rgc pours a deep red-cognac color with generous carbonation and a settling tan head .  there 's moderate carbonation to it as well .

looks like a ton of carbonation . golden , cloudy . great looking beer and i 'm excited to taste my first jolly pumpkin .  aroma : hops . the crystal hops dominate the aroma . the malt is there , but overpowered by hops . but i do n't taste the balance that an esb should have . the hops weigh far more than the malt in this beer . notes : this tasted like a very good ipa , but did not have the balance i was expecting , for an esb . a great beer , but did n't fit the style as well as i would have liked .

strong medicinal smell almost a eucalyptus quality also some fresh cut wheat or alfalfa , and some small notes of tropical fruit . smell is subtle at first and as the beer warms it really opens up . best quality of the brew is the smell . taste and mouthfeel is not as exciting as the smell . not bad at all a tingly carbonation and a little on the thin side .  good carbonation .

above average head retention & lacing s : lemony with white pepper & orange peel t : follows the nose , also some breadyness & candi sugar , apple peels & general spiceyness up front . finishes with apple peel , lemony & herbal hops & a lovely spiceyness & just a bit of grapefruit at the apex mf : medium bodied , lively carbonation , very nice balance superb drinkabilty i could stay on this all night !  mouthfeel is pretty good however , with a nice medium feel .
s : crisp aroma with strong malt presence and hints of flowery hoppiness .  m = moderately carbonated . good .

a : forms a nice 1.5 finger frothy head in my sa perfect pint glass with very good retention . it 's a crystal clear beer with varying colors , being auburn orange at the thinner parts and ruby red at the thicker , and a good amount of bubbles floating up from the etch at the bottom . perfect appearance at least .  good mouthfeel for this light body but the hops balance the feel .

the retention was downright insane and it essentially sat there like whipped cream . beautiful looking beer .  this is my first review and hope it looks well , even if not my favorite beer . leaves a malt taste on the roof and tongue . this is the first scottish ale i 've tried . for comparison , i love dark ales , like ommegang abbey belgium ale and founders breakfast stout . bottle serving .

appearance : cloudy golden yellow with an amazing , big , billowy head that last all the way through the beer , incredible lacing too which sticks all over the glass . the best looking tripel i 've ever seen .  m : full body with mild carbonation ; slightly clinging .

this beer pours a hazy honey golden orange with a huge fluffy white head , that leaves some seriously sticky lacing . i could only think to myself that this is an absolutely beautiful beer .  mouthfeel was really good for a light beer . liked the carbonation , and felt richer than it tasted .

smell : the smell really is impressive . heavy heavy coffee . good malt to support , but great coffee aromas . taste : feels like i 'm enjoying a nice cup of coffee fresh out of the percolator after waking up in a tent .  it 's very creamy and goes down easy . i 'm really disappointed with this .
looks great ! great color , small head .  m : tingly carbonation , medium body and refreshing enough .
amazing nose of peach with a high , frothy , long lasting head with an almost soapy mouthfeel .  the mouthfeel is the pinnacle of this brew . full-bodied with a dry crisp feel .

poured a deep , uber cloudy orangish color with good carbonation leaving a nice white cap s : loads of faded hops , fruits..apricot and others with booze t : big faded hops powered by fruitiness and booze .  the body is light-medium with good carbonation .
a - pours as a perfectly clear golden color with a finger of off white head that has decent retention .  mouthfeel is pretty good , it has a nice full body , and a good finish .
appearance : pours a deep , ruby-brown body with excellent clarity and a tall , foaming , sand dollar-colored head .  mouthfeel was good , with plenty of carbonation and a nice smoothness to it .

it pours a beautiful clear coppery-brown with just a little head .  the mouthfeel is thick and oily with a mild burn going down . have a bottle of this is all i can handle , which is good because the full bottle would have me a little too buzzed .
a toasted head has great retention and lace .  ) the body is a hefty medium , bordering on the truly heavy , with a light moderate carbonation and a fairly chewy feel . harsh .
had a gorgeous impenetrable chestnut coloration , massive amounts of creeping carbonation , and a thick , creamy off-white head that displayed amazing retention .  big body , low carbonation .
the smell is divine with fruits and spice and honey , and a little malt . although not a belgian champion it 's still a fine tripel .  nice mouthfeel for a pale ale .

m : moderate to heavy mouthfeel d : smells was awesome , taste was too much for me .  mouthfeel : well-carbonated , as expected from the heady pour drinkability : low- i could n't get over the tire flavor , which is a shame because every other aspect of the beer was delightful
a very well lagered and fined beer . probably filtered , too .  mouthfeel : medium to light with lively carbonation .
a : pours to a frothey tan head with a deep and beautiful copper body . excellent lacing .  good mouthfeel and texture for a tap beer .

really delightful . very nice aroma sits about halfway between a brown ale and a porter .  hints of chocolate up front , but quickly overrun by the massive spices . reminds me of chewing on a mixture of green baking herbs , and about as pleasing on my palate . an interesting brew to say the least , but not one i 'd purchase again .
pours a deep murky brown with a nice frothy light-tan head that lasts and leaves great lacing .  mouthfeel is quite nice and full .

this brew pours out a deep , hazy red amber color crested with a massive head that retains very well and leaves huge , sticky lacing .  yeast , stale hops , a little grass , so boring with a duvel quality ... the taste is equally as bad , bitter toffee , light stale hops , way too much yeast , sour finish . pass .

the aroma is spicy with loads of malt and touch of hops . the nose is spot on with what i think a marzen should smell like . overall a decent marzen .  a zesty tingle on the tongue at first , nice medium body , but the cinnamon is too much .

s -- tropical fruits dominate . this is like a mix of a belgian tripel and and ipa . very crisp and refreshing nose . t -- not quite as good on the palate , a little too dry of a finish but still a pleasant taste . m -- on the thin side and too dry , average d -- nice beer , but nothing that stands out to me .  the mouthfeel is about right for a stout , a bit thick with low carbonation .

excellent retention . something you could stick your finger in and feel the foams welcoming grasp .  it is bubbly on the tongue and does leave you dry . it 's smooth , but just kind of basic . it 's a very approachable stout .
i thought i did n't like saisons until i tried this one . great head , fine bubbles that stuck to the glass the whole way down .  '' the mouthfeel is good . its quite smooth and slightly creamy .

big malty nose with hints of very dark caramel malts and lots of fruity yeast esters . light toasty wood aroma and some chocolate as it warms up .  mouthfeel is light and refreshing making the beer overall a decent session beer .

sweetish and beautiful . t : unfortunately , the alcohol flavor jumps to the front , and while it 's not quite overwhelming , it 's a large part of the flavor , which i do n't find pleasant .  has a nice medium to full body with light carbonation .
this beer looks great , clean and clear , good carbonation and head .  the mouthfeel is fine . it is a low/medium bodied beer with good carbonation .

a : very dark brown with appealing 2-3 finger , rocky , off-white head with very good retention and abundant lacing in rings .  this is my first , of hopefully many reviews , so bare with me . once they were chilled i poured them into a pint glass and sat back with my favorite tv shows a- pours a dark red almost brownish color s- smells like your average porter , did n't really pick up on too much vanilla t- taste more of chocolate or toffee but with hints of vanilla m- pretty smooth , goes down easy without any bite o- not sure if i would buy a case of it , but its good when thrown in a variety pack

s : the aroma contains hops , dark fruit , roasted malts and a bit of chocolate . t : the taste starts out very bitter with flavors of dark chocolate and a strong hops presence .  m-creamy and good mouthfeel d-did n't finish my 1/5 share of the bomber .

bottle : poured a dark porter with a super huge medium brown foamy head with super great retention and lacing - almost to the point where i am wondering if something is wrong .  nice creamy mouthfeel .
that creamy two finger nitro head looks damn sexy .  mouthfeel- medium mouthfeel ( for the style ) . carbonation level was perfect for bringing out the bittering hops .

bottle ( 2011 ) port bottle shop carlsbad , ca transparent golden with a thick and persistent nearly white head , with lots of lacing left down the glass . gorgeous pale ale .  the mouth feel was thick and creamy ( a high gravity ) overall not a `` session beer '' but one to enjoy and move on .

and then the sniff - it was like straight up coffee ! i took a nice long pull and let it wash around for a second . it was just short of carbonated espresso . if you let it settle out on your tongue , you can pull out some lighter hits of malt in there , but this one is definitely about the coffee . if you like coffee , this one is for you .  i liked the mouthfeel , smooth and gentle .
a - scotch / almond color . beautiful head with great lace .  mouthfeel is medium/light with good carbonation .
purchased as a 22 from wine and beer westpark in glen allen , va - tulip pours dark but with mahogany edges , perfect head with awesome lacing .  moderate hops with lots of body , almost chewy .

the aroma is that of fresh american hops that have been sitting in the aging tank for a while . this beer is dry hopped every day for a month and the aroma tell the story . citrusy aromas that gram the oral senses and tell a story of freshness . it is surprisingly balanced and the hop aroma and flavor is a real treat . score : my personal taste score was a 93 / 100 .  carbonation was crisp for a medium body .

there is a magical cascading effect within the beer as it settles . a beautiful off white head remains perfect throughout the experience lacing is awesome .  smooth with a creamy but dry finish . i walked away thinking that the `` smoked vanilla , coffee , and birch '' was meant to be flavor descriptors rather than actual ingrediants . all of these elemtns were way too weak to be appreciated for what other beers can do with them . call it a single , nix the mention of the adjuncts , and this beer would be alright .

this is an impressive looking belgian , from a 355 ml bottle it pours a deep hazy apricot colour with a great deal of carbonation action , and a massive creamy head that gets chunky on the pour , rises above the rim of my chalice glass and holds its form . solid lacing down the side of the glass .  mouthfeel is medium bodied and crisp . good carbonation , but the overall trainwreck of flavor in the brew makes this one hard to take down .

the aroma is very enticing ... it 's fruity and easily smelled from afar..thankfully this is not overloaded with cinnamon as was my fear ... instead , there is a rich perfumy sourness of rotting apples , musty basement and faint tobacco . very nice , and not tainted with fusels as i have noted in ron 's prior entries .  it has a very soft mouthfeel , a little like soda to be honest and you can barely notice the alcohol .
two fingers of thick creamy head with good retention and plenty of lacing .  m- good carbonation and substantial body , not bad here .

appearance : the look of this beer is exceptional . it is a burnt brown color with a huge pillowy head . there is tons of sticky lacing that makes this beer look geourgious .  not really much going on that i can discern m : this is one category where this beer does well with a nice light feel and pleasant carbonation d : why would i want another ?
aroma is piney and citrusy hops .  the feel was pleasantly smooth , but was unimpressed with the drinkability as seemed to reform a head with every drink .

the smell is very strong of hops . very floral and powerful . the taste it really dominated by hops and the bitterness at the end is quite nice .  mouthfeel is medium , carbonation average-high with some pleasant warming feel .
: - ) s- nose is wonderful . if you 've had sam adams ' triple bock , it smells just like that .  mouthfeel is thick and smooth , no watery sensation at all .
a : nearly black in color , a very dark cola color with a thick , foamy cocoa head . great retention and lacing .  mouthfeel was real good .

sam adams poured a nice golden brown with a biscuit like head . very nice .  as i drink more my palate adjusts but it does n't ever really get over the off flavors m - pretty thick , not too carbonated , nice mouth coating qualities d - burnt coffee does not go down very well , plust the thickness of the beer limits my ability to quaff this completely i like coffee , i like stouts , and i like a lot of coffee stouts ( new glarus and founders breakfast stout for instance ) .

dark brown with good clarity , this beer has a dense , light brown head with excellent retention and lacing .  smells of raisins , a hint of semi-sweet choc ? mouthfeel is nice , thick , syrupy & smooth ... the way i want a barleywine .

original rating date : october 19 , 2008 pours dark copper , thick , creamy head . strong lacing down the glass .  very rich flavor of dark malts and smoke , with hints of coffee and chocolate as well . the finish is almost all smoke , much too intense for my liking . ive used this many times in making caribou pot roasts in the crockpot . they even have a recipe on their website , which is delicious . i was informed that this beer has won more medals at the great american beer festival than any other beer , quite an accomplishment .

a big , beautiful whack of tropical fruits on the nose - pineapple , passionfruit . superb . the tropical fruits are still there on the palate but perhaps a little more resinous than i was expecting .  mouthfeel is medium , well carbed , nice on all fronts but where it needs to be . big failure , in my opinion .

pours a lager-yellow , huge creamy white head that dissipates down to a film leaving very much lace . nice looking beer .  the mouthfeel was sticky and thick . there was tight and crisp carbonation that was nice .
has a mashed ripe banana smell with sprucey / piney notes .  the body and carbonation levels are appropriate .

this has got to be one the best smelling ipa 's out there . the fruity and hoppy flavours balance out perfectly to leave a tasty , dry , almost graperuit-esque finish which is just fantastic . this beer packs a mighty punch .  m - nice average mouthfeel .
a : light straw yellow . plenty of carbonation , bone white head with medium to heavy lacing .  fine mouthfeel , nothing objectionable , but it 's not a stand-out lager either .
smell- this smelled like pure chocolate and coffee , my mouth was watering upon the smell .  medium mouthfeel .

a : yellow , straw hues , slightly hazy , enormous whipped meringue head , long lasting retention , nice lacing .  i have the mom version the head was initially strong , though sudsy and it fell quickly . carbonation is plentiful from the surface of the brew come hop aromas -- minty and herbal -- and coriander . it does n't smell as though an authentic yeast was used , which fits my preconceived notions for rogue 's methods the flavor confirms my american yeast suspicions . light fruity flavors , strong hop contributions , though little spice .

aroma is of fresh peaches , and is absolutely marvelous ; the best part of this beer . however , also plain and unexciting . good for what it is , but not anything that really excites me .  m - light to medium carbonation with medium carbonation .

some alcohol noted as well but very pleasant on the nose . t - the taste starts sweet , fruity and malty reminding me a lot of a traditional abbey abt .  palate : very enjoyable . great , smooth , and light on the throat . it would be stellar with cheese .

smells and tastes of molasses , raisins , brown sugar and bourbon soaked oak barrels . very pungent and boozy in the nose and finish as well .  mouthfeel - explodes in the mouth with carbonation , yet maintaining a noteworthy smoothness afterwards . the body is sturdy but not overly big .
poured into a goblet , revealing huge tan head , barely any body . lots of head .  the mouth feel is pretty good and when ice cold very easy to drink .

appearance : poured a milky orangy and yellowish hazy color , typical of hefeweizens , especially authentic german ones . yielded a huge 3 finger creamy head that came right out of the glass but maintained its shape is it was thick and creamy .  it is carbonated well . it is crisp and goes down smooth .
served in a pint glass poured from a 12oz bottle a : pours a deep black color with thick foamy head reminiscent of chocolate milk .  m - thick , syrupy , smooth , a bit refreshing .
bottled april 22 , 2009 poured into a pint glass amber with a very thick white head . very good retention and lacing .  it is very finely carbonated , giving a tickle on the tongue .

appearance : pours a deep black with hints of red and a thick beige head that will not dissipate . this is one of the most enticing beers that i have ever seen .  medium feel in my mouth with good carbonation .

smell is immensely yeasty with hints of clove , orange , and vanilla . decent nose if you ask me .  m : medium body , low to medium carbonation . smooth and creamy . d : something does n't quite work for me .

the smell was so pungent i could smell it a foot and a half away , which was great . this beer was a great pleasure both to see and smell . taste : immediate bitterness that is the mainstay throughout the beer . perhaps , the appearance and smell had me too excited , but i was somehat dissappointed in the taste .  mouthfeel : really thick and chewy . this part would be enjoyable in a good-tasting brew .
pours a great deep amber color with a thick bubbly off white head .  it had a really good mouthfeel .

overall the aroma is very nice . first sip , small tingly carbonation and average body . flavor is much less complex and rich than the nose advertised. , some toffee and fruit followed by a very clean yet somewhat empty finish .  m- medium in body and good carbonation .
appearance is very much like celebration . orangish amber color with a very nice head - great retention , lots of lacing .  mouthfeel - nice body , pretty crisp .
smell is delicious ; porter , plus chocolate , plus raspberry . highly encouraging . so wonderful up front , so nasty in the back .  the carbonation feels pretty crisp .

brilliantly clear light goldenrod , forming a large meringue-like rocky white head with excellent retention and gorgeous lacing .  mouthfeel is fine . medium bodied with the right amount of carbonation .

a- black beer into ayinger glass , huge head with infinite retention , probably 4 fingers on average . nice light mocha color and a ton of lace everywhere .  syrupu sweetness , not cloying , with hop dryness in the blend . this is what imperial pilsner is supposed to be ? what happened to the pilsner part ?

; save water , shower with a friend . i got a full , finger 's worth of deep brown head with good retention . color was a deep , dark brown with ruby highlights and ne-quality clarity .  mouthfeel is light bodied with good carbonation .
looks pretty damn nice .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied . fair carbonation .

pours a lovely , crystal clear dark amber color with a nice 1/2 '' tan head that persists all the way down , coating the entire glass with heavy lacing . the best looking ipa i 've ever seen .  saccharine all the way . how can you add fake sweetener to bier ? the beer is best described as diet raspberry 7 up . i already go to the gym 4 times a week so that i can drink all the fabulous beer i desire . flavors were overwhelmingly sweet , and tart . complexion was shirley temple , and body was crisp .

smell - a wonderful yeast or dough or wheat smell dominates , with orange or another citrus fruit tagging along . irresistibly smooth finish , tastes much the way it smells although the wheat is less noticeable .  m : very nicely carbonated for this type of beer .

well , i like meantime , and michael jackson knew his stuff , so pretty high expecations on this one ... into the two bros pint ... a - nice looking , great sized head , very rocky and attractive . s - the kent goldings make a big impact on the aroma .  oily mouthfeel with next to no carbonation . quite thick and heavy , coating every area of the mouth .
massive head over clear copper liquid .  it 's still fairly sturdy though , and carbonation is low but solid .

this is a beer you have once or twice and then just get it as the `` exotic '' for your gf to help justify the stuff you bought for yourself . pours a light pinkish-amber with a very very light pink fluffy head that faded quickly . if you like strawberries , which i do very much , then the smell and taste will immediately remind you of something more likely to be served at an orange julius or other shake/juice mixer .  very tame malt , very little hops , and weak alcohol that 's more like aftershave . definitely not over-carbonated , the texture fits the style . actually the best element of this beer .
a pint of the black stuff , or the priest , looks as good as ever , enjoyable to watch it settle over a minute or so .  mouthfeel : trademark lager crispness and smoothness , light bodied and dry .
bear republic tribute ale is a very clear , very lively , deep crimson brown berr with a huge , lumpy , beige head .  m - pretty thin and definitely refreshing .
pours a two finger cream head that fades slowly , leaving a good lace . nice deep amber color .  flavor was very strong ginger , and this made the mouthfeel quite crisp and pretty good .

pours a clear amber color with a creamy off white tannacios head that leaves great lacing .  smells sour , big nodes of orange and very tart lemon juice . there 's a bit of a funky hop in there , as well . no real spice of which to speak , nor any hint of wheat . very sour , almost cidery . starts more tart , like lemon juice , moves into a dryer , white wine middle , and ending on a more of a light , semi-sweet orange sour . a unique beer , to say the least . could benefit from a bit of something at the end , but is drinkable enough as it is .

lovely , bright cherry red color ... head is large at first , simmers down quickly ... aroma : mmmmm ... .complex ! quite a rich and invigorating aroma , i postpone consumption to prolong my time drinking it deep into the nose ... really nice !  mouthfeel : medium thickness , almost chewy , minimal froth .
a : pale clear amber , it poured with a big cream head with lacing that slowly died .  m - great carbonation , finishes well .
served in a sam adams bl glass , the beer pours a clear copper color with a half-inch off-white head . head retention and lacing is very good .  adequate carbonation .

this is a seriously complex nose , just tons going on ... fruits , mainly peach , some pineapple ? certainly lemon , white grape , sure , some white pepper , dry lemon rind , citrus , gosh ... it goes on and on and on ... certainly some funk and wildness , dry white wine ... yeah , this is hard to pin down and extremely academic , enjoyable , and all around good . t. follows , lots of dry white wine , peachy , semi-sweet , spicy , earthy , some tire , champagne , peach again , no real hop , dry , wild , funky , lemon-citric , seriously interesting , challenging , to be sure , but i am digging it . fun to try and get your palate around . d. not really , this is something to share and comment on , and take your time with .  char davies , the artist in 1998 , made a fully interactive immersive visual/aural virtual artwork called ephemere , which furthers the work begun in osmose started in 1995 and displayed in the national gallery of canada in ottawa on june 26 , 1998. who cares ? this beer is almost close to a champaign ( and i would think that the yeast probably is champaign ) . also there is bitterness , which is nice to know that at least there are some hops to the so called beer . it is not advisable to use apples with fermenting , as the yeast creates funky flavors from apples , but this is much better than expected . although i would not want to drink this beer on a regular bases , thus low score on drinkability , i think it has a great taste like a grandsmith apples i use to eat as a kid .

( a great place ) poured a wonderfully rich yellow color . it was cloudy with a half inch of creamy white head . nice lacing with this beer .  the mouth-feel is thick almost porter-like with the cooling of the alcohol evaporation .

and lists it as a strong pale ale aroma : grapefruit flowers on a sugary base . mouthfeel : medium body , a bit oily overall impression : nice and easy , a bit boring maybe , but thats more about me than the beer .  mouthfeel was good and very drinkable ; however , it was slightly bitter ... something i was n't expecting this to have considering the malts .
pours an opaque black with tight tan head .  the drink is carbonated a little more than average as well . mf- very crisp beer with little or no after taste . one of the smoother beers around .

bottle states brewed on the banks of the mighty st. vrain bottled on date printed on the label 09/12/07 , drank 11/16/07 poured from a bottle into a pint glass nice two fingers of foam billowy and thick , lacing all the way to the finish . the mouthfeel was on the thin side with a tad too much carbonation for my liking overall this beer very solid style wise , it would make a good session beer , but i was turned off by the high carbonation and thin mouthfeel .  mouthfeel was smooth , light , though i do n't know i 'd go as far as crisp .
as black as an overcast night in the woods with no light . thick creamy , milky , tan head .  m : it has a nice mouthfeel .
a- this one pours out a beautiful dark ruby red colored body with a small tightly knit finger of foam .  m - crisp and refreshing o - overall pretty meh .

appearance : black in color sporting a two finger creamy head that lasted a long time .  mouthfeel is light ( duh ) , but not too thin , and nicely carbonated , giving it a bit of a zip , but not too effervescent . probably the best part of the beer .
a - a mildly assertive pour yields a bubbly two-finger head with decent retention and frothy lacing down the glass . really a nice looking beer .  good carbonation .

a- clear dark reddish copper hue with a billowy tan head that last forever and leaves tons of sticky lacing on the glass . edit : holy shit , this beer is so hoppy it turns your tongue yellow !  the mouth is thick and malty . as far as drinkability , i have to say that i would be really happy to have one of these if i was alive 4000 years ago but for now i 'm going to have to go for something else .
a : this pours a lovely cloudy golden/orange color . a huge foamy head forms and leaves tons of sticky lace down my snifter .  body is light and crisp and finishes clean .
a nice amber color with a thick tan head . lace was thick and copious .  medium mouthfeel .

a -- pours thick with pitch black color and a dark one finger head in my snifter . m -- the pour looked thick but it obviously was an illusion because this is watery and leaves a gross aftertaste d -- hugely let down by this beer , might have to drain pour it because of the aftertaste .  very smooth without being too full bodied .

s- very delicate yet strong lemony aroma . t- great yeast character elevates the otherwise bland hop/malt balance to something very enjoyable . m- very smooth yet light .  mouthfeel is crisp and a little sizzly . refreshingly light bodied and clean .

a- pours a deep oily black with a three finger tall foamy brown head that has incredible retention ( after 5 minutes there 's still a finger worth left ) .  full body , syrupy like samichlaus . very similar tastes and mouthfeel .
pours a rich brown color with a large froth of dense , creamy head . retention is good , but lacing is downright gorgeous .  m/d ) very soft mouthfeel .

the aroma is very nice , it smells like pine and citrusy hops , pepper ( spice ) , strawberries , bready malt and just an overall hoppy and fruity smell . it smells very nice , and the aroma is n't overpowering .  there 's also just a hint of citrus from the orange peel ( or orange oil extract ) the smooth mouthfeel and moderate body is not unlike that of a german hefeweizen .

poured this 12 ounce gem into a british pint glass and really enjoyed this smooth stout jet black appearance with 2 fingers of foamy tan colored head and retention ; this brew looks perfect , and staring at that glass rekindles an image of a british pub aroma of a sweet , biscuitty , and dark chocolate notes rich , full bodied , toasty malt , balanced with some hops which accentuate the side of my tongue , and a finish with a bit of zing that lingers on the palate .  m - a fairly heavy mouthfeel with all the sweetness .

s - smells very inviting ! full of citrusy hop aromas ( pineapple , grapefruit , and orange ) and some pine scents as well . t - taste is different than expected . d - moderately drinkable - it would be nice if the malt flavors competed a little more with the hops to help balance it a little .  mouthfeel : soft creaminess , light to medium carbonation , with a medium to full body .
the beer poured into the glass crystal clear medium maber with an off-white frothy head which lasted to lace the glass .  m - crisp and decent carbonation .
s : big chocolate aroma , oak , vanilla and some booze . t : wow !  good body and mouthfeel .

exceptional appearance with enormous meringue-like dark brown head , opaque black body , and gobs of lace as the beer goes down .  light-medium caramel malt sweetness up front , continued in the middle with a hint of earthy hop bitterness , finishing with a more of the same . medium mouthfeel .

the aroma is nothing short of amazing . it immediately presents with big raisin , molasses , strawberry , and bubblegum . i have had most of the unibroue beers , but this was really outstanding even for them .  the mouthfeel is very smooth , with fine/sharp bubbles .

reminded me of candied yams on thanksgiving . almost no hops were detectable and the alcohol was hidden nicely . t : first sip was scrumptious , showcasing much of what i just smelled . unfortunately , as the drinks went by , so did the complexity .  mouthfeel - good smoothness , a medium body on par with the style , crisply carbonated .

i smell a fruity and floral characteristic along with a strong citrusy hop overtone . this is a classic ipa and the brewers knew what they were doing with this batch .  m- really good carbonation , low abv and the nearly great sweet/tart balance make it actually react quite nicely with the mouth .

pours a dark brown with hints of red at the edges , crackling four finger light tan head settles to a finger tall , and remains all the way through , leaves temporary sheets of lacing that fade ( probably due to the abv ) .  light body and nice and creamy . moderate carbonation .
aroma is very enticing-sweet caramel malts and fresh bread dough dominating along with some flowery and piney notes .  mouthfeel is creamy and crisp .

the smell is as excepted sweet and more sweet . hints of flowers and something a bit citrusy . wow ! the taste is sooo much bigger than the smell and really does n't do it justice .  the mouthfeel is moderately thick and full for a pilsner and has a creamy texture . the citrusy hops create a crisp bite towards the end .
a : very lively , clear , beautiful orange/light amber color , borderline perfect head .  this is a medium bodied , well carbonated beer .

caramel and prune or fig in the aroma . lots of malty sweetness in the flavor , along with sticky fruit , but there is a graininess that is a bit astringent in there as well , though very minute . this is a pretty good beer , excepting the tiny bit of astringency .  the body is nice and thick , with a flavorful malt profile : sweet medium caramel malts with a bit of roast character . hops , by the way , are almost nonexistent , which would n't be bad if not for the oxidation , which makes the faint floral flavor seem dull . overall not bad , but has the same type of oxidized or maybe just oversparged flavor common to other corporate breweries like gordon-biersch .

very sexy . s - great smell , definitely get a heavy does of burnt chocolate , some roasted coffee and other malts . great example of roasted scents . i would gauge that there was a spectacular effort put into tempering this brew to get these scents from the malts . i like sours but certainly not mixed with this style . very bitter as you will note from almost every review but this one had an almost sour milk character that turned me off during my dinner which was centered around beef .  the body is somewhere between medium and full , with a creamy mouthfeel .

nutty aroma with lots of caramel , hay and oats seem to scream out at me .  the body is on the full side , though not quite as much as most stouts ( i suppose increased attenuation should have been expected with the switch in yeast strain ) , and has a solidly low key carbonation .
pours near black with tan head .  m - solid and full , with good carbonation .

smell : the smell is a wonderful mix of rich malts and strong , powerfully complex hops that are almost perfectly balanced . perhaps this flying dog may stand the test ... taste and mouthfeel : the taste is not as good as expected , but still not bad . drinkability and overall : this beer is just a tiny bit above the average ipa , but definitly nothing too seek out .  the aftertaste lingers nicely , and the mouthfeel is firm . full bodied and smooth , but lacking an extra punch .

great black appearance with cascade of bubbles when poured that lasted a minute , leaving 1/2 inch tan head that stayed until the glass was empty .  a - opaque black color with a small head that disappears quickly s - rich chocolate-like aroma , mild yeast esters , some smokiness , no hop perceived t - roasted malt flavor dominates , some yeasty esters and mild hop flavors take a secondary role , very gentle mild hop finish with some lingering smokiness m - smooth creamy medium body with moderately low carbonation d - this is a decent enough oatmeal stout . the head and retention is disappointing , but the smell , taste and mouthfeel are acceptable .

the smell was very promising with wonderful aromas of sweet , bready malt with banana , clove , and a banana bread finish .  mouthfeel was nice - weizenbock like . bananas , black beans , chile peppers and/or pepper jack cheese with some creamyness amidst the carbonation . interesting , no doubt , and worth seeking out if you want something really different .

the aroma is full on citrus hops . love it . the flavor is much more balanced than the nose . the citrus blast is there but the malt `` grinds '' away at it . overall another great beer from surly .  the mouthfeel is very light bodied and good for the class .

pours a dark cola brown with hints of plum . finger of cake like head leaves small islands of lace down the side of the leffe chalice .  mouthfeel good . creamy and subtle carbonation . cant complain about this .

`` the cheeky ale '' pours out a beautiful reddish and slighly brown amber with a tan head .  the mouthfeel was good , but the drinkability hass to be chopped down due to the smell and the taste of this beer .

the appearance is the epitimy of excellence . huge mountainous head supported by sunshine golden body , medium carbonation , tons of rocky , chunky lacing left behind only to be washed away with the high alcohol gobbles .  mouth is no complaints , it 's low-medium body with relatively high carbonation .
s : the nose is awesome . coffee . just so much going on .  soft prickly carbonation does cleans the pallet , of this light to medium body beer with moderate astringency and warming alcohol .
overly sweet at times , but still nice . if it was n't for the mild astringent smell i 'd give it a 5 .  m : creamy and sticks to the mouth for awhile .
it pours a decently frothy tan colored head .  m - it was very crisp and sharp .
pours a nice dark brown/black with a quarter inch head , typical for founders stuff .  medium mouhfeel with some carbonation . smooth and buttery feel . pretty dry finish .
the smell is of malty blueberries , you will not be disappointed .  the mouth is pretty nice , feels rich but easy to drink .

i love the appearence of this beer , the deep dark color and the nice tan foamy head make for an inviting glass .  m - tongue ripping bitterness . medium to full body and tingly carbonation to go with it . good .

smell is the leader of the pack , amazing scent of coffee , cream , smoke . drinkability suffers from the mouthfeel since this is the only non style rating , but i really like this porter .  taste is mild but the mouthfeel is full pleasantly full and quite nice .
pours a very lovely rich golden color with a creamy white head that clings to the sides of the glass as you drink .  mouthfeel : full-bodied with a strong , expressive carbonation .

pours an opaque brown with a khaki head that never seems to leave the beer . you can slightly see carbonation bubbles when you bring the glass to the light . very nice lacing .  light body with good carbonation .

pours with a deep red-brown body topped by a medium thick lasting head with good lace .  bottled under license by the cheval blanc in montreal . light golden ale witha medium head that did not disapear too quickly . the honey taste is very discreet . i could recognize the usual taste of malt from the cheval blanc . enjoyable but not exceptionnal

smells like ... .oranges ! ! ! fresh , ripe oranges . tart , citrusy oranges . the beer has strong carbonation , a bit much for my liking ... .almost soda-like in the most extreme case . hints honey at times . needless to say , great pick for hot weather .  m - pretty thick , smooth and a bit refreshing .
excellent lacing and a fully lasting head .  nice lively mouthfeel .

a : pours a cloudy , medium brown color with two fingers of billowy , pale tan head . exceptional retention and lace , vigorous carbonation .  ) and is a deep rich molasses s : once again , may have been too cold for phenols to waft up t : slightly sweet really tasty m : nice and cold d : pour me another

this beer reminded me an awful lot of duvel , but niot quite as good . poured to a highly carbonated golden yellow , with thick pilowy white head that lasted the entire beer , and left excellent lacing .  the mouthfeel is good ; slightly thick and very smooth . however , it is a little bubble and will sting the recesses of your mouth .

a : beautiful beer ! it 's a perfectly clear light amber color topped by a big-bubble , thin but foamy head . lacing is alright , but the beer looks so good it makes up for that in other areas .  m : smooth and medium bodied .

absolutely amazing grapefruit , lemon , and orange aroma . also has a touch of sweet toffee and vanilla . this was a beautiful hazy golden pour , with typical cask frothy head . very well balanced flavor , then a wonderful dry bitter finish . this is an amazing brew , and the cask only adds to it .  m : a nice , medium body .

ale here in western ny so quickly.my second time trying this new black ipa style of beer my first being rogue black brutal wich i had mixed feelings about , this poured a deep dark brown but not black some ruby colored highlights thruought a thick 2 finger head atop that never completely settled just a fantastic creamy mass left with gobs of lace behind in my impy pint glass , just awesome.mix of piney and tropical fruit hops and black malt in the nose mainly i picked up some pineapple and molasses wich was nice and it strayed away from the one dimensional resiny hop profile and caramel malt base.the hops are big but so is the black malt element of this beer sure its big and piney and citrusy but the dark bread and molasses in there is large as well in finely balanced that black malt character really shows itself.the alcohol creeps a bit but this is a very interesting brew it has it all big hops and some malty sweetness , another top notch brew form one of the best .  it is medium bodied and smooth in the mouth .

the aroma was fruity , but not overwhelmingly so . the carbonation tickled my tongue carrying on the light fruity taste and something else , a slight sour aftertaste i could n't identify . the body was light , not like the chewy trappists dubbels and quads i love . a little more pepper a little less sour , but not as generally pleasing as i 'd hoped .  served in a pint glass mug a : pours a clear bronze color with about an inch of thick head s : a smell provides a nice rye scent with a very sweet undertone contributed by the honey addition t : very nice smooth tasting beer , has a slight hint of honey and perhaps a slight rye note but other than that there isnt much to comment on , smooth and slightly sweet but thats about it m : very smooth in the mouth with a slight bite on the tongue as it is drank d : high level of drinkability , very subdued taste that is great for a hot summer day but leaves the drinking looking for more otherwise .
aroma : very complex . banana , clove , butter , bubblegum , and hints of alcohol .  medium mouthfeel .
smells of coffee and also some sweet chocolate .  mouthfeel is nice , actually - light bodied , spritzy carbonation .
bottle : poured a deep pitch-black stout with a motor oil consistency and a small foamy head with good retention and some lacing .  velvety . good amount of carbonation .
a-pours a really attractive hazed-out , bright orange with a firm and lasting two inch , bone white head that brought about nice sticky ribbons of lace .  good carbonation .
great color , substantial head on pour . beautiful appearance .  m- decent carbonation , light and airy .

the first thing i noticed about this beer was the strong and wonderful flower aroma . quite spicy and with a very strong odor of coriander . quite a nice smelling saison in the same class as hennepin .  could be a bit less carbonated .

very aromatic . t : consistently bitter from start to finish , but not overwhelmingly so . i love the scent and the hop flavors , and i can see why this beer is very appealing to others ... but it 's just not my thing .  m : felt good going down had a nice thick feel to it .
a- looks awesome . pours a crytal clear light brassy orange , with a massive white oamy , fluffy head that slowly shrinks down leaving behind all kinds of webbing lace .  mouthfeel is pretty good .
poured - beautiful dark color .  all right taste , almost neutral , with a bit of skunkiness . goes down very smoothly .
the nose was sweet , dominated by roasted malts , chocolate , treacle and burnt toffee , very pleasant indeed .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel was pretty good overall .

smell is dominant dark fruit ( plum and fig ) with just hints of chocolate cake , cherries , and that leather smell . very complex . there is a dark smooth malt character and some caramel as well . i could smell this all day . taste is the nose , followed by a whiff of smoke and finishing like a rich deep red wine . my brother commented that he picked up on dr. pepper like qualities . caramel malt . mouthfeel was oily and clingy . drinkability : i know it 's a great beer but for me drinkability was just ok .  i 'm not sure what a `` baltic '' porter is supposed to taste like ; but this one is quite different from most porters i 've had . sweet molasses aroma that is greater than any chocolate or mocha that might be found . a strong level of metal present also . sweet , almost like brandy . reminds me far more of a double bock than a porter . i can not detect any hops at all . too sweet for me , making it more one-dimensional without any complexity .
a beautiful deep amber with ruby and copper hues . frothy white head with superb retention and lacing down the glass .  decent carbonation , neither too intrusive nor too laid back .
excellent , excellent , excellent bottle condition , hazy , champagne head pour .  m- medium bodied with a decent carbonation level .

poured a solid black , even when i held my led flashlight up behind it , with about an inch of thick , sturdy light brown head that had great retention and moderate lacing .  m/d : a medium body with good carbonation .
d - the smell is excellent , the rest is mediocre .  the mouthfeel is slightly creamy and very enjoyable . this drinks nicely . there is a lot going for this though , the mouthfeel in particular .

the appearance is a deep coffee color , heading almost to burgundy . the light tan head is large and resistant , preventing me from quickly getting into it .  it had a medium bodied with good carbonation .
pours an opaque , oil-slick jet black with a big , durable tan head that never completely goes away .  feels right in body , but the taste is just off .
a-bronze and brilliantly clear . huge eggshell head .  m : pretty creamy and lightly carbonated . easy to swallow a mouthful .

aroma is dark , malty , and seductive . roasty sweet malts , golden raisins , dried fruit , scorched caramel , and bittersweet dry cocoa are rounded out by musty yeast notes similar to damp concrete .  m : good mouthfeel .

appearance : pours a beautiful hazy dark amber color with a finger of foamy off white head that leaves a little bit of lacing and good retention .  being of fan of bocks , i was fully prepared to love this ubiquitous doppelbock . it was kind of sweet and malty , smelled great , felt nice going down -- quite satisfying . there was a slightly funky smell to it , and an even funkier taste . i thought that was more common in highly hopped beers . at $ 10 for the four pack , i hate to try it again for fear of wasting my hard-earned beer money .

it had a wonderful , fruity , rich , creamy , almost cherry ice cream soda type of aroma.the first mouthful had a cherry , hoppytaste with a very smooth mouthfeel.then a very bitter backtaste made itself evident . definitely a slow sipping brew .  this beer has noticeable viscosity and a big thick feel . minimal carbonation .

the aroma is wonderful . it is dark and roasty , yet with a sweet chocolaty undertone , along with a slight hint of anise . the alcohol is n't quite as well masked as the aroma indicated , and there is some decent hop bitterness throughout .  t : slight sweet taste , but does not taste much like anything actually , fairly bland m : smooth , light on carbonation . d : mouthfeel was nice , went down easily enough just did n't care for the smell or taste of the beer .

( a ) - pours a clear golden yellow/orange color that produced a huge foamy/fluffy white head with great retention .  recommended by bert from bert 's better beers . smells like dark chocolate , burn caramel , and vanilla -- sort of like an chocolate chip oatmeal cookie . smooth roast malt , dare i say a tad burnt . there 's a mild pharmaceutical character in back that i 'm not a fan of . i drank half this bottle one night and the second half the following afternoon .

this is a light caramel colored beer . the smell of this bear makes me eager to drink it . it 's a combination of peach , apricot , and orange . this is a nice light ( in color and mouthfeel ) beer that will be great going into spring .  m - lighter side of heavy , pretty smooth .
in honor of the black wych appearance - dark . black . dark as the light on a moonless night .  medium mouthfeel .

pretty well on track with many of the other belgians i have had . obviously its carefully produced with natural ingredients from the taste and it looks great .  m - full bodied and chewy with a moderately dry finish with some alcohol noticeable .
pours black with a long lasting brown head that leaves plenty of lacing .  pleasantly carbonated on the palate , with a dry finish .

see-thru burnt orange body with a huge frothy head . excellent retention and plentiful lacing .  the flavor is a bit better as the taste of both a good belgian tripple and a solid ipa can both be percieved ; however , the flavors compete for dominance instead of blending harmoniously . i think the problem here is that tripple is a big , expressinve beer . with exit 4 the subtle flavors are masked behind a second layer of bold expressiveness . i love the brewery for pushing the envelope and i look forward to buying the next release in the series . with innovation like this , flying fish is sure to hit a huge winner sooner than later .

this smelled like freshly ground coffee , chocolate , muffins , brownies , and finished with a roasted woodsy character . wow . i want to dip my whole face in this beer .  m=fairly thin , a little medium . watery .

a-pours a cloudy orange ... i 'm docking points because pilsner 's should have good clarity ... also excessive head ... s-outstanding aroma ... spicy , floral and somewhat fruity ... very inviting and the type of beer you could sit and smell all day long . but i found it an exciting , and tasting brew ... .one of the best smelling beers i have ever experienced .  body is extremely light and spritzy ; refreshing and very inoffensive in character .

s : super hoppy . i love it . t : i 'm having trouble believing this is a barleywine . i know american bws are supposed to be hoppy but hot damn is this awesome . destroys your palate with an intense amount of hops .  the mouthfeel is medium-light bodied with a watery texture , and a little too much carbonation .

s - heavy red wine , oak characteristics and obviously a brett brew t - follows the smell , close your eyes and you might be deceived that you are n't drinking a beer almost .  a bit bland for the style . body is a bit like soda water , and fades really fast .

s- smell is awesome . tons of tropical fruits pineapple , apricot , and grapefruit a bit of sweetness coming through from the malts . t- follows the nose really well . a very nice hop forward beer .  lack of carbonation , and this beer 's thin , watery mouthfeel combine to make a less-than-awesome drinking experience .

the nose is very complex , a mix of fruity , spicy , earthy and oaky tones . black licorice or anise also comes to mind . there is also a drying , acrid presence . drinkability of this one is lowered by the fact that i do n't really enjoy this old ale . i was really excited when i opened the bottle and i feel let down .  the carbonation sort of ruins the mouthfeel from the can and hides the taste .

22oz bomber into pint glass a nearly white head disappeared quickly , no lacing , hazy golden orange amber gives a nice appearance 3.5 s a really good apricot scent dominates its aroma you pour your glass 4.5 t apricot takes the lead on the flavor but there are sweet bread and grains now also .  m : thin and watery , very little carbonation , too thin to be cloying , but i 'd rather this beer be full bodied .

it smells awesome , everything works together and you get something else every whiff no issues here t much more booze then the nose , more toffee , smoke , and fruit with some burnt brown sugar , still very nice but without as much balance m enters silky then the bubbles make it feel creamy , quite thick and the flavors linger , the heat lingers too and that 's my only complaint in this area o for a big fresh barley wine i thought it was pretty good , the barrel agings there but not overpowering and its oh so mellow i was hoping this one would suck so i would n't need to buy a couple of them to age , pretty expensive but this would be amazing after some time , pretty mellow considering the 13.8 % fresh i can only imagine this 5 years down the road  was excited to see this one.. but again newcastle has let me down again ... on the bottle it says `` blood red ale '' .. it pours a reddish-brown color.. smells a little funky ... way too carbonated for my liking .
