smells robust with citrusy hops , orange peel and pine . medium bodied and a bit watery at first which is subsequently overcome by a good balance of hops .  carbonation a bit high . fails on this point . d- easy going macro lager .

really great smell on it . can definitely smell the hops coming out . lots of earthy , dirty , grittiness to it .  the most negative parts of this beer include the smell and mouthfeel . the smell is pretty bland , not giving any info on the beer itself and the mouthfeel seems watered down after witnessing the color of the beer .
s : very fruity , dark fruits ( raisins , plumbs ) and malts . t : very fruity , specifically raisins .  3.0 m thin .

smells great . big , overripe tropical fruit and citrus with a little bit of grass underneath . i actually coughed and spilled some while pouring and thought , `` man , that smells awesome ! '' while cleaning it up . still good , just a letdown after the nose .  the flavor was both too light and 'way too bitter for a pils . it was watery and lacking in aroma . not much foam - what there was disappeared quickly . the word i 'd use to describe this beer is `` insubstantial . ''
smell : smells like a nice rich coffee from sbux with tons of caramel added .  m : thin , watery , light-bodied , not something you 'd expect with the smell .
this brew has a delicious smell of peanut brittle and roasted malts .  m : water thin , light side of champagne-like carbonation .

i prefered the tap version as the apricots were so intense in the aroma as the bottle had more funk and barnyard . apricot , lemon and peach flavors . moderate acidity for a cantillon . the palate could be drier and the carbonation more lively but this a stellar offering by cantillon once again .  mouthfeel was light in body and watery in texture with a fizzy carbonation .

the aroma was simply outstanding . i have tried a number of the best coffee beers but none even came close to the nose on this one . pure and simple . every time i smelled this , i imagined myself walking into a coffee shop . the flavor profile was not quite as coffee heavy as the nose , but it was indeed more complex . malty rich up front .  caramel , coffee and cocoa are there , but overall balance is towards the dry and bitter mouthfeel - 2.0 lightly carbonated , bordering on flat and a little watery .

it has the wonderful spicy aroma that the style should always have . slight phenols , cloves , a sweet bready malt and a beautiful underlying fruitiness are all there . it finishes very very clean and does n't linger at all .  m - light bodied , very thin feeling , and very little carbonation o - not too impressed with this beer .
smell is downright incredible , with lots of oily hops , citrus , and a complexity i ca n't describe .  mouthfeel on both is not much , just clear water with a bit of beer bubbles .
huge tropical fruit aromas on this one -- passion fruit , mango , pineapple and bubble gum . creamy , with a good warming alcohol finish .  mouthfeel is similar to that of water , not much to it .

m- thick and oily , slick and refreshing . d- very tart and complex flavor combination of hops .  mouthfeel : thin and watery ( or slim-bodied , which sounds more positive ) , medium-low carbonation ( too low for the style ) .
aroma is pungent with grapefruit , sharp citric hops , with cloaked , faint suggestions of oranges , apples , and toasty grains .  the body was light and very watery .

amazingly strong - smells of syrupy semi-sweet chocolate and very deep roasty and toasty malts ; smells like very fresh brewed espresso ... actually , the `` freshness '' of the smell is really quite intense . taste : very burnt and roasty malt characteristics that are reminiscent of fresh brewed espresso and grounds ; faint flavors of semi-sweet baking chocolate ; i have to admit , this would be an amazing morning drink .  perhaps age will remedy.. m : explosive mouthfeel upon drinking , but the body is very light , with the alcohol evident .
very good . t - starts out quite fruity , sweet and tart with heavy notes of strawberries .  m : this was the most dissapointing . aside from the lingering dry finish this was a very thin porter .
ahhh , nice smoke on the nose ! i love smoke beers and i was really hoping this would have some campfire nose and it does .  mouthfeel : pretty thin , with sharp carbonation and a watery finish .

aroma : an amazing , complex aroma which far exceeds any other pils aroma i have smelled . lemony , peppery , summery , yeasty and malty all zipping around my nose . taste : does n't live up to the aroma but is n't bad .  m- thin highly carbonated .

smells great ! you go the same whitepepper honey spice wheatishness of duvel only with a wonderfully crisp , weedy background . tastes very nearly as good as it smells . big nodes of weeds , pollen , and wild flowers backing up a spicy , crisp , lightly lemony belgian pale .  couple hints of charcoal & burnt toast - but just hints the whole bottle was thin and watery , and the harshness lasted throughout .
nose is roasty malts , campfire smoke , and sweet chocolate cookies . mmm .  the mouthfeel is syrupy and shows none of the carbonation that the pour hinted at .

s - prominent citrus hops , mostly orange , with some floral , and a nice , strong , sweet caramel malt undertone . t - hop flavors again with grapefruit and pine .  the mouth is super thin . the thinnest mouth i 've ever had on an ipa . d= the thin mouth makes me go for sips more often and the flavor does n't linger long ... great flavor on this one no doubt .
the smell is wonderful , but what happened in the translation to taste ?  3.0 m too thin for my taste and my experience with better scottish ales ( like oskar blues ) .
s- it almost smells like a hoppier bock with plum and some chocolaty malt aromas .  really thin for an imperial stout .

aroma was outstanding . rich and full with dry , whole grain oats and sweet , cereal-like notes ( kind of like sticking your nose in a box of quaker oats ) . drinkability however was quite good .  very complex and interesting m : disappointing ! very thin for a barley wine .
smell : lemon and muscat grapes . smells very sweet and potent . probably honey or even clover honey .  m - thin , watery , overly carbonated .

750ml bottle ( cork & cage always cool ) purchased at carmel mtn . fruit in the nose , sweet apricot perhaps . slightly musty , too .  mouthfeel/ drinkability : the carbonation isnt stinging and seems appropriate . the body of the beer seems far too thin .

location cellar 70 serving 22oz the scent of this piva is spot on and really is inviting . i have n't had any other coffee stouts , so i am by far means an expert .  feels very watery , not overly carbonated , but bubbles hard in your stomach , not letting you drink too many of these .

smells like delicious ginger snaps , cinnamon and some clove . delicious . it has a medium body with a good amount of carbonation . definitely a sipper , but a very good sipper .  the problem is that the beverage is thin and flat on the palate and leaves a really unpleasant metallic aftertaste .

smell : varies as it warms : bacon , chocolate , hickory , raisin , wood and more ... taste : dope .  no attempt whatsoever to hide the alcohol and the addition of the heavy acidic espresso taste and a watery mouthfeel make this hard to down .

the aroma is phenominal . funky , yeasty , wet wood , barn yard , and sour lemons and oranges .  a - medium to dark amber ; almost no head , but what little bubbling there was at the edge of the glass managed to leave a slight bit of lacing s - there was nearly no aroma , and what was there was nothing distinctive t - good malt/hop balance with pleasantly surprising bitter finish m - far too thin and too little carbonation in this sample ; a bit of a sticky finish d - though it will not be mistaken for a world-class brew , this one is easy to suck down since it is thin and flavorful ; without the sticky finish , it would score a half-tick higher
really interesting .  m - light and fizzy , thin bodied .

there 's even some odd sediment that almost looks like it belongs in hot & sour soup . the aroma is welcoming though - deep , filling , and robust with mocha goodness . the combination of malted barley and coffee hide the barely noticeable smell of alcohol . the taste is also very robust - nearly syrupy without carbonation , but still good .  mouthfeel is painfully carbonated . light bodied , way way to much carbonation .

aroma : lush and full of fruit , beautiful and deliriously deep , slightly spicy , with further fruity develops , cherries and berries , but burnt . juicy hops and rich malt jump out through the nose , a perfect barleywine bouquet .  the mouthfeel is surprisingly flat .

smells rich and sweet with a nice peaty smokiness to it . overall it 's nice .  flavor is rather plain , roasty , sweet , a bit of coffee and coco , the hops seem to be hiding somewhere , i detect little to none , little carbonation , short finish , with a bit of dark bread , and rasins , very thin body.drinkable but not very memoriable .

smell is very strong , like a clove-orange christmas pomander . really spicey and orange-peely , with coriander , grass and soap . if this thing tastes as good as it smells , i 'm gon na love it . the taste is dominated by the clove , soap and cookie-dough malt . it tastes good , but not as good or as complex as it smells . alcohol is notable from the warm burn in the aftertaste . all around , a very interesting beer .  ( btw the mouthfeel matches ) .

the head is disappointing , only rising a little then gone right away ... the aroma is really dark fruits , raisins , caramel with a slight hop finish ... the taste is ok , does n't quite live up to a great quad though .  mouthfeel feels thin and weak ; this is my only real complaint with this beer .

it smells great t-comes in with grassy belgian malts and then belgian sugars that are fairly boozy and have a bitterness to them . i 'm not getting too many good hops in this .  flavor is of arange , and body is highly carbonated . prickly mouthfeel , and a bit boring overall

it was quite amazing . nice bitter coffee notes , with more chocolate notes and sweet malts than with the aroma . this was smelling great , drinking good and going down easy .  sweet crackery finish , m - thin with very low carbonation .

poured worthily into a duvel glass an orange amber with a thick white froth appearing and clinging nicely as a sip smelling of glorious flowery pine , dank indeed , bursts into bitter pine in the front of the mouth before cascading oily bubbles across just enough malt to save the day , without much abv burn , from what is otherwise a seriously bitter villain lacking a bit of nuance .  m : thin body with almost no carbonation at all .
smoked gouda cheese , which is one of my favorite cheeses , some peet smokiness , a bit of earthiness , and a little sourness .  mouthfeel : medium to light treading dangerously close to watery .

the nose is incredible as it is with many of de dolle beers . big floral esters , mint , lemon , sweet malts and subtle but detectable hops . amazing brew , perfect for summertime , actually this is drinkable anytime ... beware of the burps !  the body is very thin -- like there was a lot of adjuncts added .

smell is of bourbon barrels , alcohol and some deep plum and cherry/chocolate on the nose . taste follows with notes of the barrel and a very lingering close ... nice.. good feel and the drinkability is extravagant given the potency , as the alcohol is present on the nose but not on the tongue .  mouthfeel is very thin .
smell : good bold nose .  has a malty aroma , enticing , maybe some wheat too ? fizzy palate , mallty taste , fruity , not very lingering . thirst-quenching .

smell : super strong pine , grapefruit , and bitterness warns the tastebuds through the nose what is to come . taste : hearty caramel sweetness with a very strong and biting bitterenss .  m- spritzy , carbonation fills your mouth swelling your cheeks slightly . rough , bubbly and thin .

smell- the jasmine is def . present in the nose of this one , along with fruity , citrus , hop notes . taste/mouthfeel- starts out with a nice hop presence but then fades quickly drinkability- very easy drinking beer , having it with some food helps the overall taste of the beer too .  i picked up a carton of this pretty cheap the only downfall its in cans anyways it pours a golden amber see thru colour with nice carbonation that leaves a bubbly two finger head and sporadic lacing , the aroma is pretty macro with grains and a feint bubblegum aroma , it has a thin mouthfeel with a rather grainy taste and isnt nothing to write home about , its definately better than the macroswill that sells for much more and easier to down but its not a beer that i would drink if i wanted a nice beer with character .

s - pleasant pine ( blue spruce ) and orange pith citrus mesh with a faint peppery alcohol to create a truly delightful aroma . t - a bit of faint light malt with a sharp pine flavor .  i will admit that i did not like the mouthfeel very much . too bubbly .

exquisite critrusy , lemony aroma ; actually smells 'juicy ' . just amazing . flavour consists of traditional hefeweizen attributes with the addition of citrusy , american style hops .  the body was very thin and the beer lacked substance .
this beer smells amazing but its taste is over the top .  it tastes ok. kind of watered down . cant taste any malt or hops . it was too bubbly , seemed over-carbonated .

intense aroma of pumpkin , vanilla , brown sugar , and pie crust . sweet and malty , bursting with pumpkin flavour as well as vanilla , cookie dough , and an earthy bitterness in the finish . i like pumpkin beer , but only in small doses . considering this is like pumpkin beer on steroids , this was shockingly easy to drink . i was worried i would fatigue on it part way through , but there was no such problem .  the mouthfeel , as mentioned , is very watery and razor thin .

spicy aroma along with a vanilla-infused custard smell , nice .  m- this is precisely the opposite mouthfeel that i want . it feels like it wants to be sweet and sticky , but it really just falls watery on the tongue .

smell is strong and at first of piney , grassy , spicey hops with some citrus not all that different from an ipa . some caramellly and toffee smelling malt and a bit of booze hits the nose as well to differentiate it . taste at first is boozy . it is supported by the hops , but they are n't nearly as dominant as in the aroma . plenty of malt sweetness is there , but some fruit flavors appear as well . overall a very good beer , but it falls a bit below the expectations set by the aroma .  mouthfeel : very carbonated with a thin , almost watery feeling .
s- it smells of pumpkin pie very strong spices . t- it 's a very sweet beer .  thin , harsh , and astringent- the mouthfeel is where the beer suffers the most .

pour is a burnt gold or darkish amber with a foamy white head , but the aroma takes over immediately . smell reminds of an american barley wine . very rich and malty with tons of hops , it could pass for sn 's bigfoot .  not much to say about natural ice other than that it is cheap . little taste that i could discern , but nothing abhorrent at that . maybe some sweetness , a bit more complex than some of its stablemates . of course , it is highly drinkable , which is the point . pressed for cash and desirous of a little buzz ? you could definitely do worse .

s : as soon as i popped this one , i loved the smell of it . i was hoping after the great smell , it would have a taste i loved , but unfortunately not a taste that suits me .  a : it 's still carbonated , that 's something at least . too fizzy .

the brothers consistently nail aroma . bubblegum and tart cherry with moderate roasted qualities and a faint hint of wheat twang .  it actually smells more like a belgian dubbel . it does n't have much complexity and it drinks very watery . this is by far the thinnest quad i 've ever come across .
s - sweet hop delight . much stronger hop aroma than doppelbocks i have had before . earthy hop aroma with a very sweet scent as well .  the mouthfeel is watery with medium carbonation .

nose was erupting from the pour with plenty of darker malts , some dark wheats , a bit of a roasty and toasty aroma , a very slight chocolate , some dark fruits with a bit of fig , hint of booze , some toffee , and lots of dark wheat aromas . taste starts with darker wheats and malts again , a slight caramelized wheat flavor , some brown sugar and molasses , plenty of toffee , darker wheat flavors , a bit of a cola like syrup flavor but just a hint , some darker malts , roasted malts and some toasted malts , slight chocolate again , more fruits , fig and touch of a nutty flavor , hint of coffee , fairly complex , and even a hint of warming booze , that comes out a bit more on the finish but never heavy , very slightly sticky and hint of sweetness but dries slightly .  feel : active , assaulting carbonation and a light , watery body .

the aroma is pretty complex like any respectable barleywine , but definitely more on the malt side . brown sugar is obvious and is of pleasant company to figs , peaches , alcohol and an all-around complex fruitiness .  tasting it my first impression was how thin the body was for an english porter , compared to , for instance , the excellent fuller 's london porter or young 's double chocolate .

hard pour gets a beautiful head to rise up , just a little more than two fingers worth of off-white frothiness . smells phenomenal . a bouquet of citrus hops , with a little bit of floral and maybe piney for good measure . so nicely balanced , just a little bit of bitter and the rest is flavor . the alcohol would probably catch me a buzz after just a couple , but it certainly weighs in a little lower than some comparable ipas , which is nice .  not much at all going on except for some sweetness and a very slight bitterness that gives way to a watery finish . not the worst macro lager by any means .
very powerful sweet aroma . overall : fantastic beer , will definitely get again .  the body is thin and watery ; one hardly notices the beer until it is gone .

sweet and sugary , but delicious and unique . alcohol is absolutely brutal on this bitch as the heat slaps you in the face with the force of 10,000 fighting japanese midget minnow farmers .  mouthfeel is thin for the style .

at long last i was finally able to snag the great westy 12 , pours a deep brown with a suprisingly thin head that was gone pretty quickly not leaving anything behind.whoa the aromas are just incredibly complex and rich , some almond and raisin almost a cinnamon bun type aroma to it , just awesome.flavors are more mellow than expected , i get some star anice and raisin up front with some mellow orange tinge in the lngering finish.i like the `` 12 '' better than the `` 8 '' but i have had some better quads but still a pleasure to drink for sure .  the body of this is way too light for a porter .

s - sweet malt , candy , prune , marmalade t - sweet malt that very quickly becomes medicinal ( cough syrup ) and spicy m - low carbonation and syrupy with a neutral finish d - enjoyable flavors , but the medicinal taste is overbearing  m : taste was below average for me , but the mouthfeel is even worse . super thin . light carbonation and no body make this almost watery .
amazing smell ; right in line with what i expect from stone .  md - thin and not much of a body to it .
s - good smell , lots going on .  mouthfeel is boring and watery .

the beer is certainly lighter than i expected with an almost straw color . the nose on this brew is phenomenal ! i 'm immediately transported to magical grapefruit land as the beer screams citrus into my nostrils . there is a piney base note to this smell to that compliments the soaring citrus very well . not on hops of course , as the grapefruity citrus notes yielded to a piney bite on the finish , but rather the malt character . while still a world class ipa , i felt that the backbone of this brew just was n't quite as strong as i would have liked and the huge hop profile was almost overwhelming .  thin , watery mouthfeel .
smells of pine , oak , citrus , caramel , very sweet smelling ... tons of things going on . not bitter at all , just very very very sweet . its definitely a sipper .  body is thin and flat .

s : bold oaky qualites up front . big on the coffee as well . wow i wan na dive in . i drank the whole bomber but it was overtime . if the chocolate and vanilla can push thru a bit with time it will be a real winner .  the body is light and really deters the taste .

aroma definitely carries a strong banana smell to it with some clove in there as well . it smells like a hefeweizen for sure , but it 's categorized as a wit here . it starts out with a good banana presence , as was seen on the nose . no surprise there .  mouthfeel is thin for a ris , almost watery .
smell : damn this smells great . i 'm getting sugar coated rasperries , sweet malts , milk chocolate , and toffee .  mouthfeel is thin , almost no carbonation .
positives : great aroma of sweet chocolate .  mouthfeel is thin and syrupy .
this is probably the most impressive smelling amber style ale i have enjoyed .  the presence of tannin explains how , while quite watery , satan red is also quite drying .

aroma was very pleasing . deep and rotund hop nose is neither too flowering , too citrusy , and definitely stops shy of being too grassy . really a unique aroma , something that has become kind of rare these last few years .  tastes like someone put artificial flavoring in carbonated water .

aroma is huge apricot honey-butter you smell from across the room . amazing . super wowowowow . an incredible rich aroma : great smelling beer . taste is an underlying sweet walnut toffee with apricot honey-butter with a huge fruity citrus hop bitterness that lasts forever .  mouthfeel is almost cloying from the sweetness and really is the only category this beer suffers .

dark roasted malts , espresso , bitter chocolate , vanilla bean , and some black currant . very one dimensional with little complexity . you mainly get a big slap in the face of dark roasted malt , with some bitter chocolate , and coffee in the finish .  m- not a lot of carbonation , kind of syrupy actually . i feel if it would have been carbonated more it would have helped a lot .

smell : complex nose boasts belgian yeast with a sweet apricot note and some underlying white pepper spice . complexities abound . taste : a well balanced tripel with a nice peppery spice and undistinguishable fruit presence . overall : solid , solid tripel . very fine beer .  m : flat . way too sweet for the ( non-existant ) level of carbonation .

hops are juicy smelling . very complex and citrus-fruity aroma . t : mmmm ! d : this is a tasty beer on the verge of being terrific . a solid offering , i would have a few of these .  carbonation is way too high .

the smell was amazing -- probably the highlight of the beer . it got better as the temp increased . overall , it 's a pretty solid novelty beer .  mouthfeel : a bit on the fizzy side - really scrubs the tongue .

definitely a woodsy component going on , and i 'm thinking rosemary bark or dried thyme . not much funk , really , but the acid backbone is there making for a quite enjoyable drink on its own . phenomenal .  skimpy in body , vapidly dextrinous and approaching watery in mouthfeel .

pretty good .  it does n't taste bad or good , kind of like water . it tastes like bubble water with a hint of sweetness . it 's for getting your swill on , and nothing else . too bad this is what most americans think of , when they think of australian beer .

smells great . spicy , malty , slight peppermint .  starts with fruit taste , looses interest with a thin mouthfeel and water middle although helped by a supporting co2 texture and some tartness ( carbondated water ) ending with lactic acid and dry pucker on the back of the tongue and esophagus .

it 's supposedly a witbier heavily flavored with raspberries -- and just a touch of honey . the berry aroma is all-consuming . 8 inches from my nose , it 's attacking my nostrils like a schoolbully . if i 'm picking raspberry seeds out of my teeth with new glarus rapsberry tart or lindemans framboise , i 'm picking the raspberry jolly rancher wrapper out of my teeth with this one . intensely fruity .  m : dammit , i hate porters like this . light , watery body , slightly oily , and slick on the palate . this would have been so much better with more body to it .

very sharp and fruity hops , with a good amount of grapefruit and pineapple . the hops seem to disappear from the flavor , very surprising considering the aroma . the hops are more tea-like , sitting on top of a sweet bread-like malt base .  2.5 m very light , i am not impressed . it is very close to water in feel .
huge pepper aroma and a very pronounced and balanced flavor . thanks to the lovely folks at elysian fields today , very gracious hosts .  too thin .

top of the line nose on this one , just fantastic . my first impression was damn ! the consensus was this was an excellent beer , & there was a marked difference once it warmed - a collection of `` yeah , it 's ok '' changed to `` damn , this is good '' after 10-15 minutes . really glad i got to try this one , thanks again tucker !  thin mouthfeel .

smell - citrus and strong pine notes with a little bit of earthy smell . very nice on the nose . taste - hop taste comes across pretty strong with an orange/grapefruit taste .  very pale straw yellow color , hazy but filtered look no aroma noted water like very light bodied taste and looks like water ... . however better than most would give credit to seeing how its bud .
there is a good strong malty and coffee like smell .  mouthfeel was pretty watery and went down quickly .

has a nice aroma of sweet carmely malt and spicey hops .  above average taste for an adunct lager , but not great by any measure . this is definately better than budweiser , coors or miller , but not exactly to die for . foster 's price point is right about miller/bud level , but always slightly higher . it 's worth the extra coins if you 're on a budget . much more enjoyable than the run-of-the-mill macros .
at first , the nose was lots of tart apple and/or pears . after the drink sat for a bit the nose became mostly bananas and vanilla .  mouthfeel is overly carbonated .

the beer is wonderful to look at and has a very nice robust and scotch like in complexity nose . the taste is what killed this one for me and the fact that it has almost no carbonation.did i get a bad beer ?  better than expected , but as someone who despises ab products + light beer i was n't expecting much trouble is , within the same can it tasted like lemonade in some sips , water in others . giving it a 4 on drinkability because it 's light , so one could drink a lot of these if they chose to .
smell was amazing , coffee , toffee , bitter chocolate , sugar , fruit .  mouthfeel - one of the most water beers i 've had .
powerful hop aroma , lots of citrus . pleasant , but nothing to get too excited about .  mouthfeel is thin and weak .

this is good , but it 's a little overrated here . it 's tasty and it smells fantastic . i know real porters have sour ale , but usually that sour ale adds creaminess , here it almost has a coors light sourness ( acrid-overdrive ) to it thats off-putting .  mouthfeel is very thin and overly carbonated .

had this out of a bottle poured into a snifter ... a : jet black with a very small head , decent lacing ... s/t : smells and tastes like creme brulee .  fizzy ... gross . m- watery , thin , minimal carbonation , and nothing lingering .

pretty hop-forward , but the taste does n't quite live up the incredible nose . the citrusy-pine aroma is somewhat over-powered by a faintly peppery and slightly acidic bite . not bad , but the nose really had me expecting something special .  very light in body with a slick mouthfeel at first that becomes almost slimy .
a fantastic aroma if you ask me ! great stuff !  the mouthfeel leans toward the thin and watery side .

this nose is so unique and amazing . as i take first sip i wasnt ready for the electric sour rush that attacks the tongue .  my big complaint is the mouthfeel . this stuff had some serious astringency to it leaving my mouth prickly and dry .
the sweet smelling belgian malts are very nice . the flavor starts out very well .  body is very thin , drinkability is ok , but there 's not very much to this beer .

definite lactose on the nose although emphasis is placed much more firmly upon the strong roasted and baker 's chocolate qualities of the beer . once again , lactose shows itself with a vaguely milky start and a kiss of sugar at the finish ( along with bitter chocolate ) .  mouthfeel is very thin with low carbonation , almost watery , drinkability is poor , huge bitterness and watery mouthfeel is a disappointment .

in the flavor : oodles of grapefruit and lime , fresh grass , a bit of dank weed , some sweet honey and black pepper . good hop profile ; great for a pale ale . i would n't say this winter offering from ska has flavors that really gel with the season , but it is a nice little pale .  flavor : then , i drank some & everything went downhill . it was watery & disappointing .

smell- lots of dark fruits off the starting line . the dark fruit aroma is huge . followed by a hint of banana esters . very inviting , but also oddly fearsome . taste- not nearly as complex as aroma let on . as it warms , it gets better , but not that extremely rich , complex blend of tastes that a lot of belgian holiday beers have . drinkability- good , but not great .  m = thin . thats it .

aroma - this is where the beer shines i feel . a great funk , barnyard , grassy , astringent blast right to your nostrils . taste - definitely follows the nose . barnyard and belgian yeast right up front , almost a brett taste , the astringency is in the back with grassy notes . great smell and decent tasting beer , i am enjoying it !  m : thin body with not much carbonation .
very interesting . smells sweet but different .  the body is a bit thin and feels too bubbly .
a nice balance .  mouthfeel - very light and dry .
back to the smell - oak , but the lovely old sort . . .  tragically the mouthfeel is watery and the carbonation ( which others had noted ) , distracts from the overall experience .

smells great ( but nothing like a gumball imo ) . incredible . very bitter for a pale ale , or pale wheat ale , whatever . it certainly smelled good , but nothing more than the typical tropical fruit-heavy pale/ipa .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and very watery .

surprisingly hoppy aroma for the style with a prominent earthy pine presence as well as hints of citrus and tropical . it smells great just not like a wheat beer . clean , crisp and easy drinking with a slightly dry finish .  very thin , and watery . lower carbonation .

t - not as complex as i had hoped for , but still good . starts off with bourbon vanilla flavors with some caramel malt sweetness mid palate , then big oak flavors with a bit of spice through the long finish .  has a bit of a sweet maltiness and maple flavor does come out more as it warms m : very thin feel for a porter and leaves an odd buttery coating d : nothing really appauling , and nothing overpowering so it is drinkable , but i probably wo n't get another
the smell is wonderful . tannin , grapes , apples , apple peels , raisins , caramel , touch of cocoa , and a hint of alcohol .  the body is too full and filling .

if that is what you like , though , this is an excellent beer . i have read that this is brewed by a sake brewer , and that may be all you need to describe the taste . for someone who appreciates sake this is a very interesting beer , and definately worth trying .  mouthfeel - pretty astringent . almost watery except for the stickiness of the body .

big whiffs of tangerines , honeydew melons , bubble gum , concentrated pineapple juice , honeyed graham crackers , and lesser notions of iron-rich blood , spicy tomato juice , and grapes- via a lightly woody and vaguely oxided sense of madeira . for as varied and intriguing as the nose is , the taste is fairly straitforward and unnuanced .  very thin , and barely any head .

dark fruits like plum and rasin , some molasses , and alcohol , smells nice . taste - hmm , starts out mild , chocolate , malts , and some rather light bourbon . overall - was excited after pouring , smelling , then i took a drink , wow dissapointing .  m - watery and sticky . its almost a thin beer .

aroma of tart dried apricots , fresh apricots , canned apricots ... uhh , pretty much just apricots . quite a great smell actually , as i like apricots ( this is why i ordered an apricot ale ) . decent apricot ale , maybe a shade better than the apricot wheats i have tasted off the shelves , but not the game changer i was hoping for .  mouthfeel is disappointing , wet , but not substantial .
if you like hops , you 'll like this . it is overloaded with hops , but very very tasty .  mouthfeel : not much carbonation and the body is kind of watery .
this was hard to decide on , the smell was really intriguing , but taste more mediocre .  one thing about this beer is it feels extremely watery .

s : holy hops ! strong citrus and pine hop aroma , sweet and fruity , not very bitter smelling . t : follows the nose , tropical fruit and citrus hops dominate , followed by piney flavors . o : this beer gives me a rock-solid .  mouthfeel was much too thin to be of any merit .

the smell was magnificent , and like i said i wish it had been in a snifter to catch more of these floral and citrusy aromas . outstanding .  i am dissapionted in the carbination as it is nearly flat with a medium/light feel .
smell- nice nose of hard alcohol , vanilla , deep caramel and barrel flavors .  feels watery with a sweet burn on the way down . soapy .

s : holy hops , batman ! intense , complex , and amazing . t : starts off with citrus and herbal hops , then transitions to a bit of caramel malt before finishing with a wave of piney bitterness . delicious . m : medium bodied with a good dose of initially spiky , finally smooth carbonation .  it feels more watery than i 'd like my porter , however .

a very attractive beer . powerful aroma . moist , sweet raisins at the forefront , with bitter chocolate , roasted malt , soy sauce and sweet sherry behind .  mouthfeel : seltzer drinkability : would be good but the mouthfeel sucks .
the smell is nice and wheaty . definitely smell the 12 percent .  mouthfeel is very thin , again very soda like .

that 's what i get in the nose . fresh hot bowl of oatmeal delivered fresh to your nose with dallop of caramelized brown sugar and a heaping of fresh raspberries . a deep burgundy/purple color , it almost looks like a shiraz . i love the complexity and uniquness of this beer , but it tastes too much like a wine cooler for me to love . i just ca n't handle all of the fruit .  alcohol is very well masked for a 6.5 % way too much carbonation for my liking .
really intense and really pleasant . 4.5 t : taste is much like the nose .  mouthfeel is very flat .
mainly coffee and bittersweet cocoa come through on the nose . minimal hop characteristic if any at all .  body was light and feel was watery .

s - from the first crack of this beer , the smell is great . fruits are in the forefront , with a bit of bitterness . great smell , i do n't think it gets a whole lot better than this . this is still a phenomenal tasting beer , but comparing it to the smell , it lacks a bit . m - mouthfeel is good , slightly syrupy and the bitterness fades at a good rate . overall , this beer is great . i 've had it several times and i have found that if you let it sit for a while , the bitterness dies out a bit , but the fruitiness goes with it .  overall , feels unbalanced , too much carbonation and a little too dull .

really nice aroma . smells of pecans , buttery crust , vanilla and dark fruit .  it 's watery on the palate , surprisingly so - i 've had beers of 3 to 4 % alcohol that had more body . the finish is lightly astringent and bitter .

s- very large coffee smell . great complexity . t- taste starts with sweet fruits and a little bit of chocolate then is balance excellently by fresh bitter coffee .  immediately upon entering the mouth it felt very watery and light for an 80/- .

down to my last g'knight so i felt the need to review this beauty and hopefully it wo n't be long before i can get more . i 'll never forget the first time i popped one of these open , the smell was amazing , i could drink it straight from the can . pure sweetness in the nose , a bit of resiny hops , caramel , cake , so sweet you can taste it .  the flavor was spicy and malty and the mouthfeel was tingly along with a burning sensation as it is swallowed .

smell is one of the best ever , strong flowery , grassy smell . slight grainy smell also . you know what is about to happen .  really fizzy ( like coca-cola fizzy ) on the tongue , with a metallic finish , not really what i was hoping for , dissapointing .

smells wonderful ! t - flavor is a bit subdued , really disappointing after such an amazing nose . more tart cherry , with flavors of brown sugar , vinegar , tobacco , and high quantities of oak .  m : watery , very light-bodied , body of a light lager .

a : pours a muddy muddy thick black with a little ring of head that sticks around but i was not expecting a head anyways , its just dark and inviting black as night s : smells incredibly sweet , like a sweet port , huge huge nose on this , plums and rum raisins with hints of sweet and dark chocolate . i mean there is not real reason to get more specific it smells pretty much like exactly what is listed here , very luxurious . t/mf : the carbonation is a nice touch here and allows an extremely heavy and creamy body to impart the flavor all across the tongue .  it tasted mostly like water with a very light toffee/sweet taste in the back of the tongue . that 's it . it was very drinkable in the same way water is drinkable . when a brewer wants you to chill his beer , there must be a issue with the flavor at cellar temps . i ca n't believe some people consider this to be the flagship for the style .

wow , the smell is the absolute best part of this brew - strong on the citrus . when first tasting dreadnaught , i picked up more piney hop taste than the smell indicates . the more i drank , however , the citrus hop flavor came through . i paid $ 8.99 for this bomber and it was worth it ( although pricey for an everyday beer ) .  the mouthfeel is pretty thin and watery .
aroma is clean and bright . sassafras along with quiet vanilla sit beneath a strong phenolic note .  mouthfeel is thin .

also present are dark chocolates , licorice , spice , robust yeasts , sweet malts and some caramel that all lead to a very complex and pleasing aroma . the taste is not as complex .  2.5 m thin , with only the grain tastes and the slightest stickiness keeping it from being water itself .

the smell was fantastic ! a hop bomb . nice hop finish lingered on my tongue . i 'm anxious to try the imperial version of this brew .  the mouthfeel is very watered down like an american pale ale but i thought the pumpkin taste was enjoyable .

smell : by far the most enjoyable aspect of this beer . the smell is incredibly complex with a strong prune backbone and hints of everything from lemon to chocolate . i like smelling it more than drinking it .  i must say this beer is best on tap as everywhere i 've tried it otherwise all of its carbonation seems to be non-existant .

s : mmmmm ! banana , caramel , chocolate , pecan . twinge is a big negative . better as it warms , but not great . looked and smelled great but flavor was not smooth and a little imbalanced .  pretty easy to drink with a light , watery mouthfeel .

s : big pumpkin with plenty of spices . d : not as good as pumpking but still pretty good .  mouthfeel is watery . this style needs more body - the maltiness is there , but there is very little roasted character & not enough creaminess .
smell : very , very fruity ! it smells almost as good as a lady .  the mouthfeel is this beer 's weakest point . also , it feels a bit heavy on the palate and is almost syrupy .

s-what comes through first is a perfect balance of sweet caramel malt and a blast of citrus hops . d- this brew is pretty awesome . brews that emphasize the citrus/spicy hop combo are hard to come by and this one does an excellent job with it .  the mouthfeel was flat and very dissapointing .

smell : hops across the board , floral with fruits all paired with citrus . great , strong hop scent , but not aggravating in the least , floral .  taste is weak , almost watery , has to be drank ice cold or has a taste like vomit . bottom line is compared to other cheap beers pbr excels in taste , quality , and conveniently the price , 7 bucks a 12 pack .

sweet tropical notes , mainly mango accompany a major amount of hops in the scent . there was a lot i liked but overall very good .  pretty nice . the body is as thin as water . that leads to a very drinkable beer , actually , since it goes down ... well , like water .

the aroma is very good , with some slightly tart chocolate-covered cherries and lots of caramel malts and toffee as well .  good for a lager , but way too much carbonation really throwing this beer off .

there is definitely a nice malty aroma as well . it definitely wants me to take a sip . t : the taste is somewhat disappointing to me following the pleasant aroma . there is n't a lot going on here .  the mouthfeel was watery , the body medium/light and the carbonation average .

subsequent sips bring forth strong chocolate notes mixed with a nice bitterness.the aroma a each sip is truly fantastic . finished nice and creamy with a strong bitter note present .  mouthfeel was very watery and not smooth in the slightest .

another malt bomb for me . lots of rich malts with dark fruity characteristics . plumbs come to mind with a cranberry aroma layered with cinnamon and a maple kind of sweetness . the taste is not quite as rich as the aroma . slight hints of pine and not quite as much fruit presence as i 'd expected . decent , but the aroma certainly outshines the actual flavors .  i 'm going to have to go against the gimmick and with the style here , the mouthfeel just is n't there . i 'm not impressed at all , it 's like a half flat beer that you 've left on your desk whilst reviewing a beer and forgotten about it only to come back to it 30 mins later . the shining point of this beer is it 's drinkability .

this is a fairly average offering in liquor stores round the calgary area , but it is one i can never pass up : this is a very flavourful beer by any means , though it is the most mass-produced of the scotch ales . i love the hue of amber/red glow to this beer . the colour itself is almost appetising . the aroma is my favourite part of the beer . sweet candy , or blueberry gum , rich sweet malt that evokes red licorice , candy cane , sweet bread , sourdough , and other sweet confectionaries . the taste is not as full as the aroma . this is a sweet offering from the time it hits your tongue to the time it leaves your breath : up front there are cherries and irish-red tastes . the hops are there , adding a touch of balance and grass to the finish . the mouthfeel is well carbonated , full , and heavy .  the mouthfeel on this one fluctuates but it has one of the worst finishes i can recall in a beer . the thin body and soda-like carbonation ( and some wheaty texture ) save this some , but the finish is just harsh . artificial flavor , sticks to the teeth , chewing on cardboard , something is wrong here finish to the mouthfeel .

the duchesse . i liked the aroma - sour cherry , tart , musty . i hope it does n't pervade the taste .  i 'm gon na have to say the mouthfeel is what keeps this from being very drinkable . it felt almost like flat soda .

pours a deep amber ruby body with a nice modest off white head . smells of a massive combination of strong barley wine and oak . there 's flavors of raisons , plums and caramel on the nose with lots of vanilla and toasted notes from the oak . bourbon and dark fruit play out initially .  water with a little spice and alcohol . the smell is the best part with mainly cinnamon . the taste is one dimensional cinnamon with a super light water taste on the back . no malt or pumpkin to be found . not a good beer nor a good pumpkin ale but if someone handed me one i would have no problem finishing it . also you could down 3 or 4 no problem and being $ 6 a 6 pack you ca n't beat that .
overall : well , the smell is great , one of the best .  the mouthfeel is way to under carbonated and watery for the style .

s : extremely rich and fragrant . tons of fudge brownie , boozy spirit barrel , cherry , dark fruit , and solvent alcohol . not too intrusive , but feels a little `` tacked on '' if you get my meaning .  thin to medium mouthfeel with zero carbonation -- lifeless .
wow , this started off so well , looking great and smelling great , but simply fell apart at the taste .  mouthfeel very thin , almost light-bodied , and lacking in bitterness .
when i pulled the cork out , a delightful smell hit me right away , but went away quickly .  the mouthfeel is light to medium bodied and watery .

s- lots and lots of chocolate here . roasted malts as well .  not so much the taste as it had a good belgian style wheatiness to it but the body was extremely thin and almost watery . i was looking for more in the way of the mouthfeel .

5.0 s : lots of oatmeal is apparent . this may be the most oatmeal laden beer i 've had . awesome balance between sweet and roasted flavors . 4.0 t : the taste is just about as good as the nose , but the mouthfeel is too distracting for me to enjoy it .  the mouthfeel is disappointing with absolutely no carbonation and mild flavors lingering around . overall , i could have possibly gotten a flat beer but this beer had potential ( when carbonated ) but it didnt come through in my bottle .

not overly complex , but interesting enough to keep your attention . d-i polished off the bomber effortlessly . really goes down nicely , and the alcohol is hidden fairly well .  very watery . the mouthfeel was thin and watery as well .
wish this tasted half as good as it smelled .  mouthfeel is thin , macro thin .
s : pretty nose . grapes , sour cherries , grape skins and rose petals . flowery finish .  m : bitter , almost no carbonation , light to medium body .

s - big aroma of cherry juice , some apple juice , molasses , malts , just a great smell . t - a nice balance of molasses , licorice , malts , some cherry .  this is very much like corona . not as good as miller light .

it 's quite clear and straw/amber colored . it has a very strong smell of fresh hops . pine , citrus , and maybe a bit of tropical fruit , but quite spicy . the smell is the only part of this beer to reflect it 's ipa label .  mouthfeel is also watery with not much body and no carbonation but essentially pretty drinkable due to the fact that is just resembles colored water .

s - mostly raspberry , which i found quite appealing . some caramel and roasted malt .  the lack of body really disappointed me . while surprisingly drinkable , this beer needs to be heavier to match the taste , so more body and more alcohol are needed .

subtly fills your nostrils with sheer weight as well as clove , coriander spice , lemon peel , vanilla bean , has a lively yeastiness , some banana notes , while light of touch it 's never not there . the fruit mainly banana , pear , apricot , more skin and pit than flesh .  m - weak and thin . lifeless .

huge hop aroma , a nice scottish style malt presnece behind the agresive hop bitterenes .  a nice chocolatey finish that lingers for a while on the palate is the best part about this beer . m : poor .
the nose was amazing . hints of fruit , plums , raisons , apples , yeast , with a few earthy woody notes .  mouthfeel is rather thin for a scotch ale .

intresting , very intens smell , very nice hop aroma , tons of hops , citrus flavour , very similar to pliny the elder , i want to taste this one t : similar to the nose but not that strong , wheat , tons of hops , citrus , sweet malts , nice slightly bitter finish , this could be the little brother of pliny the elder , but this is softer , not so strong , m : very smooth , very well balanced , d : very drinkable , alcohol is well hidden , i could drink this all day long , yammy , well done struise .  it was ice cold thanks to the cooler and that made it tasty . watery but that 's alright because your not expecting anything but that from bud ice .

it is overpoweringly fruity and has an amazing aroma . it pours a cloudy light rose pink with a huge head.you are overwhelmed by the raspberry nose .  appearance : dark amber color with a nice 1/2 '' off white head ... unfortunately this reminded me of a pop on the pour smell : pine , hops , citrus taste : kinda watery , slight citrus ( maybe cascade hops ) mouthfeel : thin drinkability : could do two in a night , but i 'd rather drink something that tastes better

v=ql-n78agg_y appearance : clear golden , 1-finger head , excellent lacing aroma : hop oil , banana , lemon citrus , hibiscus , buttery biscuit , dry floral notes , hint of pine flavor : medium body , earthiness , dirt , grapefruit , pine , cup-cake icing sweetness , banana , bready malts , lemon rind , medium carbonation , mild bitterness pairings : fried shrimp brew + pairing : buttery dough on the shrimp balances this brew well  for the level of alcohol , there is hardly any hotness at all and a bizarrely watery and light body for a barleywine . could also stand some more hops , as i could hardly detect any at all .
t : hugely ( and distractingly ) sweet . almost medicinal o : a very complex sipper of a beer that i found overly sweet . enjoyed the non-ba version much better .  mouthfeel is weak and watery .

aroma is overwhelming with citrusy peach essence of hop . so sweet and spicy , very cali . i usually sniff for 15-20 seconds but this beer merits much more nasal enjoyment .  m : light carbonation with a very light watery body .

majestic sniffs . taste is equally multifacited . one of the maltier versions i 've encountered , laid out in a doughy , bready fashion . this is a very fine hefeweizen  aside from that , the taste , like the smell , is unremarkable mouthfeel is borderline watery .

it has a great smell of having trouble explaining other than sweet . this is a very drinkable beer but there are many more much better .  no finish , the faintest body , texture is nil , nothing to recommend it at all .

smell : this one is all about that distinctive fruity grape note ( thinks welsh 's grape jelly filled grape bubblegum ) in the beginning that then gets washed over by a classic cantillon urine and yeast wave . truly unique and highly enjoyable . taste : same as the nose but more integrated and not as grape dominant as the nose .  body is way too thick , sweet , and syrupy .
very attractive nose . taste is muddled malty sweetness up front , picking up some golden raisins and dried apples along the way .  watery and flat in my mouth .

awesome hop aroma of german noble hops . smells like tettnanger to me ... pleasant , dry and crisp character . decent hop bitterness and flavor .  the mouthfeel is poor . it seems to lack enough carbonation .

smell is a strong dose of mixed raw grains , silage , molasses , a bit of smoky roasted malt , some earthy nut aspects especially as it warms . the mouthfeel is quite light and drinkable , bordering on watery , despite the huge malt nose . taste is also very thin , not nearly as intense as the smell . mild caramel sweetness , some mixed malt body , a hint of vanilla .  head falls into the liquid way too quickly and seems to look more like bubble bath suds that the typical beautiful belgian head . certainly is the high point of the beer . alcohol comes a little too strong on the palate and seems to take over the other flavors . flat on the tonque . outrageously overpriced and overrated .

a fantastic malty aroma , scents of autumn air , sweet and with just a touch of hops .  the mouthfeel is a lowlight , though , with a very thin , watery body being punctuated by small , prickly bubbles .

it smelled of the mediterranean sea and beautiful , long-legged , not to be fucked with , italian women with sensuous lips . a very sweet , lemony ipa that is excellent for what it is , and enjoyable , for a time .  here we go : a - opaque reddish-brown , small head with minimal lacing s - malts , hint of hops , not much else t - much like the aroma , mildly sweet malts , faint hop bitterness with weak coffee m - thin , a bit too thin for a brown ale d - no problem putting down a few if i chose to , but i do n't think i would unless it was my only alternative to bmc lagers .

a bit of lacing & zero head retention , really dragged this score down s : pumpkins & pumpkin pie spices , cinnamon , allspice , & nutmeg t : pumpkin , cinnamon , nutmeg , dryness & brown sugar up front . spices start to dominate as this warms , cinnamon & nutmeg especially , plus some squashy/pumpkin notes as well . finishes warming with nutmeg & cinnamon mf : medium bodied , fairly low carbonation & a nice warming sensation , expected a bit more malt depth though drinks pretty easy , the abv is well hidden , but lacks the total package of say , an ichabod , but i would certainly grab a sixer of this during the fall every year  m - the body is vanishingly thin and i feel the carbonation is too high for an english porter .
one of the most refreshing smelling beers i have ever sampled .  taste is rich and sweet , slightly nutty , but this beer really sufferes from it 's thin and watery mouthfeel .
overall the beer looks and smells fantastic . it falls way short on flavor and drinkibilty .  mouthfeel is disappointing ; thin and watery , with too much carbonation for my taste .

the aromas of a black pepper-like spicy hop and light earthy grain blend together to make the mouth water .  mouthfeel is where the beer suffers . it just feels wrong . a very tasty and aromatic beer , and if you can get past or prefer the super-low carbonation level .

coffee dominates the nose and overpowers the other smells that are underneath . nevertheless , the smell is very enticing .  i feel like i have now experienced the true port/lost abbey experience , this is the first one i 've had that is flat ... a : pours dark brown with caramel highlights , zero head even after stiff pour , some clarity s : nose is predominantly oak and vanilla , some char quality in there , stout base takes a back seat t : vanilla and bourbon again dominate , some ashy character in there along with light notes of leather and tobacco , a bit of of boozieness on the finish mf : low carbonation is an understatement , medium body o : good flavors here , the lack of carbonation takes away from the quality a bit , for the premium price tag , i would expect carbonation .

pours a clear medium deep cranberry red with no head but very nice looking . nose is initially a `` gray smoke '' quality , almost like the smoke from putting out a fire with water , that then develops a bit of an oak barrel nose . layered , complex and appealing nose . mouthfeel is without carbonation ; has a big sour character but without any discernable fruit or style and definitely needs more acid for my taste .  getting some sweetness from the milk sugar too , but not a lot m- thin . flat .

the nose is great , with notes of roasted barley , chocolate malt , and a little bit of coffee . has some creaminess as well which is very nice . the beer is medium bodied , but is a bit light on carbonation .  over carbonated , watery .
overall , i really liked the smell of the beer - the flavor , not so much .  the first thing i notice with this beer is the watery mouthfeel . the mouthfeel is terrible .
tons of chocolate malt , coffee , anise , plums , raisons a fruit blender of aromas . it really needed more hops to balance this bad boy out .  m/d - weak and thin mouthfeel .

s- smells almost exactly like a liqueur-filled chocolate . chocolate covered raisins . a little marshmallow .  crisp to the point of being overdone , loads and loads of soda like carbonation . notes : ho hum , average , run of the mill , mediocre ... etc .

a big aroma of pine on the nose , a little lemon rind and malt too . the pine is huge at first and hits your nose during the pour . a piney , bitter start as expected . i think a little all spice or cinnamon replacing the pepper would do this ale some good .  body is a nip thin . a bit too still , but more carbonation would have blasted through the empty body of the beer , making it even less desirable .

anywho , nice nose . love the nose . really nice citrusy hops with just a touch of wheaty sourness in there , but barely any . just a nice fresh smell . the beer has quite a bit of flavor for only 4.8 % abv .  the beer was thin bodied and very easy to drink . for a faint tasting , macro lager it was n't too bad .

light tan head for a second , poor retention and lacing ... the aroma is sweet with lots of nice sweet bourbon on the front . its a really nice smooth bourbon , makes you really want to drink it ... the taste really lets me down sadly .  medium bodied , but watery .

smell- the smell is another one of my favorite parts about it . i can smell mangos i think . taste- ok at first it is a little bitter but once it settles it has a great full flavor tast to it .  mostly smells and tastes like a lager pretending to be an ale . that hint of lager ( as in yuengling lager ) sits there in the background , but then there 's a nice hit of hops in there too . it 's odd , but not necessarily bad ( although certainly not a good american pale in any sense of the word ... it 's a cheap beer masquerading as an american pale ) . not great , but one to try if you 're tired of lager as your cheap beer for the minute .
aroma is lots of banana and lemon , very nice and assertive .  mouthfeel this one was clumsy and , worst of all , lacked the fluffy character of a good hefe weizen .

s : pine and citrus hop aroma . the smell is reminiscent of pliny the elder , kind of a marijuana smell also , like green flash imperial ipa .  feel : very thin bodied and a bit too light in body for an ipa or even an apa .
aroma - dark fruits with a caramel and sweet malts .  the body was water and medium light .

smell : awesome . juicy citrus hop hit the nose hard . taste : does n't quite live up to the smell , but still very good . the hops are more herbal with some citrus in there as well . still very good and really glad to have tried this .  mouthfeel : body is thin and water and a little flat ; finsih is wet and is like drinking malt flavored water . the flavors are mild and meek , the body is super watery and does n't offer much , so i do n't feel i will be drinking this again .

smell : citrusy , with hints of spices , very powerful if you can wait a minute or so before you drink it .  i was again surprised to find a very thin mouth feel dominated by carbonation which seemed to accent the minimal hops to make them more pronounced .

just great smell . taste : 3.5 a little one dimensional . it has an amazing aroma , but doesnt match with taste . overall , would enjoy more with tweak to malt content , but for a one off beer , still quite enjoyable . recommend trying .  mouthfeel is overly fizzy , making an already light beer even fluffier . overall , this is an interesting beer that could be very refreshing if less carbonated .

smell is just plain wonderful . it 's like an entire garden of raspberries up your nose .  m - syrupy , mouth coating body with an obnoxious amount of carbonation . carbonation is prickly and really too much as i feel like i ca n't taste everything because of it . it does get better the more you let it warm and let the carbonation die down .

s : roasted malt is very prevalent and dominates right away . lots of great stuff going on in the aroma . t : as in the nose , sweet roasted malt is the main characteristic .  very light bodied , an ok mouthfeel.. just way too watery and thin , not much for taste , just some lemon zest on the after taste .

beautiful beer at 6.8 % abv certainly packs a punch , a - perfect for the style , a big fluffy head fell away at moderate pace , lacing well , pours a hazy orange s - a highlight for me , big amarillo hop aroma , citrus , fruity no negatives in the aroma dept . t - a little bit less than a std dipa bitterness but still kicked liked a wild goat , beautiful flavours , crystal or other malts coming through m - well controlled and certainly right for me .  appearance : golden with extremely high head with low head retention smell : sublte hop aroma , taste : light and refreshing , herbal with some decent hop flavor mouthfeel : light bodied , way too much carbonation , jeez ... drinkability : great flavor belgian pale but its overcarbonated .
smell : smells like a banana laffy taffy . also get some pumpkin spice aroma in there too .  m - way too much carbonation for my taste .

massively nutty aroma , packed with roasted peanut butter , walnut brownies , and nuttella - very inviting . not terribly smoky ( more roasty ) , just a mild edge of charcoal that also lends a hint of toasted marshmallow . plenty of coffee notes as well - this is just about perfect , exactly what i want in the style . strangely , there is not a hint of alcohol in this beer - which makes this dangerously drinkable , but still , not exactly a lawnmower beer !  t : cheap carbonated corn . m : if it werent for the bottle this beer would have sunk years ago .
it has a very sweet aroma to it and that makes it all the more appealing . smell is more prevalent the more it warms up .  mouthfeel is very flat and is not impressing at all .

aroma is wonderful ... lots of raspberries , but not overdone like , say lindemanns , and not fake syrup like norwester . mouthfeel is flittering with a light body and very snappy finish . malts are gamey and `` corny '' .  m - very thin and watery with flat carbonation .
aroma is a staggering , fresh , really rich chocolate .  the body is light and really lacking .
nose offers delightful citrus - sharp grapefruit juice , apricot , and a pleasant wet lawn grassy component .  mouthfeel : absolutely no carbonation .

although very skunky it smells alot like pot which to me is an awesome characteristic . i am curious if the fermentation process of beck 's involves any hemp but it seem 's unprobable .  mouthfeel is very , very light -- it goes down like nothing at all .
very good smell . taste- there is a good amount of alcohol and hop bitterness on the palate for this one .  m - thin , a little harsh and a bit drying .

the pure white fluffy head looked like snow had fallen on a green-apple tree ! the smell of grannysmith apple and candied sugar . the taste was the same as the nose except at the finish , some good tart apple rhine gives a good semi-dry finish .  the mouthfeel is flat , but predictable as there are virtually no bubbles in the glass after the first minute or so . as far as drinkability goes , i 'd save it for the hot summer days , the ballpark and the cheap 30 pack for the party .

it 's sitting across the table but throwing great scents my way hazy amber orange with some sudsy head juicyfruit aromas : immense , zesty citrus , mint . not much pine , which is a nice change from the norm . good , robust , woody bitterness ( it really hangs on the tongue ) with excellent hop depth . mint .  nose was fruity apples , peaches , apricots , but the mouthfeel was watery and very sour ... not like the lead-in on a flemish sour ... just tartly sour .

the smell is close to overwhelming , but exceptionally pleasant nonetheless . oak , vanilla , toffee , caramel , dark chocolate , raisins , bourbon/brandy , and maybe a touch of cinnamon all alternately ( yet congruently ) jump out at you . quite a complex and interesting beer , the drinkablility is hard to judge due to the faux-thin nature of the body .  smells and tastes bland and grain like . almost stale . it is a good beer to party with if all your doin is playin beer pong or circle .
the aroma is sensational . sweet , fruity , yeasty .  m- strange , slick mouthfeel with a semi dry finish .

aroma is a decadent mocha and milk chocolate , but the taste does n't quite live up to it .  very sweet flavour , largely the same elements as in the aroma , but far too sugary and overwhelmingly sweet for me .
overall : a solid fresh hop pale ale with a really good aroma .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and watery with almost no carbonation .
the smell was full of bourbon , as expected , that blended well with the fruity aromas expected from a tripel , along with spiced notes .  the mouhfeel is weak , watery , thin .

s : extreme vanilla , boozy bourbon notes . otherwise this is solid . d : weighing in at 13 % abv , one gibcs could do you in ... yet , i think i could handle two ... and that 's saying a lot , especially after starting this session w/ one tripel karmeliet and one piraat ( both 33cl ) . an excellent extreme imperial stout .  m : despite its creamy appearance , the head feels thin on the palate . the brew itself is thin and watery , especially as it warms . the carbonation barely registers .
mesmerizing , really .  palate scraping astringency . the lack of carbonation particularly makes me wonder if i should have given this more time in the cellar to condition .
the smell is really quite wonderful ; nearly perfect . the roast and sweetness are the perfect marriage of complimentary elements .  mouthfeel was slightly thick and flat .

s- very wonderful aroma here . very nice hop smells come from this .  thin watery and light in body o - did not even reach moderate expectations of being a porter and tasting barrel aged , just not very good in my opinion .

n : this is a beautiful , mouthwatering nose . smells very close to liquid pumpkin pie .  a - light , clear , yellow color with a thick head that dissipated quickly s - beer , cheap beer t - beer from a can , cheap beer from a can m - thin , flat , not much d - went down smooth , probably because i 'd wisely iced it down with some ice and rock salt so it would get really cold .
the smell is truly incredible , and the taste is malty and pleasant .  mouth is thin and watery . too simple and too one dimensional and thin .

very interesting bouqet-smells very much like a moscato d'asti frum the muscat grapes . also floral , sweet honeyed bready malts , and fresh ( not roasted ) nuts in the nose . medium to full-bodied and viscous , this could present a cloying sweetness after a while and as such is not a session beer , but definitely something unique and worth trying .  where this beer falls off is the mouthfeel ; it was like coca-cola without the carbonation . drinkability would be pretty good i guess , if you can get pas the average flavors and thin mouthfeel .
smells of raisins and roast malt and a little chocolate , very nice .  mouthfeel is entirely too thin and watery .

the haze really detracted from the appearance for me ... ... but it made up for the look with the smell . i honestly smelled this for a few minutes before tasting . the smell was very citrus like , with lots of malt and hop spice .  the mouthfeel is light to medium bodied and just way too thin and watery for an oatmeal stout .

lots of apricot and sweet smells on this one .  good lacing down the glass s : coffee , sweet bready malts t : coffee , slight harsh maltiness also slight hint of chocolate m : light very thin bodied beer .
aromas are awesome . i can smell this for a couple of feet away .  m - kind of flat on the palate with very little carbonation . hop profile caught me off guard and the mouthfeel is pretty weak .
smell - the smell was an enchanting citrus odor between grapefruit and lemon meshed with faint aromatic pine hops and a hint of grain underneath .  m : thin body and light carbonation .

s- large amount of aromatics here ! strongly grapefruit in character , citrus of oranges and lemons behind that , notebook paper , and minute hops profile . t- the grapefruit is a tease . i prefer to smell it to be honest , but that wo n't last forever . the hops become distracting towards the middle , but it is no where near the annoyance of a hop bomb .  thin and watery .
big grapefruit aroma . good head . high 75 ibu .  the mouthfeel is pretty sad on this one . very watery and thin .

the aroma is fantastic , sweet , sour , chocolate malt all blending to a wonderful bouquet . taste is a bit too spicy , but otherwise very pleasantly complex . mouthfeel is dry and acrid , not as smooth as some others .  the mouthfeel is unbalanced as if the carbonation and the liquid will not merge . for as much noise the carbonation made on opening the bottle , it seems quite on the palate .

really great nose on this beer . as mentioned before dry hop feel to this one o - this is a tasty brew overall and the nose on it is just superb .  s. nonexistent . m. also nonexistent . just plain and unoffensive . light beer on amber side ? nothing to brag about but goes down like water . above average in it 's class .

a thick , delightful malt smell dominates the nose , with elements that are clearly fruity ( but not acidic ) shining noticeably through . this smell perfectly prepares the drinker for a sweet , although not cloying , wave of maltiness which has very pronounced toffee , caramel , and bread-like flavors .  mouthfeel is too thin for me .

aroma is smack you in the face hop blast appropriate for a pnw ipa . taking dry-hopping to its logical extreme with several whole hop cones in each bottle .  not much depth at all m- lacking for a stout -- - no creaminess and it 's pretty thin overall d- wo n't seek this out again and i hope the rest of the breweries selections are better -- - really loses you in the mouthfeel

the smell is quite good : belgian yeast funk , candi sugar , orange peel and coriander . it has more of the belgian yeast aroma than most wit brews . not as heavy on the orange peel and coriander as most wits ; which i find to be a good thing .  the finish is lightly sweet rather than crisp , and the mouthfeel , which started out thin , ends on a watery , undercarbonated note . zywiec is an average epl , making it a below average beer in general .

s - strong tropical fruit aroma with hints of mango , lemon , and other citrus fruits . a slightly sweet smell from the malt is a welcome addition to the strong hop presence . d - the nose was much better than the taste .  mouthfeel is overyly fizzy and thin .

i can taste all the spices and pumpkin , but for whatever reason the taste does n't live up to what this brew smells like . it 's a lot weaker tasting than i thought it would be , at least compared to the aroma anyway .  watery mouthfeel in terms of a stout .
the smell is amazing . coffee dominates , and while i 'm not a coffee drinker , i like the smell of it .  it drinks as a light beer ; it is very thin and weak , much unlike guinness .

the aroma , however , is a-one , outstanding , and really well captured in the wineglass : nice , fresh pumpkin accompanied by strong notes of cinnamon , nutmeg , clove , maybe some ginger ... wow , this is the smell i look for in my pumpkin ales - imo they nailed it . that said , i feel the flavor takes a step back ; maybe the nose raised expectations too high ... still very nice , with the pumpkin and spices pulling through , but perhaps not as robustly as the nose had led me to believe ; there 's also a not entirely pleasant though subtle bitterness to it , as well as a bit a boozy bite to the finish .  high gravity beer , this one is king . drink alot of water when drinking or a major headache occurs . so drink with caution .

smells awesome ; there 's an herbal hoppiness with orange/tangerine notes , some slight pine , and lots of biscuit/nutty malt with an undertone of sweet caramel . it finishes with a clean bitterness and biscuity malt .  very carbonated ... .too much .

the nose ... wow . i get bubble gum and cotton candy , with a strong citrus and floral hop character . this smells fantastic ... eeeh ! ! it 's not a bad thing , just strange . i think it 's too aggressively hopped and unbalanced in the taste department for my tastes , but still damn good .  ( m ) thin mouthfeel with some bitterness loosely gripping at the tongue , barely holding on .
this beers saving grace is a fantastic odor .  horrible macro version of the style .
laced well . smelled freaking fantastic . toasty , dark fruits .  empty , chalky mouthfeel , not much going on here .

up top , a cardboard-colored head recedes quickly to a wisp of foam , but is revived nicely with a quick swirl of the pint glass . the aroma brings everything the style should have : floral , bubble-gum like hops with tropical fruit , pine sap , and spiciness from the rye . still , it 's quite tasty . mouthfeel is dry and juicy at the same time , with an uppity carbonation level that fuels the aggression from the hops .  the mouthfeel is astringent .

i look at these two next to each other and woder if i have not walked into a paint shop and someone mixed my color swatch perfectly ... the aroma is fantastic . it has all the elments of a wonderful malt bomb , and just enough hop remnants to keep it interesting .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied . it took much diligence to see my way to the end of this beer , and , were it not for the runaway carbonation , it could 've been far better . one to revisit , provided they clear up the carbonation issue .

smells amazing ! smells like raspberry muffins , with the sweet and tangy fruity smell and the bread-y , yeast-y almost sour smell of muffins . raspberry taste is very muted , almost would n't even know it was there . if only it tasted as good as it smelled .  m - crisp start but the finish ends up being very watery .

s- huge cherry notes with wheat right behind it . this has that waxy taste to it that is just very unappealing . great smells and mouthfeel to it , but i can not get over that medicinal taste .  a thin mouthfeel and not a lot of carbonation .

smell is very sugary with a fruit and spice scent of apple butter . apple , cinnamon , clove , raisin , grape , figs , black pepper and sweet prunes are all in here . taste is drier than expected sweet but not very . good spice flavor that builds as you sip . the flavor just is n't anywhere as complex as the smell . mouthfeel is good nice drinkable belgian here that is worth a try , only problem is that there are lots better around .  mouthfeel is thin .

the aroma seems to transcend the dopplebock style with a delightful boozy elixier : notes of dark rum , brandy , sherry and the like . currants , produce , fresh grass , and a slight hint of citrusy hops provide a great balance to the smell . this is not a beer for the faint of palate . i 'm not exactly sure how i feel about samichlaus ... one one hand , it 's an exceptionally complex , well-crafted beer that probably deserves its own style .  the mouthfeel is light and watery , not much substance . a very watered down dunkel , i would skip this in the future .
the aroma is very nice . taste - the taste is all strawberries as predicted .  m : really unappealing .
smells really really good , actually . i suppose old men are always less handsome when they take their clothes off .  the mouthfeel was very thin for a stout .

s : smell is awesome . so complex for a stout which are normally one dimensional . coffee and dark unsweetened cocoa powder , whiskey/bourbon and even some woody notes that are muted .  m - medium-thin mouthfeel with low carbonation . a bit watery , the consistency of this beer is not what i wanted . too thin , not creamy enough for me .

with the smell of opening a brand-new gar of rasberry jam . it has a powerful rasberry flavor that overpowers pretty much all the malt flavor .  the mouthfeel was flat leaving a watery feel in the mouth .

s : love the nose on this one ! was expecting a typical citrus hoppy aroma , but instead it was a more roasted/toasted & earthy .  that being said i want to keep track of beers i have tried and will start to try reviewing beers i drink ) from a sampler pack found at specs liquor . tastes flat to me . no alcohol taste that i can tell of and not a whole lot of flavor . goes down easy and not much of an aftertaste .

huge sweet and bready malts rise to the nose upon an initial whiff .  it 's piercing , almost . the nose lands itself squarely on the tongue , unadulterated . what you are left with is a diminished , pale , watery finish . this , fortunately , leads to high quaffability .

the aroma is sweet fruits and some spice including coriander , orange peel is present as well .  feels thin and watery on the tongue with a low level of carbonation . bitterness is harsh and detracts from drinkability , mouthfeel is unsatisfying , and the flavors are n't interesting and complex enough to yield repeated enjoyment .

taste is very boring after the wonderful aroma . this almost has no taste whatsoever .  very little mouthfeel , this beer is meant to be drank ice cold as implied with the cold indicator on the can unlike most beers that i drink .

aroma was intensely hoppy yet smooth and balanced . piney and floral hops , citrus and fruity esters came through strong along with a touch of candy-like sweetness . cascade hops and hop oils soon became bitter and biting and left a noticeable film on my tongue . unquestionably , this was the most bitter and unbalanced ipa i have had to date .  m : this feels fairly thin ; the flavors fall quickly off the tongue , resulting in a watery finish .
the smell is utterly fantastic , easily one of the best smelling beers i 've ever come across .  mouthfeel : lacking . too light for the style .
very nice . t : sugar sweet ( touch of brown sugar ) along with some malt sweetness .  very thin feel , little oily .
very inviting . smells very welcoming , but lacking in other areas .  m - slick and watery .
s : i thought i died and went to heaven the first time i smelled this beer . caramel and toffee aromas dominate with some hints of berries .  very watery .

the smell is surprising sweet with peaches and apricots on top of the big citrus hop base . this is an interesting dipa though i wish the flavor measured up to the unique aroma . still worth trying .  mouthfeel was light in body and watery in texture with a flat carbonation .
smell- unbelievable aroma ! overall- has a great aroma but falls short with the taste .  it was flat on the tongue and mouthfeel was very weak .

half inch head and thick head retention s : straight dole pineapple orange juice or something like it ! phenomenally citrusy . t : more dole juice ! crisp bite at the front before smooth finish . o : delicious ! very unique . probably could n't have more than one but very enjoyable . the fruit juice character is pretty interesting , that 's for sure .  the sweetness died out in the taste , however , which was flat and slightly watered-down . a weird bitterness gave an unpleasant mouthfeel but still not difficult to drink .
