fantastic smell of sweet banana and a slight tart cloves .  m - too thin , light body , fizzy carbonation . the mouthfeel on this beer is no good .

grapefruit ! my favorite aroma in beer and life for some strange reason , but enough about me ... .once i break from my grapefruit coma , i do notice pine and a little lemon rind in the background t - there is that damn grapefruit again , i just ca n't get away from it . immense hop flavor with a surprising amount of malt that finds its way through the hops .  m - the downfall of this beer . carbonation is way to high , almost makes the beer feel fuzzy .

s- strong aroma of banana , clove , yeast , pear , bubblegum , wheat , nuttiness , and spice . complex and aromatic . t- banana , clove , pear , lots of spice , and the alcohol was surprisingly prominent , some warming . m- pretty high carbonation , crisp , finishes dry , drinks smooth o- first weizenbock i have ever had .  mf : thin bodied and only moderate carbonation makes this beer a bit too watery .

in my opinion , racer 5 is one of the best smelling beers on the market . one whiff revels a cascade of piney and citrus hops aroma . it 's the quintessential west coast ipa aroma . for a beer topping out at 7.0 % , racer 5 is ridiculously drinkable .  palate is watery with that adjuncty grain flavor , but not too offensive . easy drinking .
s : peaches . need i say more ? t : lots of peach favor , with a big sour bite at the end .  i thought that the mouthfeel was kind of watered down ... it needed more `` oommff '' .

abv present , but smells delicious . alcohol , somewhat dry .  carbonation is minimal , almost flat . again understanding its aged but this beer is pretty sweet and without some degree of carbonation to clear out the palette at the end it becomes cloying .

nose brings toffee , yeast , cherries , dried apricots , chocolate , coffee ice cream , and spices . very complex and wonderous . palate gives us sour cherries , yeast , sweetened iced tea , hints of caramel and toast , and some overall tartness . the mouth has some good , sharp peaks midpalate and the finish is a slow , deliberate fade . a very smooth and clean finish overall .  medium body , almost non existent carbonation , sweet sticky syrupy mouthfeel . i think the lack of carbonation ruins the mouthfeel and makes this taste and smell overly sweet .

smells fantastic . spicy , fruity and different . really intriguing . tastes similar to the aroma -- some malty , almost candy-like , sweetness underneath , but with a strong bitterness taking centre stage .  this is a drinkable brew that definatly packs a punch , but it 's kind of one dimensional and thin .
complex and strong aroma of wild flowers , banana , orange and coriander .  carbonation is too high .
smell is piney , citrus , caramel , spices , very nice , reminds me of the holidays , neat cinnamon-hop aroma .  the mouthfeel is way thin , but drinkability is ok .

smells like apples , tastes like hops . very tasty . the fragrance certainly did not match the taste , which is a good thing .  flavor is good and somewhat spicy , but fades too quickly because body is too thin and watery .

fantastic . i 'm a big fan of floral ipas , and not so into the bitterness . delicious . reminds me a lot of abrasive in this respect ( the floral/citrus vs. bitter balance ) , though not quite on that level .  carbonation is way too strong .

just flat out wonderful , this is just an exceptional nose here . the nose on this is just flat out fantastic .  the malt is lightly roasted , but mild with candisugar and syrupy cane sugar . add to that the thin body caused by a lot of sugar and it will add up to a c for me .
the aromas are very fine and intense i was very impressed ! !  m - watery . too thin , especially for a beer so strong , and meant to be malt-forward .

s - beautiful dark malt and deep cherry aroma .  cloying , sticky raspberry and malty sweetness combine with a major lack of carbonation and a very thin body to achieve complete unbalane in my opinion .

s : the best component of this beer , gratifying spices on top of a light roasted malt . d : good smell and its light make for easy drinking , but i would prefer more commanding flavors and spices .  it 's drinkable , but the body and carbonation are really lacking .

pours dark orangey brown , slightly hazy at first , then extremely cloudy as i pour in some of the yeast dregs . the aroma is huge - sweet brown sugar and honey with floral notes , alcohol and some breadiness . flavors are very aggressive in this fresh form - a huge honey presence meets with the aggressive bittering hops and some dark fruit sherry notes . excellent barley wine , both in its fresh and aged form - a testament to the value of bottle conditioning and cellarable beers .  taste is that of a standard belgian wit , but the body was off-puttingly thin . it was watered down , far too light for my tastes of wit beers .
welcoming . t : very nice ... molasses , cranberry-cherry , fruity overall , leather earthiness , and not extemely sour , but rather with a dry finish .  slightly watery body and bland carbonation .

very enticing . taste has quite a bit of belgian yeast and spice .  mouthfeel is very light and watery and it has a similar taste as many other bmc beers , however it does have some light maltiness to it that most macro lagers lack .

wow ... the nose on this is excellent ! tons of roasted malts , coffee beans and dark chocolate . very nice ... the taste is n't quite as profound as the nose , but it holds up well . i am really glad i had the chance to try it ... after all , it has been on my wants list for some time .  i really like a strong flavor from my beer ... or food for that matter m : watery . with the cloudy , opaque look of this stuff i was expecting ( and hoping for ) a little creamier or more substantial mouthfeel .

beautiful aromas of freshly baked banana bread , vanilla coke , toasted candied coconut . definitely will be cracking some more of these open in the future , alcohol is well hidden and i tend to consider rr a bit too hyped but this is a very nice beer .  this beer is incredibly watery and light on the palate .

the smell is bold of hops ! wow , this beer is very hoppy with enough malt to counteract the bitterness . it ends up being quite flavorful and works well .  mouthfeel is lacking as was expected . all in all this one is a step above the macro light brews .
very nice start of a semi-grainy and fully malted pilsner barley . delicious .  mouthfeel 2/5 mouthfeel got too watery as the beer warmed .
the smell is strong pundget and fruity , sweet and tangy . overall , pretty good .  mouthfeel is thin and watery .
this is a lovely slow-sipping beer .  but the overall mouthfeel is unbalanced , with simply too much fizz against a generally thin texture .
very very nice . very complex .  carbonation is ridiculously high .

it smells like when i picked hops and stuck my head into a box of them . it smells so fresh it 's wonderful . the taste was rather assertive in hoppiness .  the mouthfeel is confusing as it feels too thin for the amount of sweetness on the taste buds .
the sweet malts balance this very nicely . m & d : medium body beer , nice level of carbonation , makes for a semi-creamy mouthfeel . just an outstanding ipa .  thin and tingly mouthfeel .
smell - pumpkin , nutmeg , cinnamon , malts , brown sugar , spices . smells like liquid pumpkin pie . rather smooth and easy drinking .  seemed flat and had a flat taste .
the nose is nice . very nice . the nose just teases me with anticipation that the flavor never delivers .  biting carbonation , was that a hint of roastiness ?

light lacing , but the clarity of the body makes this look awesome ... the aroma keeps this awesome start going , a perfect hop balance between the citra oranges and some pine from the simcoe ; orange pine . some added grapefruit just makes this even better ... the awesome start is equally matched by the monumentally failure in taste , this is horrible . tastes like licking a lawnmower bag , citra pine resin bomb , with alcohol , disgusting ... mouthfeel is as bad and hurts the taste even more , too much carbonation , way too bubbly . a terrible taste , this needs to be avoided .  chocolately , dark . dry chalky taste , sweet . some warming . watery porter-like .
the nose had a definite saaz quality to it .  taste : carbonated water , with hops and light malt thrown in . mouthfeel : light and quickly fading .
really quite nice and the flavors are very detectable .  mouthfeel very flat for a belgian dubbel .

& raspberry , great if weird scents going on here ... t : raspberry , plums , figs , & strawberry jam verging om pop tart filling , very weird , plus leafy hops up front .  mouthfeel is kind of thin and not very pleasant as the carbonation dies down and leaves a sort of flat cola sensation , without the stickiness .
s- the dry hopping really comes through nicely . it 's quite floral with just a touch of an orange juice aroma .  m - maybe i 've had too many rises recently , but this is thin , very very thin .

4.5 s : smells delicious ! smells like a smoked pig wrapped in bacon . the smoke covers it up like it covers up everything else . very nice . 4.0 m : heavier medium body .  mouthfeel is thin and a bit watery .

smell : funky dog , tart , lemon , peach . mouthfeel : medium body and medium-high carbonation overall : nice to try , but unbalanced .  mouthfeel : this is where the beer went south for me . the carbonation was almost non-existent , which was in stark contrast to the initial appearance .

i love the smell of this stuff , there is n't a better smelling stout in the world , even if its from a can .  nose : it 's aroma is a little bit malty , a little bit citrusy flavor : the taste has some lemon/citrus notes w/ some hints of maltiness , but the big thing that you notice is how fizzy this beer is . it 's far too fizzy for me .
smell is an excellently projected , and wonderfully layered and clean tangerine , apricot , pear and lemon .  mouthfeel is way watery and i feel like it is slightly udnercarbonated .
awesome smell , couldnt wait to drink it !  mouthfeel : way too carbonated .
bright grapefruit and citrus with a very sweet candy malt aroma . candy coated hops ... yum !  almost watery .
looks good , smells amazing , but the taste is very underwhelming .  thin and watery for a dark beer . little carbonation . needless to say , i was disapointed in this beer .

smelled fantastic ! citrus fruits dominate - grapefruit , lemon , orange . taste was disappointing after the wonderful smell . the smell was very sweet , but it tasted bitter and sour . actually , the taste is pretty appropriate , since it tasted like unripened fruit . this is the the first of the vertical epics i 've tried and i was n't very impressed .  m : watery , high carbonation .

smell - i thought the nose on this beer was the best part . malt with grassiness . fresh smelling , almost floral . taste - wow ! that 's one bold and bitter finish !  it does bring vanilla to mind . the sweetness almost removes it from the style of beer . far to thin for a brown ale .
a velvety mouth feel , really enjoyable .  the mouthfeel is the downfall , it is watery with a dry finish , it just does n't convey the flavors to the tongue well enough .

a very nice set of smells on this one .  the herbal hops will become medicinal with traces of alluminum and will become a bit less appealing as it goes from a zippy feel to rather stagnent . a flat and bitter hop flavor is the finish .

2008 vintage a- almost stout-like in appearance , no head , fizzy swirl of carb in the middle of a color-devoid structure ... s-vanilla , cherry , oak , intense , strong , amazing smells ... .omg ... .there is n't a single hint of sour beer behind this nose . simply smooth vanilla and cherry ... awesome ... .ca n't remember a better nose on a sour ... . t- starts off smooth , nothing much going on *served at 39 degrees f.* then spice , phenols , tartness , tanginess , oh man ... this is great ... . m- solid brick of a mouthfeel , with a few glimmers of carbonation ... nothing exceptionally nasty about the 'brick ' that i speak of , but it is different ... .all together a different beer but for mouthfeel , i 'd expect something flat to taste like this , but in all it provides the right amount of carbonation ! duchesse on crack ...  far too thin and light for a bock . carbonation was assertive , but the body just felt thin and watery .

s : fragrant yeast character , a lot of banana , sweet malt . t : light caramel hits at first and then melds into a lot of banana , with hints of molasses .  however , extremely thin for a beer , and not very carbonated either .
the aroma is like thanksgiving dinner , total pumpkin pie .  mouthfeel is extremely thin- it felt like a porter rather than an ris .

a - black with a huge coffee colored head s - smells delicious - very sweet , chocolate malts . the most balanced smell to a stout i have had the pleasure of knowing .  mouthfeel is flat and thin . medium bodied and watery in texture , this brew falls short of anything special on the palate .
smell is strong , and fruity for the most part .  tingly , thin watery feel .

rarely , have i encountered an iipa with a nose as complex as this . it 's earthy , fruity , funky , dank . wow . dripping with pine and citrus oils . behind the woodsiness and sweetness a delicate floral aroma gently emerges ... seriously could smell this and be happy . thick , oily dark orange pour with a sustained white , frothy head . shit this is good . thick and mouth coating body never becomes oily or cloying . dripping and oozing with oily and resinous hops throughout but still manages to show a wonderful balance . thanks a ton brian !  mouthfeel was poor .

s- wow , i have to say that belgian ipa 's really smell great ... nice sweet caramel malt and bready yeast finished with a shit-ton of floral hops , only way stone knows how , but these hops are different than typical stone hops , much lighter floral scents . d- i love ipa 's and i like belgian trippel 's , however , i can not explain my discontent for blending the two i find them not enjoyable at all ...  mouthfeel : the carbonation is very high , way too high , for a milk stout . the body is thin . drinkability : just an ok beer , the mouthfeel also hurts the drinkability .
smells nearly exactly like pumpkin pie . this was my first pumpkin beer , and it 's not a style i 'm particularly enamored with .  mouthfeel is very thin and weak .

very natural and fresh apple . not a big fan of the coriander .  the weak malt presence and light flavor really hasnt enough oomph to fire up the taste buds . this one lacks that definitive crisp and bitter roastiness of the traditional dry stout . or watering their beers down ? actually , this wasnt that bad - light , thin and watered down , but not terrible .

the spices really compliment the berry smell . very unique and inviting . the highlight of this beer is the incredible aroma . t - not quite as impressive as the nose leads to believe .  mouthfeel is all wrong . way too much carbonation and way too thin of a body .
roasty , some coffee and chocolate . decadent .  the mouthfeel was a bit thin and watery .

s : chocolate covered cherries , vanilla , mocha , amazing ! t : huge vanilla ( a little much for me ) , oak , bakers chocolate , mocha .  m : mild , almost weak or watery . does not have stout presence at all ; feels like flat cola , if anything .

the smell is phenomenal , with loads of tropical fruits , pineapple , passion fruits , grape , mango and green apples . this boquet is really amarillo , and everything amarillo can be . any possible malt-notes in the nose is totally subdued by this awesome onslaught of amarillo !  mouthfeel - super watery overall - the only thing this beer has going for it is the aroma which is misleading .
smells of loads of caramel , vanilla , sugar , lactose . basically like dessert . far too sweet .  as many others have said , i 'm not liking the extra carbonation .

smells delicious . ( t ) bold combination of mild coffee and chocolate , with a sweet , smoky flavor .  taste : decidedly like its nose , only more so ; large notes of bittersweet chocolate and espresso rule the roost , here ; not nearly as sweet as you might imagine ; total lack of carbonation left the impression of a somewhat light , thin mouthfeel .

the nose on this evoked some memories of the amazing speedway stouts i had during sdbw with their vanilla and their toasted coconut variations .  it is very thin like any us macro , making it very drinkable like water .

insanely tart notes of lemon zest , white grape rinds , and dry oak barrels . so incredibly tart ; for me , the only comparable wild ale is batch 2 beatification ( in terms of sheer sourness ) . fantastic beer .  `` simple '' is the best word i can use to describe the taste , but it does deliver with scorched malts with a touch of lactose . my biggest complaint with this beer is the mouthfeel- it 's way too watery .
very nice sherry character to it with a hint of a woody edge .  slightly watery body with adequate carbonation . mouthfeel is slick and thin with a metallic and astringent finish as it dries .

lots of roasted malts and black coffee in the nose .  heard great things about this , found it in buffalo bought a 96 vintage.started promising i liked the color and the nice head , after that all downhill.had little to no smell , the taste was peppery ( overpoweringly so ) and way to sour ! the beer was way to thin and watery to go along with that taste.didnt finish the bottle just to peppery and thin for me , waiste of six bucks .

aromas are lemon citrus and light spicings of coriander and nutmeg , with a toasty character , also . pineapple and mango aromas release as the beer warms .  the flavor echoes the aroma , but the mouthfeel is n't quite up to scratch - weirdly thin and watery , which does no favors to the toasty , nutty , tea-like , and hoppy notes that are all individually assertive but harmonious and balanced in tandem , like a good jazz band .

heady ginger smell , nice . t : heavy ginger and sweet malt , quite medicinal .  thin mouthfeel with average macro carbonation . touch of caustic mouthfeel in the middle with the bitterness and petrol notes .

wow , one of the best smelling old ales i 've ever smelled . as it warms up so many different smells come out , yet it stays balanced . i thought this beer smelled amazing and was very complex and balanced . while the taste was a step down and a tiny disappointment after the smell , it was still very good . i thought it also had an amazing mouthfeel and while definitely a sipper , the abv is well hidden .  the mouthfeel needs work . it is n't creamy at all , it is just really watery and lacking carbonation .
s : very hoppy . has a floral , citrusy sweetness that is very deep and pleasant . faint candy smell also present .  mouthfeel : thin and watery body , medium carbonation overall : highly overrated .
smell : bacon ! ! again with bacon smelling rauchbiers . i love it ! ! but , it 's a bit weak .  fizzy carbonation and no body .

mmmm , that head really released a lot of wonderful aromas . pine and citrus predominate and , man , it smells good . very 'merry christmas ' , but not in the tinsel-and-cookies kinda way , but the 'i 'm some crank wandering around in a pine forest and i 'm giving presents to strangers ' kinda way . it definately ai n't normal , but it sure is delicious .  mouthfeel is very watery w/ average crabonation .

this is delicious beer . the aroma is just like liquor soaked fruit , with a hint of cinnamon . it 's got a nice clear amber color .  t- vanilla/cream soda , one-dimensional caramel malt . very vanilla . m- mouth is unrefined and rough in the way i would expect from good ol bmc . sweetness lingers in an unpleasant and sticky way .

strong vanilla notes , sugar , and faint chocolate aroma..southern tier really has a knack for completely nailing the nose on their brews t - do n't know if i could drink any more than the 9oz i was poured . this is incredibly sweet , and extremely rich . a perfect dessert beer .  m- thin and watery this could be improved greatly , but then it would probably be too sweet .

s : fragrant molasses , baked dark bread , brown sugar , sweet , loving the nose . t : baked brown bread again , baker 's chocolate with a fair amount of roast . d : great nose , solid taste , in the end a nice effort , it needs more sweetness to be really good , it definitely has potential .  the first part of the taste it quite strong and somewhat acidic but as you move to the middle and rear of your mouth the beer becomes very thin .

aroma packs an immediate bourbon punch and is balanced by rich vanilla and milk chocolate . molasses , raisins , brown sugar and caramel with very little roast , burnt or hop aromas . non-existent alcohol and the sweetness is very pleasant and smooth . flavor is similarly smooth and balanced with surprisingly more of a milk chocolate , vanilla and molasses presence than in the nose . bourbon is still present , particularly in the finish , but never harsh . warming throughout , yet the balance between the barrel and base beer is remarkable . mouthfeel is slightly thinner than hoped for , medium thick with light carbonation ; slightly milky in character . i do n't feel like this detracts from my enjoyment of the beer , but for the style would have expected something a little more robust .  for a russian imperial this is even for 9.7 incredibly weak and watery it 's the first thing i notice . the mouthfeel on this is not good , it 's even weaker than most american stouts i 've had .

s : a really interesting mix , i get a strong strawberry aroma mixed with a heavy caramel smell . there is also a nice hop/citrus aroma in the middle , some tangerine maybe . overall a really nice beer , very drinkable .  it 's also crisp . for a beer that looked so terrible ( albeit , it was dark ) and had such a poor mouthfeel , it sure tasted good .

taste- delicious representation of the smell . strong hops up front , especially for a pale ale , then dry malt .  carbonation appears low . beer is thin and boring , not much there at all . mild sweetness very water like . bummer .

the aroma continues to provoke the senses with a luscious , mouthwatering perfume . its flavor had a tough time catching up to its exceptional aroma , but still came through with a graceful sequence of sweet malts modestly checked with a light hop scheme .  it was very thin bodied as well .

smell : ah ... it 's been a while since i smelled something so interesting , so refreshing . sour concord grape juice , light farmy funk , an undercurrent of yogurty lactic tang , nutty sherry , and oaky port . really , a great nose . taste : sour through-and-through , with a spicy , envigorating tartness that swells in intensity as you hold it on your palate , then dissipates slightly before a clean , bracingly tart finish . very good , very bright , and very refreshing , but i do wish there were a bit more depth in the malt profile . this is exceptionally flavorful , interesting , and drinkable , especially at only 6 % abv .  m surprisingly watery for the body ; slightly carbonated with a light , watery finish . my major complaint is with the mouthfeel , the watery texture really detracts from its drinkability in my book .
taste s not as rich as the aroma , but still excellent . slightly warming alcohol if felt but not tasted .  mouthfeel is flat but this is the only disappointment .

a nice white head , great retention and lacing ... the aroma is fantastic , so fresh , just plucked pine needles with pineapples and an assortment of tropical fruits ... taste is equally great , bitting pine and alcohol of a dipa , but muted and so drinkable .  mf : too smooth and wet . watery even , but not creamy .

beautiful hop smell : floral , grass , the smell of spring basically . a little bit of bread & cracker smell . very aromatic , but not overwhelming , a smooth & even hop character . the lovely hop character is forward in the taste , but again not overwhelming or destructive to the tastebuds .  the palate is thin .
